<HTML>
<TITLE>Membership in SIA</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><I>Membership</I></B></FONT><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+3><I><STRONG>A Few Ways SIA Serves You:</STRONG></I><br><p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <STRONG>Exposure</STRONG></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>By joining SIA, your firm and its profile --  including officers and lines of business --  are automatically placed in our <A HREF="siapub1.htm#Year"><I>Securities Industry Yearbook</I></A>. This directory gives your firm visibility, indicates professionalism and is the key source book on securities firms. It is distributed to thousands of institutional and retail investors, municipalities, members of the press, public libraries, securities firms, corporate and government officials.  <A HREF=sia01b.htm>Member firms</A> are also listed in SIA's Directory and Guide and here, through the Internet.</FONT><br><p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <STRONG>Lobbying</STRONG></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>SIA maintains a database of several thousand securities executives throughout the country.  These Grassroots volunteers establish personal relationships with members of Congress or build on existing relationships to express our industry's views on tax legislation, government regulation and other issues.<p>SIA provides Grassroots members with timely information on developments in the nation's Capitol by means of the <A HREF="siapub6.htm#Legis"><I>Legislative Alert</I></A> newsletter and the <A HREF="siapub6.htm#Grass"><I>SIA On The Hill: A Grassroots Report.</I></A>  Moreover, SIA has a professional government relations office in Washington, which carries out the day-to-day business of representing the securities industry.  SIA promotes our industry's position on a state level as well.<p>SIA produces studies and makes use of professional lobbying and press relations to make our case. Our efforts affect everyone's bottom line and the prosperity of our industry.</FONT><br><p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <STRONG>Business Meetings</STRONG></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>Members choose from a menu of business meetings, seminars, conferences, and roundtables that focus on management issues, sales and marketing, telecommunications, operations, government relations, compliance and more!</FONT><br><p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <STRONG>Networking</STRONG></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>Our Roundtable groups, such as those for CEOs, CFOs, Sales and Operations executives, will enable you to brainstorm with others who have comparable responsibilities in similar firms. The participants always leave these sessions with ideas of practical value -- derived from exchanging information with counterparts in similar, non-competing firms.<p>Solutions can be found by talking with counterparts who have faced similar situations and who will often give you helpful money saving or money making advice.<p>The Association embodies a great many industry and staff experts. Almost all of your questions can be answered either immediately by a staff person or by drawing upon the resources of our member professionals.</FONT><br><p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <STRONG>Studies and Surveys</STRONG></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>To help securities firms gain critical information, SIA conducts confidential <A HREF="sia02e.htm">studies and surveys</A> enabling firms to compare compensation schedules, pay standards, management practices, productivity and profitability.</FONT><br><p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <STRONG>Publications</STRONG></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>Firms receive a host of need-to-know <A HREF="sia02e.htm">publications</A> including SIA's Washington Reports, Management Bulletins, Legal Alerts, Tax Briefs, Trends and more. In addition, the annual Securities Industry Yearbook and periodic special studies are available at low member rates.</FONT><br><p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <STRONG>Professional Staff</STRONG></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>SIA's experienced staff officers can help find answers to your questions either directly or through SIA's network of contacts at member firms.</FONT><br><p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <STRONG>Cost Savers</STRONG></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>Voice and data networks; and the SIA/Sprint long distance program are but a few examples of group discount programs offered through SIA. The Sprint program alone can save your firm many times the cost of dues. And there's more to come!<p><B>SIA/Sprint:</B> Member firms now enjoy savings of 15%, 25%, 30% and more on the cost of their long distance bills, by signing up for our SIA/Sprint program.  Many are saving dollar amounts which would more than offset their entire SIA dues bill.  Some firms are saving a multiple of that amount.  Even existing Sprint customers can save money.  This service is for SIA members only.<p><B>Surveys:</B>   Are you paying too much for those positions which are easily filled?  Are you losing your top producers because they are not being paid competitively?  SIA's annual surveys on salaries and RR earnings can make your compensation system work for you.<p><B>Other Services:</B>  Enjoy discounts on the following: rental cars, private area lines and other communication services, insurance products, shipping services, subscriptions to <I>Business Week</I>, Internet access and related services, airfares -- to name just a few.  Utilize SIA's RR screening test, attend the Annual Meeting (SIA members only) or a conference at low member rates.  Join a committee or just pick up the phone -- the value of interacting with fellow members is enormous.</FONT><br><p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <STRONG>Eligibility Standards</STRONG></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>Membership in SIA is open to broker/dealers in securities headquartered in North America  enjoying a good business reputation and meeting certain prescribed conditions and minimum standards. These are:<p><B>1)</B>  net worth of at least $50,000;<p><B>2)</B>  in the case of applicants with a history of less than five years in the securities business, evidence of prior experience in the business on the part of those in key management positions.<p>Also eligible for membership, subject to the same business experience requirements applicable to broker/dealers, are bond departments of commercial banks dealing in municipal, government and government agency securities,as well as underwriters of open-end mutual funds with net assets of $100 million or more.<p>Specifically excluded from membership are organizations whose business consists exclusively of the sale of variable annuities, the business of insurance or the rendering of investment advisory services.</FONT><br><p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <STRONG>How to Apply</STRONG></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>To obtain information regarding membership, contact <A HREF="mailto:pwilliams@sia.com"><B>Phil Williams</B></A>, Securities Industry Association, 120 Broadway, New York, New York 10271-0080, Phone: (212) 608-1500 or Fax: (212) 587-3988.<p>Admission to membership is granted by action of the Board of Directors. Completed <A HREF="siafrm00.htm"><B>applications</B></A> are referred to the Membership Committee for approval prior to presentation to the Board for final action.</FONT><br><p>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <STRONG>Annual Membership Dues - Fiscal 1997</STRONG></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3><center><B><I>New members receive a 50% discount on their first year dues.</B></I></center></FONT><br><p>
<FONT SIZE=3><B>Broker-Dealers</B><br>
This two-part schedule applies to all U.S. broker-dealers other than those dealing solely in municipal, government and government agency securities.  Gross revenues include all forms of income for the previous calendar year.  The number of employees is as of previous year end.  Each firm provided the data.<p>
<B>1. Charge Based on Revenues</B><p>
<center><TABLE BORDER=3 CELLPADDING=3 CELLSPACING=3>
<tr><td align=center colspan=2><B>Gross Revenues<br>(in millions)</B></td><td align=left colspan=3><B>Base<BR> Charge</B></td></tr>
<tr><td align=right>Up to</td><td>$1/2</td><td>$640</td><td>-----------</td><td>----------</td></tr>
<tr><td align=right>1/2-</td><td>1</td><td>658</td><td>+.000973</td><td>on excess of 1/2 million</td></tr>
<tr><td align=right>1-</td><td>5</td><td>1,145</td><td>+.000912</td><td> on excess of 1 million</td</tr>
<tr><td align=right>5-</td><td>10</td><td>4,793</td><td>+.000879</td><td> on excess of  5 million</td</tr>
<tr><td align=right>10-</td><td>15</td><td>9,188</td><td>+.000834</td><td>on excess of  10 million</td</tr>
<tr><td align=right>15-</td><td>20</td><td>13,358</td><td>+.000750</td><td>on excess of  15 million</td</tr>
<tr><td align=right>20-</td><td>25</td><td>17,108</td><td>+.000727</td><td>on excess of  20 million</td</tr>
<tr><td align=right>25-</td><td>30</td><td>20,743</td><td>+.000717</td><td>on excess of  25 million</td</tr>
<tr><td align=right>30-</td><td>35</td><td>24,328</td><td>+.000598</td><td>on excess of  30 million</td</tr>
<tr><td align=right>35-</td><td>40</td><td>27,318</td><td>+.000391</td><td>on excess of 35 million</td</tr>
<tr><td align=right>40-</td><td>45</td><td>29,273</td><td>+.000370</td><td>on excess of  40 million</td</tr>
<tr><td align=right>45-</td><td>210</td><td>31,123</td><td>+.000283</td><td>on excess of  45 million</td</tr>
<tr><td align=right>210-</td><td>310</td><td>77,818</td><td>+.000239</td><td>on excess of  210 million</td</tr>
<tr><td align=right>310-</td><td>1,000</td><td>101,718</td><td>+.000073</td><td>on excess of  310 million</td</tr>
<tr><td align=right>Over</td><td>1,000</td><td>152,088</td><td>+.000063</td><td>on excess of 1 billion</td</tr>
</table></center> <p>
<B>2.</B>  $1.75 for each full-time employee of any kind.<br>
<B>3.</B>  $2.00 for each independent contractor.<br><br>
<B>Municipal Dealers and Bank Bond Departments</B><br>
This schedule applies to members acting solely as dealers and/or brokers in municipal, government and government agency securities, including bond departments of commercial banks.  The classification is determined by the dollar amount of municipal issues managed and co-managed, plus government agency issues underwritten during the preceding year.<p>
<center><TABLE BORDER=3 CELLPADDING=3 CELLSPACING=3>
<tr><td align=right><B>Underwriting Volume<br>(in millions)</B></td><td align=right><B>Dues</B></td></tr>
<tr><td align=right>Under $1</td><td align=right>$990</td></tr>
<tr><td align=right>1 to 4.99</td><td align=right> 1,664</td></tr>
<tr><td align=right>5 to 24.99</td><td align=right>2,391</td></tr>
<tr><td align=right>25 to 99.99</td><td align=right>4,296</td></tr>
<tr><td align=right>100 to 199.99</td><td align=right>8,116</td></tr>  
<tr><td align=right>200 and over</td><td align=right>10,486</td></tr>
</table></center><p>
<B>Canadian and Mexican Broker-Dealers</B><br>
Canadian and Mexican firms may hold a single membership encompassing the Canadian or Mexican parent and its U.S. subsidiaries. Dues consist of (a) $4,700 for the Canadian or Mexican parent, plus (b) the application of the broker-dealer dues schedule (see above) to the U.S. affiliate, if one exists.<p>
<B>Investment Management Companies</B><br>
The classification is determined by the amount of mutual fund sales in the previous calendar year,  including dividends reinvested but excluding capital gains reinvested.<br><p>
<center><TABLE BORDER=3 CELLPADDING=3 CELLSPACING=3>
<tr><td align=right><B>Fund Sales<br>(in millions)</B></td><td align=right><B>Dues</B></td></tr>
<tr><td align=right>Under $25</td><td align=right>$3,130</td></tr>
<tr><td align=right>25 to 49.99</td><td align=right>6,924</td></tr>
<tr><td align=right>50 to 99.99</td><td align=right>13,894</td></tr>
<tr><td align=right>100 and over</td><td align=right>20,207</td></tr>
</table></center><p>
<STRONG><CENTER>Computation of Gross Revenues</CENTER></STRONG><P>
<EM><STRONG>What to Include:</STRONG></EM><P>
Other than the exceptions below, include all revenues in gross form from all sources for the entity that is the SIA member -- including off-shore revenues, revenues of subsidiaries, commodities, trading, insurance, interest income, etc.  Make no deductions for expenses.<P>
<EM><STRONG>Exceptions:</STRONG></EM><P>
<OL>
<LH></LH>
<LI>Trading gains and losses should be netted.<P>
<LI>Interest expense should be deducted from interest income.  Only on repos and reverse repos.<P>
<LI>Do not include unrealized gains or losses on securities in inventory as of the previous year.<P>
<LI>Do not include that portion of commissions retained by any firms that clear for you.  Example: clearing firm retains 15%; your firm gets 85%.  Include the 85% in your reported gross.<P>
<LI>Firms that use independent contractors should only report revenues that you retain.  Independent contractors are not counted as employees.
</OL>
<P>
<HR><FONT SIZE=2>SIA dues are deductible as a normal business expense. However, 25% of SIA's dues relate to lobbying activities and are not deductible by SIA members.</FONT><br>
