<TITLE>Advocacy  Activities</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><EM>Advocacy Activities</EM></B></FONT><P><P>
<HR NOSHADE=2>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=+2>Representation of Membership Views</FONT></STRONG><P>
<dd>SIA is the leading proponent of the securities industry and the capital markets.  It marshals the support, expertise, and views of its member firms and vigorously advocates public policies that contribute to the financial well-being of investors, and the economic strength of the nation and its capital markets.<P>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=+2><A NAME="fedst">Federal and State Legislation</A></FONT></STRONG><P>
<dd>The Association advances the industry's public policy messages at the federal level through its office in Washington, DC.  SIA employs a variety of advocacy, educational, informational and grassroots tools to ensure a full exchange of views between member firms and legislators.  It speaks as the authoritative voice for securities firms at congressional hearings and through  issue briefing papers and meetings with policy makers.  In addition, it draws on a strong grassroots organization to present the industry's unified message, conducts legislative conferences, and issues the <A HREF="siapub6.htm#Capitol"> Capitol Chronicle</A> to keep members informed of legislative and regulatory developments as they happen.  In addition, SIA provides guidance to individual members to set up appointments and meetings with legislators and to provide additional information where needed.  Contact <A HREF="mailto:sjudge@sia.com">Steve Judge</A>.<P>
<dd>The Association conducts similar activities in its New York office to address legislative and regulatory developments at the state level.  Through a network of member firm representatives, SIA committee members, and SIA state affiliates, the Association keeps close track of the many state legislative and regulatory issues that could have a significant effect on the business operations of securities firms.  It also periodically issues a newsletter, <A HREF="siapub6.htm#State"> Stateview</A>, to keep members current.  Contact <A HREF="mailto:states@sia.com">James Everett</A>.<P>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=+2><A NAME="grass">Grassroots Network</A></FONT></STRONG><P>
<dd>A strong, active Grassroots Network is an indispensable resource to policy makers and is critical to the success of SIA's legislative advocacy program.  SIA's Washington office maintains a state-of-the-art computer database of thousands of securities industry executives, branch managers, and registered representatives who have established personal relationships with government officials.  The sophisticated software allows SIA's staff to deploy industry employees instantaneously to contact lawmakers when legislative action is imminent on a key issue.  SIA issues <A HREF="siapub6.htm#Legis"> Legislative Alerts</A> to urge Grassroots volunteers to take immediate action on pending legislation.  It also publishes <A HREF="siapub6.htm#Grass"><I>SIA on the Hill: A Grassroots Report</I></A> to inform participants on the progress of legislation and to update them on the industry's activities on Capitol Hill.  Contact <A HREF="mailto:smorgan@sia.com">Suzanne Morgan</A>.<P>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=+2><A NAME="pac">Political  Action Committee</A></FONT></STRONG><P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association Political Action Committee (SIA-PAC) is the federally registered political action committee of SIA.  Its purpose is political-- to participate in the election of candidates for Congress who are committed to preserving the sound economic policies on which the securities industry is built and who have demonstrated leadership potential necessary to address the complexities of the financial services marketplace.  SIA-PAC enables SIA members to collectively support individuals for the U.S. Senate and House of Representatives who share the industry's interests.  A viable PAC is an important adjunct to SIA's legislative advocacy program.  It operates in compliance with federal election laws and makes contributions on a non-partisan basis.  Contact <A HREF="mailto:smorgan@sia.com">Suzanne Morgan</A>.<P>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=+2><A NAME="reglgl">Regulatory and Legal Resources</A></FONT></STRONG><P>
<dd>The Association's Office of General Counsel (OGC), located in Washington, DC and New York, works with SIA's committees to shape the industry's positions on and responses to the legal and regulatory issues that affect the industry.  SIA attorneys coordinate industry responses to rulemaking proposals; draft comment letters to the SEC, SROs, and other federal agencies; initiate rulemaking proposals or requests for "no action" letters on behalf of the industry; and analyze regulatory proposals and monitor their progress.  The OGC also provides substantive support for legislative efforts, such as testifying before Congress on important legal issues and providing legal arguments in support of SIA's legislative positions.  In addition, the OGC actively promotes the interests of the securities industry in the courts by filing amicus curiae briefs in important securities law cases and initiating legal challenges against unconstitutional laws or excessive regulations.  The Association's Litigation Committee pays particular attention to gathering information and data to assist members in defending litigation and arbitration matters.  SIA has put together a modest list of <A HREF="experts.doc"> expert witnesses</A> on securities matters and has listed them by locale.  Also available is a <A HREF="briefs.doc"> library of briefs</A> that is based on SIA's own experiences on a variety of topics ranging from arbitration, punitive damages, Section 12(2) of the 1933 Securities Act, choice of law clauses and other common issues faced by brokerage firms.  <A HREF="siapub6.htm#Alert"> Legal Alert </A>and <A HREF="siapub6.htm#Reg"> Regulatory Review</A> keep members informed about significant legislative and regulatory developments.  Contact <A HREF="mailto:skaswell@sia.com">Stuart Kaswell</A>. <P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1><FONT SIZE=3>&copy; 1997 Securities Industry Association</FONT>
