<HTML>
<BODY><body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
<TITLE>Best Compliance Practices</TITLE>
<FONT SIZE=+4><STRONG><EM>Best Compliance Practices</EM></STRONG></FONT><P><P>
<HR NOSHADE=4>  
In order to enhance public trust in and to better ensure the integrity of the securities industry, SIA's Board of Directors, at its November 10, 1995 meeting, endorsed a set of "Best Compliance Practices" for voluntary adoption by SIA member firms.  The Best Compliance Practices address the following four categories:<P> 
<DD>1. Role of compliance professionals<BR> 
<DD>2. Relationships with investors<BR> 
<DD>3. Internal firm policies<BR>
<DD>4. Relationships with regulators<P> 
The Best Compliance Practices outlined in each of the four categories are derived primarily from the experience of compliance professionals at global investment banks and national broker-dealers. The practices initially were developed by the Compliance Subcommittee of SIA's Public Trust and Confidence Committee.  They are aspirational in nature and are designed to foster ethical standards in the conduct of a securities business. The Board recognizes that the diversity of firms in the industry as to size, business mix, culture etc., and differences in the structure and size of the staffs of their compliance departments, will require each firm to appropriately modify these practices to suit its particular characteristics. The Board also recognizes that many of the items included are more applicable for full-service firms serving retail customers and less tailored to for firms providing discount services or those serving institutional clientele.  Accordingly, firms may choose to adopt, reject or modify some or all of these practices.<P>
<STRONG>Role of Compliance Professionals</STRONG><P>
Firms should emphasize the high value of their reputation and interest in contributing to enhanced investor protection and to the integrity of the securities industry. Hence, they should be committed to high standards of conduct and to support the positive and unique role served by the firms' employees whose primary responsibilities are, in part or in total, related to compliance or legal functions ("Compliance Professionals").  Accordingly, they should:<P> 
<UL TYPE=circle>
<LH></LH>
<LI>Insist on compliance and high ethical standards throughout their organizations with senior management leading by example.<P> 
<LI>Emphasize that compliance with securities industry laws, rules and ethical standards is expected of every employee, and that line managers are responsible for effectively supervising employees under their direction to insure adherence.<P> 
<LI>Consider the compliance record of individuals, branch offices or other organizational entities under the control or supervision of managers and supervisors in their personal performance evaluations. <P>
<LI>Provide appropriate vehicles and resources for the transmission of compliance and regulatory information to employees throughout their organizations and sufficiently emphasize compliance and regulatory subjects in employee training. <P>
<LI>Make available to all employees an effective means of communicating (including confidential or anonymous communications, if appropriate) compliance, regulatory or ethical concerns to Compliance Professionals and/or senior management without fear of retaliation. <P>
<LI>Support and provide adequate resources to Compliance Professionals. <P>
<LI>Maintain a reporting relationship and/or unrestricted access to senior management for Compliance Professionals. <P>
<LI>Encourage the development, professionalism and retention of the firms' Compliance Professionals with compensation, benefits and recognition in keeping with their contributions.<P> 
<LI>While preserving the ultimate decision-making responsibility of line managers, involve Compliance Professionals and recognize their input as an integral component of decisions relating to hiring and terminating employees.<P> 
<LI>Actively involve their Compliance Professionals, along with line managers and supervisors, in the firms' internal disciplinary process to insure fair, consistent and appropriate action in instances of violations of industry laws, regulations or ethical standards.<P> 
<LI>Require Compliance Professionals to review disclosure language in all regulatory filings on registered representatives to promote the integrity of the regulatory reporting system while preserving fairness for the individual.<P> 
<LI>Insure sufficient access to information for Compliance Professionals to enable them to carry out their responsibilities.<P> 
<LI>Share knowledge or techniques which one firm has found effective in improving compliance and supervision with other firms for the common good of the industry.<P> 
</UL>
<STRONG>Relationships with Investors</STRONG><P>
The investor shall have the right to: <P>
 <UL TYPE=circle>
<LH></LH>
<LI>Competent and courteous service and, in the case of a full-service retail customer, advice at a fair price. <P>
<LI>In the case of a full-service retail customer, recommendations consistent with the stated investment goals and needs as disclosed by the investor.<P>
<LI>In the case of a full service retail customer, appropriate disclosure of the benefits and risks associated with a strategy or transaction recommended by the registered representative.<P> 
<LI>Timely and accurate account and transactional information, including associated costs, communicated in an understandable fashion.<P> 
<LI>Prompt attention and fair consideration to complaints or problems.<P> 
<LI>Confidential treatment of account or transactional information.
</UL>
<P> 
The firm and registered representative shall have the right to: 
 <UL TYPE=circle>
<LH></LH>
<LI>In the case of a full-service retail customer, rely on information provided by the investor concerning his or her investment goals, needs, resources and experience.<P> 
<LI>In the case of a full-service retail customer, notification by the investor of changes in financial circumstances which may affect the investment recommendations provided by the firm or registered representative.<P> 
<LI>Timely payment of financial obligations assumed by the investor.<P> 
<LI>Rely on the investor to read all documents provided by the firm or registered representative and to promptly bring problems or questions concerning their accounts to the attention of the firm or registered representative.<P> 
<LI>Reasonable compensation for services provided.
</UL>
<P> 
<STRONG>Internal Firm Policies</STRONG><P>
<UL TYPE=circle>
<LH></LH>
<LI>Managers and supervisors should be required to conduct reasonable inquiries and background reviews before finalizing hiring decisions.  Such inquiries should include a CRD review with permission of the candidate.  Managers and supervisors should be encouraged to consult with Compliance Professionals regarding any "yes" answer on a candidate's record or responses to Form U4 "Disciplinary Questions."<P> 
<LI>Individuals who are the subject of special supervision directed by the SEC, SROs, states or other regulatory authorities should be identified, and the manager or supervisor should acknowledge his or her understanding of the special supervisory procedures which he or she has committed to carry out.<P> 
<LI>Firms' internal policies should provide that internal disciplinary actions may be taken against registered representatives and other employees for specified types of misconduct.<P> 
<LI>Supervisory procedures should be delineated in writing and include the reports to be used as guidelines for review, the record keeping requirements and delegation process. The procedures should also identify the employees to whom responsibilities have been delegated. 
<LI>Firms should maintain written records of supervisory responsibility for each business unit in the organization. <P>
<LI>As part of their continuing education requirements, firms should create a written Firm Element Continuing Education Plan.  Firms should give due recognition to the beneficial aspects of a continuing education program and promote internally the positive role such a program may serve.  The area(s) responsible for executing and documenting the firms' execution of the training plan should be clearly designated. <P>
<LI>Business unit policies should include a strong emphasis on good sales practices and supervisory reviews.  These should be a part of firm goals, particularly for sales and trading departments.<P> 
<LI>Employees who deal with the public, particularly traders, research analysts and bankers, should be required to conduct their investments and trading in a manner that minimizes conflicts with the best interests of public customers.
</UL>
<P> 
<STRONG>Relationships with Regulators</STRONG><P>
<UL TYPE=circle>
<LH></LH>
<LI>Consistent with the firm's legal obligations to its shareholders, employees and clients and its commitment to high ethical standards, dealings with regulators should be timely, forthright and cooperative. <P>
<LI>Ongoing regulatory reporting obligations should be discharged in a timely, accurate manner with appropriate attention to dealing fairly with individual employees.<P> 
<LI>The firms' legal and/or compliance departments should be actively included in the regulatory examination process to gain the potential benefit of an early discovery of problems and give the firms an opportunity to correct them. <P>
<LI>It is important that employees understand the role regulators play in the securities industry.  Through ongoing education, employees will be better able to work within the regulatory guidelines and legal framework. <P>
<LI>For the common good of the industry, firms should be willing to share with regulators their policies, procedures, technology and organizational structures designed to achieve effective self-regulation. 
</UL>
<P>For more information, contact <A HREF="mailto:megert@sia.com">Mark Egert</A>.
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>&copy; 1997 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia06c.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballrite.gif" ALT="Next Page"></A>
