<HTML>
<TITLE>Values Statement</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><A NAME="I"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"></A><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><EM> Values Statement</EM><BR></B></FONT><P><P>
<HR NOSHADE=4>
<DD>On November 9, 1995, members of the Securities Industry
Association unanimously amended the trade association's by-laws to
include an industrywide values statement and clarify procedures to
terminate SIA membership of  firms or individuals who violate the
association's principles. <P>
<DD> The by-law changes were approved by the more than 600 securities industry
executives gathered for the trade association's annual meeting on November 11, 1995.  "A new dialogue with investors" was the
meeting's theme.<P>
<DD>"The addition of a value statement to the by-laws is an effort to
establish as policy what has been for years the guiding principle of SIA
members, many of which have instituted their own value statements to
promote ethical and professional standards," the SIA said in its memo
proposing the by-law changes.  "The statement is for the guidance of member
firms and is not intended to supplant each firms' own set of values."<P>
<DD>The value statement of the SIA's by-laws states:  "Recognizing their
fundamental role in the continued growth and development of capital
markets, as well as their responsibility to issuers and investors, SIA
member firms hold these values: adherence to ethical and professional
standards; commitment to the best interests of clients; and exercise of unquestioned integrity in
business and personal dealings in the industry and within the firms.<P>
<DD>"SIA member firms uphold these values through responsible management:
superior products and services; thorough and ongoing professional education
for employees; and clear, consistent and complete information for clients
about products, services and the risks and rewards associated with
investing and the capital markets."<P>
<DD>The SIA's members also today approved unanimously clarifications in its
policy to terminate member firms' affiliation with the association when the
firm is found to violate ethical standards or regulations and laws.<P>
<DD>SIA members can be suspended or expelled from membership if they cease to
meet membership qualifications and act in ways "detrimental to the best
interests of the Association or injurious to the securities industry or
tending to bring the securities business into disrepute."<P>
<DD>The amendment to the SIA by-law provision states:  "If any director of
SIA or chief executive of a member of the association believes that any
member of the association has committed any acts detrimental to the
association, injurious to the securities industry, or tending to bring the
securities business into disrepute, and  wishes to have that member
suspended or expelled, that director or chief executive of a member shall
file a formal complaint in writing with the chairman of the membership
committee.  This complaint must contain specific instances when and where
such actions were committed.  Upon receipt of the complaint, the chairman
of the Membership Committee shall investigate the allegations as he or she
deems appropriate and prepare a report and distribute it to the Membership
Committee.  A meeting of the Membership Committee shall then be scheduled
and the complaints considered.<P>
<DD>A vote of three-fourths of the members present at the meeting shall
decide whether or not to bring this complaint to the Board.  If so decided,
the chairman of the Membership Committee shall present the committee's
recommendations to the Board of Directors."<P>
For more information, contact <A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">Jim Spellman</A> or <A HREF="mailto:dkittell@sia.com">Don Kittell</A>.
<br><br><HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1997 Securities Industry Association
