<HTML>
<BODY><body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
<TITLE>Internet  Security Tools</TITLE>
<STRONG><EM><FONT SIZE=+4>Internet  Security Tools</FONT></EM></STRONG><P>
<HR NOSHADE=3>
<FONT SIZE=4>SIA has developed the following information to assist its members in addressing security issues as they relate to the Internet.   It should be noted that  SIA is providing this data strictly on an informational basis and it should not be construed as an endorsement of any of the products listed.  It is not intended to be representative of all products or information available on this subject  nor does SIA attest to the accuracy of any of the information provided on any product or service. </FONT> <HR>
<STRONG><H2>Encryption Policy and Its Effect on Information Security for SIA Members</H2></STRONG><P>
<STRONG>Introduction</STRONG><P>
Encryption is a core technology in our business, used to protect 
confidential communications between ourselves and our clients. 
Federal regulations and recent proposals governing the export of 
encryption technology place our ability to continue to provide 
confidential communications at risk. <P>
Encryption technology is the subject of extremely restrictive regulation 
that makes it very difficult for our technology professionals to buy, 
build, and deploy software and hardware.  This <A HREF="sia07bc.htm"> paper</A> will familiarize 
you with the basics of cryptography policy as it relates to the current
debate over cryptography export and the Administration's various "Clipper" 
proposals. <P>
Our business is at risk by poorly constructed encryption policy.  The Information 
Security Subcommittee of SIA's Technology Management Committee  will continue to work to assure that we can 
protect our data and our customer's data.  Changes in 
encryption policy will most likely come out of the Digital Privacy and 
Security Working Group (DPSWG), an ad hoc coalition of industry 
representatives and public interest groups coordinated by the <A HREF="http://www.cdt.org">Center for 
Democracy and Technology </A>(CDT) whose input is solicited by the 
Administration on encryption issues. <P>
DPSWG members have worked together since 1986 when it was essential 
to the passage of the Electronic Communications Privacy Act and the 
ongoing industry and public interest opposition to the Clipper Chip.<P>
<STRONG><H2>Products</H2></STRONG>
<dd><STRONG><FONT SIZE=+1>Certificate Services</FONT></STRONG> -- Public and private keys (encryption)
<UL>
<LH></LH>
<LI><STRONG><EM><A HREF="http://www.magi.com/~devon/table.html">KyberPASS</A></EM></STRONG>
<LI><STRONG><EM><A HREF="http://www.incog.com/product/ca.html">Sun</A></EM></STRONG>
