<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association">
<P>
For Release: <STRONG>Friday, January 10, 1997</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531								
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+3><B>SIA Applauds SEC Decision to Lower Minimum<BR>Quote Size for Nasdaq Market Makers</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, D.C.</STRONG> -- The Securities Industry Association applauded the Securities and Exchange Commission for its decision to lower the minimum quote size for Nasdaq market makers from 1000 to 100 shares.  The pilot will allow market makers to display the actual size of the customer limit orders on the Nasdaq screen.
<P>
<dd>"This decision will prove to be a benefit for market makers and investors, by giving them the best of the dealer market and the limit order exposure of the auction market," said Bernard Madoff, chairman of the SIA Trading Committee.
<P>
<dd>The SIA Trading Committee will monitor the implementation of the pilot program and its effect on trading liquidity and the interests of investors.
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<P>
