<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Thursday, January 9, 1997</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531								
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+3><B>SIA Lauds 'Super IRA' Bill to Help <br>Baby Boomers Save for Retirement</B></FONT></CENTER>
<p>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, D.C.</STRONG> -- Marc E. Lackritz, president of the Securities Industry Association, today issued the statement below after Representatives Bill Thomas (R-CA) and Richard Neal (D-MA) introduced the Savings and Investment Incentive Act of 1997, or "Super IRA" bill.
<p>
<dd>" Few issues will come before Congress that are more important than helping Americans adequately prepare for their retirements.  As the recent Advisory Committee report on Social Security reminds us, the federal safety net is in jeopardy.  Future generations will not be able to depend on Social Security or Medicare to the same extent as todays retirees.  And survey after survey shows that Americans are saving only about one third of the amount they will need to maintain a comfortable standard of living in retirement, even if the level of federal benefits remains unchanged.
<p>
<dd>"The 104th Congress began an effort to expand Individual Retirement Accounts (IRAs) by increasing the contribution limits of non-working spouses.  Even with this change, however, the current rules and regulations restrict IRAs so severely that only a few working Americans can deduct their contributions.  The income limitations on deductible contributions have not been changed since 1986, and the rules are so complex that many people are unsure whether they can make a deductible contribution.  Current rules also impose a staggering penalty on savers who may need to tap those funds for down payments on a first home, educational expenses for their children, or other family emergencies.
<p>
<dd>"The Thomas/Neal Super IRA bill, on the other hand, will promote savings by allowing all Americans to make both deductible and non-deductible contributions to a new kind of IRA that earns tax-free income.  Individuals would also be able to make penalty-free withdrawals to cover educational expenses, financially devastating medical expenses, the purchase of a first home, and living expenses in times of unemployment.  The Super IRA bill will give Americans one of the most significant tools they need to increase their personal savings -- nearly 70 percent of people surveyed said they would increase their retirement savings if they could contribute to a tax-deferred IRA."
<p>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 760 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S., SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1997 Securities Industry Association
