<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Tuesday, January 7, 1997</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531								
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+3><B>Alliance Bill Offers 'Good' Blueprint to Rebuild Financial Laws, Regulations Governing Securities, Banking, Insurance Industries</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2>Piecemeal Decisions Created Confusing, Conflicting Bureaucracy</FONT></CENTER> 
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, D.C.</STRONG> -- Steve Judge, Senior Vice President for Government Affairs of the Securities Industry Association, released the following statement after the introduction today of legislation to overhaul federal laws and regulations governing the securities, banking, and insurance industries.
<P>
<dd>"The legislation introduced today is a significant step in Congress toward enactment of comprehensive reform of financial services laws and regulations.  Reflecting a broad consensus of the banking, insurance, and securities industries, the bill directly addresses the inadequacies of the current regulatory system.  This system is built on a series of piecemeal regulatory actions that have exploited loopholes in Depression-era laws as the needs of investors and issuers have changed.  As a result, regulators are forced to make strained interpretations of antiquated laws that ill-serve an economy dependent on sophisticated financial investment strategies and information technology. 
<P>
<dd>"The Alliance bill is a good blueprint from which a comprehensive reform of federal laws and regulations can be built.  Unlike current law, the bill sets out the services that the securities, banking, and insurance industries can each provide and explains how they will be regulated.  We appreciate the hard work and effort of Representatives Marge Roukema (R-NJ) and Bruce F. Vento (D-MN) in developing the legislation.
<P>
<dd>"This legislation recognizes the importance of functional regulation -- that securities regulators should regulate all securities activities regardless of which entity provides the services.   Another important principle -- a two-way street -- is embraced by the bill.  This means that, as banks engage in securities activities, securities firms, likewise, can engage in banking activities.  Finally, the bill removes the temptation of banks to use their federal subsidies to the disadvantage of the rest of the industry.  Under this legislation, banks would not be permitted to use federal deposit insurance to cover their securities accounts.
<P>
<dd>"We encourage the House and Senate Banking Committees to settle down and work toward enacting a comprehensive overhaul of federal financial services laws along the lines of the bill introduced today."
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 760 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S., SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1997 Securities Industry Association
