<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Monday, January 6, 1997</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531								
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+3><B>SIA Welcomes Social Security<BR>Task Force Recommendations</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2>Lackritz Calls For Solution That Increases Savings,<BR>
Gives Americans More Choice and Access to Greater Returns, Opportunities</FONT></CENTER> 
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, D.C.</STRONG> -- Marc E. Lackritz, President of the Securities Industry Association, issued the following statement after the release today of a report by the Advisory Council on Social Security:
<P>
<dd>"We commend the Advisory Council on Social Security for its dedication and hard work in producing a thoughtful report and recommendations to fix Social Security.  We look forward to working with Congress and the White House on ways to ensure Social Security's viability.
<P>
<dd>"We agree with the unanimous consensus of the council that the current Social Security system needs to be improved to meet the oncoming retirement needs of the Baby Boomers, who will be reaching age 65 in only 15 years.  America's demographic trends work against the financial health of Social Security in two ways.
<P>
<dd>First, the growth rate for retirees will outpace that for workers.  When Social Security was founded In the 1930s, there were 16 workers per Social Security beneficiary; by the year 2030, there will be only two per one beneficiary.  Second, Americans are living longer.  The number of Americans over the age of 70 will nearly double in the next 34 years -- from 24.1- million to 47-million persons.  These two trends mean that fewer and fewer people will be contributing to Social Security at a time when a growing number of retirees will be receiving Social Security benefits for longer periods of retirement.
<P>
<dd>"The Social Security problem should be tackled now.  Waiting entails too much risk and increases the costs to remedy the problem.  A solution needs to embrace two principles.  First, it should generate new savings.  It's commonly accepted that the nation's savings rate must be increased -- it's now far below that of any other industrialized country, a factor that hampers the creation of new jobs and growth.  We need to create a new culture of savings in this country.  Social Security reforms could play a key role in this challenge.  Second, Americans should be given more choice in their financial futures and more access to opportunities for higher returns on their contributions than they have now. 
<P>
<dd>"More Americans today are investing in stocks, bonds, and mutual funds than at any other time in the country's history.  The securities industry has developed tremendous expertise in helping Americans and their families realize their financial goals.  We stand ready to help policymakers develop solutions to improving Social Security by providing expertise on the securities markets and the investment process.  Any solution should incorporate the willingness of the U.S. securities industry to help an even greater number of Americans build their nest-eggs."
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 760 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S., SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1997 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="97sia04.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Press Releases"></A>
