<HEAD>
<TITLE>Letter to Congress MFN China</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body background="sia3abac.gif">
<IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
June 10, 1996 <P><P>
Dear Members of the U.S. Congress: <P>
<dd>On behalf of the Securities Industry Association, we are writing to urge the renewal of China's most-favored-nation (MFN) trading status.  We strongly believe such an extension is in the best interests of both the U.S. and China.  We agree with President Clinton, former President Bush, and presumptive Republican Presidential nominee Bob Dole --  who have all expressed strong support for renewing normal trading relations with China --  that expanding the political and economic ties between our two countries will promote Chinas political development and foster additional market-opening reforms.  The increased trade and investment that accompany MFN renewal will benefit the U.S. economy and the nation's capital markets. <P>
<dd>Although we do not agree with many of the Chinese governments policies, shutting down our trading relationship will not bring about desperately needed domestic reforms.  The securities industrys presence in China promotes economic growth -- a critical step toward further democratic reforms.<P>  
<dd>Indeed, the U.S. securities industry, and other U.S. suppliers of goods and services, have helped China become one of the worlds fastest growing economies.  Economic growth has improved the standard of living of the Chinese people by raising incomes, fostering free markets, and increasing support for the rule of law.  Undoubtedly, there will be many more opportunities in the coming years to continue to use our influence in Chinas markets to achieve domestic reforms.<P>
<dd>China will soon become one of the most important international markets for the U.S. securities industry's products and services.  For example, over the next decade, China is poised to invest $1 trillion in transportation and communications infrastructure improvements and energy-related capital equipment.  The U.S. securities industry is the global leader in providing low-cost capital to finance these types of projects, and China will undoubtedly wish to take advantage of our expertise.  But U.S. firms will not be able to play a role in that development if our nation's trade policy locks us out of China's markets.  The positive impact the U.S. business community has had on China's economic and political policies will cease unless its MFN status is renewed.  If we cast this emerging economic giant aside, our foreign competitors will eagerly pounce on the opportunities we have abandoned.<P>
<dd>Many legitimate trade issues between the U.S. and China remain unresolved.  The U.S. securities industry faces serious impediments to entering and conducting business in Chinas burgeoning market for financial services.  These issues can be resolved over time if the U.S. and China continue an open dialogue, through which long-term trust and stable trading relationships can be nurtured.  Closing down normal trading relationships with China will only turn the clock back on the progress we have made to date.<P>
<dd>We look forward to working with you to ensure renewal of Chinas MFN status, and on other trade initiatives which expand economic growth and create new job opportunities for all Americans.<P>
Sincerely,<P>
Marc E. Lackritz<BR>					
President<P>						
Steve Judge <BR>
Senior Vice President, Government Affairs<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
For more information, contact <A HREF="mailto:khofeditz@sia.com">Kristin Hofeditz</A>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
