<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Comments to Securities and Exchange Commission</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<body background="sia3abac.gif">
<IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
<P>
December 9, 1996
<P>
Jonathan G. Katz<BR>
Secretary<BR>
Securities and Exchange Commission<BR>
450 Fifth Street, NW<BR>
Washington, DC 20549<BR>
Email:  <A HREF="mailto:rule-comments@sec.gov">rule-comments@sec.gov</A>
<P>
<dd><B>Re:</B>  Proposed Rule Change by New York Stock Exchange, Inc.
<dd>Relating to NYSE Rules 342, 440 and 472 (File No. SR-NYSE - 96-26)
<P>
Dear Mr. Katz:
<P>
<dd>The Technology Regulatory Subcommittee<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>1</SUP></B></FONT> of the Securities Industry Association ("SIA")<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>2</SUP></B></FONT> appreciates the opportunity to provide comments to the Securities and Exchange Commission (the "Commission" or "SEC") regarding the proposed rule change by New York Stock Exchange, Inc. ("NYSE") relating to amendments to NYSE Rules 342 ("Offices-Approval, Supervision and Control"), 440("Books and Records") and 472 ("Communications with the Public") (collectively, the "Proposed Rule Change").  
<P>
<dd>For the reasons set forth below, the Technology Regulatory Subcommittee strongly believes that the Commission should approve the Proposed Rule Change promptly.
<P>
<dd>We applaud the NYSE for its prompt and practical action regarding supervision of customer communications.  The Commission previously had addressed the use of electronic media by broker-dealers, investment advisers and transfer agents in its May 9, 1996 interpretive release.<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>3</SUP></B></FONT>  In the release, the SEC strongly encouraged self-regulatory organizations - like the NYSE - to continue to work with broker-dealers to adapt their supervisory review requirements governing communication with customers to accommodate the use of electronic communication.<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>4</SUP></B></FONT>  The NYSE responded swiftly both to the SEC release and to industry calls for change by forming an Electronic Communication Committee and meeting with industry representatives, including SIA's Technology Regulatory Subcommittee.  The NYSE's Electronic Communication Committee recommended, and on September 5, 1996 the NYSE Board of Directors adopted, the Proposed Rule Change.
<P>
<dd>SIA strongly supports the flexible approach that the NYSE embraces in the Proposed Rule Change.  The Proposed Rule Change would remove the current requirement that firms review all items of correspondence relating to business in advance of sending them to the public.  Instead, the Proposed Rule Change would give firms flexibility to develop procedures for review of correspondence tailored to the nature and size of a firm's business and customers.  Rather than requiring firms to conduct pre-review in all cases, the Proposed Rule Change would require firms to develop written procedures for review of communications with the public that are designed to provide reasonable supervision of associated persons.  To the extent a firm does not conduct pre-use review, the firm also would be required periodically to educate and train employees about its policies and procedures, document that education and training, and conduct surveillance to ensure compliance with its procedures.
<P>
<dd>We believe that the Proposed Rule Change not only is directly responsive to the SEC's request for SROs to adapt supervision rules to accommodate the use of electronic communication, but also is sensible, practical and prudent.  A less flexible position may have resulted in most firms prohibiting their associated persons from communicating electronically with customers.  The NYSE has demonstrated in the Proposed Rule Change its willingness to foster the responsible use of technology by its members.<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>5</SUP></B></FONT>  The flexibility afforded by moving away from a "one-size-fits-all" requirement will not diminish general supervisory responsibilities.  The burden will now be on firms to develop supervisory approaches that they can demonstrate are reasonable.  SIA plans to encourage its members to share ideas about developing these approaches and hopes to continue working with the regulatory authorities, through the Technology Regulatory Subcommittee or other appropriate SIA groups, to articulate the elements of reasonable standards.<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>6</SUP></B></FONT> 
<P>
<dd>We note that the SEC recently proposed for comment amendments to its broker-dealer books and records rules.<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>7</SUP></B></FONT>  We are concerned that, in at least one respect, the proposed amendments, if adopted, would conflict both with the Proposed Rule Change and the SEC's call for supervisory rules that accommodate electronic communication.  In particular, Rule 17a-4, as proposed for amendment, would require broker-dealers to preserve books and records indicating that all out-going communications have been approved by a principal of the member.<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>8</SUP></B></FONT>  The communication approval requirement in the Proposed Rule Change, which does not require review of all communications with the public, is more consistent with the SEC's earlier call for accommodation of new forms of technology.  This aspect of the books and records proposal is a step in the wrong direction.  SIA plans to comment separately (and more extensively) on the books and records release.
<P>
<dd>We also note that the National Association of Securities Dealers is considering amendments to its rules governing supervision of communications with the public and books and records that would parallel those of the NYSE.  We are encouraged by this development, hope that the proposal will be submitted promptly to the SEC and ask the Commission to act quickly once it is received.  A uniform and consistent regulatory approach is of utmost importance to the securities industry.
<P>
<dd>Again, we praise the NYSE for its prompt action and the practical approach evidenced by the Proposed Rule Change and hope that the SEC approves it expeditiously.
<P>
<dd>If you have any questions regarding our letter or would like any further information, please do not hesitate to contact the undersigned at (212) 449-9699 or Mark A. Egert, SIA Staff Adviser to the Technology Regulatory Subcommittee, at (212) 618-0508.
<P>
Very truly yours,
<P>
Kenneth S. Spirer, Chairman<BR>
Technology Regulatory Subcommittee<BR>
of SIA's Technology Issues Committee
<P>
c:<BR>
<dd>Edward Kwalwasser, Group Executive Vice President, New York Stock Exchange
<dd>Don Van Weezel, Managing Director of Regulatory Affairs, New York Stock Exchange
<dd>Mary Anne Furlong, Director, Member Firm Regulation, New York Stock Exchange
<dd>Salvatore Pallante, Senior Vice President, Member Firm Regulation, New York Stock Exchange
<P>
____________________
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+1><B>Footnotes</B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>1</SUP></B></FONT> SIA's Technology Issues Committee formed the Technology Regulatory Subcommittee to accomplish its compliance and regulatory goals; namely, monitoring and responding to regulatory and legislative proposals having a potential impact on the use of technology by the securities industry and initiating action for the purpose of ensuring coordinated regulation and enabling the more practical and efficient use of technology.  The Subcommittee consists of representatives from 14 SIA committees and groups which, in turn, have representation from approximately 335 SIA members.
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>2</SUP></B></FONT> The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 760 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S., SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>3</SUP></B></FONT> See Securities Act Release No. 7288 (May 9, 1996), published in 61 <I>Federal Register</I> 24644 (May 15, 1996).
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>4</SUP></B></FONT> <I>Id.</I> at note 5, 61 <I>Federal Register</I> at 24645 ('"The Commission believes . . . that SROs' rules concerning the supervisory requirement for electronic communication should be based on the content and audience of the message, and not merely the electronic form of the communication.  . . . SROs should consider whether electronic mail communications, that, as a practical matter replace or substitute for telephone conversations, in many cases, would not require advance authorization or prior supervisory review.")
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>5</SUP></B></FONT> The Proposed Rule Change also is consistent with the Commission's move away from dictating substantive regulatory standards for specific problems and toward an approach based on broad regulatory goals.  This enlightened approach gives regulators and firms the flexibility to allow regulations and compliance procedures to evolve with changes in markets, technology and business.
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>6</SUP></B></FONT> For example, SIA's Internet Update conference, scheduled for February 4, 1997, will include a regulatory panel with representatives from the SEC, NYSE, NASD and NASAA and a workshop led by industry compliance professionals during which we hope members can exchange ideas for developing reasonable policies and procedures to supervise the use of electronic communications.
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>7</SUP></B></FONT> <I>See</I> Exchange Act Release 37850 (Oct. 22, 1996), published in 61 <I>Federal Register</I> 55593 (Oct. 28, 1996).
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>8</SUP></B></FONT> <I>See</I> proposed Rule 17a-4(b)(4), id. 61 <I>Federal Register</I> at 55600-55601.
<P>
