<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>19</SUP></B></FONT>The SEC recognized in the 1995 Release that consent could, in some cases, make effective an otherwise ineffective electronic delivery.  In example 1 of the 1995 Release, for instance, a company places its final prospectus on its Internet Web site and then confirms by mail the sale of securities to investors with a note stating that the final prospectus is available on its Web site and giving the Internet location of the Web site.  The SEC stated that, absent other factors, these procedures would not satisfy delivery requirements under the Securities Act of 1933 because not all investors purchasing securities could be presumed to have the ability to access the final prospectus via an Internet Web site.  The "other factors" that the SEC cites are "express consent from the investor or an investor's actually accessing the document on the Web site."  See the 1995 Release, 60 Federal Register at 53,461.
