<HEAD>
<TITLE>Comment Letter-SEC Proposed Trading Practice Rules</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body background="sia3abac.gif">
<IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
July 16, 1996<P>
Jonathan G. Katz <BR>
Secretary<BR>
Securities and Exchange Commission<BR>
450 Fifth Street, NW<BR>
Washington, DC 20549<P>
<dd>Re:	<EM>SEC Proposed Trading Practice Rules Concerning Securities Offerings, <BR>
<dd>Release Nos. 33-7282; 34-37094; File No. S7-11-96; 61 Fed. Register 17108</EM><P>
Dear Mr. Katz:<P>
<dd>On behalf of the Federal Regulation Committee and the Capital Markets Committee ("the Committees") of the Securities Industry Association ("SIA") <SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>1</STRONG></FONT></SUP> we appreciate the opportunity to provide comments to the Securities and Exchange Commission ("SEC" or "Commission") regarding the Commission's proposed new regulation concerning trading practice rules governing securities offerings.<P>
<dd>The Commission adopted the existing framework for the trading practice rules in 1955, when by any measure -- trading volume, transparency, investor access to timely information, etc. --U.S. trading markets were far less developed and more vulnerable to potentially manipulative practices.  The last four decades have also seen the emergence of a sophisticated "buy side" in the form of institutional investors.  These changes, as well as the development of effective market surveillance capabilities by self-regulatory organizations and by the Commission, have created an environment where market manipulation is far less likely to succeed, and far more likely to be detected and prosecuted.<P>
<dd>At the outset, we wish to underscore that we are very pleased with the overall thrust of the proposed rules and we believe that in most respects they are a substantial improvement over the existing trading practice requirements.  We agree with the Commission's release accompanying the proposed Regulation M (the "Release") that the proposal "would create a simpler, more flexible framework to govern the market conduct of persons with a significant interest in the outcome of an offering" by "reduc[ing] regulatory burdens on issuers, underwriters, and other offering participants by focusing restrictions on potentially manipulative conduct in connection with the pricing of an offering, while retaining core investor safeguards."<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>2</STRONG></FONT></SUP>    The Commission's Staff is to be congratulated for its thoughtful efforts to improve this complex regulatory structure.<P>
<dd>Notwithstanding our general praise for Regulation M, however, we question whether the proposed new rules in their present form are sufficient to achieve the Commission's ultimate goal of eliminating unnecessary regulations.  As discussed below, in a number of respects the new requirements are still too restrictive and, like the current trading practice rules, will cause undesirable side-effects.  In several instances Regulation M is actually more burdensome than the current trading practice rules, with no clear explanation in the Release as to why additional regulatory burdens are appropriate.  In particular, we believe that the disparity between the proposed treatment of financial affiliates of distribution participants and financial affiliates of issuers or selling shareholders, discussed at pages 5-7 below, will have disturbing consequences.  The changes suggested below should alleviate the deficiencies that we note in the proposed rules.<P>
 A.  <STRONG>Application of Regulation M to Affiliated Purchasers</STRONG>.<P>  
<dd><EM>Summary</EM>.  The Commission's proposed definition of affiliated purchasers fails to delete an anachronistic holdover from Rule 10b-6, requiring that a money manager or similar entity and its affiliated distribution participant maintain themselves as separate legal entities with separate officers and professional staffs in order to be excepted from the definition.  In addition, affiliated purchasers of issuers and selling shareholders that provide securities-related services, such as underwriting, other broker-dealer activities or investment management, should receive the benefit of the exemptions provided under Rule 101 rather than the much more restrictive exemptions available under Rule 102.<P>  
<dd>1.  <STRONG>Definition of Affiliated Purchasers</STRONG>.<P>
<dd>The Release suggests that its definition of "affiliated purchasers" was updated to "reflect the structural complexity of multi-service financial organizations."  However, the proposed definition falls short of its intended purpose.  Proposed Rule 100 would define the term "affiliated purchaser" to include:<P>
<OL>
<LH></LH>
<LI>any person that acts "in concert" with a distribution participant, issuer or selling shareholder in connection with the distribution of a covered security;<P>
<LI>an affiliate that controls the purchase of such securities by a distribution participant, issuer or selling shareholder; or<P> 
<LI>an affiliate of a distribution participant, issuer or selling shareholder that regularly purchases securities, or that acts as an investment adviser with respect to the purchase or sale of securities.  In the case of distribution participants, the definition would not apply if the affiliate (a) is "a separate and distinct organizational entity from the distribution participant, with no officers (or persons performing similar functions) or employees (other than clerical, ministerial, or support personnel) in common with the distribution participant"; (b) only makes bids in the ordinary course of business; and (c) has information barriers in place to segregate the flow of information between itself and its affiliates that might result in unlawful activity.
</OL>
<P>
<dd>As an initial matter, we note that the "information barrier" requirement is confusing.  Information barriers have long existed between corporate finance departments and trading desks to prevent the misuse of material non-public information in other contexts.  However, the purpose and scope of an information barrier requirement in this context is unclear, since information about an offering is generally publicly available.  As the Release explains, the real purpose of this requirement is "to separate . . . corporate finance activities conducted in connection with a distribution from the trading operations of the affiliate. . . ."<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>3</STRONG></FONT></SUP>   Although an information barrier might be consistent with this goal if it is designed merely to ensure that the affiliate only receives information that is available to other customers,<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>4</STRONG></FONT></SUP>  as currently drafted the requirement "to segregate the flow of information between [a distribution participant] and its affiliates" appears to sweep more broadly.  We recommend that the Commission reconsider whether this requirement is designed to achieve its intended purpose.<P>
<dd>We are also concerned that the treatment of distribution participants' affiliates<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>5</STRONG></FONT></SUP>  is too restrictive.  It carries over from Rule 10b-6 the requirements that financial service firms erect separate legal structures for money manager affiliates, including separate officers or professional staff. Preserving the 10b-6 structural restrictions is both burdensome and unnecessary.  We urge that the structural requirements of paragraph (3)(i) of the definition be deleted for the following reasons:<P>
<dd>First, paragraphs (1) and (2) of the definition of affiliated purchaser are sufficient to ensure that no manipulation can occur.  If the affiliate is not acting in concert with persons involved in the distribution and does not control persons involved in the distribution, it is difficult to imagine that the structural requirements would add any meaningful additional protection against manipulation.<P>  
<dd>Second, the inclusion in the definition of any affiliate "who regularly purchases securities for its own account or for the account of others, or who recommends or exercises investment discretion with respect to the purchase or sale of securities", unless the affiliate's bids, purchases or inducements to purchase "are made in the ordinary course of business" is a second layer of assurance that is sufficiently broad to close any unforeseen loophole in paragraphs (1) and (2).<P> 
<dd>Third, the structural requirements are inconsistent with the other elements of the definition.  The "control", "in concert" and "ordinary course of business" aspects of the test emphasize the actual role played by the affiliate.  In contrast, a test based on legal structure emphasizes status rather than function, i.e., form over substance.<P>  
<dd>Finally, it should be noted that the structural requirements are out of step with closely analogous SEC requirements.  In Rule 10b-18 the Commission relies entirely on the concepts of "control" and " acting in concert" rather than legal structure to define the term "affiliated purchaser."  In another area of securities law the Commission considers information barriers without structural requirements to be a sufficient protection against fraud.  Rule 14e-3(b)(2) provides a safe harbor from fraud in connection with a tender offer if, "taking into consideration the nature of the person's business"  it has implemented information barriers that are "reasonable under the circumstances."  Assuming arguendo that the Commission is correct about the utility of the proposed information barrier requirement in the context of preventing market manipulation, the flexibility of this highly effective anti-fraud provision suggests that the structural requirements are unduly rigid.<P>
<dd>The inflexibility of the structural requirement contained in the proposed definition of affiliated purchasers is unnecessarily burdensome for investment advisers and other fiduciary affiliated activities.  A number of broker-dealers have investment advisers organized in divisions inside the broker-dealer rather than as separate affiliates.  Even affiliates that are separate legal entities frequently need to have at least some key officers or employees in common with a parent.<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>6</STRONG></FONT></SUP>   Broker-dealers should be able to choose how to organize their money management, investment advisory and similar operations based on business needs, rather than to avoid regulatory consequences that do not appear to be well grounded in public policy.<P>  
<dd>Moreover, the requirement preserves (or perhaps aggravates) the existing undesirable incentive for universal banks and other non-U.S. entities to drop the U.S. tranche of their offerings, rather than review and reorganize their branches around the world in order to comply with the definition.  For example, tax laws and banking regulations in many countries make it almost impossible for many non-U.S. banks with U.S. broker-dealer subsidiaries to reorganize their other affiliates as separately organized entities rather than branches.  Under the proposed definition, if a U.S. broker-dealer has a single senior officer who is also an officer of a parent non-U.S. bank, the parent would automatically be subject to the trading practice rules.<P>

2.  <STRONG>Financial Service Affiliates of Issuers</STRONG>.<P>
<dd>Affiliated purchasers of issuers and selling shareholders that are engaged in securities-related services should receive the benefit of the exemptions provided under Rule 101 rather than the much more restrictive exemptions available under Rule 102.  Specifically, affiliates of issuers or selling shareholders engaged in underwriting, other broker-dealer activities, and investment management should be treated under Rule 101 rather than Rule 102.  Under the current trading practice rules such affiliates do not face greater regulatory restrictions merely because of their affiliation with the issuer.  Although this may be an unintended consequence of the way the Commission structured the proposed rules, this is a particularly conspicuous instance in which proposed Regulation M imposes an increased regulatory burden that does not appear to be supported by any policy considerations.<P>
<dd>a.  <STRONG>Distribution participants</STRONG>.  We do not disagree with the Commission's stated reasons for wishing to make the exceptions available to issuers and selling shareholders narrower than the exceptions available to distribution participants.  However, the same logic suggests that a distribution participant should not be removed from Rule 101 merely because it has a parent or affiliate that is the issuer or a selling shareholder.  For example, we do not see why a distribution participant should lose the benefit of the exceptions in Rule 101 for 144A distributions or for actively-traded securities merely because it is affiliated with the issuer or a selling shareholder.  The activities of all distribution participants should be exclusively regulated by Rule 101.  This changed treatment for distribution participants affiliated with issuers will create new regulatory disincentives for offerings such as asset-backed securities and unit investment trusts, where the underwriter is often affiliated with the issuer.  In response to the Commission's Question 44, at a minimum Regulation M should provide more guidance as to how the "affiliated purchaser" requirement would apply where a distribution participant is an affiliate of an issuer or selling shareholder.<P>
<dd>b.  <STRONG>Broker-Dealer Activities</STRONG>.  We also believe that affiliates' broker-dealer activities in general should be governed by Rule 101 rather than Rule 102.  Here again, there does not appear to be any clear reason for depriving a broker-dealer of the Rule 101 exemptions simply because it is affiliated with the issuer or a selling shareholder. For example, under Rule 102 as proposed, a broker-dealer affiliate of an issuer or selling shareholder would not be able to use the de minimis exemption of Rule 101.  Results such as this seem entirely arbitrary and contrary to the public interest served by permitting a broker-dealer's customary services to be available to its customers despite the offering by an affiliated issuer.<P>
<dd>Subjecting broker-dealer affiliates to different restrictions depending on whether their parent is acting as a distribution participant or as an issuer or selling shareholder will also impede product development.  For example, offerings of equity-linked notes by certain issuers could be deterred unless broker-dealer affiliates are permitted to engage in related hedging activity.  Equity-linked notes are debt instruments that have a rate of return based on the performance of a different issuer.  These notes are usually hedged by purchasing the equity securities to which the notes are linked as closely as possible to the time the offering is priced.  A number of issuers of equity-linked notes have broker-dealer affiliates that engage in these hedging activities.  Section 102 should clarify that it does not serve to retroactively undo approval that the Staff has previously given for products such as equity-linked notes, nor to prospectively discourage development of other products.<P>  
<dd>c.  <STRONG>Investment Management Activities</STRONG>.  In addition to underwriting and other broker-dealer activities, we also believe that the exceptions in Rule 101 should be available to issuer or selling shareholder affiliates engaged in investment management activities.  Moreover, as noted in footnote 5 on page 3 above, the exception from the definition of "affiliated purchaser" in Rule 100 should apply to all investment management affiliates, not just the investment management affiliates of distribution participants.<P>
<dd>The difference between the treatment of investment management affiliates of distribution participants and those of issuers and selling shareholders is striking.  An investment management affiliate that purchases a covered security in the ordinary course of its business would be out entirely from the trading practice restrictions if its parent is a distribution participant and the affiliate meets the other conditions set out in the Rule 100 definition of "affiliated purchaser."  Even where a distribution participant's investment management affiliate was within the definition of "affiliated purchaser" it would be eligible for the broader exemptions of Rule 101.  However, an investment management affiliate of an issuer or selling shareholder that purchases a covered security would always fall within the definition of "affiliated purchaser" and would run afoul of Rule 102 unless one of the much narrower exemptions to Rule 102 applies.  This would create enormous fiduciary conflicts and compliance burdens for investment management affiliates, particularly those with parents that make shelf offerings or engage in venture capital activities.<P>  
<dd>The asset management businesses of an issuer should not be prohibited from purchasing securities of an affiliated issuer if the affiliated issuer's shares form part of an index (such as the S&P 500, the S&P 100, or the FTSE) or other computer-driven quantitative strategy that the asset manager is tracking.  If such relief is not granted, substantial difficulties will be posed for an asset manager affiliate of a large financial services company whose securities are publicly issued and form part of a standard index, both in serving its clients and in complying with other requirements set by ERISA or bank regulators.<P>  
<dd>d.  <STRONG>Foreign Market-Makers</STRONG>.  This disparate treatment would also have severe and undesirable effects on foreign issuers.  To avoid creating a disincentive for foreign issuers to offer their securities in U.S. markets because of the prospect that their affiliates will be forced out of the market on a global basis, Rule 102 should permit broker-dealer affiliates and asset management affiliates of foreign issuers to continue making markets and engaging in portfolio trading overseas.  This would be especially true for issuers that have affiliates that are market-makers in foreign markets where they are not allowed to cease making a market during a distribution.   In order to avoid unnecessary regulatory conflicts, Rule 102 should be clarified to permit this activity.<P>
 B.  <STRONG>Securities and Activities Covered by Rule 101</STRONG>.<P>
<dd>1.  <STRONG>Restricted Periods</STRONG>.<P>	
<dd>We generally support the proposed restricted periods contained in Regulation M.  In response to Question 9, we believe that the restricted periods pose a problem for exchange offers.  As the Release  notes, exchange offers are often priced well in advance of commencement of the offering period.  Thus, covered securities in many exchange offers could face very substantial restricted periods.  The period between pricing and commencement of the offering for these types of securities is often six months or more, and sometimes over a year.  Among other concerns, this would have the effect of blocking the issuer from making other equity offerings during the substantial time period of the restricted period.  To avoid such an extreme restricted period, we recommend that in the case of exchange offers the restricted period should only apply during the pricing period.  Rule 10b-5 and the restrictions placed on issuers and selling shareholders under Rule 102 should suffice to address any concerns about potential abuses.<P>  
<dd>2.  <STRONG>Derivative Securities and Reference Securities</STRONG>.<P>  
<dd>We are pleased that the Commission proposes to eliminate the provision of the existing trading practice rules that extends coverage to any security of the "same class and series" as the security in distribution.  Their proposed replacements, "covered securities" and "reference securities," are a substantial improvement.  However, the proposed definition of "reference security" raises several issues that should be clarified.<P>  
<dd>The discussion in the Release suggests that by "reference security" the Commission primarily has in mind securities underlying a convertible or preferred security.  For example, the Release points to common stock underlying distributions of preferred equity redemption cumulative stocks or equity-linked notes as illustrations of the types of securities that it intends to reach.<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>7</STRONG></FONT></SUP>   Specifically, we understand that the Commission does not intend to reach two other types of securities: (i) securities of an unaffiliated issuer even if the price might theoretically affect the price of the security in distribution; and (ii) debt securities of an issuer that has a debt security in distribution.  We hope that the Commission will confirm this understanding in any adopting release concerning Regulation M.<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>8</STRONG></FONT></SUP><P> 
<dd>3.  <STRONG>Prospective Underwriters and Shelf Registration</STRONG>.<P>  
<dd>The Commission's proposal to examine each takedown off of a shelf offering individually, rather than treating the entire shelf offering as a single distribution, is a substantial improvement over the current Commission interpretation of Rule 10b-6.  However, the Commission's proposed definition of "prospective underwriters" who would be covered by the restrictions of Rule 101 is in some respects unnecessarily broad.  Subpart two of that definition states that "prospective underwriter" includes anyone "[w]ho has reached, or reasonably expects to reach, an understanding with the issuer, selling securityholder, or managing underwriter that such person will become an underwriter, whether or not the terms and conditions of the underwriting have been agreed upon."<P>  
<dd>As a practical matter it is often difficult or impossible for a broker-dealer to know when it has reached a point where it "reasonably expect[s] to reach an understanding with the issuer. . . ."  This standard invites second-guessing by the Commission or self-regulatory organizations.  Issuers entertain many solicited and unsolicited underwriting proposals, sometimes over extended periods.  Frequently, a broker-dealer has no idea whether the issuer is seriously interested or just testing the waters.  In these circumstances a broker-dealer should not be deemed to be a participant in a distribution unless the issuer has notified the broker-dealer that it will be involved in a presently proposed distribution or knows that it will be the executing broker-dealer.  Therefore, we recommend that the Commission delete subpart two of the proposed definition of "prospective underwriter and delete the term "or reasonably expects" from subpart one.<P>
<dd>4.  <STRONG>Average Daily Trading Volume</STRONG>.  While we believe that while the average daily trading volume ("ADTV") test is helpful in many respects, it may be a more useful tool with regard to equity securities than fixed income debt securities.  Collecting volume data is more difficult for debt securities than for equity securities, and new issues of many debt securities may not have a 90-day trading history until long after the distribution ends.  Such securities may nevertheless have characteristics, such as institutional ownership and liquidity, suggesting that the risk of manipulation is remote.  Consequently, we suggest that the Commission consider whether to create an exemption from Rule 101 for debt securities meeting certain tests demonstrating that the securities are held predominantly by institutions in liquid markets.  For example, the Commission might condition such an exemption on a requirement that the participants in the distribution are contractually obligated to sell the securities in large lots, or that a specified minimum amount of an issuer's securities are in non-affiliate hands.<P>  
C.  <STRONG>Securities and Activities Excepted From Rule 101</STRONG>.<P>
<dd>1.  <STRONG>Circulation of Materials Outside the United States</STRONG>.<P>
<dd>In response to Question 29, the exemption from Rule 101 for research materials that satisfy Rule 138 or 139 under the Securities Act should be broadened so that offering materials and research materials circulated outside the United States are excepted from the rule.
<dd>2.  <STRONG>Basket Transactions</STRONG>.<P>
<dd>We agree with the Commission that an exception for basket transactions is necessary.  While the proposal represents a substantial improvement over the 1991 no-action relief provided to the SIA,<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>9</STRONG></FONT></SUP>  in two respects we think that the Commission's proposed basket exemption is still too narrow.  First, to qualify for the exemption a basket must contain at least 20 stocks, and the aggregate value of any bids or purchases of the covered security must constitute 5 per cent or less of the basket being purchased.  While we understand that the Commission is trying to achieve a rough balance of flexibility against the potential for abuse, the experience of Committee members suggests that many basket strategies are based on portfolios of between 10 and 20 stocks (as well as much larger numbers of stocks).  We believe baskets as small as 10 stocks are still sufficiently large to pose little realistic danger of abuse.<P>  
<dd>Therefore, we recommend expanding the exception to include baskets of 10 or more stocks, where the aggregate value of any bids or purchases of the covered security constitutes 10 per cent or less of the basket being purchased.  If the Commission is uncomfortable with that level, it may wish to change the parameters to 15 or more securities, and to transactions in covered securities constituting 10 per cent or less of the total value of the basket being purchased.<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>10</STRONG></FONT></SUP>   This approach has the virtue of being consistent with an existing New York Stock Exchange requirement.<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>11</STRONG></FONT></SUP><P> 
<dd>Second, the exemption permitting bids and purchases to rebalance an existing basket related to a standardized index is too limited.  It is not clear why rebalancing should only be permitted to adjust a basket position to a standardized index, as opposed to rebalancing as part of a customized portfolio management strategy.  Given the recordkeeping currently required for basket program trading activity, the Commission and self-regulatory organizations can audit a firm's claim that a trade was for rebalancing purposes with respect to any basket strategy, not just those where the basket is tied to a standardized index.  We recommend that purchases of covered securities should be permitted to rebalance a basket as long as the rebalancing is consistent with rebalancing activity in other stocks contained in the basket.  We also believe that this adjustment is necessary to permit prudent risk management of the derivatives activities of broker-dealers.<P>
<dd>3.  <STRONG>De Minimis Transactions</STRONG>.<P>  
<dd>The Commission's proposed standard for de minimis transactions is troubling because the proposed standard -- purchases that total less than one per cent of a security's ADTV -- would rarely apply to inadvertent trades in the institutional market.  It is possible that, with a codified de minimis standard, in years to come Commission Staff may be reluctant to recognize the de minimis nature of inadvertent and truly inconsequential transactions that do not fall within the standard.  Alternatively, if the Staff is willing to continue providing guidance on transactions outside the de minimis standard, there will continue to be a substantial need for such guidance if the de minimis standard is too narrow.  Therefore, we think it is very important to strike the correct balance at the outset in setting the standard.<P>  
<dd>We recommend raising the de minimis threshold to five per cent of ADTV.  This threshold should still be low enough to avoid any noticeable market impact or any likelihood of manipulative intent, especially with the companion requirement that the firm must have established and enforced policies in place reasonably designed to achieve compliance with Rule 101.  It should be noted that, for trades done with manipulative intent (such as an effort to mark the close on the evening of pricing), the Commission would retain the residual capability to find that the rule has been violated, whether the de minimis standard is set at one per cent or five per cent.<P>
<dd>4.  <STRONG>Distributions of 144A Securities</STRONG>.<P>  
<dd>We commend the SEC for proposing to extend the exception for 144A securities of foreign issuers to include 144A securities by domestic issuers.  The Commission's proposal is welcome, and eliminates the heretofore inexplicable disparity between securities offered by foreign issuers and those offered by U.S. issuers.  However, the Commission could safely extend the relief to securities offered to institutional accredited investors as well as to qualified institutional purchasers ("QIBs").  By limiting relief solely to offerings of 144A securities made exclusively to QIBs, the proposed rule would unnecessarily be of no avail in the usual offering.  Typically, offerings of 144A securities are made as part of distributions with three tranches: (i) an offshore or Regulation S tranche, (ii) a 144A tranche and (iii) an accredited investor tranche (generally limited to institutional accredited investors).  Purely domestic 144A offerings also frequently include an institutional accredited investor tranche.<P>  
<dd>As proposed, the rule would either require a significant change in current market practice or require distribution participants to forego the benefits of the proposed exemption.  We do not believe there is a sound policy basis for putting distribution participants to this choice.  Institutional accredited investors are capable of determining for themselves whether they wish to invest and, if so, the price at which they are prepared to purchase.<P>
<dd>If the Commission is reluctant to extend the 144A exception to institutional accredited investors, we propose as an intermediate step that the exception be extended to 144A offerings in which only a small percentage of the domestic portion of the offering are sold to institutional accredited investors.  For example, if 80 per cent of an offering was subscribed by QIBs, the QIBs would effectively ensure against any abuse in pricing to the same extent as if institutional accredited investors were entirely excluded from the offering.  Institutional accredited investors would benefit by receiving investment opportunities that otherwise would not be open to them, and issuers and distribution participants would benefit from the additional flexibility the rule would afford for a relatively small portion of the offering.  While we believe this approach would be more complex to apply and therefore less desirable than a straight exemption for institutional accredited investors, it would be preferable to excluding institutional accredited investors altogether.<P>
<dd>5.  <STRONG>Investment Grade Nonconvertible Securities</STRONG>.<P>  
<dd>We believe that investment grade asset-backed securities should be treated like investment-grade nonconvertible debt under Rule 101.  Asset-backed securities are priced and traded like debt securities, and we are not aware of any reason why they should be treated differently for purposes of the trading rules.<P>
<dd>6.  <STRONG>Need for a Block Exemption</STRONG>.<P>
<dd>We recommend retaining the current exemption for unsolicited purchases of blocks of covered securities that are made directly from shareholders without the intermediation of another broker-dealer.  This activity is beneficial to shareholders and issuers, and raises no perceptible risk of market manipulation.  Shareholders learning of an impending offering sometimes wish to reduce their position in the issuer's outstanding securities.  By taking a block off the market, the distribution participant provides the liquidity expected by the selling shareholder and preserves an orderly market.<P>  
<dd>D.  <STRONG>Expanded Disclosure and Recordkeeping of Aftermarket Activities</STRONG>.<P>
<dd><STRONG>Summary</STRONG>.  Proposed new Rule 104 would replace Rule 10b-7 governing stabilization.  We are pleased that the new rule would liberalize regulation of stabilization pricing.  Regrettably, the proposed changes are somewhat regressive in other respects.  Rule 104 and proposed amendments to Rule 17a-2 would add new reporting and recordkeeping requirements regarding certain aftermarket activity by distribution participants following termination of formal syndicate activity.  Contrary to assertions in the Release, these new requirements would add substantial new regulatory burdens without any evidence of possible abuses in this area.<P>
<dd>1.  <STRONG>Stabilization</STRONG>.  As it relates to determining permissible stabilization pricing levels, we agree with the Release that the proposal will ease much of the complexity of Rule 10b-7, particularly in the context of multinational offerings.  Rule 104 will enable underwriters to adjust stabilizing bids to reflect fluctuations in markets and currencies, and will eliminate the arguably parochial exclusive focus of Rule 10b-7 on U.S. markets to determine permissible stabilization prices.  This is a welcome change.<P> 
<dd>In contrast to proposed Rule 104's liberalization of stabilization pricing, the rule does not alter the current notification requirements, and the release does not suggest that the Commission has considered whether or not to do so.  The proposed rule retains the current requirement that the underwriter must notify both the market on which the transaction is placed and the person with whom the bid is placed every time a stabilizing bid is made.  The additional obligation to disclose the purpose of the transaction to the contra party seems unnecessary and may be unworkable in operation, especially in increasingly automated trading environments.<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>12</STRONG></FONT></SUP><P> 
<dd>The required notification accompanying every stabilization bid sends a signal that the distribution has not been completed.  This is one of the major reasons why underwriters are reluctant to make stabilizing bids.  The Commission should consider changing the requirement to a single general notification to the market through any required prospectus or through notification of the market's regulator of the underwriter's intention to make possibly stabilizing bids from time to time.<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>13</STRONG></FONT></SUP><P>   
<dd>2.  <STRONG>Aftermarket Activities</STRONG>.  The proposal adds entirely new obligations with respects to certain activities occurring after the underwriting syndicate has formally ceased.  The proposal requires disclosure of syndicate covering bids and penalty bids to the self-regulatory organization with direct authority over the market on which the transaction is effected, and creates new record-keeping obligations on the part of syndicate managers as well as tracking and reporting obligations on the part of other syndicate participants.<P>  
<dd>Syndicate short covering bids and penalty bids serve important and legitimate functions in protecting the pricing of the offering and, indirectly, the issuer's interest.  Regrettably, while the Release recognizes the legitimate functions of these aftermarket activities,<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>14</STRONG></FONT></SUP>  it does not point to any specific experiences or instances of abuse, or even any concerns, much less a plausible hypothesis, to warrant the proposed new requirement.  Expanded record-keeping with regard to these activities is not justified in the absence of any legitimate concern about, or demonstrated abuse of, syndicate covering transactions or penalty bids.  For similar reasons, we also object to the proposed new obligation to report aftermarket activities to self-regulatory organizations.<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>15</STRONG></FONT></SUP><P> 
<dd>The Release asserts that "this record keeping requirement will impose little, if any, additional burden on underwriters, because underwriters are already required to keep detailed syndicate account records."<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>16</STRONG></FONT></SUP>   We respectfully disagree.  While estimating the existing recordkeeping burden under Rule 17a-2 is extremely difficult, we challenge the Commission's assumption that it is fairly minor.<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>17</STRONG></FONT></SUP>   The Release entirely fails to consider that, whenever record-keeping requirements are changed, broker-dealers are required to make systems changes.  The nature of those systems changes varies from firm to firm and these costs are difficult to quantify, but reprogramming and retraining costs are real, and deserve greater weight than the Release assigns to them.<P>
<dd>Finally, in light of the costs and time needed to make systems changes in order to comply with new record-keeping requirements for syndicate covering transactions and penalty bids, we urge that if the Commission decides to proceed with these requirements it should set a nine month delayed effective date for this specific requirement to enable broker-dealers to make necessary systems changes.<P>
<dd>E. <STRONG> Alternative Approaches to Trading Practice Regulation</STRONG>.<P> 
<dd>We continue to favor a safe harbor approach to reform of the trading practice rules for reasons set forth in response to the Commission's previous concept release on the trading practice rules.<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>18</STRONG></FONT></SUP>   Rule 10b-18 is a useful model.  That Rule sets forth a safe harbor defining activity by an issuer that will not be deemed to violate Section 9(a)(2) of the Exchange Act or Rule 10b-5 under the Exchange Act.  Conduct that does not fall within the specific requirements of Rule 10b-18, however, is not necessarily deemed manipulative.<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>19</STRONG></FONT></SUP>   Similarly, we believe that the exceptions to proposed Rules 101 and 102 should be converted into non-exclusive safe harbors from either Section 9(a)(2) of the Exchange Act and Rule 10b-5 under the Exchange Act (as in the case of Rule 10b-18) or a general prohibition of manipulation during, or for the purpose of facilitating, a distribution.  It is unclear why a safe harbor approach is seen as valid for corporate repurchases but unacceptable for purchases related to underwriting activity.  Also, the absence of a safe harbor will result in continuing need for underwriters, issuers and their respective counsel to have emergency consultations with the Staff in unanticipated situations.<P>
<dd><STRONG>Conclusion</STRONG>.<P>
<dd>The Committees again wish to thank the Commission for the opportunity to comment on these major rule proposals.  We believe that proposed Regulation M is a highly constructive proposal that will reduce unnecessary costs to broker-dealers and other market participants without fostering any increased risk of market manipulation.  We believe that the Commission's proposal can be made even better, substantially improving the effectiveness of its trading practice rules.  The SEC needs to make many or all of the changes proposed above to fully achieve its stated objective of less complicated rules and reduced regulatory burdens.  We hope that our recommendations will assist the Commission as it considers refinement of the proposed new rules.<P>
<dd>If SIA or the Committees can provide further information please contact the undersigned, or George R. Kramer, SIA Assistant General Counsel, at (202)296-9410.<P>
Sincerely,<P><P>
Perry Taylor<BR>						
Chairman<BR>						 
Capital Markets Committee<P>
C. Evan Stewart<BR>
Chair<BR>
Federal Regulation Committee<P><P>
cc:  
<dd>The Honorable Arthur Levitt, Chairman, Securities and Exchange Commission
<dd>The Honorable Steven M. H. Wallman, Commissioner
<dd>The Honorable Norman S. Johnson, Commissioner
<dd>The Honorable Isaac Hunt, Jr., Commissioner
<dd>Michael E. Schlein, Chief of Staff, Office of the Chairman
<dd>Dr. Richard Lindsey, Director, Division of Market Regulation
<dd>Larry E. Bergman, Associate Director, Division of Market Regulation
<dd>Nancy J. Sanow, Assistant Director, Office of Trading Practices<P><P>
Notes:<P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>1</STRONG></FONT></SUP>The Securities Industry Association ("SIA") brings together the business interests of more than 730 securities firms in North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- investment banks, brokers, dealers and mutual fund companies, as well as exchange specialists -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  Collectively, they manage the accounts of more than 50 million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.   SIA members collectively account for 90% of securities firm revenue in the United States.  <P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>2</STRONG></FONT></SUP>61 FR 17108.<P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>3</STRONG></FONT></SUP>61 FR 17116.<P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>4</STRONG></FONT></SUP>Although we are not sure what such a requirement adds that is not already covered by the "in concert" and "control" elements.<P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>5</STRONG></FONT></SUP>In response to Question 43, we believe that the definition of "affiliated purchaser"in Rule 100 should be the same for affiliates of issuers and selling shareholders as it is for affiliates of distribution participants.  We do not understand why the Commission proposes to make the definition more restrictive toward affiliates of isuers and selling shareholders.<P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>6</STRONG></FONT></SUP>For example, many firms find that in order to maintain an effective information barrier between separately organized affiliates they need to have at least one compliance official common to both organizations who stands on top of the "Chinese Wall." <P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>7</STRONG></FONT></SUP>61 FR 17114, n. 31.<P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>8</STRONG></FONT></SUP>We also note that the Commission currently provides a safe harbor from the trading practice rules for securities that are not convertible within 60 days to the security that is in distribution.  Just as with derivative securities, "the manipulative potential of trades in [such securities] for the purpose of affecting the price of an underlying security is sufficiently attenuated such that these securities should not be covered by Regulation M."  61 FR 17114.  Consequently, we suggest that in the final rules the Commission continue to treat securities that are not convertible within 60 days as outside the scope of the trading practice rules.<P>
 <SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>9</STRONG></FONT></SUP>Letter to John T. Shinkle, Chairman, SIA Federal Regulation Committee, from William H. Heyman, Director, Division of Market Regulation , August 6, 1991 (File No. TP 91-339).<P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>10</STRONG></FONT></SUP>We propose 10 per cent rather than 6.67 per cent (which is one-fifteenth of 100 per cent) because we do not think that requiring that baskets be perfectly balanced is necessary as long as the distribution security represents a reasonably small portion of the basket.<P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>11</STRONG></FONT></SUP>This approach would be consistent with a New York Stock Exchange requirement that members make daily reports of program trades involving fifteen or more stocks.  See New York Stock Exchange Information Memo 88-26 (Oct. 6, 1988).<P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>12</STRONG></FONT></SUP>The proposed amendment to Rule 17a-2 would also substantially extend the period during which records relating to stabilization bids must be maintained by the managing underwriter.  While the Committees do not strongly object to this lengthened retention period, it should be noted that the Release does not offer any reason for lengthening this requirement.<P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>13</STRONG></FONT></SUP>The London Stock Exchange has followed this approach, and as a consequence stabilizing bids are more common there.  Rule 10.04(2) of Ch. 3, Rules of the Securities and Investment Board.<P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>14</STRONG></FONT></SUP>Id. at 17124-25. <P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>15</STRONG></FONT></SUP>The Committees are also concerned that the Release focuses on whether to extend regulation of aftermarket activities even further.  For example, question 60 invites comment on whether to impose price level restrictions on syndicate covering transactions.  The Committees believe that the Commission should posit its concerns about aftermarket activities before soliciting comment on whether to impose any new regulatory requirements for such activities.<P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>16</STRONG></FONT></SUP>61 FR 17125. <P> 
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>17</STRONG></FONT></SUP>The release claims that creating and maintaining these records would require five hours per offering.  Id. at 17129.  The Release does not state the Commission's basis for its estimate of either the existing burden or its belief that the incremental cost would be minimal. <P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>18</STRONG></FONT></SUP>Letter to Jonathan G. Katz, Secretary, Securities and Exchange Commission from Robert F. Price, Chairman, SIA Federal Regulation Committee, Sept. 12, 1994 (File No. S7-14-94).<P>
<SUP><FONT SIZE=1><STRONG>19</STRONG></FONT></SUP>Notably, proposed Rule 103 also adopts a safe harbor approach for Nasdaq passive market making (albeit a safe harbor only from proposed Rule 101, not from Section 9(a)(2) or Rule 10b-5). <P><HR>
For more information, please contact <A HREF="mailto:gkramer@sia.com"> George Kramer.</A>
