<FONT SIZE=+4><I><B>International Studies</B></I></FONT><BR><BR>
<A NAME="Foreign"><HR NOSHADE SIZE=1></A>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <B>Foreign Activity Report</B></FONT><p>
<A HREF="foreign.htm"><IMG SRC="foreign0.gif" ALT="SIA Trends" BORDER=1 HSPACE=35 VSPACE=6 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<FONT SIZE=3>A quarterly report that tracks purchases and sales of U.S. securities by foreign investors and U.S. purchases and sales of foreign securities.   Both gross activity and net purchases are shown for the following securities: U.S. stocks; U.S. corporate bonds; U.S. treasuries; U.S. agency bonds; foreign stocks and foreign bonds.  Data is shown for all world markets and most major nations.  Also included is a country by country breakdown in transactions in ADRs as well as transactions in emerging markets' equities by country and their market capitalization. <P> Yearly subscription is $50; $75 for non-members.  Contact: <A HREF=mailto:dstrongin@sia.com>David Strongin</A></FONT><P>
<A NAME="FSL"><HR NOSHADE SIZE=1></A>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <B>Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation Forum Finance Ministers Meeting:  Advancing Global Growth Through Capital Market Development (1996)</B></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>Prepared for the 1996 meeting of APEC Finance Ministers, this paper reviews the importance of APEC to the U.S. securities industry, recommends steps which Finance Ministers should consider in developing APEC's emerging markets, and sets forth guiding principles for free trade in financial services.  The APEC dialogue is an important element in building the foundation for enhanced U.S. economic growth and global competitiveness, and offers some of the best opportunities for the U.S. securities industry.  Papers produced for the APEC Leaders Meetings (1994, 1995) are also available.  No charge.<P> Contact: <A HREF=mailto:dstrongin@sia.com>David Strongin</A></FONT><P>
<A NAME="Asia"><HR NOSHADE SIZE=1></A>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <B>Asian Capital Markets: Market Access Restrictions and Regulatory Environment Facing U.S. Securities Firms (1994)</B></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>Study summarizing difficulties faced by U.S. securities firms in nine Asian Capital markets. Issues covered include local licensing issues, foreign investment and issuance of securities. Also includes data on market capitalization and listed companies for each country. No charge. Contact: <A HREF=mailto:dstrongin@sia.com>David Strongin</A></FONT><P>
<A NAME="USFS"><HR NOSHADE SIZE=1></A>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <B>U.S. Financial Services in Foreign Markets: Contributing to a More Competitive U.S. Economy (1993)</B></FONT><p><FONT SIZE=3>Position paper detailing the importance of the U.S. financial services sector to the U.S. and world economies and the significance of open access to foreign markets. The paper argues that the U.S. must adopt sound policies to enhance the international competitiveness of the financial services sector. No charge. Contact: <A HREF=mailto:dstrongin@sia.com>David Strongin</A></FONT><P>
<A NAME="ICSA"><HR NOSHADE SIZE=1></A>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <B>ICSA Handbook: An International Guide to Regulatory Organizations and Securities Industry Data (1994)</B></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>This handbook is a ready guide to regulatory organizations and trade associations which comprise the eight member countries (Australia, Canada, France, Japan, Korea, Switzerland, U.K. and the U.S.) of the International Councils of Securities Associations (ICSA). Also included is essential data on the securities industry and capital markets. The book relies on data supplied by each ICSA member. Cost is $20 for members; $35 for non-members. Contact: <A HREF=mailto:dstrongin@sia.com>David Strongin</A></FONT><P>
<A NAME="Japan"><HR NOSHADE SIZE=1></A>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <B>Opportunities for Expanding Your Asset Management Business: Essential Considerations in Accessing the Japanese Pension Fund Market (1995)</B></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>The U.S.-Japan Financial Services Agreement, signed in February 1995, produced agreements to liberalize a number of previously closed areas of Japan's financial services sector.  This pamphlet provides some basic considerations that U.S. companies should bear in mind as they seek to gain access to the new opportunities in the Japanese pension fund market.  Free to members.  $25 for non-members.  Contact:  <A HREF=mailto:dstrongin@sia.com>David Strongin</A></FONT><P>
<A NAME="India"><HR NOSHADE SIZE=1></A>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <B>India's Capital Markets: Opportunities for Growth and Expansion (1995)</B></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>Report summarizes problem areas in India which substantially impede the ability of India's financial services community to allocate efficiently the capital needed to fuel future economic growth.  Also reviews growth in India's economy and capital markets.  Free to members. $25 for non-members.  Contact:  <A HREF=mailto:dstrongin@sia.com>David Strongin</A></FONT><P>
<A NAME="Korea"><HR NOSHADE SIZE=1></A>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <B>U.S. Securities Firms in Korea: Difficulties Encountered in Establishing and Expanding in Korea's Capital Markets (1995)</B></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>Only three decades ago, Korea stood as one of the world's poorest countries.  Today, Korea stands as one of Asia's wealthiest emerging markets, sporting one of the fastest economic growth rates.  This paper reviews the difficulties faced by U.S. securities firms in Korea's capital markets, including ceilings on foreign ownership and restrictive foreign exchange controls.  Free to members. $10 for non-members.  Contact:  <A HREF=mailto:dstrongin@sia.com>David Strongin</A></FONT><P>
<A NAME="Multi"><HR NOSHADE SIZE=1></A>
<FONT SIZE=5><IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <B>The Multilateral Agreement on Investment: A Comprehensive Approach for Liberalizing and Protecting International Investment</B></FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=3>Position paper underscoring the importance of a comprehensive, binding and enforceable Multilateral Agreement on Investment (MIA).  U.S. investors currently hold foreign direct and portfolio investment exceeding $1.8 trillion.   An MAI must: 1) include high standards for liberalization of investment regimes; 2) incorporate a broad definition of investment, including portfolio investment; and 3) complement and enhance existing multilateral agreements by furthering liberalization of all services.  An agreement meeting these conditions would stimulate and expand the flow of capital, enhance global economic growth and job creation.  No charge.  Contact:  <A HREF=mailto:dstrongin@sia.com>David Strongin</A></FONT><P>
