<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>variance</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><body background="sia3abac.gif">
<IMG SRC="sialog.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
<B><FONT  SIZE=+4>An Overview Of VAR Modeling</FONT></B>
<P><HR>
The paper which follows provides a basic introduction to the principles of value-at-risk (VAR) modeling.  Currently, VAR models are used by major dealers as a modern tool in managing risk.  We believe, however, that these models also hold promise as a methodology for determining regulatory capital standards.
<P>
The paper was sent to the International Organization for Securities Commissions Technical Committee, Consultative Committee, and Working Party 3.  The paper was presented to IOSCO as background for a forthcoming presentation on VAR models to IOSCO by Goldman, Sachs & Co. on behalf of the London Investment Banking Association (LIBA) and the Securities Industry Association (SIA).  The presentation will be held on September 19, and coincide with IOSCOs Annual Conference.
<P>
Additional information on the use of VAR models and on risk management issues for derivatives can be obtained from the London Investment Banking Association, Key Risk Management Issues for Derivatives.                                          (Tel#: 0171-796-3606; Fax#: 0171-796-4345)
<HR>
<P><B>Introduction</B>
<P>This paper provides a basic introduction to the principles of value-at-risk (VAR) 
modeling.  Currently, VAR models are used by the major dealers as a modern tool in 
managing risk.  We believe, however, that these models also hold promise as a methodology for 
determining regulatory capital standards.
<P>
VAR for a portfolio is defined as the maximum loss expected not to be exceeded 
with a specific probability over a specific holding period.  While the details of methods of 
calculating VAR vary, the basic steps are as follows:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>price data relating to the types of instruments currently held are collected 
for the chosen observation period;
<P>
<LI> based on this price data and a statistical analysis of past price 
movements over a given observation period, the institution determines the losses or 
gains that would have occurred on its current positions if these were held for 
a specified &quot;holding period&quot; (e.g., one day or ten days) during the 
observation period; and
<P>
<LI> the institution selects a &quot;confidence interval&quot; (e.g., 99%) to be applied to 
the distribution of gains or losses to assess the maximum loss that would 
be expected not to be exceeded with this probability, thereby determining 
the value at risk of the current portfolio.
</UL>
<P>
<B>Advantages Of VAR For Dealers And Regulators</B>
<P>VAR modeling is the most powerful tool presently available for assessing market 
risk and potential exposures to counterparties.  It allows for comprehensive risk 
assessment across different risk types and markets, rather than looking at isolated factors, for 
example, duration for a bond portfolio or beta risk for an equity position.  In having a common 
&quot;vocabulary&quot; for measuring the risk of different assets it allows an assessment of relative risk 
among different asset types, and provides a tool for capital allocation.  Among the key benefits 
of VAR are:
<P>
<I>Regulatory recognition of VAR models would allow closer links between internal risk 
management and supervisory standards</I>
<P>
<dd>Utilization of VAR models by regulators would create a consistent framework 
<dd>from within which regulators, traders and risk managers could examine and 
<dd>discuss questions of risk.  In addition, we believe regulators would obtain a 
<dd>better insight into the hedging strategies utilized by dealers. 
<P>
<I>Use of VAR models is recognized best practice for risk management</I>
<P>
<dd>This is clear from industry practice at the leading securities firms and banks, and 
<dd>is reflected in the key industry reports on risk management, such as those by the 
<dd>Group of Thirty in 1993 and the Derivatives Policy Group in 1995.  Moreover, the 
<dd>derivatives risk management guidelines published by IOSCO and the Basle 
<dd>Committee in 1994 clearly identified the benefits of VAR modeling. We expect that
<dd>continued refinement of the technique as more experience is gained with it will 
<dd>expand the role of VAR modeling in modern risk management.
<P>
<I>VAR models-based capital charges would permit recognition of the risk reducing benefits 
of portfolio diversification</I>
<P>
<dd>Recognizing portfolio diversification (through recognizing correlations between 
<dd>markets) <FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>1</SUP></B></FONT> allows for a more accurate assessment of the incremental risk (or risk 
<dd>reduction) arising from adding an additional position to a portfolio.  For example, it is 
<dd>possible to observe a close correlation between, say, German and Belgian 
<dd>government bond price changes.  Thus the risk in a long position in German government 
<dd>bonds will be reduced if a short Belgian government bond position is added to the 
<dd>portfolio. <FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>2</SUP></B></FONT>
<P>
<I>VAR allows capital charges to reflect ongoing changes in the volatility of risk factors</I>
<P>
<dd>Historically, externally imposed capital requirements have been fixed on the basis 
<dd>of average volatilities for relatively broad asset classes.  In contrast, determining 
<dd>capital requirements through internal models allows charges to reflect the true volatilities 
<dd>of various asset classes and to vary over time in response to changes in volatility.
<P>
<B>Issues Relating To Use Of VAR</B>
<P>
Using VAR models demands careful judgment and a full appreciation of their 
potential limitations.  Since VAR is intended to assist a firm in managing risk as part of its 
daily business, it principally looks at incremental changes in price, rather than at very large 
fluctuations.  Also, some models make a simplifying assumption that prices are normally distributed.
<P>
The major dealers who utilize VAR models should supplement them with other 
techniques to remedy any potential shortcomings.  Two particularly important safeguards 
merit mention.  First, firms should conduct <B>stress tests</B> to revalue their portfolios under 
extreme events or price movements.  Stress tests can also be used to examine the durability of 
the correlation assumptions used in a VAR model.  Secondly, firms should use <B>backtesting</B> to check that the model performs well in tracking actual P&amp;L fluctuations, which also serves 
to verify that the assumptions underlying the model are reasonable.  Backtesting involves 
a comparison over time of VAR to actual P&amp;L.  Finally, it must be emphasized that VAR 
models are but one element of modern risk management and need to be supplemented by 
other methods, especially a robust internal control framework.
<P>
 A sound risk management framework would include:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>an independent risk management unit implementing a clear, comprehensive Board-approved risk management policy;
<P>
<LI>a timely risk reporting system for all relevant units, analyzing material risks; 
<P>
<LI>a clear, comprehensive set of risk limits, with appropriate monitoring and follow up procedures;
<P>
<LI>periodic reassessment of the underlying assumptions and parameters of models;
<P>
<LI>appropriate specific risk management policies, addressing the variability of individual issuer volatility relative to the market as a whole; and
<P>
<LI>review by, as appropriate, internal auditors, credit rating agencies, management consultants, auditors, and supervisors.
</UL>
<P>
These and other safeguards provide the components of an effective risk management policy which allow firms to address concerns regarding aspects of the modeling process.  We therefore believe that a qualitative supervisory assessment of the adequacy of these safeguards provides the best means of addressing prudential concerns over specific aspects of VAR models.  We would accordingly welcome the opportunity to work with IOSCO members and the IOSCO secretariat to discuss the appropriate supervisory framework for the use of models, with the goal of the swift adoption of models-based capital adequacy requirements.
<P>
<CENTER><B>KEY CONSIDERATIONS IN THE USE OF VAR</B></CENTER>
<P>
Value-at-Risk (VAR) models are powerful modern tools for measuring market risk in an integrated manner across a range of trading activities.  However, the use of VAR models raises complex issues concerning the appropriate parameters and assumptions underlying the models, as well as other factors that influence the accuracy and appropriateness of the model for use by an institution.  These issues merit careful on-going review by management:
<P>
<I>Holding Period</I>
<P>
<dd>The holding period is an important quantitative parameter of a VAR model, and 
<dd>its choice requires careful deliberation.  The holding period chosen will need to 
<dd>reflect the uses of the VAR model in question and the liquidity profile of the institution's 
<dd>trading activity.  A ten day holding period means that the model operates on the 
<dd>assumption that it would take a minimum of ten days before the institution can trade 
<dd>out of or hedge a position, during which time losses could accumulate.  Thus, the 
<dd>holding period is, in many respects, an estimate of the liquidity of an instrument.  
<dd>However, choosing a holding period that is appropriate for a range of instruments with 
<dd>differing liquidity, can be difficult.  Also, differing holding periods can reflect the uses of 
<dd>the model: a trader may be interested in normal market conditions and therefore a 
<dd>one-day holding period, while a risk manager who is more concerned by the prospect 
<dd>of illiquid markets may use a longer holding period.
<P>
<I>Observation Period and Historical Data</I>
<P>
<dd>The appropriate historical observation period used for models should also be assessed
<dd> carefully by firms.  In particular, questions such as weighting of data, and the appropriate 
<dd>length of the observation period have to be considered.  In the latter respect, the quality
<dd> and availability of data will be an important consideration.  As a result, thought may be 
<dd>given to different observation periods for different portfolios depending on data availability.
<dd>However, a common observation period is needed for recognizing correlations when
<dd>calculating an integrated VAR number. 
<P>
<I>Confidence Interval</I>
<P>
<dd>A confidence interval is a measure of the probability that there will be price movements 
<dd>within a given range.  This can be expressed in a number of ways.  Perhaps most 
<dd>common is reference to a percentage: calculating a VAR number of $1 million at a 97.5% 
<dd>confidence interval means that there is only a 2.5% chance that losses on the portfolio in 
<dd>question will exceed $1 million.  The confidence interval can also be expressed in terms 
<dd>of how often the maximum loss is expected to exceeded:  $1 million VAR at a 97.5% 
<dd>confidence interval also means (using a one day holding period) that a loss greater than 
<dd>$1 million will occur, on average, approximately once every 40 trading days.  Thus a choice 
<dd>of a confidence interval is, to a large extent, a choice about an institution's appetite for risk.
<P>
<P><I>Non-Linear Risks</I>
<P>
<dd>Firms with large options portfolios or positions in other instruments with embedded options 
<dd>features need to pay particular regard to the difficulty in measuring the full range of non-linear 
<dd>risks associated with such instruments.
<P>
<I>Estimation Method</I>
<P>
<dd>There are three general methods of calculating VAR: the analytic method; the historical 
<dd>simulation method; and the &quot;Monte Carlo&quot; simulation method.  The analytic method assumes <dd>a normal distribution, but financial markets often evidence &quot;fat tails&quot;  i.e., more frequent <dd>extreme price movements than would be predicted.  &quot;Fat tails&quot; can be incorporated into a <dd>VAR calculation using either the historical or the Monte Carlo simulation methods.
<P>
<B>Footnotes:</B>
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>1   </SUP></B></FONT>   Correlation is the extent to which two markets or risks move in line with each other, and can range from +1 (meaning perfectly correlated) to -1 (inversely correlated).  A correlation of 0 means there is no observable relationship between the two markets or risks.
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>2 </SUP></B></FONT>     The extent of the correlation recognized is determined by observing the statistical relationship between the two prices over time.
