<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Securities Regulatory Reform Letters</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association">
<P>
<B><CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+3><B>A RISING TIDE AND NEW OPPORTUNITIES</B></FONT></CENTER></B>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+1>Remarks of Marc E. Lackritz<BR>
President, Securities Industry Association<BR>
SIA Annual Meeting<BR>
Boca Raton, Florida<BR>
November 8, 1996</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<B>I.  Introduction</B>
<P>
<dd>Our industry is in the midst of a record year in 1996, thanks to investors doing well, the cost of capital staying low, a good economy, and the tremendous efforts of you all.  SIA has also had a terrific year, with the joint efforts of our leadership, our Board, our committees, and our staff producing some notable successes.  These achievements show what we can do with our industry-association partnership, focus, energy, a favorable political climate and bull markets.  President John F. Kennedy often noted that a "rising tide lifts all boats," and that has certainly been the case this year for investors, issuers, and our industry.
<P>
<dd>Before I review the data and achievements, I'd like to thank Buzzy Krongard for all his work this year as SIA Chairman.  Buzzy has sharpened our focus and led by example.  He single-handedly has fostered an effective, productive relationship with the SEC and Chairman Levitt, and his testimony before the Senate Banking Committee led directly to the "de minimis" exemption from state registration now enshrined in federal law.  Moreover, Buzzy spoke at more SIA conferences, division, regional and committee meetings than he can remember.  And he dove into tough issues affecting the industry, whether at the Justice Department, the SEC or the SROs.  It's a real tribute to Buzzy that he's managed to do all this while leading Alex. Brown to a record year.
<P>
<dd>Buzzy, on behalf of the organization and my colleagues on the staff, thank you.  In that same spirit, I know we all look forward to Jim Higgins' leadership in the coming year.
<P>
<B>II.  The Rising Tide of the Industry</B>
<P>
<dd>On our present course, our industry will break almost all the records of 1993.  The cost of capital is low, and investors continue to reap the rewards of higher stock prices and a higher bond market.
<P>
<dd>For the fifth consecutive year, we will raise over $1 trillion of capital for U.S. business.
<P>
<dd>Total underwriting will likely break 1993's record, especially for IPOs and equities.  As a result, underwriting revenues were $5.7 billion in the first half and total industry revenue was $60 billion -- an incredible 40% higher than last year's first half.
<P>
<dd>The combination of lower interest rates and steady price appreciation for both stocks and bonds has been a boon to investors.  From January 1995 through October 1996, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 59%.  In the 1990s, the Dow has risen 131%.  In the fixed-income market, long-term Treasury bonds are up 79% in the 1990s and corporate bonds have risen 74% over the same time period.
<P>
<dd>Since 1975, household financial assets have jumped from $1.6 trillion to $11.3 trillion through the first half of 1996.  While 21 years ago a majority of these assets were in bank deposits, today the overwhelming percentage of those assets, 72%, are in capital markets products, and that percentage keeps rising.
<P>
<dd>When investors do well and issuers do well, our industry does well.  Pre-tax profits will be the highest ever, easily beating 1993's record of $8.6 billion, and pre-tax return on equity (ROE) for all firms will be higher than any other year in the 1990s.  Discounters and regional firms are faring especially well, with pre-tax ROE averaging around 50%.
<P>
<B>III.  SIA/Industry Achievements</B>
<P>
<dd>Buzzy described many of our legislative achievements yesterday.  From Congress's override of the President's veto of federal securities litigation reform in December 1995, to the recent signing of securities regulatory reform into law last month, we've had a very successful year of advocacy.
<P>
<dd>The securities litigation reform law already has reduced the number of class action strike suits filed in federal court.  Only 40 class action securities-related litigations have been filed in federal court so far this year, compared to an average of 140 cases per year in previous years.
<P>
<dd>And the securities regulatory reform law is like nine lawyers face down at the bottom of the inland causeway -- a good start -- at clearing the underbrush from our regulatory system.  Importantly, it preempted state regulation of larger investment advisers and exempted mutual funds and securities of issuers that are listed on major exchanges from state registration requirements.  Moreover, it broadened the SEC's general exemptive authority so that it can more effectively address obsolete statutory requirements and ensure that the letter of the law is consistent with the spirit of the law.
<P>
<dd>Our perseverance in advocating tax incentives for savings and investment also paid off when Congress approved changes in pension rules to reduce barriers that were disincentives to pension savings.  Small businesses especially benefited from the reforms and the expansion of pension availability.  And importantly, Congress also increased the amount that a single-income couple can put away in an IRA from $2,250 to $4,000.
<P>
<dd>Some of you may also remember that the Clinton Administration proposed various revenue-raising provisions aimed at capital markets instruments that would have been effective on the date of proposal -- December 7, 1995.  SIA and other trade groups explained that the effective dates had "frozen" the markets in specific products; and we successfully argued that the proposals would have increased the capital costs of U.S. firms and reduced economic growth.  The effective dates were renounced by the Chairmen of the tax-writing committees, and Congress adopted a budget package with none of the controversial proposals.
<P>
<dd>And in the last week of the Congressional session, after a long drive to achieve comprehensive financial services reform fell short, we were able to help win passage of a provision to give securities firms with limited-purpose banks relief from the "temporary" 7-percent asset growth cap.
<P>
<dd>Perhaps more importantly, a bipartisan group of House members said they intend to re-introduce legislation in the next Congress that is strongly supported by the Alliance for Financial Modernization, of which SIA is a founding member.  This measure is built on SIA's key principles for financial services modernization: competition without federal subsidies, a full two-way street, and functional regulation.  Recent actions by the Fed and the Comptroller to unilaterally deregulate financial services by administrative fiat underscore the urgency for Congressional action.  The legislation must allow all financial services providers to compete fairly in all markets.
<P>
<dd>As Buzzy also mentioned yesterday, our legislative victories were not confined to the federal level.  We broke a nine-year stalemate in New York with the passage of a bill to eliminate the officers' add-back under the alternative tax.  New York-based firms will no longer have to pay tax on salaries paid to employees with officer titles.  The New York legislature also improved the exemption from the Unincorporated Business Tax to reflect the current activities of entities engaged in self-trading.
<P>
<dd>The overwhelming defeat of California Proposition 211 was a huge victory for both issuers and investors.  If the initiative had passed, it would have increased the cost of raising capital, making it more difficult for companies to expand, while cutting the returns of investors.  This initiative -- a dagger pointed at the hearts of investors, high-tech companies, their employees and shareholders everywhere-- was defeated because of the active involvement of SIA, the entire securities industry, and a coalition of high-tech companies, venture capital firms, accounting firms and other concerned businesses.
<P>
<dd>Speaking of technology, I'm pleased to report that SIA has had a positive impact on promoting pro-technology policies.  For example, our Technology Regulatory Subcommittee and Federal Regulation Committee played a vital role in urging the wholesale review of the regulatory status of email.  As a result of our efforts, the New York Stock Exchange issued a new proposal which will give firms the flexibility to satisfy increased customer demand for modern, cutting-edge communications.
<P>
<dd>In addition, the Ad Hoc Record Retention Committee moved closer to persuading the SEC to amend its record retention rules to permit firms to use any media to store their books and records, which will lead to huge cost savings and enormous benefits and efficiencies in interacting with customers.
<P>
<dd>Investors also benefited from SEC's new order execution rules.  As the SEC, the Department of Justice and NASDAQ sparred over the proper structure for executing trades in the dealer market, our newly re-established Trading Committee -- under Bernie Madoff's strong leadership -- successfully urged policies that put investors' interests first without crippling dealers in the process.  The implementation of these new policies in early January will be another test of our ability to change.
<P>
<dd>Like our effort in facilitating the industry's seamless transition to T+3 last year, SIA again is leading the way to heighten industry awareness, provide potential solutions, and ensure adequate testing of systems to make a successful and seamless conversion to the Year 2000 on all our computers.
<P>
<dd>We will continue to work with regulators to ensure that regulation doesn't strangle new technology in the crib.  The SEC's new general exemptive authority is a good first step toward working together to discard outdated and inefficient regulation.  Under Chairman Levitt's leadership, with the strong support of Commissioner Wallman, the SEC has already begun that process.  
<P>
<dd>Technology has propelled our economy into the information age and produced enormous changes in our industry.  Most important, though, it has transformed our culture into a transparent society, where all information is available to all people at all times, and new transaction channels are becoming ubiquitous.  Some technological gurus, who ten years ago foresaw with great certainty the replacement of the daily newspaper with on-line news, now predict with the same certainty the decline of our business because intermediaries can easily be by-passed in cyberspace.  But to quote Mark Twain, "Rumors of our demise are greatly exaggerated."  There will always be a market, and a need, for knowledge, judgment and wisdom.
<P>
<dd>That is why our Public Trust and Confidence Committee, under Irv Weiser's leadership, has redoubled our efforts to educate ourselves and our customers and clients, and to promote best practices in the industry.  In that way, we will better serve investors and be more prepared for this era of change.
<P>
<B>IV.  SIA Services</B>
<P>
<dd>With change, however, comes opportunity, and our job at SIA is also to help you manage change and create and take advantage of opportunities.  This year, we offered a new Internet Access conference to let you know about the benefits of connectivity, such as lower costs versus snail mail, fax or telephone calls; faster and more targeted communications; and knowledge of this revolutionary medium that will have a major impact on our business.  
<P>
<dd>Last year we began offering Internet access, security and World Wide Web services at special rates.  So far, 120 member firms have established home pages with direct links to SIA's home page.  Participating firms can communicate electronically with their clients and other industry members, establish a marketing presence on the Web, access the vast universe of business information or glean a variety of information from SIA's home page.  Our goal is to get 100% of our members linked to the Internet by June, 1997.
<P>
<dd>Our demographics are also changing dramatically, as baby boomers move toward retirement, the elderly are living longer, and women are controlling more financial assets.  Our Retirement Products Committee, under Kris Coffey's outstanding stewardship, introduced a Retirement Savings conference to help us learn how to market and address the vast financial needs of these groups in their retirement years.  The Committee also established a Retirement Network to share information, ideas, and questions about retirement.
<P>
<B>V.  Change and the Importance of Trust</B>
<P>
<dd>As the economy and the financial marketplace continue to evolve and as new competitors emerge from every sector and every country, our advantage will be that we've taken the time to educate and guide investors and issuers through the maze of often intimidating and confusing information.  As long as we maintain investors' trust, we'll have the opportunity to continue adding value.  And we'll outperform the competition by being smarter, better, and faster at making markets, providing capital, operating more efficiently, offering sounder knowledge and advice, or tailoring products and services to fit specific needs.
<P>
<dd>Economists and historians are describing our current era as the Third Industrial Revolution -- following the invention of the steam engine in the 18th century and the electrification of the economy in the 19th century.  If we are in the midst of the Digital Revolution, by almost all measures it will create vast new opportunities for investors, issuers and our industry.
<P>
<dd>SIA's value will be in increasing the public's trust and confidence in our industry.  By bringing our diverse and varied membership together with our terrific professional staff, we can all take advantage of the new opportunities provided by new markets and new investors.  Collectively, we will prove the doomsayers wrong, as our best times still lie ahead of us.
<P>
<dd>Again, congratulations on a terrific year.  This rising tide has most certainly lifted all boats.  Thank you.
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia09.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Previous"></A></body></HTML>
</BODY>
