<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Member Issues </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+3><B><CENTER>Overview of The National Securities Markets <BR>Improvement Act of 1996</CENTER></B></FONT>
<P>
<BR>
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+1><B>Title I, the "Capital Markets Efficiency Act of 1996":</B></FONT>
<P>
<dd><B>Preemption of State Registration Requirements for Certain Issuers.</B>  This provision exempts mutual funds and securities of issuers that are listed on major exchanges from state registration requirements.  It also exempts securities sold to "qualified purchasers" as defined by the SEC.  It preserves state antifraud authority, and states' authority to collect fees, except that states cannot require filings or fees with respect to securities of issuers that are listed on major exchanges.  In addition, it directs the SEC to report back to Congress in one year on additional steps that could be taken  to achieve uniformity among state regulatory requirements not addressed in the bill.  (Effective on date of enactment, except for a rulemaking and a report required of the SEC).
<P>
<dd><B>Preemption of Duplicative State Requirements Relating to Broker-Dealer Regulation.</B>  With respect to broker-dealer regulation, the bill bars states from setting books and records or capital, margin or bonding requirements that are different from, or in addition to, SEC or SRO requirements.  (Effective on date of enactment). 
<P>
<dd>The bill also permits brokers to service existing customers who are temporarily located outside the state of their residence, without triggering an obligation to register with the state where the customer is temporarily located.  If a customer moves to a new state, a broker will not be in violation of the state's registration requirements as long as he or she files an application within 10 business days of learning of the customers' change of residence, and a broker will be able to service a customer for 60 days while the license application is pending, unless the state denies the application or stays the application for cause.  These exemptions from state licensing requirements only apply if a broker is otherwise statutorily eligible to register with the state and is licensed in at least one other state, and if the broker's firm is registered with the state where the customer is now located.  (Effective on date of enactment).
<P>
<dd><B>Removal of Restrictions on Sources of Broker-Dealer Funding.</B>  Title I also eliminates restrictions on sources of funding for broker-dealers to permit extensions of credit by any lender and without regard to the lending limits under the federal Reserve Board's margin rules.  (Effective on date of enactment).
<P>
<dd><B>Broader SEC Exemptive Authority; Consideration of Impact of Regulatory Actions on Capital Formation.</B>  Title I grants the SEC general exemptive authority under the Securities Act and the Exchange Act, and requires the SEC, whenever it is required to consider whether an action is in the public interest, to consider not only the protection of investors, but also whether the action will promote efficiency, competition, and capital formation.  (Effective on date of enactment).
<P>
<dd><B>Coordination Among Examination Authorities.</B>  This title requires SRO and SEC examination authorities to more effectively coordinate their routine examinations of broker-dealers that are subject to examination by more than one regulatory authority.  (Effective on date of enactment).
<P>
<dd><B>Other Provisions.</B>  Title I also contains a provision directing the SEC to consider privatizing the EDGAR disclosure system, and a provision directing the SEC to adopt rules concerning the status under the registration provisions of the Securities Act of foreign press conferences and foreign press releases by issuers engaged in a distribution.  (Effective on date of enactment; except that SEC action regarding EDGAR and foreign press conferences is not required until 180 days and one year following date of enactment, respectively).
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+1><B>Title II, the "Investment Company Act Amendments of 1996": </B></FONT>
<P>
<dd><B>Qualified Purchaser Investment Pools.</B>  Title II enacts an assortment of improvements to investment company regulation.  Perhaps most notably, it creates an exemption from the Investment Company Act for investment pools sold solely to "qualified purchasers" as defined by the SEC.  (Effective on the earlier of 180 days after enactment or the date on which certain specified SEC rulemaking occurs).
<P>
<dd><B>Other Improvements.</B>  This title also liberalizes the Investment Company Act prohibitions against funds of funds.  It contains provisions simplifying the calculation and payment of registration fees by investment companies, increasing the flexibility of funds to advertise, deregulating the fees charged on variable insurance contracts, requiring certain new information in periodic reports to the SEC and to shareholders, broadening the SEC's record keeping authority over investment companies, and prohibiting the use of names by investment companies that the SEC by rule or order defines as materially deceptive or misleading.  Title II also excepts qualified purchaser pools from the Investment Company Act's prohibition on performance fees.  (Effective on date of enactment, except that provision regarding payment of registration fees becomes effective on the earlier of one year after enactment or the effective date of final rules or regulations issued by the SEC).
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+1><B>Title III, the "Investment Advisers Supervision Coordination Act":</B></FONT>
<P>
<dd><B>Federal Preemption for Large Advisers.</B>  Title III preempts state regulation of any investment advisers with assets under management of not less than $25,000,000 that are registered with the SEC, as well as any adviser to an investment company.  The SEC's jurisdiction is limited to these classes of advisers, except that the SEC by rule or order can extend SEC registration to advisers who otherwise are subject to exclusive state regulation.  (Effective on date of enactment).
<P>
<dd><B>Continuing State Authority and De Minimis Exception to State Authority.</B>  Notwithstanding exclusive SEC jurisdiction over certain advisers, a state may require registration of an investment adviser representative who has a place of business located within the state, or who falls within the exemption from the definition of investment adviser contained in Section 202(a)(11) of the Investment Advisers Act -- e.g., a broker or dealer whose performance of advisory services is solely incidental to his or her profession and who receives no special compensation for advisory services.  However, states would be barred from requiring the registration of any adviser who does not have a place of business located within the state, and during the preceding 12 months had fewer than 6 clients who resided in the state.  Effective 180 days after date of enactment).
<P>
<dd>In addition, states may continue to require filing or registration fees from persons as to whom state registration requirements are otherwise preempted.  States can also require the filing of any documents filed with the SEC, together with consent to service of process (Effective 180 days after date of enactment).
<P>
<dd><B>Elimination of Conflicting Requirements Among Different States.</B>  For advisers subject to state registration, states would be barred from enforcing books and records, capital or bonding requirements other than those of the state in which the adviser maintains its principal place of business.  (Effective 180 days after date of enactment).
<P>
<dd><B>Central Depository; Toll Free Hot Line.</B>  The title also authorizes the SEC to require advisers to file any fee, application or report required under the Act through a central filing depository, and requires the SEC to provide for the establishment of a toll-free telephone line to provide prompt information on advisers' disciplinary histories.  (Effective 180 days after date of enactment).
<P>
<dd><B>Other Provisions.</B>  The title authorizes the SEC to bar convicted felons from registering with the SEC as advisers.  The title authorizes (but does not appropriate or fund) $20,000,000 to the SEC's investment adviser program for each of fiscal 1997 and 1998.  (Effective 180 days after date of enactment).
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+1><B>Title IV, the "Securities and Exchange Commission Authorization Act of 1996":</B></FONT>
<P>
<dd><B>Reduction in 6(b) Fees.</B>  Title IV authorizes an appropriation of $300,000,000 for the SEC for fiscal 1997.  It also sets the levels for fees under Section 6(b) of the Securities Act so that they are designed to recover the costs of funding the SEC.  Those fees will decline in steps from $295 per $1,000,000 of securities offered in fiscal 1998 to $67 per $1,000,000 in fiscal year 2007.  (Effective on date of enactment, subject to periodic adjustments in fee levels specified in the provision).
<P>
<dd><B>Transaction Fees.</B>  This title also creates a new fee for NASDAQ market transactions, so that NASDAQ transactions will be subject to the same fees imposed on exchange transactions.  The fee rate for both NASDAQ transactions and exchange transactions will be 1/300 of one per cent, to be reduced to 1/800 of one per cent beginning in fiscal year 2007.  (Effective as of September 1, 1997 with respect to NASDAQ transactions and effective as of October 1, 1997 with respect to exchange-traded securities and off-exchange transactions of exchange-traded securities.  Payments for transactions occurring between September 1 and December 31 are due on March 15 of the following year; payments for transactions occurring between January 1 and August 31 are due on the following September 30).
<P>
<B><FONT  SIZE=+1>Title V, "Reducing the Cost of Saving and Investment:</FONT></B>
<P>
<dd><B>Small Business Capital Formation.</B>  Title V exempts from the Investment Company Act certain companies whose activities are limited to the promotion of economic, business or industrial development of enterprises doing business in the state in which the company is organized.  This title also broadens the type of securities in which business development companies ("BDCs") may invest to encourage investment by BDCs in "microcap" companies.  The title also liberalizes the capital structure restrictions that apply to BDCs.  It exempts from federal regulation any company that is not engaged in the business of issuing redeemable securities, the operations of which are subject to regulation by the State in which the company is organized under a statute  (Effective on the date of enactment).
<P>
<dd><B>International Accounting Standards.</B>  The title includes a "sense of the Congress" on the importance of establishing comprehensive international accounting standards and asks the SEC to report back in one year on progress toward achieving such standards.  (Effective on the date of enactment).
<P>
<dd><B>Preferencing Study; Other Studies.</B>  The SEC is also directed to conduct several studies.  It is to study the impact of "preferencing" customer order (the practice of a broker acting as a dealer on an exchange directing the orders of customers to buy or sell securities to itself for execution rather than crossing them with same-priced orders or quotations entered prior in time) on investors and on the national market system.  Separate studies are required concerning the impact of technological advances, the ability of shareholders to have proposals related to social issues and corporate practices included in proxy statements,  and the impact of disparate state licensing requirements on associated persons of broker-dealers.  (Effective on the date of enactment, with deadlines for submission of reports specified in the provision).
<P>
<dd><B>Church Employee Pension Plans.</B>  Title V contains a provision exempting church employee pension plans described in section 414(e) of the Internal Revenue Code from most federal securities regulation.  (Effective on the date of enactment).
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia09.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Member Issues">
</BODY>
