<HTML>
<TITLE>Legislative Update</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association">
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><EM>Legislative Update</EM></B></FONT>
<FONT  SIZE=-1><P></FONT>
<HR>
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+1><B>On the Hill</B></FONT>
<P>
<I>International Tax Reform</I> - Representatives of SIA's Subcommittee on International Tax Reform met separately on October 16 with John Buckley, Chief Tax Counsel for the Ways and Means Committee Democrats; Patricia McClanahan, Tax Counsel, Senate Finance Committee Democrats; and Craig Kramer, AA/LD for Representative Sandy Levin (D-MI) to discuss our international tax reform proposals.
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+1><B>At the IRS/Treasury</B></FONT>
<P>
<I>Independent Contractor</I> - The IRS's "Worker Classification Training Manual" is currently being revised to reflect changes made by the Small Business Job Protection Act.  When it was issued in August, the Manual recognized that rules imposed by a business on its workers in order to comply with governmental requirements should be given little weight in determining a worker's employment status.  SIA is continuing to discuss our views with Treasury and IRS officials that the Training Manual should be revised to clarify that policies a business imposes on its workers for consumer protection purposes should be given no weight in determining a worker's employment status for tax purposes.
<P>
<I>Pension Simplification</I> - SIA and other members of the Retirement Savings Network met with Mark Irwy, Treasury Benefits Counsel on October 15 to discuss the implementation of the pension related provisions of the Small Business Job Protection Act of 1996 (P.L. 104-188).
<P>
<I>"Logos" on Substitute Forms 1099</I> - SIA sent a letter last week to IRS Commissioner Peggy Richardson in opposition to any change in policy that would prohibit the use of identifying logos on substitute Forms 1099.  SIA is working with other trade groups and financial service firms in opposition to the proposed IRS policy change.
<P>
<I>Proposed Regulations Under Section 865(j)</I> - SIA submitted a letter to the IRS on October 14 commenting on the proposed Treasury Regulations issued on July 5, 1996 under Section 865 (j) of the Code.  This provision relates to the sourcing of loss from dispositions of stock, including losses by U.S. persons from dispositions of stock of foreign corporations.
<P>
<I>Nonbank Trustees of Medical Savings Accounts</I> - The new law creating the pilot MSA program was intended to permit existing nonbank IRA trustees to participate in the program.  New section 220(d)(1)(B) of the Code requires that the trustees of an MSA must be a "bank" (as defined in section 408(n)), an insurance company (as defined in section 816), or another person who demonstrates to the satisfaction of the Secretary that the manner in which they will administer the trust will be consistent with the requirements of section 220.  SIA will send a letter this week to the IRS Commissioner Peggy Richardson and Acting Assistant Secretary for Tax Policy Don Lubick requesting that financial institutions that currently satisfy the requirements relating to nonbank trustees and custodians (collectively "trustees") of IRAs under section 408(a) of the Code be treated as eligible trustees of MSAs under new Code section 220.
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+1><B>Securities Industry Association</B></FONT> 
<P>
<I>SIA Hosts Event for Rep. Rob Portman</I> - Representative Rob Portman (R-OH) was the guest of honor at a breakfast sponsored by SIA in Cincinnati, Ohio on October 17.
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+1><B>New York Times Articles on Pension Related Issues</B></FONT> 
<P>
Congress enacted the Savings Incentive Match Plan (SIMPLE) as part of the Small Business Job Protection Act to encourage small businesses to provide pension coverage for their workers.  The October 13 edition of the New York Times included an article discussing the differing views in the securities industry assessing the potential interest in the small business community for the new plan.
<P>
This edition of the paper also contained the first of a two-part series on the growth and use of deferred compensation plans which provide generous tax breaks to executives but are not available to all employees.  The article describes the use of deferred compensation as follows:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>The deal is simple.  Rather than take all their pay, and pay taxes on it, executives let the company hold on to some.  The company invests the money, and the executives do not pay taxes on any of it until they take the money out years later.
<LI>It sounds like the I.R.A. or 401(k) savings plans used by tens of millions of Americans.  Except this deal excludes the rank and file and has special benefits:  there are no Government limits on how much can be put away, and many top executives have put away millions.  A lot of companies guarantee them high interest rates on the money and throw in matching contributions.
</UL>
<P>
The articles present a devastating critique of the use of deferred compensation plans to benefit highly paid executives and may spur Congressional action next year to place limits on the use of such plans.
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
For more information, contact <A HREF="mailto:ftoohey@sia.com">Frank Toohey</A>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
