<TITLE>Administration Encryption Legislation</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif">
<IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I>Administration Will Propose Encryption Legislation Justice Department Official Announces at House Judiciary Hearing</I></B></FONT><BR><BR>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Summary of Hearing</B></FONT> --  September 25, 1996
<P>
<dd><B>Jamie Gorelick, Department of Justice</B>, and <B>William Crowell, National Security Agency</B> opposed <A HREF=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c104:H.R.3011:>H.R. 3011</A> and Gorelick told the Committee the President is reviewing a proposal on U.S. encryption export policy and may release it shortly.  Gorelick said eliminating all export controls on strong encryption would undermine public safety and would cause our trading partners to raise import restrictions because " foreign countries have the same concerns we do."  <B>Gorelick and Crowell</B> told the Committee the Administration is seeking to strike a balance between the needs of a free marketplace and the concerns of law enforcement and national security officials.  Gorelick would not reveal what the proposal contains, but said it will permit stronger encryption with some kind of key recovery system.  Some of the proposal will require legislation other parts will be implemented administratively, she added.
<P>
<dd><B><A HREF="ripley.doc">Patricia Ripley</A>, Bear, Stearns & Co., Inc.; Melinda Brown, Lotus Development Corporation; Roberta Katz, Netscape Communications Corporation; and Dr. Charles Deneka, Corning, Inc.</B> strongly supported the "Security and Freedom Through Encryption Act" (SAFE), but Administration officials opposed it in a House Judiciary Committee hearing Wednesday.  The measure (H.R. 3011), introduced by Rep. Bob Goodlatte (R-VA), would relax export controls on encryption products.
<P>
<STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+1>Highlights of Testimony</FONT></STRONG>
<P>
<dd>Testifying on behalf of his bill, <B>Rep. Goodlatte</B> said "the chief roadblock to electronic commerce on the Internet is government regulation of encryption."  He criticized the Administration's proposal and accused it of using export controls to try to keep domestic computer users from obtaining strong encryption.
<P>
<dd><B>Gorelick</B> said there is a growing consensus around the world that a key recovery system is the best way to achieve the balance between encouraging the use of strong encryption to protect privacy and commerce, but in a way that preserves law enforcement's ability to protect public safety.  Under this system, she described, a key for a given encryption product would be deposited with a trusted third party or escrow agent, which could be a private party or a governmental entity.  The government would then be able, upon presenting a certification from the relevant law enforcement official, to obtain the keys from the escrow agent in order to decrypt information obtained pursuant to legal authorization, she said.  The government will not mandate a key recovery system, but she predicted "people will see it is in their best interest to promote it."
<P>
<dd><B>Gorelick</B> also said that the U.S. has been engaged in ongoing discussions with foreign governments, which are now anxious to join the U.S. in developing international standards to address this issue on a global scale.  She said the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) is meeting on September 26 - 27, 1996 "to consider draft principles that would acknowledge the need for encryption products and services that allow for lawful government access to protect public safety and national security."
<P>
<dd><B>Crowell</B> said the encryption debate has often been mischaracterized by "myths and distractions" as to the availability and quality of encryption products available.  He dispelled the argument that strong encryption is widely available when he specified "it is widely available but not widely used."  <B>Crowell</B> said key management infrastructure (KMI) is the keystone of the Administration's encryption policy reform proposal since encryption has little chance of becoming widely used until there is such an international framework in place.
<P>
<dd><B>Ripley</B> told the Committee the current export restrictions on encryption make it difficult for Bear, Stearns to transmit information securely to its overseas offices.  "But even worse, the restrictions prohibit us from providing strong, American-made encryption software to our non-US clients and hampers our efforts to communicate securely with them.  Companies based in the foreign countries where were doing business can use any encryption scheme they want.  This leaves Bear, Stearns and other U.S. securities firms at a disadvantage," she explained.
<P>
<dd><B>Ripley</B> said Bear, Stearns does not support the commercial key escrow (CKE) system for several reasons.  She said 56 bits is not sufficiently secure and that many overseas clients already use stronger products that are available abroad and can be imported into the U.S.  She said allowing third party access to the keys, even if the government is the third party, is not acceptable.  The CKE proposal is untested, unworkable, and designed to fit the needs of law enforcement and national security, not the needs of the business community and its clients, she added.
<P>
<dd><B>Deneka</B> said export licenses now granted do not provide sufficient t security.  "We need secure global connectivity with our foreign suppliers and customers, not just subsidiaries.  If we cannot offer the requisite security, then our suppliers and customers will do business with other companies that can," he said.
<P>
<dd><B>Katz</B> said encryption is essential for electronic commerce and for continued U.S. leadership in the information economy.  "The security of data flowing over interconnected networks is essential, and citizens and businesses must be able to use available technologies to protect their valuable information," she said.
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+1><B>Member Concerns</B></FONT>
<P>
<B>How does H.R. 3011 balance free market access and privacy with the needs of law enforcement officials?</B>
<P>
<dd><B>Rep. Robert Scott (D-VA)</B> asked how does H.R. 3011 balances free market access and privacy with the needs of law enforcement officials.  <B>Rep. Goodlatte</B> said SAFE would allow U.S. manufacturers of software to match foreign competition in encryption technology and would prohibit the federal government from establishing a key escrow system.
<P>
<B>Is there any other case in the history of the U.S. where valuable information is mandated to be deposited with a third party?</B>
<P>
<dd><B>Rep. Goodlatte</B> noted that the administration's proposal would mandate encryption keys be deposited with a third party and asked if this is requirement had ever been previously asked of the private sector.  <B>Gorelick</B> challenged Goodlatte's description of the Administration's policy and said no proposal requires that domestically.  The Administration is seeking to use export policy to encourage the development of a key management system that would work internationally, she said.  "We are not seeking to mandate a key management recovery system," she emphasized.
<P>
<B>Isn't the Administration stalling on relaxing export controls to force industry into accepting a key escrow system?</B>
<P>
<dd><B>Rep.  Goodlatte</B> asked if the Administration was stalling on relaxing export controls to force industry into accepting a key escrow system.  <B>Gorelick</B> said the delay is because they're trying to get international cooperation.
<P>
<B>Is the administration bypassing Congress to enact policy that harms U.S. business?</B>
<P>
<dd><B>Rep. John Conyers (D-MI)</B> accused the administration of bypassing Congress to enact policy that harms U.S. business.  <B>Gorelick</B> disagreed and said the international agreement is perhaps the most important component of the proposal.
<P>
<B>Does the Administration proposal prohibit export of strong encryption unless the government access to the key?</B>
<P>
<dd><B>Rep. John Bryant (D-TX)</B> asked if the Administration proposal prohibits the export of strong encryption unless the government has access to the key.  <B>Gorelick</B> said the plan will "encourage key recovery systems."  Bryant followed up by asking who will use the product, Gorelick said the demand will come from foreign partners and the rest of the market.
<P>
<B>Does the government's policy control demand of encryption products?</B>
<P>
<dd><B>Rep. Zoe Lofgren (D-CA)</B> said the key escrowed material has no market  the industry is being asked to produce software that won't sell.  Crowell said the government's policy will create demand.
<P>
<B>Has the Administration given your organization the opportunity to participate in the development of its proposal?</B>
<P>
<dd><B>Rep. Goodlatte</B> asked if the administration has made itself available to hear the concerns of the private industry while developing its proposal.  <B>Ripley, Katz, and Brown</B> said they had been in contact with the Administration regarding this issue but had not had the opportunity to discuss the proposal with Administration officials.
<P>
<B>Isn't it the securities industry's policy to aid law enforcement officials during investigations already?</B>
<P>
<dd><B>Rep. Goodlatte</B> asked if the securities industry already helps law enforcement officials conduct investigations and <B>Ripley</B> said it did.  The securities industry cooperates fully with the government with regard to criminal acts.  She said key escrow is not necessary because, with the appropriate court orders, the securities industry would continue to provide the government the information it needs.
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia09.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Member Issues"></A></body></HTML>
