<HEAD>
<TITLE>Securities Regulatory Reform Letters</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR><FONT  SIZE=+4><B><EM>Securities Regulatory Reform Letters</EM></B></FONT><P><TABLE BORDER=4 WIDTH=100% HEIGHT=45% CELLPADDING=2 CELLSPACING=2>
<TR><TD>Letter to<BR> <A HREF="#dingell">The Honorable John D. Dingell</A></TD><TD>Letter to<BR><A HREF="#damato"> The Honorable Alfonse M. D'Amato</A></TD><TD>Letter to<BR> <A HREF="#sarbanes">The Honorable Paul S. Sarbanes</A></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<A NAME="dingell"><HR></A>
August 29, 1996<P>
The Honorable John D. Dingell<BR>
Ranking Minority Member, Committee on Commerce<BR>
United States House of Representatives<BR>
Room 2328, Rayburn House Office Building<BR>
Washington, D.C. 20515<P>
Dear Representative Dingell:<P>
<dd>We are writing to strongly support the enactment of securities regulatory reform legislation in the last weeks of this session of Congress.<P>
<dd>Time has emerged as the only serious opponent to HR. 3005, the securities regulatory reform legislation that with your support was approved by the Commerce Committee and the full House.  This legislation, as well as its Senate counterpart, S. 1815, is an important initiative that moves regulation of our country's securities markets toward the 21st century.  However, the window of opportunity for enacting the legislation is narrowing as the end of the session draws near.  We were disappointed that the conferees on the two bills were not able to finalize legislation prior to the August recess.  We hope Congress will act quickly when it returns in September to culminate this remarkable bipartisan legislative effort.  It would be very regrettable if, after months of hard work by many in Congress, including you and your staff, this major legislation were to die in the homestretch because of unnecessary delays.  <P>
<dd>It would be particularly unfortunate if Congress missed the opportunity to enact the provision of HR 3005 that eliminates antiquated restrictions on broker-dealers by repealing Section 8(a) of the Exchange Act, and amending Section 7 to permit extensions of credit to market makers, underwriters and broker-dealers engaged in a securities business with customers.  This would remove the existing impairment on the ability of U.S. broker-dealers to obtain funds on the most favorable terms available to the market.  It would help U.S. securities firms compete with other financial institutions and foreign competitors on a more even footing.<P>
<dd>Of equal importance, the legislation provides an opportunity to provide uniform federal standards in areas such as books and records requirements and uniform exemptions for secondary market trading.  As with any nationwide industry that is comprehensively regulated at the federal level, permitting states to have additional requirements that are inconsistent with each other and with federal requirements simply adds unnecessary regulatory costs.  The legislation also contains important provisions modernizing the regulation of mutual funds and other investment companies.<P>
<dd>We are eager to work with you in the remaining weeks of the legislative session to enact final legislation that will substantially strengthen our nation's capital markets, better protect investors, and ensure that the American economy remains the most dynamic and healthy in the world.  <P>
Sincerely,<P>
Marc E. Lackritz<BR>
President<BR>
Securities Industry Association<P>
<A NAME="damato"><HR></A>
August 29, 1996<P>
The Honorable Alfonse M. D'Amato<BR>
Chairman, Committee on Banking, Housing, and Urban Affairs<BR>
United States Senate<BR>
Room 520, Hart Senate Office Building<BR>
Washington, D.C. 20510<P>
Dear Mr. Chairman:<P>
<dd>We are writing to strongly support the enactment of securities regulatory reform legislation in the last weeks of this session of Congress.<P>
<dd>Time has emerged as the only serious opponent to S. 1815, the securities regulatory reform legislation that you have so ably moved through your Committee and the full Senate.  This legislation, as well as its House counterpart, HR 3005, is an important initiative that moves regulation of our country's securities markets toward the 21st century.  However, the window of opportunity for enacting the legislation is narrowing as the end of the session draws near.  We were disappointed that the conferees on the two bills were not able to finalize legislation prior to the August recess.  We hope Congress will act quickly when it returns in September to culminate this remarkable bipartisan legislative effort.  It would be very regrettable if, after months of hard work by many in Congress, including you and your staff, this major legislation were to die in the homestretch because of unnecessary delays.<P>
<dd>It would be particularly unfortunate if Congress missed the opportunity to eliminate antiquated restrictions on broker-dealers by repealing Section 8(a) of the Exchange Act, and amending Section 7 to permit extensions of credit to market makers, underwriters and broker-dealers engaged in a securities business with customers.  This would remove the existing impairment on the ability of U.S. broker-dealers to obtain funds on the most favorable terms available to the market.  It would help U.S. securities firms compete with other financial institutions and foreign competitors on a more even footing. <P>
<dd>Equal importance, the legislation provides an opportunity to provide uniform federal standards in areas such as books and records requirements and uniform exemptions for secondary market trading.  As with any nationwide industry that is comprehensively regulated at the federal level, permitting states to have additional requirements that are inconsistent with each other and with federal requirements simply adds unnecessary regulatory costs.  The legislation also contains important provisions modernizing the regulation of mutual funds and other investment companies.<P>
<dd>We are eager to work with you in the remaining weeks of the legislative session to enact final legislation that will substantially strengthen our nation's capital markets, better protect investors, and ensure that the American economy remains the most dynamic and healthy in the world.<P>  
Sincerely,<P>
Marc E. Lackritz<BR>
President<BR>
Securities Industry Association
<A NAME="sarbanes"><HR></A>
August 29, 1996<P>
The Honorable Paul S. Sarbanes<BR>
Ranking Minority Member, Committee on Banking, Housing, and Urban Affairs<BR>
United States Senate<BR>
Room 309, Hart Senate Office Building<BR>
Washington, D.C. 20510<P>
Dear Senator Sarbanes:<P>
<dd>We are writing to strongly support the enactment of securities regulatory reform legislation in the last weeks of this session of Congress.<P>
<dd>Time has emerged as the only serious opponent to S. 1815, the securities regulatory reform legislation that with your support was approved by the Senate Banking Committee and the full Senate.  This legislation, as well as its House counterpart, HR 3005, is an important initiative that moves regulation of our country's securities markets toward the 21st century.  However, the window of opportunity for enacting the legislation is narrowing as the end of the session draws near.  We were disappointed that the conferees on the two bills were not able to finalize legislation prior to the August recess.  We hope Congress will act quickly when it returns in September to culminate this remarkable bipartisan legislative effort.  It would be very regrettable if, after months of hard work by many in Congress, including you and your staff, this major legislation were to die in the homestretch because of unnecessary delays.<P>
<dd>It would be particularly unfortunate if Congress missed the opportunity to eliminate antiquated restrictions on broker-dealers by repealing Section 8(a) of the Exchange Act, and amending Section 7 to permit extensions of credit to market makers, underwriters and broker-dealers engaged in a securities business with customers.  This would remove the existing impairment on the ability of U.S. broker-dealers to obtain funds on the most favorable terms available to the market.  It would help U.S. securities firms compete with other financial institutions and foreign competitors on a more even footing. <P>
<dd>Of equal importance, the legislation provides an opportunity to provide uniform federal standards in areas such as books and records requirements and uniform exemptions for secondary market trading.  As with any nationwide industry that is comprehensively regulated at the federal level, permitting states to have additional requirements that are inconsistent with each other and with federal requirements simply adds unnecessary regulatory costs.  The legislation also contains important provisions modernizing the regulation of mutual funds and other investment companies.<P>
<dd>We are eager to work with you in the remaining weeks of the legislative session to enact final legislation that will substantially strengthen our nation's capital markets, better protect investors, and ensure that the American economy remains the most dynamic and healthy in the world.<P>  
Sincerely,<P>
Marc E. Lackritz<BR>
President<BR>
Securities Industry Association<P>
<HR>
