<TITLE>HR 3005</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+4><B><EM>SIA Member Support Needed on Securities Legislation</EM></B></FONT></CENTER><HR>
A  House and Senate conference committee will resume negotiations on September 3 on legislation to reform regulation of our country's securities markets (H.R. 3005).  If a conferee (listed below) is from your state, please contact that legislator before September 3, using the <A HREF="#sample">sample letter shown below</A> or your own, to let him or her know that our industry supports the following goals:<P>
<UL>
<LI>Eliminate antiquated credit-margin restrictions on broker-dealers.<P>
<LI>Require states to have uniform standards for broker-dealer books and records (as set by the SEC and the NASD).<P>
<LI>Broaden the SEC's exemptive authority.<P>
<LI>Eliminate redundant and inconsistent state regulatory requirements for securities firm mutual fund prospectuses.
</UL>
<P>
<B>Your input is essential to the passage of this vital piece of legislation.</B><P>
<CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=100%>
<TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><B>House Conferees</B><P></TD><TD VALIGN="TOP"><B>Senate Conferees</B><P></TD></TR>
<TR><TD VALIGN="TOP">Rep. Thomas Bliley (R-VA)<BR>		
Rep. Jack Fields (R-TX)	<BR>
Rep. Michael Oxley (R-OH)<BR>		
Rep. Dan Schaefer (R-CO)<BR>
Rep. W.J. (Billy) Tauzin (R-LA)<BR>		
Rep. Rick White (R-WA)<BR>
Rep. Dan Frisa (R-NY)<BR>
Rep. Nathan Deal (R-GA)<BR>
Rep. John Dingell (D-MI)<BR>
Rep. Edward Markey (D-MA)<BR>
Rep. Rick Boucher (D-VA)<BR>
Rep. Bart Gordon (D-TN)<BR>
Rep. Elizabeth Furse (D-OR)<BR>
Rep. Ron Klink (D-PA)<BR>
</TD><TD VALIGN=" TOP">Sen. Alfonse D'Amato (R-NY)<BR>
Sen. Phil Gramm (R-TX)<BR>
Sen. Robert Bennett (R-UT)<BR>
Sen. Paul Sarbanes (D-MD)<BR>
Sen. Christopher Dod (D-CT)<P></TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER><P>
<A NAME="sample"><HR></A>
<CENTER><B>Sample Letter</B></CENTER>
<P><P>
The Honorable _______________<BR>
United States Senate<BR>
Washington, DC  20515<P>
or
<P>
The Honorable ______________<BR>	
U. S. House of Representatives	<BR>
Washington, DC  20515<P>			
Dear [Insert member of Congress here] :<P>
The Senate and House have passed separate versions of bipartisan legislation to move regulation of our country's securities markets toward the 21st century.  The conferees are now working to resolve their differences. <P>
I am writing to seek your help in urging the conferees to approve legislation that truly modernizes important aspects of U.S. securities regulation.  If the final bill embodies each of the points outlined below, I believe it will eliminate unnecessary regulation, improve the competitiveness of the United States in global markets, and reduce the cost of raising capital without compromising important investor protections.  This would represent a major legislative achievement for the 104th Congress.<P>
Our industry supports the following goals:<P>
<UL>
<LI>Eliminate antiquated restrictions on broker-dealers by repealing Section 8(a) of the Exchange Act, and amending Section 7 to permit extensions of credit to market makers, underwriters and broker-dealers engaged in a securities business with customers.  This would remove the existing impairment on the ability of U.S. broker-dealers to obtain funds on the most favorable terms available to the market.  It would help U.S. securities firms compete with foreign competitors and other financial institutions on a more even footing.<P>
<LI>Eliminate the overlap between state and federal regulation of investment advisers by giving the SEC exclusive jurisdiction over larger advisers and providing exclusive state jurisdiction over smaller advisers.  Even the SEC acknowledges that the current regulatory structure gives it greater regulatory responsibility than it has the resources to perform.  We support divesting some of that authority to the states.  The result will be a regulatory structure that provides better protection for investors, while reducing unnecessary regulatory duplication and burdens on securities firms that perform advisory services.<P>
<LI>Provide uniform standards for broker-dealer financial responsibility requirements.  The SEC and the NASD already have comprehensive nationwide requirements relating to books and records, capital standards and all other aspects of broker-dealers' financial responsibility.  As with any nationwide industry that is comprehensively regulated at the federal level, permitting states to have additional requirements that are inconsistent with each other and with federal requirements simply adds unnecessary regulatory costs.  This will be particularly important to securities firms with offices in many states.<P>
<LI>Create uniform exemptions for secondary market trading.  There is a nationwide consensus, among both federal and state regulators and lawmakers, that secondary market transactions of major corporate issuers should be exempt from registration requirements as long as appropriate information about the issuer is publicly available.  Unfortunately, technical differences among state exemptions impair the liquidity of many securities.  This hurts investors, who are forced to trade securities at inferior prices, as well as broker-dealers who wish to make markets in those securities.<P>
<LI>Broaden the SEC's exemptive authority so that it can more effectively address statutory requirements that have outlived their usefulness and ensure that the letter of the law is consistent with the spirit of the law.<P>
<LI>Enable securities firms' mutual funds to produce readable prospectuses by eliminating redundant and inconsistent state regulatory requirements.<P>
<LI>Require meaningful coordination among examination authorities in conducting routine examinations.  The SEC and self-regulatory organizations agreed last fall to try to coordinate better.  To ensure that the agreement is followed, it should be enacted into law, accompanied by reasonable sanctions for any self-regulatory organization that fails to coordinate its routine examinations with other regulators.  This provision would not in any way limit the ability of any regulator to conduct an examination for cause.  It will be extremely helpful to the many securities firms that belong to more than one self-regulatory organization.
</UL>
<P>
These key provisions, taken together, will substantially strengthen our nation's capital markets, better protect investors and ensure that the American economy remains the most dynamic and healthy in the world.  Should you have any questions, please do not hesitate to call me.<P> 
Sincerely,<P>
<HR>
Please contact <A HREF="mailto:smorganom">Suzanne Morgan</A> if you have any questions or require more information on the above legislation.
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
