<HEAD>
<TITLE> MEL China Statement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3><B>Oral Statement of Marc E. Lackritz <BR>Before House Committee on Banking and Financial Services</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=+3><I>The Status of China's Capital Markets and Its<BR>Implications for the United States</I><P></B></FONT></CENTER><HR>
<P>
<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
<dd>Mr. Chairman and members of the Committee, I am Marc Lackritz, president of the Securities Industry Association.  I appreciate the opportunity to present SIA's views on recent developments in China's capital markets and the prospects for broad based financial market reform.  We are eager to share with you our assessment of the implications of continued Chinese economic growth for the United States.  
<P>
<dd>The Administration, Congress, and this committee in particular, have worked diligently to open foreign markets and help the U.S. financial services sector capitalize on new business opportunities.  I would like to express my appreciation to you for your hard work.  These new markets have helped the U.S. economy maintain steady growth, and increased employment, and so access to foreign markets is a crucial component of U.S. economic growth.  China  a potential economic giant  is one of the most important of these foreign markets.
<P>
<dd>These hearings closely follow actions taken by the President and the House to extend mostfavored-nation trading status to China.  We thank you, Mr. Chairman, for your leadership on MFN.  We realize that many legitimate trade issues between the U.S. and China remain.  The U.S. securities industry continues to face serious problems entering and doing business in China.  However, we are convinced that the extension of MFN status is in America's and China's best interests, and will help pave the way for further needed reform of China's economic and political institutions.  Indeed, revoking MFN would not have advanced any U.S. policy goals, but it would have damaged our economy and jeopardized 200,000 American jobs.
<P>
<dd>Mr. Chairman, I want to stress three points.  First, the enormous opportunity that China presents to the U.S.; second, the development of Chinas capital markets; and third, critical reforms China must make to its capital markets in order to realize its full economic potential.
<P>
1.	<B>Chinas Growing Economy Creates Opportunity for the U.S.</B>
<P>
<dd>China, with over 1.2 billion people and another 300 million expected in the next decade, is the world's most populous country.  China also has exhibited one of the world's fastest economic growth rates  with real GDP approaching 10% per annum during the past eighteen years.  Such incredible growth rates imply that Chinas economy will double about once every seven years.
<P>
<dd>With a level playing field between the U.S. and its international competitors, the potential opportunities for U.S. exporters in China are enormous.    Demand for consumer goods will increase as incomes of Chinese consumers expand.  Consumer items Americans take for granted  such as vacuum cleaners, dishwashers and microwave ovens  reach only 5% of Chinese consumers.
<P>
<dd>Financing China's infrastructure is also a vast opportunity.  Over the next decade analysts predict China will invest over $1 trillion in transportation and communications infrastructure improvements and energyrelated capital equipment.  Moreover, China plans to increase its electricitygenerating capacity by more than 50% by the year 2000  the equivalent of building a power system as big as that of the Netherlands during each of the next five years.  However, China's private and public sectors alone cannot mobilize the massive financial resources which are necessary for growth.  Much of the infrastructure development will be funded through foreign sources, and this opportunity has generated substantial interest by the U.S. securities industry and its client base.
<P>
2.	<B>Financial Market Developments in China</B>
<P>
<dd>Over the last few years China has made impressive reforms to its capital markets.  For example, since 1990, the Shanghai and Shenzen stock exchanges have been established.  At the end of May 1996, market capitalization stood at about $55 billion  over 25 times the $2 billion from 1991.  The trading value of Chinese stocks rose from $820 million in 1991 to near $50 billion in 1995.  When measured by these criteria, it has only taken China four short years to rank in the middletier of emerging markets.
<P>
<dd>Customers of U.S. securities firms are optimistic about China's prospects and have eagerly purchased Chinese stocks.  Two classes of shares are listed on the Chinese stock exchanges.  A shares are available only to Chinese citizens; and B shares sold only to foreign investors.  Although investors were originally quite interested in B shares, the stocks have turnedout to be illiquid.  As a result, foreign investors have turned to Chinese shares listed in New York or Hong Kong .  
<P>
<dd>China has already become an active participant in international markets in an effort to raise debt and equity capital for various enterprises.  From 1991 through the first half of 1995, China raised nearly $14 billion with international debt and equity financings, the fifth largest total among emerging markets.  
<P>
<P>
3.	<B>Chinese Financial Market Reform: Next Steps</B>
<P>
<dd>Our industry understands the importance of the Chinese market and has consistently worked to reduce trade barriers and to achieve greater market access.  Despite difficulties entering and operating in China, many U.S. securities firms have established offices in China and participate in China's international securities offerings.
<P>
<dd>Several key elements must be in place to ensure growth of China's capital markets.  Among these are the convertibility of China's currency, promulgation of transparent regulations and laws to protect investors from fraud and/or market manipulation, expanding the local investor base, and expanding foreign access.
<P>
<I>Currency Convertibility</I>
<dd>Currency convertibility is critical to attracting increased direct and portfolio investment flows.  Until this reform is made, and an efficient foreign exchange market is developed, the Chinese market will be unnecessarily hampered.
<P>
<I>Promoting Regulation and Transparency</I>
<dd>Efficient capital markets will only develop if a legal framework is in place to assure all participants have access to material information and play by fair rules.  Rulemaking notices should be published in a manner which allows sufficient opportunity for comment by interested parties, whether domestic or foreign.  Moreover, a system of corporate law, which covers such elements as the organization of stock companies, the issuance of securities, and the rights of shareholders, offers predictability and stability, the foundation of efficient capital markets.
<P>
<I>Expanding the Local Investor Base</I>
<dd>Developing a local institutional and retail investor base is critical if China is to become a major capital market.  Clearly, the development of a regulatory system which is perceived as fair to all investors will be a central element in encouraging investors to invest their savings in the debt and equity markets.  Collective investment vehicles, such as mutual funds, offer investors professional management, which securities firms believe would be a useful tool in expanding the investors presence in the market.
<P>
<I>Liberalizing Foreign Access</I>
<dd>China has taken slow and uneven steps to open its capital markets.  As China has begun to turn to the securities markets to meet its capital needs, U.S. firms have helped channel both foreign and domestic savings to these markets.  U.S. firms have brought modern financing techniques, state of the art technology, and innovative products to the emerging markets, providing the capital and expertise needed to finance infrastructure projects.  Still, U.S. firms face discriminatory treatment in both gaining market access to China and being accorded national treatment once established.
<P>
<B>Conclusion</B>
<P>
<dd>Despite the problems, the U.S. securities industry can contribute substantially to the development of China's financial markets so that Chinese firms can raise lowcost capital and support job creation.  And as China becomes wealthier it can support a higher level of U.S. exports.  Given the enormous opportunities that China presents for the U.S., it is imperative that we work together to address the risks that lie ahead.  Many such risks are easy to identify, but are difficult to abate.
<P>
<dd>It is the "triple helix" of the government, the Communist party, and business that poses perhaps the largest risk.  These three interests are closely intertwined: the party controls the government; the government creates, owns, and controls business; and business produces leadership for the party and government.  This is hardly the "frontier mentality" or the truly free markets that have provided the foundation for our own unique growth and prosperity.
<P>
<dd>And so the risks in China are greatjust as the opportunity and potential are.  Given our industry's proficiency and expertise in balancing risk and reward, and given that the financial markets are the nerve center of the economy, the fate of the U.S. securities industry in China may well hold the key to whether the enormous economic potential in China will ultimately be unlocked.  
<P>
<dd>Thank you very much.
<P>
<HR>
If you have any questions or need more information, contact <A HREF="mailto:dstrongin@sia.com">David Strongin </A> or <A HREF="mailto:khofeditz@sia.com">Kristin Hofeditz</A>.
Also available, for your review, is the <A HREF="china.doc">written statement</A> of Marc Lackritz before the House Committee on Banking and Financial Services.
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia09.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="siahome.gif" ALT="Homepage"></A>
</BODY>
</HTML>
