</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Federal Income Tax Statement of Summary</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3><B>Statement of the Securities Industry Association Before the Committee on Ways and Means of the House of Representatives</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=+2>Submitted for the Record of the Hearing on the Impact on International Competitiveness of Replacing the Federal Income Tax</B></FONT></CENTER><HR>
<P>
<B>Summary of Statement:</B>
<P>
<dd>During the last decade, the securities industry has been transformed from a largely domestic-oriented industry to an industry in which U.S. and international financial institutions compete against each other in the principal capital markets around the world.  The globalization of the securities industry has not been paralleled by comparable changes in the federal income tax structure, however.  As a result, the current federal income tax system has a strong structural bias against the international operations of U.S.-domiciled securities companies.  To preserve the United States international competitiveness in financial services, the taxation of business income earned abroad needs significant reform.
<P>
<dd>Against this background, the <A HREF="fedinc.doc"> full testimony</A> discusses the consumption-tax alternatives being considered by the Committee to replace the existing federal income tax structure.  The testimony briefly assesses the impact of those proposals for fundamental tax reform, both on a general level and as they specifically relate to the U.S.-based securities industry.  The testimony, however, concludes that the proposals provide only a sketchy framework for how U.S.-based securities firms would be taxed in the increasingly global economy.  Accordingly, the testimony offers two structural principles that should be part of any fundamental tax reform package in order to ensure that the U.S.-based securities industry is taxed fairly and in a fashion that promotes, rather than inhibits, the competitiveness of that industry.
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
If you have any questions or need more information, contact <A HREF="mailto:ftoohey@sia.com">Frank Toohey</A> or <A HREF="mailto:sjudge@sia.com">Steve Judge</A>.
