<HTML>
<TITLE>Independent Contractor Testimony Summary</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+4><B><EM>Summary of Contents and Recommendations</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=+3>Written Testimony of the Securities Industry Association<BR>Before Subcommittee on Oversight<BR>Committee on Ways and Means<BR>United States House of Representatives </EM><P></B></FONT></CENTER><HR>
<dd>We respectfully urge Congress to clarify that actions undertaken by a business to satisfy a "duty to supervise" required by law or regulation in a regulated industry is not determinative of either employment or independent contractor status.<P>
<dd>In assessing worker classification, the "20 factor" common law test fails to distinguish between the "right to control" and the "duty to supervise."  Where a service recipient has the "right to control" when, where, and how a service is provided, the service provider is properly classified as an employee.  This situation must be distinguished in the regulated industry context.<P>
<dd>In the securities industry, as in other regulated industries, government regulatory agencies and self-regulatory bodies impose upon the securities firms a "duty to supervise" the "registered representatives" to ensure that regulatory requirements are satisfied.  Behavioral controls adopted pursuant to the regulations evidence the "duty to supervise," no a "right to control."  The compliance measures required by the regulations should not be indicative of either employee or independent contractor status.<P>
<dd>Case law supports the view that compliance with government mandates is not indicative of "control."<P>
<UL>
<LH></LH>
<LI>"Courts have consistently held that regulation imposed by government authorities does not evidence employer control."  Yellow Taxi Cab Co. v. NLRB, 721 f.2d 366, 374 (D.C. Cir. 1983).<P>
<LI>"[R]estrictions upon a worker's manner and means of performance that spring from government regulation (rather than company initiatives) do not necessarily support a conclusion of employment status.  [Citation omited.]  Indeed, employer efforts to ensure the worker's compliance with government regulations, even when those efforts restrict the manner and means of performance, do not weigh in favor of employee status."  North American Van Lines, Inc. v. NLRB, 869 F.2d 596, 599 (D.C. Cir 1989).<P>
<LI>"Government regulations constitute supervision not by the employer but by the state ... That government regulation has made supervision or control by teh lessor unnecessary is not the equivalent of the presence of actual supervision or control."  Local 777, Democratic Union Org. Comm., Seafarers Int'l Union v. NLRB, 603 F.2d 862, 875-76 (D.C. Cir. 1978). 
</UL>
<P>
<dd>Current law must be clarified to eliminate the consideration of compliance with government regulations when determining worker classification.  Such clarification could be accomplished either by eliminating the 20 factor test in favor of objective standards, such as those contained in the legislative proposals pending in the House, or by clarifying legislatively the manner in which the common law control test should be administered by the Internal Revenue Service. <P>
<HR>
Also available for your information is the <A HREF="sia09b.htm"> full text of SIA's testimony</A>.   If you have any questions or need more information, contact <A HREF="mailto:ftoohey@sia.com">Frank Toohey</A>.
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia09.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="siahome.gif" ALT="Homepage"></A>
</BODY>
</HTML>
