<TITLE>Hearing Summary-Encryption Software</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B><I>Senate Commerce Subcommittee Begins Series of Hearing on Export Control Relief for U.S. Encryption Software</I></B></FONT><BR><BR>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Summary of Hearing</B></FONT> --  June 13, 1996<P>
<dd>Kenneth Dam, National Research Council; Michael Zisman, Lotus; Jim 
Barkesdale, Netscape Communications; Jim Bidzos, RSA Data Security; 
Tim Krauskopf, Spyglass Inc.; and other representatives from the U.S. 
 information technology industry testified in strong support of the 
"Promotion of Commerce On-Line in the Digital Era Act of 1996" (S. 
1726).  SIA President Marc E. Lackritz also expressed the securities 
industry's support for the measure in a written statement submitted 
for the record.  All witnesses opposed the Clinton administration's 
proposed "commercial key escrow" system, stating that it would be 
costly and unworkable.  These statements were made at a Subcommittee 
on Science, Space and Technology of the Senate Commerce Committee 
hearing on export controls of encryption technology June 12.<P>
<dd>The "Promotion of Commerce On-Line in the Digital Era Act of 1996," 
 introduced by Subcommittee Chairman Conrad Burns (R-MT), would repeal 
 restrictions on the export of encryption technology to encourage the 
 international growth of electronic commerce.  The U.S. currently 
 prohibits the unlicensed export of encryption products with greater 
 than 40-bit key lengths.  S. 1726 would permit the general-license 
 export of publicly available encryption programs, transfer the 
 authority to regulate encryption technology exports from the State 
 Department to the Commerce Department, and prohibit the federal 
 government from imposing a key escrow system on the domestic market.<P>
<dd>The Clinton administration has proposed a "Commercial Key Escrow" 
 (CKE) system that would permit U.S. companies to export 64-bit 
 technology, but would require a copy of the key to be kept with a third 
 party or escrow agent.  The escrow agent would most likely be a bank or 
 encryption company and would only release the key under two 
 circumstances: 1) to the owner if the key had been lost and it was 
 needed to decrypt documents; or, 2) to law enforcement official if they 
 have the appropriate warrants necessary to obtain data which has been 
 encrypted with the escrowed key.<P>
<dd>The administration is expected to release a plan providing interim 
 relief to U.S. companies from export restrictions. It is unclear what 
 the plan will entail, but it will likely include a key escrow 
 requirement.  The administration has strong concerns over foreign 
 terrorists using the strong encryption products and believes law 
enforcement agency's concerns would be addressed with a key escrow 
system. <P>
<STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+1>Highlights of Testimony</FONT></STRONG><P>
<dd> Lackritz asserted S. 1726 addresses the problems with current law 
in a balanced and measured fashion.  Information security 
practitioners at securities firms are currently spending a inordinate 
amount of time working around the government's outdated encryption 
export policies, he said.  "By allowing securities firms to provide 
secure communications with clients and partners abroad, S. 1726 will 
foster growth in the capital markets, enhance the global competitive 
position of U.S. securities firms, and lead to a new era of electronic 
commerce," Lackritz said. <P>
<dd>Lackritz told the Subcommittee he opposes the CKE system for 
several reasons.  First, he said, 64-bit encryption is not 
competitive, though an improvement over the current 40-bit limit.  
 Lackritz told the subcommittee that well-funded attackers could break 
64-bit encryption easily.  In addition, he said, many overseas clients 
of securities firms are already using stronger products that are 
available abroad and can be imported into the U.S.  Those clients would have no incentive to move to a 64-bit key that would provide 
less protection than is currently available through their foreign 
suppliers, Lackritz said. <P>
<dd>Lackritz said the securities industry will not support allowing 
third party access to the keys _ even if the government is the third 
party.  "No securities firm would be comfortable giving any third 
party, no matter how trustworthy, the means to access all of its 
confidential customer data and other proprietary information," he 
testified.<P>
<dd>Finally, Lackritz said he could not support the CKE proposal 
because it was designed to fit the needs of law enforcement and 
national security, not the needs of the business community and our 
customers.  "While we recognize the need for a strong national defense 
and vigorous law enforcement efforts, we do not believe that 
restricting critical technology is the way to solve those problems," 
he said.<P>
<dd>Kenneth Dam, chairman of the Committee to Study National Cryptology 
Policy, said that the wider use of cryptology will support personal 
privacy, U.S. business, law enforcement, and national security 
interests, even though information-gathering for law enforcement and 
national security purposes may become more difficult.  Federal policies 
should promote, rather than discourage, the use of cryptology by 
relaxing export controls on encryption, Dam said.<P>
<dd>Dam testified that while escrowed encryption is still an technology 
with its own potential risks and many unresolved issues.  Rather than 
aggressively promoting escrowed encryption, he said, the government 
should explore escrowed encryption for the government's own internal 
uses as a way of gaining working experience with this technology.  
Even if commercial utility is demonstrated, he said, the adoption of 
escrowed encryption or any other standard by the commercial sector 
should be voluntary and based on business needs, not government 
pressure.<P>
<dd>Zisman, Barkesdale, Bidzos, and Krauskopf told the subcommittee 
that export relief is necessary to enable U.S. software companies to 
remain competitive internationally, provide users worldwide with the 
tools to protect their electronic information, and continue leading 
the development of the global information infrastructure.<P>
<HR> Available for your review is the  full<A HREF="encrypt.doc">  testimony</A> given by Marc Lackritz before the Senate Subcommittee on Science, Space and Technology.   For more information, contact:  <A HREF="mailto:lcostantino@sia.com">Lou Costantino</A>.      
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia09.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Member Issues"></A></body></HTML>
