<TITLE>MFN Trade Status for China</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3><B><EM>Senators Support Renewal of Most-Favored-Nation<BR> Trade
Status For China in Hearing Before <BR>
Senate Finance Committee<P>
Foreign Relations Committee
Remains Divided</EM><P></B></FONT></CENTER><HR><P>
SUMMARY OF HEARING<P>
<dd>Senate Finance Committee members stood united in favor of renewal of MFN trading status for China and called for a "policy of engagement" with China.  Chairman Bill Roth (R-DE), Ranking Minority Member Daniel Patrick Moynihan (D-NY), and Senator John Chafee (R-RI) stated strongly that the yearly debate on MFN strains U.S.-China relations, and called for an end to the "politicization of the process."  As a first step, they announced they are going to introduce legislation to change the term "MFN" to "normal trade relations," which they said is its true meaning.  MFN is not preferential status as the name might imply; indeed, there are only five countries in the world to which the U.S. does not afford MFN.
<dd>The hearing marked a sea-change in U.S. relations with China.  Many members called this year's vote on MFN renewal a choice between a "policy of engagement versus a policy of isolation."  Senator Max Baucus (D-MT) called the annual debate on MFN damaging.  He remarked that even jailed Chinese dissidents believe the U.S. should renew MFN because without it, there is no way to address problems concerning human rights, nuclear proliferation, and the environment.  Senator Frank Murkowski (R-AK) supported unconditional MFN renewal this year and permanent renewal next year.  He said it was an appropriate course of action because China is seeking membership to the World Trade Organization and all WTO members are required to extend permanent MFN to each other.  China is ineligible for full membership until the U.S. acts.<P>
<dd>Acting U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky testified that trade plays an enormous role in the U.S.-China relationship, and that U.S. interests are best promoted by maintaining MFN.  Moreover, she said the only way China will be integrated into the international community is through cooperation.  If we remain engaged with China we will effect change.<P>
<dd>Ambassador Winston Lord, Assistant Secretary for East Asia and the Pacific, for the Department of State, reiterated a statement by President Clinton that "MFN renewal is not a referendum on all China's policies, nor is it an endorsement of any specific action or behavior."  He said MFN is the normal commercial foundation upon which all but a handful of our international trading partners rest.  Withdrawal of MFN is not the best way to deal with problems we have with China; there are more appropriate policy tools available that can be targeted to achieve maximum effectiveness.<P>
<dd>At a hearing later in the day before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, Chairman Jesse Helms (R-NC) countered "there are many reasons to deny MFN treatment to China."  He said he was "astonished at President Clinton's decision to renew MFN," particularly in light of nuclear proliferation concerns.  Senators Russ Feingold (D-WI) and Olympia Snowe (R-ME) opposed MFN, Senators Thomas (R-WY), Feinstein (D-CA) and Robb (D-VA) acknowledged problems with China, but supported MFN renewal, and Senator Joe Biden (D-DE) remained undecided.<P>
For more information, contact <A HREF="mailto:khofeditz@sia.com">Kristin Hofeditz</A>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia09.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="siahome.gif" ALT="Homepage"></A>
</BODY>
</HTML>.
