<TITLE>Iran Sanctions Legislation</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+4><B><EM>House Subcommittee Hearing on Iran Sanctions Legislation</EM><P></B></FONT></CENTER><HR><P>
<dd>The House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Trade held a hearing on<A HREF="ftp://ftp.loc.gov/pub/thomas/c104/h3107.ih.txt"> H.R. 3107</A>, the "Iran Oil Sanctions Act of 1996."  C. David Welch, Acting Assistant Secretary of State for Near Eastern Affairs and Jennifer Hillman, General Counsel, Office of the U.S. Trade Representative testified before the subcommittee.<P>
<dd>Welch and Hillman supported legislation, but said H.R. 3107 does not achieve its stated goal to maximize pressure on Iran and Libya, and it would harm U.S. businesses.  They urged congress to redraft the bill to focus on Iran's oil and gas sector; and to give the president more flexibility with respect to the sanctions.  Additionally, the bill should strengthen enforcement of existing sanctions on trade with Libya.  Both witnesses and Subcommittee Chairman Phil Crane (R-IL) questioned the effectiveness of unilateral sanctions, and suggested this legislation could cause disputes between the U.S. and its trading partners.  Indeed, if the bill's sanctions were imposed, the U.S. would risk challenges by the WTO.<P>
<dd>The "Iran Oil Sanctions Act" was introduced by Rep. Benjamin Gilman (R-NY) on March 19, 1996.  The purpose of the bill is to combat terrorism by imposing sanctions on any person who makes an investment that contributes to the development of Iran's or Libya's petroleum sector.  The Senate passed similar legislation on December 21, 1995 but some of the more troublesome provisions were dropped prior to passage.  Hillman said the administration would prefer that the House adopt the Senate version of the bill. <P>
<dd>The securities industry is most concerned about the following provisions in H.R. 3107: 1) it would make the financing of prohibited investments in Iran or Libya a sanctionable activity; and 2) it would prohibit U.S. financial institutions from extending credit in excess of $10 million in a twelve month period to any sanctioned entity.  The Senate version is less draconian than H.R. 3107, for example, it does not include the financing of investment under the definition of investment in the bill.  House Banking Committee Chairman Jim Leach (R-IO) wrote a letter to Rep. Gilman and Speaker Gingrich asking for relief in those two areas and is hopeful his request will be accommodated prior to the mark up in the Ways and Means Committee. <P>
<dd>The House Ways and Means Committee is expected to mark up H.R. 3107 on Thursday, May 30, 1996.  Please contact <A HREF="mailto:khofeditz@sia.com">Kristin Hofeditz</A> (202-296-9410) or <A HREF="mailto:dstrongin@sia.com">David Strongin</A> (212-618-0513) if you have any questions about the hearing, or if you need copies of the testimony.
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia09.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="siahome.gif" ALT="Homepage"></A>
