<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>House Subcommittees Examine Federal and State Preparedness for Year 2000</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<body background="sia3abac.gif">
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT  SIZE=+3>House Subcommittees Examine Federal and State Preparedness for Year 2000 Conversion and Challenges for Personal Computer Users</FONT></B></CENTER>
<BR><BR>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+3><B>September 10, 1996</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<CENTER><B><FONT  SIZE=+2>Summary of Hearing</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<dd>The Technology Subcommittee of the House Committee on Science and the Subcommittee on Government Management, Information and Technology of the House Government Reform and Oversight Committee held a joint hearing September 10 that focused on the various levels of preparedness by federal, state, and local governments for the Year 2000 computer conversion.  The Subcommittees also tried to determine the impact of the conversion on personal computers because they are an important link in networks and other interconnected systems.
<P>
<dd>Four witnesses testified at the hearing.  <B>Harris Miller, President of the Information Technology Association of America (ITAA); Daniel Houlihan, President-elect of the National Association of State Information Resource Executives (NASIRE); Larry Olson, Deputy Secretary for Information Technology, Commonwealth of Pennsylvania; and Sally Katzen, Administrator of the Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs at the Office of Management and Budget (OMB).  Microsoft Corporation</B> submitted written testimony concerning the impact of the Year 2000 on personal computer software.
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+2><CENTER><B>Highlights of Testimony</B></CENTER></FONT>
<P>
<dd><B>Miller</B> informed the subcommittees that the systems offered by the largest PC hardware and software vendors can process data well into the next century.  The <B>Microsoft</B> testimony included similar assurances.  A problem will develop, however, when Year 2000 compliant PC systems connect via the Internet or dedicated networks with computers which have not been converted.  He emphasized the interdependence of modern computer systems and said, "Those people that believe this is a situation only for mainframes are mistaken.  It is important to remember that all computing takes place in a larger context."
<P>
<dd><B>Miller</B> also described ITAA's efforts to create a certification program to help assure users that products are Year 2000 compliant.  He said the certification process will include an independent review board to examine vendor products and services, as well as a survey that will require supporting documentation from each vendor.
<P>
<dd><B>Houlihan</B> told the subcommittees that NASIRE has taken a leading role in educating state government officials about the importance of the Year 2000 conversion issue.  The Association has also offered planning assistance and has surveyed its membership to gauge each state's readiness for the date change.  The survey's findings were generally optimistic but Houlihan expressed tremendous concern about the ability of states to handle the financial burden of conversion.  Furthermore, he told the subcommittees that he hoped the federal government would outline its plan for the Year 2000 conversion soon, so that states can assess the scope fo their projects accordingly.  
<P>
<dd><B>Olson</B> outlined Pennsylvania's project plan.  The key elements of Pennsylvania's response include: the administration's public acknowledgment of the Year 2000 conversion as a top priority issue; outreach efforts to inform businesses, local governments, and citizens; and strong project management.  <B>Olson</B> echoed <B>Houlihan's</B> concerns on the financial burden and time constraints that the states face.
<P>
<dd><B>Katzen</B> told the subcommittees that OMB is committed to raising awareness of the Year 2000 issue and that they hope to facilitate planning within the federal agencies.  OMB has already brought the issue to the attention of the President's Management Council and the newly created Chief Information Officer's Council (CIOC).  The CIOC consists of the officers who are responsible for all information issues, including the Year 2000.  She also mentioned that OMB is well situated to spread information between agencies through a recently- created inter-agency working group.  The group is developing a list of products used by Federal agencies along with information about whether they will work through the Year 2000 and creating a list of best practices for addressing the problem.  <B>Katzen</B> agreed with the other witnesses that the Federal government should provide leadership and heighten awareness for both state governments and the private sector.
<P>
<dd><B>Katzen</B> said that OMB has asked the agencies to evaluate their systems now so they can prepare for the money and time that will be necessary to make the date conversion.  She said that funding for the Year 2000 fixes will probably be reprogrammed from existing funds.  Congress has requested that the agencies report this information by November 1, 1996 when they submit their budgets to OMB.  <B>Katzen</B> was concerned that this date may be premature and suggested a February 1 deadline to coincide with the President's budget submission to Congress.  <B>Katzen</B> predicted the total cost for the Federal agencies would be less than the $30 billion figure given by the Gartner Group in April.  
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+2><CENTER><B>Member Concerns</B></CENTER></FONT>
<P>
<B>Do you see a role for the Federal government in managing the Year 2000 conversion?</B>
<P>
<dd><B>Subcommittee Chairwoman Constance Morella (R-MD)</B> asked what role would be appropriate for the federal government in dealing with Year 2000 issues.  <B>Olson</B> responded that the federal government can provide leadership and awareness of the date conversion issue.  <B>Miller</B> responded that Federal agencies with regulatory responsibilities could take the initiative to educate corporate and industry leaders on the importance of preparation for the Year 2000.
<P>
<B>How do you perceive the Federal government's modernization efforts?</B>
<P>
<dd><B>Subcommittee Chairman Steve Horn (R-CA)</B> asked the witnesses to assess the government's handling of the date conversion process.  After attending several inter-agency meetings on Year 2000 issues, <B>Miller</B> said he believes that most federal agencies are still analyzing the situation, so it is premature to make and assessment.  <B>Houlihan</B> complained that federal agencies are not providing enough information to the states.  He added that it is important for a dialogue to take place between the state and federal agencies to ensure that there is a clear understanding of their respective responsibilities.  <B>Olson</B> said Pennsylvania is not waiting for the federal government to act, but he feared that federal agencies might ask states to change their Year 2000 plans after they are already underway.
<P>
<B>Has the President made the Year 2000 date conversion a top priority for his Administration?</B>
<P>
<dd><B>Horn</B> asked <B>Katzen</B> if the President has made conversion a top priority and if someone from each agency was responsible for managing this issue.  <B>Katzen</B> said that Year 2000 has been on the agenda at several meetings of the President's Management Council.  In addition, the agencies have hired a Chief Information Officer who will manage all information issues, including the Year 2000 conversion.  She noted that although the agencies are at different stages in preparing for the Year 2000 conversion, they all understand that they must develop and abide by a plan in order to fulfill their mission.
<P>
<B>What is the effect of the Year 2000 problem on the average citizen?</B>
<P>
<dd><B>Horn</B> asked the panel to explain how the average citizen will be affected by the date conversion.  <B>Olson</B> said that Pennsylvania has already identified the applications that are necessary to continue service delivery to the citizens of his state.   The Ridge Administration has set a target date of July 1998 to complete the conversion process and begin testing these applications.  He was skeptical, however, that all Pennsylvania businesses would also be Year 2000 compliant in time.  In the personal computer market, <B>Miller</B> said that users will have the most difficulty in preventing "corrupted data" from entering their system because of the interdependence of hardware and software in networks.  Although there is currently no product that can detect whether data was created in an environment that was Year 2000 compliant, <B>Miller</B> predicted that this type of "virus detection" software would be available in the future.  He also mentioned that citizens should be aware of all the success stories that have arisen as individuals, corporations, and industries deal with the Year 2000 conversion issue and mentioned <B>SIA</B> as an example of leadership and success.
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
For more information on the Year 2000, check out:<P>
<UL>
<LH></LH>
<LI><A HREF="sia09zb.htm"> Meeting Schedule & Summaries</A><P>
<LI><A HREF="sia09zg.htm">Year 2000 Sub-Committees</A><P>
<LI><A HREF="sia09zc.htm">Year 2000 Survey</A><P>
<LI><A HREF="sia09za.htm"> Year 2000 Project Plan</A><P>
<LI><A HREF="sia09zd.htm">Testimony Before U.S. Congressional Subcommittee</A><P>
<LI>Additional Year 2000 sites include: <a href="http://www.year2000.com/cgi-bin/clock.cgi">Year 2000 Home Page</a> (sponsored by Peter deJager and The Tenagra Corporation); <a href="http://www.wa.gov:80/dis/y2000/y2000.htm">State of Washington</a> and <a href="http://www.itaa.org">Information Technology Association of America</a><P>
</UL>
