<HTML>
<TITLE>Capital Formation</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><I>Capital Formation</I></B></FONT><BR><BR>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>POSITION</STRONG></FONT><BR>
Congress should implement a meaningful capital gains differential for all productive assets and all investors to increase capital formation.  A 50% exclusion applying to real gains coupled with a one-year holding period will help create jobs, stimulate capital formation, and increase tax revenues.<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>HISTORY</STRONG></FONT><BR>
The Tax Reform Act of 1986 eliminated the capital gains differential, thus taxing capital gains at the same rates as ordinary income.  The maximum individual tax rate on capital gains was capped at 28% in 1990.  The Omnibus Reconciliation Act of 1993 increased the top marginal rate to 39.6% while maintaining the maximum capital gains of 28% -- thus creating a differential of almost 12 points for upper-income taxpayers. <P>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>STATUS</STRONG></FONT><BR>
Both the House and Senate have passed bills that contain capital gains tax cuts.  Both bills provide for a 50% capital gains deduction for individuals; but the corporate capital gains tax rate in the House bill is 25% while it is 28% in the Senate bill.  For individuals, the House bill also provides for the indexation of the basis of capital assets acquired after 1994 and held at least 3 years, and a provision to treat the loss on the sale of a home as a capital loss.  The Senate bill would increase the exclusion to 75% for investment in qualified small business stock.<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG> FACTS</STRONG></FONT><BR>
Increasing private savings and investment is an important tool for expanding the pool of funds available for capital formation and economic growth.  Federal revenue from the capital gains tax increased from $9.1 billion in 1978 to $24.5 billion in 1985 after the Revenue Act of 1978 and the Economic Recovery Tax Act of 1981 combined to reduce the maximum capital gains tax rate from almost 50% to 20%.  Since limited incentives exist to spur such savings and investment, a substantial reduction in the capital gains tax rate will go a long way toward stimulating economic growth and investment and creating new and better jobs.  This is because lower capital gains taxes reduce business capital costs, increase start-ups of new companies, and raise the value of equities and real estate.<P>
The tax code is heavily biased against long-term equity investment -- inflationary gains are subject to taxation; dividends are subject to both a corporate and an individual tax; and capital losses are limited to a $3,000 deduction annually.  Many sections of the tax code compensate for the devastating effect of inflation on income by indexing.  However, inflationary gains remain subject to the capital gains tax.  Indexing capital gains for inflation would ensure that only real economic gain is taxed. <P>
Most of our major foreign competitors alleviate the burden of the double tax on dividend income through integration.  Some do not tax capital gains at all, while others apply a significantly lower rate than the U.S.  Not coincidentally, most of our competitors have double-digit savings rates and a lower cost of capital. <P>
Reducing capital gains taxes only for some sectors, assets or investors artificially distorts the flow of capital.  Similarly, confining incentives only to new investments locks-in existing investment capital, making the gains unavailable for re-investment in new assets.  Broad-based lower capital gains taxes will make the U.S. economy more productive.  Less expensive and more available capital makes the U.S. more competitive with foreign industry and stimulates the growth of U.S. private enterprise.  Most importantly, it fuels the creation of new and better jobs.  Congress should implement a meaningful capital gains differential for all productive assets and all investors to increase capital formation.<P>
Contact: <A HREF=mailto:sjudge@sia.com>Steve Judge</A>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1><FONT SIZE=3>&copy; 1997 Securities Industry Association</FONT>
<A HREF="sia03d.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballrite.gif" ALT="Next Page"></A>
<A HREF="sia00.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="siahome.gif" ALT="Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="sia03b.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Previous"></A></body></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT07-B27-113</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA031-000653-B011-304</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.sia.com:80/sia03d.htm 199.170.0.177 19970122124403 text/html 4582
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 22 Jan 1997 12:44:05 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.3
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 4411
Last-modified: Tue, 14 Jan 1997 16:02:38 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<TITLE>Retirement Savings</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><I>Retirement Savings</I></B></FONT><BR><BR>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>POSITION</STRONG></FONT><BR>
Congress should enact proven tax options to spur personal savings, particularly for retirement, such as restoring the tax deductible Individual Retirement Account (IRA) for all taxpayers, expanding employee and employer incentives for establishing and participating in employer-sponsored savings plans, and simplifying rules and regulations governing pension and savings plans.<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>HISTORY</STRONG></FONT><BR>
Recent government policies have ignored the demographic restructuring of the U.S.  For example, the Tax Reform Act of 1986 limited the availability of the tax deductible IRA and slashed the employee contribution ceiling for 401(k) plans from $30,000 to $7,000 (indexed to inflation).  The overall trend in tax policy since 1986 has been to reduce, freeze, or limit funding and contribution levels for employer-provided retirement savings programs.  The frequent legislative changes needed to implement such policies has increased the complexity and administrative burden of pension plan regulations, discouraging the formation, and the continuation, of new and existing plans.<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>STATUS</STRONG></FONT><BR>
Both Houses of Congress have passed tax measures that would allow non-deductible $2,000 contributions to a new "back-loaded" IRA and would allow non-employed spouses to make IRA contributions.  Tax-free withdrawals from non-deductible IRAs would be allowed for certain purposes.  The Senate bill increases the income limits for deductible IRA contributions from $85,000 to $95,000 for singles, $100,000 to $120,000 for joint filers.  The Senate bill also provides a simplified 401(k) plan for small employers.<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>FACTS</STRONG></FONT><BR>
Savings and investment fuel capital formation, increase economic growth, and raise the standard of living.  Savings are also an important source of retirement income.  Over the past three decades, the U.S. net national savings rate dropped from an average of 8.5% on net national product (NNP) during the 1970s, to 4.7% during the 1980s, to only 2.4% in the 1990s.  Personal savings, as a percentage of disposable income, has dropped from an average 7.8% in the 1970s to only 4.5% in the 1990s -- the lowest personal savings rate in the industrialized world.  Personal savings in other major foreign countries range from two to three times the U.S. rate, further eroding the nation's global economic competitiveness.<P>
IRAs are a tax incentive that worked.  When Congress curtailed IRAs in 1986, IRA contributions dropped 62% from $38 billion -- almost one third of all personal savings -- to $8 billion in 1993.  Not coincidentally, the personal savings rate fell considerably.  Moreover, limits placed on IRA tax deductibility also had a much greater effect on IRA contributions than expected.  Lower-income families reduced their IRA contributions by 40-50%, those in the $40,000-50,000 phase-out range reduced their contributions by 70%, and upper-income taxpayers virtually quit contributing to an IRA despite the tax-deferred feature.<P>
IRAs are not just a substitute for other forms of savings.  A recent study by noted academic economists Dr. Glenn Hubbard, Columbia University, and Dr. Jonathan Skinner, University of Virginia, reviewed the empirical research on IRAs and 401(k) plans and confirmed that contributions to such plans represented largely new savings.<P>
Simplifying regulations and expanding provisions governing private pension and retirement plans would also encourage more employers to establish comprehensive benefit packages for employees.  More employees would take advantage of such programs further adding to the savings available for investment.<P>
<br>Contact:  <A HREF=mailto:sjudge@sia.com>Steve Judge</A>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1><FONT SIZE=3>&copy; 1997 Securities Industry Association</FONT>
