<TITLE>Financial Restructuring</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><I>Financial Restructuring</I></B></FONT><BR><BR>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>POSITION</STRONG></FONT><BR>
 SIA supports comprehensive restructuring of the financial services industry in a manner that promotes fair competition between all financial services providers, protects U.S. taxpayers, and keeps the U.S. capital markets open, competitive, and free.<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>HISTORY</STRONG></FONT> <BR>
The regulatory structure of the U.S. financial services industry has changed little since Congress passed sweeping financial reform legislation in response to the economic chaos which followed the stock market Crash of 1929 and the Great Depression.  Since that time, however, the U.S. economy and the financial services industry have changed markedly, rendering the financial framework virtually obsolete.  Despite its repeated attempts to modernize the financial services regulatory structure over the last decade and a half, Congress has failed to enact comprehensive reform.  In response, federal bank regulators and the courts have undertaken financial deregulation by administrative fiat, interpreting federal and state law to allow commercial banks to engage in a broader array of securities activities.<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>STATUS</STRONG></FONT> <BR>
Financial services modernization legislation is awaiting House floor action (H.R. 1062), but in its current form, does not provide an adequate "two-way street" nor functional regulation.  The Senate has not begun consideration of the issue. <P>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>PRINCIPLES </STRONG></FONT><BR>
Congress -- not banking regulators or the courts -- is the appropriate entity to determine the regulatory framework for the provision of financial services to best serve American consumers of financial services, and to make it possible for all financial services intermediaries to operate more flexibly and competitively, both domestically and internationally.  The following principles must be embodied in any financial services reform legislation for it to achieve the goal of creating equal competitive opportunities for all financial services providers and equal protection for all investors:<P>
Owning a federally insured commercial bank should not be a competitive advantage in the securities business.  Bank holding companies should be allowed to own full service securities firms and securities firms should be able to own or affiliate with banks (the so-called two-way-street).<P>
Taxpayers must be protected by shrinking the scope of the activities which the federal deposit insurance safety net covers inside federally insured banks, particularly those engaged in securities and securities-related activities.<P>
Functional regulation is a critical first step to ensuring fairness of competition.  Through functional regulation one agency applies the same set of rules to the same activity engaged in by any financial institution, no matter what the charter.  No significant financial activity will escape appropriate oversight because of the type of institution engaged in it. <P>
Contact: <A HREF=mailto:sjudge@sia.com>Steve Judge</A>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1><FONT SIZE=3>&copy; 1997 Securities Industry Association</FONT>
<A HREF="sia03f.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballrite.gif" ALT="Next Page"></A>
<A HREF="sia00.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="siahome.gif" ALT="Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="sia03d.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Previous"></A></body></HTML>
