<TITLE>Individual Retirement Accounts</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><I>Individual Retirement Accounts</I></B></FONT><BR><BR>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>POSITION</STRONG></FONT><BR>
 A crisis in financing retirement looms and Congress should enact incentives, such as the tested and proven IRA, to stimulate retirement savings.<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>HISTORY</STRONG></FONT><BR>
The 1981 tax act made a $2,000 tax-deductible IRA available to all taxpayers.  Despite its popularity as a savings vehicle, the Tax Reform Act of 1986 sharply limited its availability.<P>  <FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>STATUS</STRONG></FONT><BR>
Both Houses of Congress have passed tax measures that would allow non-deductible $2,000 contributions to a new "back-loaded" IRA and would allow non-employed spouses to make IRA contributions.  Tax-free withdrawals from non-deductible IRAs would be allowed for certain purposes.  The Senate bill increases the income limits for deductible IRA contributions from $85,000 to $95,000 for singles, $100,000 to $120,000 for joint filers.  The Senate bill also provides a simplified 401(k) plan for small employers.<P>     
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>FACTS</STRONG></FONT><BR>
The march of 76 million Baby Boomers toward retirement combined with a 'senior boom' and a 'baby bust' create demographic changes that heighten the immediate and urgent concern about the lack of personal saving in the U.S.  The personal saving rate has averaged 4.5% since 1986, compared with 7.2% in the years when the tax-deductible IRA was available to all taxpayers.  Encouraging individuals to save for the future not only helps individuals save for financially secure retirements, it also adds to the investment funds for capital formation.    Most Americans have very little in accumulated financial assets.  The median level of net financial assets for all U.S. families is approximately $1,000.  Even families on the verge of retirement, headed by individuals aged 55 to 64, have median net financial assets of only $6,880.    The traditional sources for funding retirement -- Social Security and employer pensions -- are inadequate and likely to play an even smaller role in the future.  Social Security, the current largest single source of retirement income for the majority of retirees, has a sizable long-range deficit and may well be insolvent by 2029.  The down-sizing of corporate America to meet the competitive challenges of the 1980s-90s has reduced the reliability of the traditional corporate-funded pension.    IRAs are a proven vehicle for stimulating personal savings for retirement.  One-in-six families took out IRAs, two-thirds of whom had annual incomes of less than $50,000.  By 1986, the $38 billion of total IRA contributions claimed on over 15 million taxpayer returns represented one third of aggregate savings.  In 1987, one year after the tax deductibility of IRA investment was curtailed, only 7.4 million  taxpayer returns -- 50% less than a year before -- claimed IRA contributions totaling $14.1 billion.    New studies by prominent researchers re-confirm that IRAs are not just a substitute for other forms of savings.  Studies indicate that 80% of IRA contributions represented new savings.<P>
Contact: <A HREF=mailto:sjudge@sia.com>Steve Judge</A>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<FONT SIZE=3>&copy; 1997 Securities Industry Association</FONT>
<A HREF="sia03g.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballrite.gif" ALT="Next Page"></A>
<A HREF="sia00.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="siahome.gif" ALT="Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="sia03e.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Previous"></A></body></HTML>
