<TITLE>Capital Markets Deregulation</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><I>Capital Markets Deregulation</I></B></FONT><BR><BR>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>POSITION</STRONG></FONT><BR> 
SIA strongly supports legislation to modernize, rationalize and improve federal securities laws.<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>HISTORY</STRONG></FONT> <BR> 
The U.S. capital markets are the envy of the world, due in large part to an unparalleled degree of confidence fostered by a strong regulatory system that emphasizes full disclosure and investor protection.  Changing times and circumstances have made some rules and statutes obsolete however, creating needless hindrances to economic growth and competitiveness.  To address these regulatory inefficiencies, House Telecommunications & Finance Subcommittee Chairman Jack Fields (R-TX) introduced the Capital Markets Deregulation and Liberalization Act of 1995 (H.R. 2131) which includes, among other things, provisions to preempt many state securities laws, exempt institutional customers from suitability rules, and institute a single examining authority for registered broker/dealers.  See <A HREF="krongar2.doc"> full statement of A. B. Krongard</A> at hearings before the Telecommunications and Finance Subcommittee.<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>MAJOR PROVISIONS</STRONG></FONT><BR>  
Institutional Suitability:  SIA supports the creation of a separate and distinct suitability requirement for institutional clients.  This standard would require institutional clients to agree in advance in writing to the scope of the brokers responsibility if the client chooses to rely on the brokers recommendations.  Institutional investors are generally more sophisticated and use more sources of information for investment advice than retail investors.  In many cases, institutional investors regard the composition of their portfolio and investment objectives -- key information used in making a suitability determination -- as confidential information which they do not share with their broker.  Blanket application of retail suitability requirements to institutional clients often creates misunderstandings about the scope of a brokers responsibilities.  If institutional clients believe they can transfer losses to their brokers, they will have less incentive to use prudent investment standards.<P>
Federal Preemption of State Securities Laws:  SIA supports provisions to appropriately preempt unnecessary and obsolete state regulation of investment companies.  The state securities regulatory system is inefficient, complex, and burdensome.  In addition to a very comprehensive federal regulatory scheme, issuers, broker-dealers, investment advisers, and investment companies must comply with a separate set of rules in every state and territory where they are licensed to do business or offer securities.  This extra layer of regulation drives up the cost of raising capital, but results in few, if any, additional benefits to investors.  The bill prudently addresses each of the major areas of state securities regulation and makes distinctions between areas where states should play a role and areas where they should not, thereby avoiding a blanket preemption of state blue sky laws and preserving state regulation where it is most effective.  SIA supports, however, full preemption of blue sky laws in the area of investment company regulation.<P>
Securities Margin Requirements:  SIA supports provisions to revise securities margin requirements by requiring the Federal Reserve Board to apply margin rules equally to banks and broker-dealers; allowing the Fed to set different margin requirements for institutional customers; and placing limits on the ability of U.S. customers to obtain margin credit from foreign credit facilities.  Sweeping changes in the financial marketplace over the past decade have rendered regulations governing extensions of credit by securities firms outmoded.  There is no longer any compelling public policy reason why securities firms should be required to comply with margin requirements that are different from those of other financial institutions. <P>
Regulatory Modernization:  SIA supports a number of provisions to correct inefficiencies in securities laws and regulations.  In addition to repealing unnecessary and overly burdensome regulations, the SEC should be required to consider whether its actions will promote efficiency, competition, and capital formation. <P> 
Contact: <A HREF=mailto:sjudge@sia.com>Steve Judge</A>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<FONT SIZE=3>&copy; 1997 Securities Industry Association</FONT>
<A HREF="sia03h.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballrite.gif" ALT="Next Page"></A>
<A HREF="sia00.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="siahome.gif" ALT="Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="sia03f.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Previous"></A></body></HTML>
