<TITLE>Deductions for Interest Payments</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><I>Treasury Department's Proposal to Deny Deductions for Interest Payments</I></B></FONT><BR>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=4>ISSUE:</FONT></STRONG><P>
A Treasury Department proposal dated December 7, 1995 would classify as equity those financial instruments which:<P>
<UL>
<LH></LH>
<LI>have a maximum term to maturity exceeding 40 years; <P>
<LI>have a maximum term or more than 20 years and are classified on the balance sheet as equity; or <P>
<LI>are payable in the stock of the issuer or a related party, including an instrument which is mandatory convertible or convertible at the issuers option.
</UL>
<P>
According to the Treasury, periodic payments of income which are characterized as equity would be deemed to be dividends rather than interest or original issue discount ("OID") and ineligible for an interest deduction for corporate tax purposes.<P>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=4>POSITION:</FONT></STRONG><P>
SIA opposes the Treasury provisions.  Re-characterization of income payments would not only deny issuers an interest deduction, but would also be the death knell for issuance of fixed rate capital securities.<P>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=4>FACTS:</FONT></STRONG><P>
<STRONG>The Treasury proposal would needlessly limit the financing alternatives available to businesses.  </STRONG>Fixed rate capital securities are issued by a wide range of the most innovative and respected manufacturing and service companies in the U.S. who collectively employ millions of American.<P>
<STRONG>The Treasury proposal would increase the cost of capital.</STRONG>  Corporations issue fixed rate capital securities because they are a less expensive means of raising capital.  For example, public utilities and other regulated industries are among the major issuers of fixed-rate capital securities.  Elimination or reduction of the advantages of issuing such securities will cause the cost of raising capital to rise, ultimately resulting in higher utility rates for business and residential consumers.<P>
<STRONG>The Treasury proposal would penalize investors.</STRONG>  Fixed rate capital securities provide investors with relatively high yields, liquidity, and regular fixed income payments from investment grade quality issues.  Without these securities, these individuals would have to accept lower yields or else take higher risks to obtain the same income.<P>
<STRONG>The Treasury proposal represents a sudden and capricious change in tax law and policy.</STRONG>  Fixed rate capital securities are not "corporate welfare."  The fact is, the tax provisions and regulations at issue here have been carefully reviewed -- some for decades -- by Treasury and IRS officials,  and have been deemed to be sound tax policy.  Treasury has not provided any new information that would justify the proposed policy changes.<P>
<STRONG>The Treasury proposal should be subject to the regular legislative process</STRONG>.  This proposal represents a substantial change in federal tax policy.  Fixed rate capital securities were not considered to be "loopholes" or "abusive transactions" before December 7, 1995.  Treasury issued these proposed changes without warning, without consulting financial market participants, without a Congressional hearing, and without full consideration and documentation.  It would be a serious mistake to enact a proposal of this magnitude without extensive hearings and careful consideration of its implications.<P>
In addition, payments of interest or original issue discount on fixed-rate capital securities have declined substantially in both number and dollar amount over the past two years, indicating little need for concern given the many other more significant tax issues with which the government must deal.<P>
<STRONG>The Treasury proposal would not raise additional revenue</STRONG>.  Federal taxes on corporate profits have risen -- not fallen -- during the 1990s.  Contrary to Treasurys assumptions, fixed rate capital notes have not undermined the corporate tax base.  These instruments account for less than 1/2 of 1 percent of the funds raised during the past few years.  Without these instruments, issuers would pay higher interest costs which would be full deductible for tax purposes.  Thus, Treasurys proposal will result in a higher cost of capital or delayed capital raising for companies without any gain in tax revenues, either from increased economic growth or elimination of perceived tax abuses. <P>
<STRONG>The Treasury proposal would impose new taxes on businesses, increase the cost of capital, and discourage investment without providing any benefits to the Treasury or helping to balance the budget</STRONG>.  This measure is not consistent with the goals of balancing the budget, strengthening the economy, and creating jobs.<P>
For more information contact  <A HREF="mailto:ftoohey@sia.com">Frank Toohey</A>. 
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<FONT SIZE=3>&copy; 1997 Securities Industry Association</FONT>
<A HREF="sia03i.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballrite.gif" ALT="Next Page"></A>
<A HREF="sia00.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="siahome.gif" ALT="Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="sia03g.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Previous"></A></body></HTML>
