<TITLE>Independent Contractors</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><I>Independent Contractors</I></B></FONT><BR><BR>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=4>ISSUE</FONT></STRONG><P>
Setting clear standards for worker classification as employees or independent contractors.<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>POSITION</B></FONT><P>
Congress must enact the Independent Contractor Tax Simplification Act (H.R. 1972) to relieve businesses from the IRS's current ambiguous, complex and burdensome 20-factor common law test.  Co-sponsorship of the bill will help ensure passage. <P>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>HISTORY</B></FONT><P>
Businesses must characterize their workers as either employees or independent contractors for tax purposes.  The distinction is important because it determines whether the payor or payee is responsible for withholding income taxes and for paying social security and unemployment taxes and pension and other fringe benefits.<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>FACTS</B></FONT><P>
H.R. 1972 will simplify and eliminate the arbitrary and inconsistent application of the current 20-factor common law test by establishing an objective three-part test.  A service provider would be classified as an independent contractor if he or she: 1) has made a significant investment in assets or training for the business; 2) has a separate place of business or markets him/herself to many service recipients; or 3) has entered into a contract with the service recipient establishing independent contractor status.<P>
Individuals will not be able to claim independent contractor status to avoid paying taxes.  H.R. 1972 requires the service recipient to report all payments to the IRS.<P>
H.R. 1972 meets the needs of the business community.  The White House Conference on Small Business has voted worker classification as the number one tax concern for small business.  The bill provides the realistic and consistent guidelines that will allow independent contractors to concentrate on making their business a success instead of worrying about IRS "compliance checks" and intrusive, unwarranted, expensive, unnecessary and time-consuming audits. <P>
The small business community strongly supports the bill.  The legislation is backed by a coalition of about 30 small business groups and organizations, including SIA, the National Federation of Independent Business, the Small Business Legislation Counsel and the Direct Sellers Association.<P>
The legislation has garnered bipartisan support in the House.  The Independent Contractor Tax Simplification Act currently has bipartisan support from 209 co-sponsors.<P>
For more information, contact   <A HREF="mailto:ftoohey@sia.com">Frank Toohey</A>. 
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<FONT SIZE=3>&copy; 1997 Securities Industry Association</FONT>
<A HREF="sia06a.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballrite.gif" ALT="Next Page"></A>
<A HREF="sia00.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="siahome.gif" ALT="Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="sia03h.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Previous"></A></body></HTML>
