<HTML>
<TITLE>Highlights of Investor Survey</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><EM>1996 Investor Survey --<BR> Highlights of Key Findings</EM></B></FONT>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE=4>
<EM><STRONG>Views Toward Brokers</STRONG></EM>
<UL>
<LI>The vast majority of investors give their brokers good reviews.  In fact, 94 percent of those with a broker are "very" (60 percent) or "somewhat" (34 percent) satisfied with the service they receive.
<LI>Seventy-one percent of investors believe the services provided by brokerage firms are a good value for the money.
<LI>Investors are most impressed with their brokers ability to provide information to make them more knowledgeable about their investment (28 percent).  Brokers also receive high marks for good, prompt service (30 percent), and convenience (18 percent).
<LI>Fifty-two percent of investors consider their broker to be a financial advisor while 46 percent do not.
<LI>Approximately 9 in 10 investors say their broker does and "excellent" or "good" job at being friendly, providing access to account information, and returning calls promptly.  Brokers receive the lowest marks for teaching clients how to make investment decisions, with only 24 percent of investors saying brokers do an "excellent" job at this.
</UL>
<P>
<EM><STRONG>View Toward Securities Industry</STRONG></EM>
<UL>
<LI>More than half of investors (55 percent) say they have a "very" or "somewhat" favorable opinion of the securities industry as a whole.  Twenty-one percent have a "very" or "somewhat" unfavorable opinion, while 24 percent were "not sure."
<LI>Investors with a broker are nearly twice as likely (20 percent) to hold a "very" favorable opinion of the industry than those without a broker (11 percent).
<LI>Men give the securities industry higher ratings than do women, with 58 percent saying they have a "very" or "somewhat" favorable opinion versus 50 percent of women.
<LI>Women and young investors are the least likely to have a "very" favorable opinion of the securities industry, with only 15 percent of women and 1 percent of investors under 40 expressing that opinion.
<LI>More than half of investors (55 percent) are unable to cite the main issues facing the securities industry when responding on an unaided basis.  However, when provided with a range of issues that may be problematic, they most frequently cite greed, putting broker interests ahead of the investors, and industry reluctance to punish wrongdoers as "big problems."
<LI>About 1 in 5 investors (21 percent) hold a "very" or "somewhat" unfavorable opinion of the securities industry.  When asked why, they most frequently cite "fraud/bribery/dishonesty," "greed/salaries/compensation too high" and "high prices or fees/markups/overcharging."
<LI>Seven in 10 investors (71 percent) think brokers services are a good value for the money, up from 63 percent a year ago.  However, two-thirds (67 percent) feel brokers are more concerned about earning commissions than giving good advice.
<LI>Three-quarters of investors (76 percent) say the securities industry should do more to educate the public about good investing.
</UL>
<EM><STRONG>Investor Confidence</STRONG></EM>
<UL>
<LI>Investors say they have a lot to learn.  Only 3 percent of investors say that know everything they need to know to make good investment decisions.  In contrast, 61 percent feel they know just some or very few things necessary to make good decisions, compared with 57 percent in 1995.
<LI>Men think they know more about investing than do women.  Forty percent of men say they know all or most of the necessary items to make good investment decisions, compared with 34 percent of women.
<LI>Investors with brokers are more likely to feel they are knowledgeable about the factors that go into making investment decisions.  Forty-one percent of investors with brokers think they know everything or most of the things necessary to make investment decisions, compared with 33 percent without brokers.  Investors using discount brokers are the most knowledgeable:  50 percent of this group feel they know everything or most of the things needed to make good decisions.
<LI>Investors indicate that they pay close attention to their holdings.  Three in 5 (60 percent) indicate that they review their investments and decide whether or not to make changes every 6 months or less.  An additional 27 percent do so about once a year.  Only 5 percent say they have never reviewed their investments.
</UL>
<EM><STRONG>Investment Goals</STRONG></EM>
<UL>
<LI>Saving for retirement is far and away the most important goal for investors, with more than half (55 percent) saying  this is their primary objective.  All investors, regardless of whether they have a broker or what type of broker they have, express similar goals for their investing.
<LI>Among younger investors (under age 40), being prepared for the future is also a primary objective (20 percent).  More than one-third of investors in this age group (36 percent) say they do not feel financially prepared to be able to retire when they want to.  In addition, 3 in 10 feel they are not financially prepared to help take care of their parents in their old age.
<LI>Gaining a better return on savings is far more important for seniors than for younger investors -- 20 percent of investors age 65 and over say this is their most important goal, compared with 5 to 7 percent of investor in other age groups.
<LI>Investors without brokers are more likely to feel unprepared financially.  Forty-three percent of investors without a broker feel unprepared for retirement, compared with 28 percent of investors with brokers.
</UL>
<EM><STRONG>Investing Style</STRONG></EM>
<UL>
<LI>Most investors say they fall into the middle of the investing style spectrum -- 40 percent say they are moderately conservative, while 30 percent call themselves moderately aggressive investors.
<LI>Men and investors under 50 are most likely to be taking risks with their investments, while women and seniors prefer to be more conservative in their investing.  Sixty-four percent of women call themselves "moderately conservative" or "conservative," compared with 54 percent of the men.  A the same time, two-thirds of investors age 65 or older say they have a "moderately conservative" (46 percent) or "conservative" (26 percent) investing style, while two in five investors under 50 describe themselves as "aggressive" or "moderately aggressive."
<LI>Investors who use a brokerage firm are more likely to describe themselves as "aggressive" or "moderately aggressive" than those who do not have a broker.  In fact, one-quarter of those without a broker (27 percent) describe themselves as "conservative," compared with just 12 percent of those with a broker.
<LI>Investors using a discount broker are most likely to be aggressive -- 52 percent say they are "aggressive" or "moderately aggressive," compared with 44 percent of those with a full service broker and 30 percent  of those without any broker.
</UL>
<EM><STRONG>Sources of Investment Advice</STRONG></EM>
<UL>
<LI>Investors turn to financial planners (19 percent) and brokers (18 percent) most for investment advice.
<LI>However, an equal number (18 percent) say that they do not rely on anyone else and act as their own advisor.  Men, more than women, rely most on themselves.  In fact, one-quarter of men (26 percent) say they rely most on themselves for investment advice, compared with 9 percent of women.
<LI>Investors age 50 or older are more likely than any other age groups to rely most on a broker or themselves.  Twenty-two percent of investors age 50 to 64 and 30 percent age 65 or older rely most on a broker, while 23 percent age 50 to 64 and 25 percent age 65 or older rely most on themselves.
<LI>Investors without a broker rely most on their spouse (22 percent) for investment advice or themselves (19 percent).
<LI>Of those investors who rely on professional advice, 8 out of 10 (83 percent) say the advice they have received from a professional has "significantly" or somewhat" improved their investment performance.
</UL>
<EM><STRONG>Broker Loyalty</STRONG></EM>
<UL>
<LI>Investors most frequently choose a specific brokerage firm based on referrals from others (37 percent), followed by the name or reputation of the brokerage form (22 percent) and wanting to work with a particular broker (19 percent).
<LI>More than half of investors (53 percent) say they feel more loyalty to the broker with whom they most often work than to their brokerage firm.  At the same time, investors are evenly divided over whether they would follow their broker if he or she left for another firm in their area (45 percent) or stay with their current firm (42 percent).
<LI>Of investors with more than one broker, the largest number (36 percent) say they do so because they receive different services and expertise from each, followed by a desire to get advice from more than one source (14 percent) and a concern over having all of their investments in a single place (12 percent).
</UL>

<EM><STRONG>Financial Planning</STRONG></EM>
<UL>
<LI>Three in 5 investors (58 percent) do not have a written financial plan setting forth their goals and how to achieve them.  Two in 5 investors who do not have a written financial plan (39 percent) say they think they should have one.  However, 57 percent do not feel this way.
<LI>Among investors who do have a financial plan, preparing for the future (38 percent) is the most frequently cited reason for having a financial plan, followed by establishing financial goals (18 percent).
<LI>Among those investors who feel they should have a plan but do not, "not getting around to it" (57 percent) is the most common reason stated for not having a financial plan.  Of those who feel they should have a plan but do not, a financial planner is mentioned most often (25 percent) as a likely source in helping to formulate a plan, followed by spouse (13 percent) and doing it themselves (12 percent).
</UL>

<EM><STRONG>Attitudes Toward Brokers Among Those Not Using A Broker</STRONG></EM>
<UL>
<LI>One-third of investors without brokers now have used a broker in the past.  The majority of these investors have previously only had a single broker (72 percent) but 10 percent had three or more brokers.
<LI>Feelings of a lack of value (20 percent) and high costs or charges (10 percent) are the most frequently cited reasons for ceasing to use a broker, followed by poor service (9 percent) and not liking the broker (6 percent).
<LI>Only one-third of those who no longer use a broker sat that they are likely to use a broker again.  Half of the investors who previously used a broker but do not now (49 percent) say they are unlikely to use a broker again.
<LI>Among investors who have never used a broker, 34 percent sat they do not think they need one, with an additional 9 percent saying they can do just as well by themselves.
<LI>Most investors who have never used a broker (60 percent) say they are unlikely to use a broker in the future.
<LI>Of investors who never used a broker but expect to in the future, 31 percent say they will do so because it is time to or they have bigger investments now, while 18 percent say they need advice or guidance or just because they feel it is worth a try (17 percent).
</UL>

<EM><STRONG>Broker Complaints</STRONG></EM>
<UL>
<LI>Most complaints had to do with bad advice or recommendations (24 percent), followed by inappropriate investments and a failure to keep the investors informed (at 19 percent each) and making trades without authorization (13 percent).
<LI>Problems were most commonly addressed through the broker or branch manager (44 percent) or by someone else within the brokerage firm (19 percent), with only 7 percent being reported as resolved through legal through legal action.
<LI>Fewer than 4 in 10 investors (39 percent) who had a complaint about their broker report that they are satisfied with the resolution of their problem.  In fact, 34 percent say they are very unsatisfied with the resolution, with another 13 percent being somewhat unsatisfied.
<LI>One of 10 investors who have used a broker have ever had a serious problem or  complaint with their broker.  Slightly more than half of the investors with a complaint (53 percent) report that the complaint occurred in the past five years.
</UL>

<EM><STRONG>Use of On-line Investing Services</STRONG></EM>
<UL>
<LI>The use of on-line investing services has nearly tripled since 1995.  More than one-third of investors (35 percent) report using computers to obtain investment information, and 7 percent of investors report having used computers to make investment trades.  One year ago, only 13 percent of investors reported having used an on-line service for obtaining investment information or making trades.
<LI>Investors who use computers to make trades say, on average, that about half of the trades they made in the last year (48 percent) were made using computers.  One in five say all the trades they made in the last year were by computer.
<LI>Three-quarters of those investors who have made trades through computers (77 percent) describe this as "very" or "fairly" useful to them.
<LI>Though one-quarter of those who do not use computers to make investment trades indicate they are likely to do this in the next 12 months, nearly one-third (32 percent) say that this is something they will definitely not do.
</UL>

<EM><STRONG>Investors Outlook for 1997</STRONG></EM>
<UL>
<LI>Two in five investors (38 percent) believe 1997 will be a "very good" or "good" year for investments.  Only 8 percent will say it will be a bad year.
</UL>

<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia00.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="siahome.gif" ALT="Homepage"></A>
