</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<BODY><body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
<TITLE>Investor Survey</TITLE>
<FONT SIZE=+4><STRONG><EM>Investor Survey Highlights</EM></STRONG></FONT><P>
<HR NOSHADE=4>
<DD>According to a national survey released November 9, 1995 by the Securities Industry Association (SIA), the majority of investors say they are "very satisfied" with their brokerage services and have a favorable opinion of the securities industry.  A significant minority of investors, however, express an unfavorable opinion of the industry, citing a number of issues including fraud/dishonesty, greed/high compensation and high commissions/fees. <P>
<DD>The first annual SIA Investor Survey, conducted by Yankelovich Partners and commissioned by the SIA, is the first-ever comprehensive opinion research conducted of the investing public.  A total of 1,505 investors were interviewed by telephone between August 25 and September 25 for their views on issues ranging from the qualities they seek in brokerage services, securities industry issues, use of on-line investing services and policy issues, such as tax and retirement legislation, that affect investing.<P>
<DD>"As an industry, we must place a priority on improving the dialogue with investors," said John L. Steffens, SIA chairman and executive vice president at Merrill Lynch & Co.  "The purpose of this research, which will be continued on an annual basis, is to regularly consult our most important audience -- our clients -- so we can better align our services with their needs."<P>
<DD>The survey found that 71 percent of investors with a full-service broker, and 67 percent of investors with a discount broker, are "very satisfied" with the service they receive, with 26 percent and 30 percent, respectively, saying they are "somewhat satisfied."  When asked what they like most about their broker's services, investors responded "good service/responds promptly" (34 percent for both those with full service and discount brokers), "provides information/makes me knowledgeable" (30 percent and 13 percent), and "convenience/helps me understand my investments" (26 percent and 25 percent).  Relatively few brokerage customers can volunteer ways in which the services they receive can be improved; 67 percent of those with a full-service broker and 60 percent of those with a discount broker could not offer suggestions for improvement.<P>
<DD>Similarly, more than half of investors surveyed (55 percent) say they have a "very" or "somewhat" favorable opinion of the securities industry.  Investors with a brokerage account are nearly twice as likely to hold a "very favorable" opinion than those without a broker.  Male investors and investors over age 65 are also more likely to express a "very favorable" opinion than are women or younger investors.<P>
<DD>Nearly a quarter of investors (24 percent), however, express a "very" or "somewhat" unfavorable opinion of the industry, citing "fraud/dishonesty" (23 percent) asthe leading reason for their negative opinion, followed by "greed/compensation too high," (16 percent) and "high commissions/fees/overcharging" (9 percent). <P>
<DD>Nearly half (46 percent) of all investors surveyed cannot volunteer any major issue facing the securities industry.  However, when prompted with a list of issues, they most often mention greed (54 percent), brokers or firms putting their own interests ahead of investors' (51 percent), and the industry's reluctance to punish wrongdoers (50 percent) as "big problems" for the industry.<P>
<DD>"Based on these findings, investors are telling us that they have a high level of satisfaction with their own brokers, but many have real concerns about the industry," Mr. Steffens said.  "At a time when more and more investors are entering the capital markets, our goal must be to address the concerns of these investors promptly and thoroughly, both at the industry and individual firm levels." <P>
<DD>Investors express a limited knowledge level when it comes to investing.  Only 5 percent of investors say they know "everything they need to know" to make good investment decisions, whereas 57 percent say they know "just some" or "very few" things necessary to make informed decisions.  When asked to rate qualities they value in brokerage firms, nearly half (47 percent) of investors say it is "absolutely essential" or "extremely desirable" for firms to teach them how to make better investment decisions.<P>  
<DD>However, brokerage firms receive the lowest marks for performance in this area, with only 7 percent of investors saying that firms do an "excellent" job of educating investors. <P>
<DD>"In our view, an educated investor is our best customer," Mr. Steffens said.  "The SIA has placed a priority on increasing education efforts -- professional and client -- in 1996 as a means to improve investors' understanding of and confidence in the investing process."<P>
<DD>Other key findings of the SIA investor survey include:<P>
<EM><STRONG>Investor Confidence</STRONG></EM><BR>
More than 7 in 10 investors say they feel "very" or "fairly" confident in their own ability to make sound investment decisions, with older investors reporting greater confidence than younger investors.<P>  
Men are only slightly more confident in their investing abilities than women, with 74 percent of men and 67 percent of women saying they are "very" or "fairly" confident.<P>
Investors doing business with a broker are more likely to feel confident in their investing abilities, compared to those without a broker.<P>
<EM><STRONG>Views Toward Brokers/Securities Industry</STRONG></EM><BR>
Three-quarters of investors with a brokerage account say their brokers help them make smarter investment decisions, while more than 60 percent of all investors say brokerage services are a good value for the money.  Women and investors over age 65 are more likely to express these views than other demographic groups.<P>
However, two-thirds of investors "strongly" or "somewhat" agree that brokers are more interested in their commissions than in providing sound investment advice.  One-third say brokers make them feel uncomfortable when they ask questions.  These views are expressed more frequently by investors who do not currently use brokerage services.<P>
<EM><STRONG>Investor Protection</STRONG></EM><BR>
The majority of investors (51 percent) feel that there should be more investor protections in place.  Two-thirds (65 percent) of those who want more protections say they should be implemented by the brokerage/securities industry, rather than by the government (25 percent).<P>
<EM><STRONG>Use of On-Line Investing Services</STRONG></EM><BR>
One-third (32 percent) of investors subscribe to an on-line service.  Of those, 41 percent use on-line services to obtain investment information or to make investments.<P>
More than half (54 percent) of investors say they "strongly" or "somewhat" agree with the statement "I would feel uncomfortable making trades on a computer."  Six in ten investors not currently using on-line services say they cannot see any benefit to using such a service.<P>
<EM><STRONG>Policy Issues</STRONG></EM><BR>
When asked to choose between a capital gains tax cut and a balanced budget, 60 percent of investors favor balancing the budget, compared to 37 percent who favor a tax cut.<P>
More than 7 in 10 investors say tax-deductible IRAs (72 percent) and a balanced budget (71 percent) are "extremely" or "very" important in encouraging investments.<P>
<DD>The SIA Investor Survey is based upon the results of telephone interviews conducted with 1,505 investors nationwide between August 25 and September 25, 1995.   The sample group consists of investors with household incomes of $50,000 and above and investable assets of $100,000 or more (excludes homes; includes 401(k)/IRAs).  Sample error for a group of this size is plus or minus 2.5 percent.<P>
<DD>Additional details are available through <A HREF="sia06aa.htm">1995 Investor Survey  --  Highlights of Key Findings</A>.<P>
A free copy of the survey is available by contacting <A HREF="mailto:rthornblad@sia.com">Dick Thornblad</A>.
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
