<HTML>
<BODY><body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
<TITLE>Encryption Policy</TITLE>
<STRONG><EM><FONT SIZE=+4>Encryption Policy and Its Effect on Information Security for SIA Members</FONT></EM></STRONG><P>
<HR NOSHADE=3>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=+1>Basic Description of Cryptography</FONT></STRONG><P>
<EM>[This description was taken from Bruce Schneier's text, "Applied
 Cryptography", the de facto textbook about cryptography currently 
 available.  If you are interested in learning more about cryptography, 
 you should obtain this book.  ISBN 0-471-59756-2 (paper) ]</EM><P>
The art and science of keeping messages secure is called cryptography 
and it is practiced by cryptographers.  The formula by which a message 
is disguised is called the cryptographic algorithm.  The encoding 
process by which the disguising takes place is called "encryption." 
Decoding the message is done through a related algorithm and the process 
is called "decryption."<P>
Usually, you feed an encryption key and your message to a cryptographic 
algorithm to obtain the encrypted message, which can then be broadcast 
over insecure channels.  This is safe because only the person with both the 
encrypted message <STRONG>and</STRONG> the encryption key can unscramble the message back 
into its undisguised version. <P>
If your encryption algorithm is strong, you should be able to give the 
encryption algorithm and some samples of encrypted messages to a nefarious 
party and they still should not be able to discover either your encryption 
key or the original decoded contents of your message.<P>
The main point of controversy arises from who has access to the encryption 
and decryption key.  (With some algorithms, they are the same key; in others 
they are different but related mathematically)<P>
Obviously, whoever has the key can decrypt the message.  Usually the key is 
given only to the intended recipient.  However several government proposals 
have advocated using systems which disclose the key to a third party or
a law enforcement agency so they can decrypt this information during an 
investigation.  The following paper will describe one such scheme being 
proposed, and the reasons we believe a better alternative must be found.<P>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=+1>Description of Current Usage of Cryptography</FONT></STRONG><P> 
Currently the financial industry integrates encryption technology into 
our services at all levels.  Encryption technology is used to protect 
sensitive store-and-forward electronic communications (such as electronic 
mail), as well as "live" real-time transactions, such as those carried by 
the FIX (Financial Information eXchange) protocol.<P>
In addition, encryption is used to authenticate the originator of 
information, such as for digital signatures. <P> 
Cryptographic protection can be varied in the protection it offers.  For 
example, if you have an email that must be kept confidential for several 
years, you can encrypt it with a strong but slower algorithm that will 
resist conventional brute force attacks for dozens of years.  However, if 
we are simply attempting to keep confidential a transaction which will 
become a matter of public record within a few minutes after transmission, 
we would choose an algorithm that gave us better performance (i.e., can be decrypted more quickly), but was not 
as resistant to a sustained multi-year attack.<P>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=+1>Description of Current Regulation of Cryptography</FONT></STRONG><P> 
Encryption technology is classified as a munition under the US ITAR 
(International Traffickers in Arms Regulations).  This restricts the 
export and sale of such products outside the US, regardless of the 
fact that many of the products that are restricted for export are 
available outside the United States already. <P>
Currently, the US government allows companies which have a majority of 
American ownership to export any cryptography products they wish to their 
own offices abroad.  However, even that process consumes non-negligible 
amounts of paperwork and non-compliance carries severe penalties. <P>
Should a company wish to communicate with its non-US customers, however, 
we are unable to provide them with cryptography that is strong enough
to defend against attackers with access to significant amounts of 
computer hardware.   The Administration allows us to export to these 
individuals only cryptography with a length limit on the key (40 bits), 
making it vulnerable to attackers with a moderate amount of computing 
power.<P>
In the attacks we have recently seen on 40-bit exportable cryptography, 
any attacker with a moderate amount of computer power has been able
to decrypt captured messages, without access to the encryption key, using 
"brute force" methods.<P>  
We find this situation unacceptable.  Knowing that our industry is targeted 
by foreign governments working on behalf of their domestic industries, we 
must have available to us the tools by which we can ensure the 
confidentiality of our business communications overseas.<P>
It is worth pointing out, that as an industry, we are responsive to regulators.   
It is clear that should a regulatory or law enforcement agency provide us with 
the necessary paperwork to obtain evidence for an investigation, we will 
always comply to the fullest extent of the law.  We remained committed to
this principle going forward into the new electronic medium. <P>
Furthermore, cryptography that is much stronger than what we are allowed 
to export is available today from other companies overseas.  In fact,
it is not uncommon for U.S enterprises to purchase crypto products 
overseas to obtain the required security and avoid the restrictions 
imposed by US law.<P>  
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=+1>Description of Current Administration Proposal on Cryptography</FONT> </STRONG><P>
The Clinton Administration is proposing a scheme called "Commercial Key Escrow" (CKE).  They believe it addresses concerns by the industry and 
business communities about their current cryptography policy.  The proposal 
has been driven by law enforcement and national security concerns.   However, 
it has been met with a less than enthusiastic response in government/industry meetings.<P>
The proposal is this: new hardware and software products are built with 
a facility for "Key Escrow," that would allow you to keep a spare copy 
of the key at the facility of a third party, called an "Escrow Agent," 
who would perform two functions:<P>
<OL>
<LH></LH>
<LI>Release of the key to you if you lose it and need to
decrypt documents that had previously been encrypted with 
the lost key; and <P>
<LI> Release of the key to law enforcement, should they obtain
the appropriate warrants necessary to obtain data which has
been encrypted with the escrowed key.
</OL><P>
In return for buying into this proposal, the Administration has offered to 
allow the export of cryptographic products with key lengths of up to 64 bits 
(24 bits stronger than what is allowed now).<P>
Proponents of CKE also insist that because we are not using escrow now, 
the escrow feature provides us with an important business continuance service 
in cases where the key is only known by a single individual and that 
individual becomes unavailable.<P>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=+1>Problems With Current Proposal</FONT></STRONG><P>
The CKE proposal was formally proposed to the business and vendor community 
at a meeting at NIST in Gaithersberg, Maryland on September 6, 1995.  The SIA 
sent representatives to participate in the activities of the meeting. <P>
Except for a few vendors that intend to market products designed for the 
system, the business and vendor community was less than enthusiastic
about the proposal.  Although there have been several meetings since then, 
the following core objections from our industry are: <P>
<EM>64 BITS IS NOT COMPETITIVE</EM><BR>
The Administration's proposal suggests that we will be allowed to raise 
the strength of our exportable cryptographic products from 40 bits to 
64 bits.  While 64 bits is better, an NSA spokesperson confirmed at the 
12/5/95 NIST CKE meeting that well funded attackers could break 64 bit 
encryption.   Well funded attackers, especially those working within 
other governments on behalf of their domestic industries, are exactly 
one of the threat models we are trying to protect ourselves against.<P>
This fact, combined with the fact that we can already obtain stronger 
encryption abroad and import it into the US, means that the increase to 
64 bit-capable products is not enough of a draw to make such products 
attractive.  In fact, many of our companies are already using products 
with more than 64-bits of encryption strength.  To downgrade to a 64-bit 
product would mean a degradation in the security we provide. <P>
<EM>INDUSTRY WANTS KEY ESCROW, BUT NOT WITH THIRD PARTIES</EM><BR>
Most companies that use encryption are receptive to the idea of key 
escrow, but for themselves.  They wish to keep the keys in their own 
offsite data centers, or in their own safe deposit boxes, and will provide
the keys to law enforcement when provided with a warrant.  The Administration 
has suggested that its idea of key escrow is the same as the idea of third 
party key escrow, when in fact one does not imply the other.<P>
Because government-approved key escrow agents are not supposed to inform 
parties whose keys have been disclosed, and in some cases keep no records
of the disclosures, there is no way for us to know whether or not the escrow 
agent has followed procedure to protect our interest. <P>
Throughout its regulated history, the securities industry has always 
cooperated with regulators and law enforcement.  There's no reason to 
suspect it won't into the future.   The regulatory scheme proposed has 
so much potential harm that it can't outweigh the presumption of proper 
behavior to be enjoyed by the industry. <P>
<EM>DISCLOSURE OF OUR KEYS TO FOREIGN POWERS</EM><BR>
The Administration has said that they will set up bilateral agreements with 
law enforcement agents in other countries so they may also obtain escrowed 
keys from escrow agents. <P>
Although we have the assurances of the Administration that they will only 
provide these keys to foreign powers that are friendly to us, it is disconcerting to realize that in the arena of foreign policy, access to these  keys by foreign powers may be negotiated away in order to fulfill higher 
purposes of an Administration foreign policy initiative.<P>
<EM>DRIVEN PRIMARILY BY LAW ENFORCEMENT NEEDS, NOT BUSINESS</EM><BR>
The Commercial Key Escrow proposal was poorly received by business and 
industry because it was designed to fit the needs of law enforcement and 
national security first, and business and industry second.<P>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=+1>Going Forward</FONT></STRONG><P>
There have been a number of developments recently that have heightened 
sensitivity to these issues.  First, the SIA signed an October 1995 letter 
to Vice President Gore stating that the CKE proposal does 
not meet our security requirements, and that these same companies will begin 
a six month study to present a better solution driven by the needs of 
business and industry with a respect for legitimate needs of law enforcement 
and national security.  The SIA has been invited by CDT to take part in
DPSWG as a interested party. <P>
Second, current policy has demonstrably failed to meet its own goals and 
it has also handicapped American commercial interests.  Several times 
graduate students have shown that, using a few powerful computers or many 
low powered computers, it is possible to break the 40-bit encryption
that is the strongest allowed for export.  It is not unreasonable to conclude 
that if this can be done by graduate students with spare computer power,
it can be done by motivated attackers. <P>
You can follow new legislation on the crypto front at <A HREF="http://www.crypto.com">http://www.crypto.com</A><P>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=+1>Conclusion</FONT></STRONG><P>
SIA's Information Security Subcommittee will continue to monitor 
developments in this area.
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>&copy; 1997 Securities Industry Association<P>
