<HTML>
<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Thursday, December 26, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+3><B>Underwritings, Merger and Acquisition Activity,<BR>Profits Outpace 1993 Highs as Industry Raises<BR>$1 Trillion in Capital for Fifth Straight Year</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2>Regional Firms, Discounters Superior Performers in 1990s<BR>As Securities Firms Post Records in Revenue, Profits</FONT></CENTER> 
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2>U.S. Investors' Holdings of Foreign Equities Top Record $506 Billion</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>New York, NY</STRONG> -- Equity and corporate bond underwritings, merger and acquisition activity, dollar and share volume, and industry revenues and profits set records as the stock and bond holdings of institutional and individual investors increased to new highs.
<P>
<dd>"Record performances were posted in nearly every aspect of the markets and our industry this year," said Jeffrey Schaefer, a Senior Vice President and Chief Economist with the Securities Industry Association.  "Low interest rates, tempered inflation, and  steady economic growth gave investors tremendous confidence to continue investing in stocks, bonds, and other securities.  While all types of securities firms benefited from the strong market, discounters and regional firms did particularly well, thanks to a record inflow of cash into mutual funds, heavy trading volume, and the spectacular growth in the industry's retail business."
<P>
<B>1996 IPOs Climb Ahead of 1993 Record By 20 Percent</B>
<P>
<dd>Securities firms raised more than $1 trillion in capital for U.S. businesses for the fifth consecutive year.  A record number of initial public offerings (866 through December 20), were brought to market this year, raising approximately $50 billion.  1996's level was nearly twice that of the year before and 20 percent more than the previous record of $41.5 billion reached in 1993 (excludes closed-end funds).  Three of the six largest IPOs were underwritten this year:  Lucent Technologies (second largest ever), Associates First Capital (fifth), and Deutsche Telekom AG (sixth).
<P>
<dd>Total stock underwriting in 1996 was running at $144 billion (ten months annualized), an all-time high, which is up 10 percent from the previous record set in 1993.  Corporate bond underwriting, however, is running at the second highest level ever ($782 billion), down 15 percent from the peak of $921 billion reached in 1993.
<P>
<dd>Merger and acquisition activity was particularly strong this year, with the value of M&A  deals managed by the industry exceeding an estimated $500 billion (based on nine months of data).  The 1996 pace is more than 40 percent above 1995's $354 billion and triple 1993's $170 billion.  Two major deals -- the Capital Cities/ABC merger with Walt Disney and the First Interstate Bankcorp merger with Wells Fargo -- were alone valued at nearly $30 billion.
<P>
<dd>"The securities firms with the resources to manage these deals profited significantly from the continued trend towards consolidation in the banking, aerospace, telecommunications, and utilities industries," Schaefer said.  "The recently announced acquisition of McDonnell Douglas Corp. by  Boeing Co. for more than $13 billion bodes well for M&A activity in 1997."
<P>
<B>U.S. Investors'  Holdings of Foreign Equities At Record</B>
<P>
<dd>Capital raising by U.S. firms continued to expand beyond the nation's borders.  Including the Deutsche Telekom AG offering, which raised $1.6 billion in the U.S. alone, total U.S.underwriting for non-U.S. based companies reached an all-time high of $70 billion this year (eleven months annualized).  This is 63 percent ahead of 1995, and 25 percent above 1993's previous record of $56 billion.
<P>
<dd>"Securities firms continue to make it easy for Americans to diversify their portfolios globally," said Schaefer.  Total American Depositary Receipts (ADRs) trading on the New York and American Stock Exchanges and the Nasdaq Stock Market totaled 346 in 1996, an all-time high, compared to 329 ADRs in 1995.
<P>
<dd>U.S. ownership of foreign companies continued to grow this year, and for the first time ever, U.S investors own more foreign equities than foreign owners have of U.S. stocks.  U.S. holdings of foreign equities stood at a record $506 billion as of September 30.  At the current rate of growth, U.S. investors will own more than $1 trillion in foreign equities by 2001.
<P>
<dd>"Steady economic growth,  a strengthening dollar, and higher interest rates relative to their home countries were key factors in attracting foreign investors to U.S. markets," Schaefer said.  "For U.S. buyers of foreign stocks, low share price valuations relative to U.S. stocks, and encouraging global economic forecasts were important reasons for their purchases of foreign securities."  In the first half of 1996, foreigners acquired $10.5 billion of U.S. equities, on track to match 1993's record $21.6 billion (full year).
<P>
<B>Mutual Fund Assets Climb Above $3.4 Trillion</B>
<P>
<dd>The flow of money into mutual funds played a significant role in the markets, continuing a decade-long trend.  Mutual fund assets have more than tripled since 1990 to top $3.4 trillion this year.  Cash streaming into stock funds through November 1996 totaled $207.7 billion; the previous high for a calendar year was $129.6 billion in 1993.
<P>
<B>Share Volume At New High As Number of Issues Sets Record</B>
<P>
<dd>Share volume on the New York and American Stock Exchanges through November were records, with an average of 410-million and 22-million shares being traded daily, increases of 18 percent and 9 percent, respectively.  On the Nasdaq Stock Market, a record 542-million shares traded daily, up 35 percent from 1995.  Dollar volume of trading exceeded $8 trillion this year, double the value of just three years ago.
<P>
<dd>The nation's three stock markets had their three busiest days ever this year, the heaviest day being July 16, when 1.6-billion shares traded.
<P>
<dd>The number of issues listed on NYSE, AMEX, and Nasdaq reached 10,783, an all-time high, at the end of November, compared to 10,040 at the end of 1995.
<P>
<B>Pre-Tax ROE, Profit Margins Higher Than Other Industries</B>
<P>
<dd>The securities industry's pre-tax profits for the year are projected to be $11.5 billion, 34 percent above 1993's previous record of $8.6 billion.   Pre-tax return on equity (ROE) for the securities industry is projected at 30 percent, the highest among industry sectors.  Manufacturing's pre-tax ROE is projected at 23.8 percent for the year and banking's at 22.2 percent.  Pre-tax profit margins for the securities industry are projected to be 18.2 percent, compared to a projected 10.3 percent for mining and a projected 8.6 percent for manufacturing.
<P>
<dd>In the 1990s, discounters and regional firms have posted the highest pre-tax returns on equity among securities firm categories.  Discounters weighed in with a 44.8 percent pre-tax ROE while regional firms generated a 43 percent pre-tax ROE.
<P>
<dd>General securities business activities (including private placement fees, service charges, dividends and interest from investment accounts that include repos and reverse repos) remained the largest source of revenue this year, reaching $46.1 billion<B><FONT  SIZE=+1>*</FONT></B>. Trading gains ($19.4 billion<B><FONT  SIZE=+1>*</FONT></B>), commissions ($18.2 billion<B><FONT  SIZE=+1>*</FONT></B>), and underwriting fees ($10.7 billion<B><FONT  SIZE=+1>*</FONT></B>) followed.  Asset management fee revenues rose to $5.1 billion<B><FONT  SIZE=+1>*</FONT></B>, reflecting an increase in funds under management as well as the rise in stock prices.
<P>
<dd>The industry's total capital reached $68.4 billion through third quarter 1996 (averaging 12-percent per year gains during the 1990s), while equity capital climbed to $39.82 billion (averaging 10 percent annual increases since 1990).
<P>
<dd>Strong balance sheets and growing demands for the services of securities firms resulted in the industry employing more people -- 262,460 for NYSE member firms dealing with the public -- by the third quarter 1996 than ever before in Wall Street's history.  During the 1990s, industry employment grew on average 4 percent annually.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=25%% ALIGN=left SIZE=1>
<B><FONT  SIZE=+1>*</FONT></B> Nine months annualized.
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 760 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S., SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
