<HTML>
<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Friday, December 20, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+3><B>SIA Blasts Fed Action to Increase<BR>Banks' Securities Business</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2>Latest Fed Move Undermines Efforts to Modernize Glass-Steagall</FONT></CENTER> 
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2>Three Principles -- No Government Subsidies, Two-Way Street,<BR>Functional Regulation -- Should Guide Rewrite of Depression-Era Laws</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, D.C.</STRONG> -- Steve Judge, Senior Vice President, Government Relations, of the Securities Industry Association, today released the following statement in response to the decision by the Federal Reserve to increase the cap on securities activities undertaken by banks.
<P>
<dd>"The Fed's decision today, on the heels of a similar action by the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, greatly increases the ability of banks to engage in the securities business, while securities firms remain barred from banking.  It's as if Santa Claus delivered all the gifts to only one house in the neighborhood.
<P>
<dd>"Piecemeal decisions by the banking regulators are rapidly expanding the financial services that banks can provide while securities firms remain constrained by the Depression-era laws.  Federal laws should promote open, fair competition among all financial services providers so that investors, issuers, and other customers can benefit.   The actions by the Fed and the OCC tilt the marketplace in favor of banks since there is no reciprocal expansion in the banking activities that securities firms can engage in.
<P>
<dd>"Nothing could benefit consumers and our economy more than the modernization of federal laws governing the financial services industry.  Our industry has embraced the digital age; but the nation's banking and securities laws have not.
<P>
<dd>"Modernizing Glass-Steagall should follow three principles.  First, there should be no government subsidies that benefit one type of financial services provider at the expense of another.  This means, for example, that the low-cost funding banks enjoy should not benefit any securities operation and that the taxpayers should not bear the types of risk securities firms face daily.  Second, there must be a two-way street.  If banks are allowed into the securities business, securities firms, likewise, should be allowed into banking.  Third, the financial services industry should be regulated by function, with all securities activities regulated by the Securities and Exchange Commission.  Similarly, all banking activities should be regulated by the Federal Reserve Board and the OCC.  Not doing so will result in overlapping bureaucracies and costly regulatory confusion.
<P>
<dd>"Congress is the best forum to develop and enact comprehensive, pro-competition legislation, and lawmakers appear poised in the next session to pass a bill.  Unfortunately, the Fed's action today undermines efforts to bring all components of the financial services industry to the table to iron out a solution.  We'll continue to work with Congress to enact much-needed legislation."
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 760 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S., SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
