<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Wednesday, December 18, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+3><B>SIA Commends SEC Overhaul of Securities<BR>Trading Rules During an Offering</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2><B>'Simpler, More Flexible Framework' Will Reduce Regulatory<BR>Burdens While Retaining Core Investor Safeguards</B></FONT></CENTER> 
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, D.C.</STRONG> -- Responding to long-standing concerns expressed by the Securities Industry Association and many securities broker-dealers, the Securities and Exchange Commission today approved new regulations that streamline rules governing trading in securities involved in an offering.  According to SIA's Senior Vice President and General Counsel, Stuart Kaswell, "SIA is very pleased with the Commission's action today.  The Commission adopted the prior framework for the trading practice rules in 1955, when by any measure -- for example, trading volume, transparency, investor access to timely information -- U.S. markets were far less developed and more vulnerable to potentially manipulative practices.  Modernizing the rules to reflect fundamental changes in the markets is therefore highly desirable.  Moreover, this will strengthen liquidity by making it possible for market-makers to stay in the market in circumstances where today they might have to withdraw.  
<P>
<dd>"We agree with the Commission that the new rules will create a simpler, more flexible framework to govern the market conduct of persons with a significant interest in the outcome of an offering by reducing regulatory burdens on issuers, underwriters, and other offering participants while retaining core investor safeguards," Kaswell said.
<P>
<dd>Kaswell noted that SIA had expressed reservations about certain aspects of the new rules when they were proposed in April.  "While we have not yet had a chance to review the final rules, SIA understands that many of the concerns that we raised have been addressed by the Commission in the final rules."
<P>
<dd>Kaswell noted that many SIA members, and in particular its Federal Regulation Committee, have urged the SEC for several years to modernize its regulations in the area of secondary market trading during a securities offering.
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 760 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S., SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
