<HTML>
<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Wednesday, November 20, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>New OCC Rules Broaden Banks' Securities Activities<BR>but Discourage Financial Services Competition</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=4><B>Comprehensive Modernization of Federal Banking, Securities Laws Needed</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, D.C.</STRONG> -- Steve Judge, Senior Vice President, Government Affairs, for the Securities Industry Association, today released the following statement in response to new rules approved by the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency to allow certain bank subsidiaries to engage in securities activities.
<P>
<dd>"Modernization of the Depression-era laws governing the financial services industry is essential.  Consumers and our economy will benefit greatly from the competition that comprehensive reforms will promote.   Enacting these reforms is so important that Congress must do the job, which it is poised now to do.
<P>
<dd>"SIA has long opposed the piecemeal approach to financial deregulation now underway by federal banking regulators.  The latest such action -- today's announcement by the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency -- is a misguided step because it will only benefit part of the financial services industry.  While we have yet to review thoroughly the OCC's new rules, their action today will allow banks to own full-service securities firms, but securities firms will not be permitted to own banks.  This tilts the marketplace in favor of banks, undermining competition within the financial services industry.  Federal policy should promote competition, not impede it.
<P>
<dd>"The concern we have now is that the OCC's action may undermine a broad-based financial services coalition, which is working with Congress to enact much-needed reforms.  One segment of the industry may now have no incentive to continue working towards enacting legislation.
<P>
<dd>"Congress is the appropriate arbiter of substantial changes in the federal laws.  In our view, the legislation that Congress and the industry should work towards achieving must follow three principles.  First, there should be no government subsidies that benefit one type of financial services provider at the expense of another.  This means, for example, that the low-cost funding banks enjoy should not benefit any securities operation and that the taxpayers should not bear the risk securities firms face daily.  Second, there must be a two-way street.  If banks are allowed into the securities business, securities firms, likewise, should be allowed into banking.  Third, the financial services industry should be regulated by function.  All securities activities should be regulated by the Securities and Exchange Commission.  Similarly, all banking activities should be regulated by the Federal Reserve Board and the OCC.  Not to do so will result in overlapping bureaucracies and costly regulatory confusion.
<P>
<dd>"The SIA is reviewing a number of legal and legislative options to respond to the OCC's decision."
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 760 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia04.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Press Releases"></A>
</BODY>
