<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Saturday, November 9, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+3><CENTER><B>1997 SIA Chairman James F. Higgins Previews<BR>Top Priorities for the Year Ahead</B></CENTER></FONT>
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+2><CENTER><B>Association To Focus on Public Trust and Confidence,<BR>Legislation To Encourage Savings, Industry Use Of Technology</B></CENTER></FONT>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Boca Raton, FL</STRONG> -- Strengthening the public's trust and confidence in the securities industry will remain a top priority of the Securities Industry Association in 1997, according to James F. Higgins, President and Chief Operating Officer of Dean Witter Financial and the association's 1997 Chairman.
<P>
<dd>Higgins addressed the more than 700 industry representatives attending the association's annual meeting here, which concludes today.
<P>
<dd>"We will remain committed to upholding the highest standards of integrity as an industry, which we believe is key to strengthening investor confidence," Higgins said.
<P>
<dd>"The SIA will continue its advocacy efforts in support of .legislation designed to encourage people to save and invest for their futures, " Higgins said.  This includes legislation concerning capital gains tax reductions and expanding the eligibility for deductible individual retirement accounts.
<P>
<dd>Higgins also outlined ways the SIA is preparing for the challenges and opportunities related to technology.  Vision 2000, developed by the SIA's Operations Committee, is addressing the issues that will be key to how the industry serves investors in the 21st Century.
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
