<HTML>
<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Saturday, November 9, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+3><CENTER><B>SIA  Initiatives Focus on Public Trust,<BR>Confidence in Financial Markets</B></CENTER></FONT>
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+2><CENTER><B>Securities Firm Handbook, Investor Publications,<BR>Seminars, Computer-Based Ethics Training<BR>Highlight Year's Efforts</B></CENTER></FONT>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Boca Raton, FL</STRONG> -- In outlining a series of initiatives launched by the Securities Industry Association to educate professionals and investors, SIA's Vice Chairman today called on securities firms to "continue building on the foundation that's been laid" to strengthen public trust and confidence in the financial markets.
<P>
<dd>"This was a year of formation and creation.  We've created many new resources and tools.  Our initiatives will grow and bear fruit if we utilize the tools at our disposal and maintain a strong focus on the fundamentals of our business," said Irving Weiser, who chairs SIA's Public Trust and Confidence Committee and is Chairman, President and Chief Executive Officer of Inter-Regional Financial Group, Inc.
<P>
<dd>According to Weiser, SIA is educating member firms about industry "best practices" in -- conducting and regulating business activities.  These practices cover client rights, confirmation statements, customer complaint resolution procedures, sales supervision and hiring policies, compliance, and operations.
<P>
<dd>The association, working with the Futures Industry Institute, he said, developed an innovative, computer-based interactive training program that enables industry professionals to review case studies and learn how to resolve the legal and ethical questions the examples pose.  The program focuses not only on the "right" and "wrong" of various issues, but helps users understand the rationale and decision-making processes they used.
<P>
<dd>SIA, Weiser said, also worked with the University of Chicago to organize an Executive Ethics Roundtable in April this year.  A second is planned for April 1997.  Stanford University is exploring with SIA whether to hold a similar program next year.
<P>
<CENTER><B>SIA Boosts Investor Education</B></CENTER> 
<P>
<dd>For investors, SIA is providing a series of tools they can use to educate themselves to make financial decisions.  These include: <I>Investor Topics</I>, a brochure about the basics of investing; SIA's <I>Your Guide to Understanding Investing</I>, a book using illustrations and easy-to-understand examples to explain financial markets and retirement planning; and, a seminar package firms can use to explain the "ten mistakes to avoid and ten investing principles to follow.
<P>
<dd>The need among investors for more education about the financial risks and rewards of investing, Weiser said, was one of the key findings of the second investor survey released by SIA on Thursday.
<P>
<dd>Each of us has the ability to make a difference in improving public trust," Weiser said.  "We need to ask ourselves what can [each of us] do to make a difference.  If each of you go back and keep the issue of public trust and confidence a topic of discussion; if you have high expectations and reinforce ethical behavior, it will become the rule and it will be reality.
<P>
<dd>"We need," Weiser concluded, "to make it clear that we have zero tolerance for ethical shortcuts or legal misdeeds.  And we need to take responsibility for focusing on the fundamentals of our business:  placing the client's needs first; ensuring quality in every aspect of our business; and demanding professionalism and the highest ethical standards at all levels of our business.  Then, and only then, will we achieve our objective of regaining and maintaining public trust and confidence."
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
