<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Friday, November 8, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2><STRONG>James F. Higgins Elected as 1997 SIA Chairman<BR>
Irving Weiser Becomes Chairman-Elect<BR>
James W. Brinkley and Roy J. Zuckerberg<BR>are Elected Vice Chairmen<BR>
Richard Pechter Remains Treasurer</STRONG></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Boca Raton, FL</STRONG> -- James F. Higgins, President and Chief Operating Officer of Dean Witter Financial, was today elected 1997 Chairman of the Securities Industry Association.  Irving Weiser, Chairman, President and CEO of Inter-Regional Financial Group, Inc., became Chairman-elect.
<P>
<dd>Higgins was 1996 Chairman-elect and will succeed 1996 Chairman A.B. Krongard, Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of Alex. Brown, Inc.  Mr. Krongard will continue in 1997 as an SIA Director and "immediate past Chairman." 
<P>
<dd>Weiser served as Vice Chairman of SIA in 1996.
<P>
<dd>James W. Brinkley, President, Legg Mason Wood Walker, and Roy J. Zuckerberg, Partner and Executive Committee Member, The Goldman Sachs Group, L.P., were elected Vice-Chairmen, succeeding Weiser and Bernard L. Madoff, Principal, Bernard L. Madoff Investment Securities.
<P>
<dd>SIA's member firms elect SIA directors, who in turn elect the chairman and other officers during the association's Annual Meeting, which runs through November 9 here.
<P>
<dd>Higgins is President and Chief Operating Officer of Dean Witter Financial.  In this position he is responsible for the branch office system and the marketing, sales and trading of all equity, futures, options, and taxable fixed-income products.
<P>
<dd>Higgins has spent his entire career at Dean Witter, joining as an account executive trainee in New York in 1971.  He was appointed branch manager of the Worcester, Massachusetts office in 1979, a position he held for four years before serving as branch manager of the Chicago office.  In 1985, he was promoted to national sales director of Dean Witter Consumer Markets.  Higgins was appointed President and Chief Operating Officer of Dean Witter Consumer Markets in 1987 and, in 1989, he was appointed to his current position.
<P>
<dd>Higgins is a member of the management committee of Dean Witter, Discover & Co., Dean Witter's parent company.  In addition, he serves on the Board of Directors of Dean Witter Trust, Dean Witter Reynolds, Dean Witter InterCapital, and the Georgetown University Board of Regents.  A native of Providence, Rhode Island, Mr. Higgins holds a bachelor's degree in business administration from Georgetown University.
<P>
<CENTER><B>Weiser Brings Strong Commitment To SIA's Public Trust And Confidence Efforts</B></CENTER>
<P>
<dd>Irving Weiser is Chairman, President and Chief Executive Officer of Inter-Regional Financial Group, Inc. and Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of Dain Bosworth Incorporated.
<P>
<dd>He joined Inter-Regional Financial Group, Inc. in 1985 as President and became Chief Executive Officer in 1990.  Named Chairman and CEO of Dain Bosworth, a brokerage and investment banking subsidiary of IFG in 1990, Weiser assumed the additional post of Chairman of the Board of IFG in May 1995.  Before joining the company, he was IFG's corporate counsel while a partner at the law firm of Dorsey and Whitney.
<P>
<dd>Weiser received a bachelor's degree from the State University of New York at Buffalo and a law degree with honors from Brooklyn Law School.  He is active in several community organizations, including Minnesota Business Partnership, Young President's Organization, Inc., United Way of the Minneapolis Area, Children's Home Society of Minnesota, the Guthrie Theater Foundation, and Temple Israel.  He chairs SIA's Public Trust and Confidence Committee.
<CENTER><B><P>
Zuckerberg and Brinkley Named Vice Chairmen</B></CENTER>
<P>
<dd>Zuckerberg is a member of Goldman Sachs' Executive Committee, Partnership Committee and co-head of the Equities Division.  He joined the firm in 1967 in Securities Sales and assumed responsibility for developing the firm's private client business in 1972.  In 1977, he was made a partner and served as co-head, and then head, of the Securities Sales Division.
<P>
<dd>Zuckerberg's community involvement includes serving as Trustee, Vice Chairman of the Board and Chairman of the nominating committee for the Long Island Jewish Medical Center, and as a Trustee of the American Red Cross in Greater New York.  In addition, he is a director of the Brookdale Foundation and Phoenix House.  He received a B.S. degree from Lowell Technological Institute.
<P>
<dd>Brinkley joined Mason & Co. as its first employee in 1962, prior to its merger with Legg & Company in 1970.  He is also Director of Legg Mason Inc. and Howard Weill Financial Inc.
<P>
<dd>In addition to serving as a member of the Regional Firms Advisory Committee of the New York Stock Exchange, Brinkley is a former Chairman of the District Business Conduct Committee of the National Association of Securities Dealers and Chairman of the Advisory Council to the Board of Governors of the NASD.  He is Vice Chairman and Trustee of the Maryland Academy of Science and Science Center and Chairman of the Investment Committee for Episcopal Social Ministries and Chairman of the Investment Committee of the Church of the Holy Comforter.  He has also served on a number of committees for the College of William and Mary, from where he received his bachelor's degree in Economics.
<P>
<CENTER><B>Pechter Continues As Treasurer</B></CENTER>
<P>
<dd>Richard S. Pechter is a Director of Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette, Inc., and also serves as Managing Director of Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette Securities Corporation, and Chairman of Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette's Financial Services Group, which incorporates DLJ's 
Regional Office System, the Pershing Division, and Wood, Struthers & Winthrop.
<P>
<dd>Pechter, who joined DLJ in 1969 as a research analyst, was named a Vice President and Treasurer of DLJ in 1971, and became Chief Financial Officer in 1973.  He served as executive vice president and chief administrative officer until 1979, when he became chief executive officer of the Pershing Division.  Pechter was elected to DLJ's Board of Directors in 1979.
<P>
<dd>A former Director of the Depository Trust Company and Interstate/Johnson Lane, Pechter is a former Trustee of the SIA's Securities Industry Institute.  Additionally, he serves on the Arbitration and Surveillance Committees of the New York Stock Exchange.  He is a past President of the Investment Association of New York, a former director of the National Securities Clearing Corporation and a former Chairman of the SIA's Firm and Industry Analysis Committee.  Pechter belongs to the Bond Club, the Yale Club and Kappa Beta Phi.  He has served as SIA's Treasurer since 1995.
<P>
<dd>Born in Altoona, Pennsylvania, he attended Phillips Academy in Andover, Massachusetts, graduated from Yale University in 1967, and received an MBA in 1968 from Harvard Business School, where he was a Baker Scholar.
<P>
<dd>Marc E. Lackritz continues as the SIA's president.
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
