<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Friday, November 8, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+3><B>SIA President Calls 1996 a Year of<BR>"Rising Tides and New Opportunities"</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2><STRONG>Digital Revolution Creates New Opportunities</STRONG></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2><STRONG>Long-Term Efforts to Pass Securities<BR>Regulatory Reform And 
Litigation Reform Succeed</STRONG></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Boca Raton, FL</STRONG> -- 1996 has been a year when the cost of capital for issuers was low, investors continued to reap the rewards of lower interest rates and high stock prices, and the securities industry will break 1993's "career year" of pre-tax profits, according to the Securities Industry Association President Marc E. Lackritz.
<P>
<dd>Lackritz reviewed the performance of the association and the industry at SIA's annual meeting here, which continues through tomorrow, November 9. 
<P>
<dd>Lackritz emphasized that the industry is headed for a "career year," stating that "favorable market conditions have benefited issuers, investors and our industry."  The industry has raised more than $1 trillion in capital for U.S. businesses for the fifth consecutive year, and equity underwritings will likely break 1993's record.
<P>
<dd>Lackritz singled out the Congressional override of President Clinton's veto of federal securities litigation reform in December 1995 and Clinton's signing of the securities regulatory reform bill into law last month as victories for which the SIA had worked extensively over the past years.  Congress also passed laws to expand the availability of pensions by simplifying
their administration, improvements sought by SIA. 
<P>
<dd>Other legislative highlights included:  the increase in the amount a single-income couple can deposit in an Individual Retirement Account from $2,250 to $4,000; and relief for limited-purpose banks from the "temporary" seven-percent asset growth cap.
<P>
<dd>SIA, according to Lackritz, will continue to work to modernize the Glass-Steagall laws regulating financial services.  In looking towards the next Congress, he said, "A bipartisan group of House members intends to reintroduce legislation . . . that contains the key principles SIA has for financial services modernization: competition without federal subsidies, a full two-way street, and functional regulation."
<P>
<dd>SIA made progress in 1996 in achieving its goal to help establish a comprehensive regulatory fabric that enables the industry to use technology effectively and efficiently.  Citing the association's vital role in urging the wholesale review of the regulatory status of email, Lackritz called for the industry to "work with regulators to ensure that regulation doesn't strangle new technology in the crib."
<P>
<dd>To help members manage this change and create opportunities, SIA has added new services, including two new conferences -- "Internet Access" and "Retirement Savings."
<P>
<dd>These, and SIA's other initiatives, will help investors and the industry take advantage of the Digital Revolution and the enormous changes it is producing, according to Lackritz.  "As the economy and the financial marketplace continue to evolve and as new competitors emerge from every sector and every country, our advantage will be that we've taken the time to educate and guide our customers and clients through the maze of often intimidating and confusing information," Lackritz said.  "As long as we maintain investors' trust, we'll have the opportunity to continue adding value." 
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
For your information, <A HREF="sia09o.htm">Marc Lackritz's remarks</A> at the 1997 SIA Annual Meeting is available.
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
