<HTML>
<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Friday, November 8, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+3><B>SIA Board Approves Letter to SEC<BR>Recommending Modernization<BR>of Regulations to Improve Capital Raising</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P> 
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2><STRONG>Rapid Advances in Technology, Globalization and Markets<BR>Create 'Pressing Need' For Prompt Reforms</STRONG></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Boca Raton, FL</STRONG> -- The Board of Directors of the Securities Industry Association today approved a far-reaching comment letter setting out the industry's response to proposals being considered by the Securities and Exchange Commission to modernize and reform laws governing how securities are offered to investors.
<P>
<dd>"While the U.S. has a capital market and regulatory regime that are generally efficient, effective and the models for many other countries, continued review and vigilance to ensure that the system remains competitive and is as effective as possible are always in order," the letter to the SEC said.  The "character, pace and magnitude of fundamental changes in the capital formation process have created a pressing need for prompt reform of certain regulatory concepts and procedures."
<P>
<dd>On July 31 this year, the SEC sought comments in response to a  "concept release."  The SEC identified five "concepts central to the regulation of securities offerings."  These are:  the quality of ongoing disclosure; the manner in which investors are informed; the timeliness of disclosure of transaction-specific information; the role of "gatekeepers;" and, the process of SEC staff review of filings.
<P>
<dd>The SEC release also requested comments on seven specific proposals for reform.  These include:  the company registration model proposed in the report of the SEC Advisory Committee; recommendations of the Task Force on Disclosure Simplification relating to the shelf-registration system; and, the expansion of Rule 144A, which allows private placements to qualified institutional buyers.
<P>
<dd>In its letter (a summary of the main points is attached) to the SEC, SIA's Capital Markets Committee identifies areas in which the need for reform is most urgent, and makes a number of suggestions for reforms.  These include:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>expand and improve Rule 144A by widening the class of qualified buyers, narrowing the definition of fungible securities and deregulating offers of Rule 144A securities;
<LI>broaden the safe harbor for Rule 144 resales of restricted securities;
<LI>permit "testing the waters" with the participation of a registered broker-dealer and modify existing positions of the SEC staff with respect to integration of private placements that follow attempted public offerings;
<LI>liberalize the restrictions on distributing research and other written information by expanding the safe harbors provided by Rules 134, 135, 138, and 139;
<LI>eliminate restrictions on bona fide press activities, wherever conducted, and extend the proposed safe harbor for offshore press activities to cover activities in the U.S.;
<LI>minimize the market timing issues associated with SEC staff review of registration statements by eliminating review in many circumstances and by creating a separate branch of the SEC with responsibility for fostering innovation in the U.S. securities markets through prompt review and approval of novel securities;
<LI>adopt certain disclosure enhancements to improve the quality of issuers' periodic reports under the Exchange Act, including greater focus by the SEC staff on defining disclosure requirements for periodic reports through the publication of guidelines for various categories of issuers and businesses;
<LI>adopt more equitable standards of underwriters' liability to reflect changes that have occurred in the role played by underwriters since the liability standards were adopted 60 years ago; and,
<LI>facilitate the settlement process by decoupling prospectus delivery from confirmation delivery.
</UL>

<P>
<dd>The letter to the SEC also indicates that SIA believes that the company registration model proposed by the SEC Advisory Committee on Capital Formation and Regulatory Processes should not be adopted.  SIA believes that most of the benefits of the company registration proposal can be achieved more simply, more expeditiously and at less cost by implementing the suggestions set forth in the letter.
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
