<HTML>
<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Thursday, November 7, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jsparre@hillandknowlton.com">Janet Sparre</A>
<dd><A HREF="mailto:pthomas@hillandknowlton.com">Paul Thomas</A>
<dd>Hill and Knowlton
<dd>212-885-0300 
<P>
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+3><B>Brokers Receive High Satisfaction<BR>Ratings from Investors,<BR>According to Annual Investor Survey</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2>Concerns of Conflict of Interest Between Investors and Brokers,<BR>and Call for More Investor Education, Among Study's Findings</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd>Ninety-four percent of investors with brokerage accounts registered satisfaction with their brokers, according to the Securities Industry Associations second annual Investor Survey, conducted by Yankelovich Partners, and released November 7, 1996.  The high rating is comparable with last years results.
<P>
<dd>These same investors had a favorable perception of the securities industry, with 63 percent having a favorable view of the industry, 19 percent unfavorable and 18 percent not sure.  These results are also comparable with last year.
<P>
<dd>At the same time, the survey found that 71 percent of investors believe the services provided by brokerage firms are a good value for the money, an increase of eight percentage points over the 1995 results.
<P>
<dd>"The fact that the industry rating is lower than the individual broker rating is not surprising," said Hal Quinley, Yankelovich Partners, the independent research firm that conducted the research.  "The results are consistent with research of other industries.  People rate their individual doctor or congressman higher than the medical profession or government.  The proportion of investors who find value with the services of brokerage firms is well above average for customer groups."
<P>
<dd>Investors who do not currently have a brokerage account rate the industry somewhat lower than those with brokers, with 45 percent registering a favorable view of the industry, 23 percent unfavorable and 32 percent not sure.
<P>
<dd>Investors most often cited "greed," "putting own interests ahead of investors interests" and "reluctance to punish wrongdoers" as "big problems" for the industry.
<P>
<dd>The survey shows that investors continue to have a deep interest in more extensive investor education and professional advice.  Seventy-six percent of investors said the securities industry should do more to educate the public about investing, and 68 percent believe that investing is so complicated that they need professional advice now more than ever.
<P>
<dd>"These survey results provide a valuable picture of investor attitudes," said A.B. "Buzzy" Krongard, chairman of the SIA and chief executive officer of Alex. Brown & Sons Incorporated in Baltimore.  "We are pleased that the high satisfaction ratings first identified last year have been confirmed, but, clearly, the industry has much work to do to address investor concerns, particularly of perceived conflicts of interests between investors and brokers.
<P>
<dd>"The survey reassures us that we are on the right track in endorsing industry best practices with respect to client rights and responsibilities, compensation practices, supervision and compliance," he said.
<P>
<dd>The survey also confirms the SIAs commitment to developing more comprehensive investor education programs and programs for industry professionals.
<P>
<dd>The 1996 SIA Investor Survey, the industrys only comprehensive research that tracks investor opinion, explored in further detail some topics covered in the 1995 study, in addition to addressing new issues affecting the securities industry.  Topics such as overall preparedness for retirement, the growth of using computers for electronic trades and broker loyalty were explored in further detail.
<P>
<dd>When asked what they liked most about their brokers services, investors responded "good service/responds promptly" (30 percent), "provides information/makes me knowledgeable" (28 percent) and "convenience/consolidation/helps me understand the investments I have" (18 percent).
<P>
Other key findings of the 1996 SIA Investor Survey include:
<P>
<B>Investor Preparedness</B>
<UL>
<LI>More than one-third of young investors (36 percent) say they do not feel financially prepared to be able to retire when they want, and 30 percent feel they are not prepared to help take care of their aging parents.
</UL>
<B>Financial Planning</B>
<UL>
<LI>Interestingly, three-in-five investors (58 percent) do not have written financial plans setting forth their goals and how to achieve them, and two in five investors who do not have written financial plans (39 percent) say they think that they should have one.
<LI>Among investors with a written financial plan, investors turn to financial planners (19 percent) and brokers (18 percent) most for investment advice; however, an equal number (18 percent) create their own financial plans.
</UL>
<B>Views Toward Brokers/Loyalty/Securities Industry</B>
<UL>
<LI>One of 10 investors who have used a broker have ever had a serious problem or  complaint with their broker.  Slightly more than half of the investors with a complaint (53 percent) report that the complaint occurred in the past five years.
<LI>Fewer than four in 10 investors (39 percent) who had a complaint about their broker report that they are satisfied with the resolution of their problem.  In fact, 34 percent say they are very unsatisfied with the resolution, with another 13 percent being somewhat unsatisfied.
<LI>More than half of investors (53 percent) say they feel more loyalty to their brokers than to their brokerage firms.
<LI>About the same proportion of investors chose the commission and flat fee as their preferred fee structure (44 percent and 43 percent, respectively).
</UL>
<B>Use of On-line Investing Services</B>
<UL>
<LI>The use of on-line investing services has nearly tripled since 1995.  More than one-third of investors (35 percent) report using computers to obtain investment information, and 7 percent of investors report having used computers to make investment trades.  One year ago, only 13 percent of investors reported having used an on-line service for obtaining investment information or making trades.
<LI>Investors who use computers to make trades say, on average, that about half of the trades they made in the last year (48 percent) were made using computers.  One in five say all the trades they made in the last year were by computer.
<LI>Three-quarters of those investors who have made trades through computers (77 percent) describe this as "very" or "fairly" useful to them.
<LI>Though one-quarter of those who do not use computers to make investment trades indicate they are likely to do this in the next 12 months, nearly one-third (32 percent) say that this is something they will definitely not do.
</UL>
<P>
<dd>The SIA Investor Survey is based on the results of telephone interviews conducted with 1,500 investors nationwide from August 27 to September 22, 1996.  Investors were asked about their views on issues that affect their investing decisions, including the qualities they seek in brokerage services, securities industry issues and use of on-line investing services.
<P>
<dd>The sample group consisted of investors with household incomes of $50,000 and above and investable assets of $100,000 or more (excludes homes; includes 401(k)/IRAs).  Random digit dialing was used to ensure that both unlisted and listed telephone numbers had an equal probability of being selected.  Sample error for the group is plus or minus 2.5 percent.
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 760 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA member -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S., SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50 million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrifts and pension plans.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
For your information and use, SIA's 1996 Investor Survey  --  <A HREF="sia06a2.htm">Highlights of Key Findings</A> is available.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia04.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Press Releases"></A>
</BODY>
</HTML>
