<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Thursday, November 7, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+3><B>First Stock Market Game Teams<BR>Trading on Internet</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2><STRONG>Securities Firms To Use Game To Train Employees</STRONG></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Boca Raton, FL</STRONG> -- More than 25,000 students and adults began playing SMG2000<FONT  SIZE=-1><SUP>TM</SUP></FONT>, the Internet version of the Stock Market Game, on September 30.  The ten-week session will end on December 13.
<P>
<dd>Using a computer linked to the Internet, adults and student teams manage hypothetical $100,000 portfolios.  They are able to conduct hypothetical stock purchases and sales and access research reports on companies and other information to help guide them in their investment decisions.
<P>
<dd>"The Stock Market Game is now firmly in the digital age," said Richard Brueckner, a Managing Director at Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette, Inc. and Chairman of the Securities Industry Foundation for Economic Education (SIFEE).  "The response to SMG2000<FONT  SIZE=-1><SUP>TM</SUP></FONT> from both schools and adults has been overwhelmingly positive."
<P>
<dd>The game is being demonstrated to representatives of the Securities Industry Association's member firms this week during the association's annual meeting, which continues here through Saturday, November 9.  Brueckner will address the meeting today on SMG2000<FONT  SIZE=-1><SUP>TM</SUP></FONT>.
<P>
<dd>Members will be offered the game to use as a training tool, teaching their new employees about the securities markets through the simulated trading.  "Even people with a basic knowledge of the securities industry can benefit from participating in SMG2000<FONT  SIZE=-1><SUP>TM</SUP></FONT>," said Brueckner.
<P>
<dd>More than 4,200 teams nationwide are playing, as well as 287 adults.  As of October 23, participants had traded $304 million in 16,552 transactions.  "As the roll-out process continues, and as more classrooms are connected to the Internet, we expect an increasing number of individuals and students will take advantage of this opportunity," Brueckner said.  SMG2000<FONT  SIZE=-1><SUP>TM</SUP></FONT> is currently available in 36 states.
<P>
<dd>Registration information can be obtained by accessing the program's <A HREF=http://www.smg2000.org>home page</A>.  The public can receive a free brochure by sending a self-addressed stamped envelope (32 cents) to: SMG2000<FONT  SIZE=-1><SUP>TM</SUP></FONT>, Securities Industry Foundation for Economic Education; 120 Broadway, 35th Fl., New York, NY 10271-0800.	
<P>
<dd>Developed in 1977, the Stock Market Game was originally a classroom teaching tool for educating students in grades 4 through 12 about the financial markets.  Since then, more than 5.5-million students have participated in the game, learning how to research companies' finances, track a stock's performance, and build and manage a portfolio of investments. 
<P>
<dd>SIFEE is the creator and sponsor of the Stock Market Game.  Local securities industry professionals offer their assistance and resources in supporting the program through the foundation.  The program's supporters include the New York and American Stock exchanges, the Nasdaq Stock Market, National Council on Economic Education, Newspapers in Education programs, and Standard and Poor's Corp.  
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
