<HTML>
<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Thursday, November 7, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+3><B>SIA Chairman Krongard Opens SIA's<BR>25th Annual Meeting</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2><STRONG>Outlines Industry Accomplishments in Gaining Litigation,<BR>Regulatory Reforms; Adopting 'Best Practices';<BR>Promoting Pro-Technology Policies</STRONG></FONT></CENTER>  
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+2><STRONG><CENTER>Announces Survey Showing Investors Consider<BR>Brokerage Services 'Good Value'</CENTER></STRONG></FONT>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Boca Raton, FL</STRONG> -- In opening its 25th annual meeting here today, the Chairman of the Securities Industry Association outlined the industry's major legislative and regulatory accomplishments this year and called on securities firms to continue strengthening their professional and investor education programs.
<P>
<dd>"In addition to educating ourselves, we must educate the public," said A. B. "Buzzy" Krongard, Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of Alex. Brown & Sons Incorporated.  "The more the public understands what we do, the better it will be for them and for us."
<P>
<dd>The need for more efforts to educate investors, he said, is one of the findings of an investor survey by Yankelovich Partners, which SIA released today.  Seventy-six percent of the investors surveyed said the securities industry should do more to educate the public about investing.
<P>
<dd>The survey, Krongard said, also found that more than half of the investors polled have "very" or "somewhat" favorable opinions of the securities industry as a whole, and 94 percent of those with brokers are "very" or "somewhat" satisfied with their individual broker.  Seventy-one percent think brokers' services are "good value for the money," up from 63 percent a year ago.
<P>
<dd>"We must, however, concentrate on those areas which the survey highlighted as needing more of our attention," Krongard said.  About one in five investors hold a "very" or "somewhat unfavorable" opinion of our industry.  When asked why, the most frequently cited reason was fraud, bribery and dishonesty, followed by greed, excessive compensation and overcharging.
<P>
<dd>"What we learn from this is that much remains to be done," Krongard said.  "We are in a race without a finish line.  Thus we shall . . . energize our efforts to promote within our industry those standards of conduct commensurate with total client satisfaction." 
<P>
<dd>Towards that end, Krongard said, SIA's Board of Directors endorsed a series of "best practices" during the last year.  These cover client rights, confirmation statements, customer complaint procedures, sales supervision and hiring policies, compliance, and operations.
<P>
<dd>Issuers and shareholders, Krongard said, promise to benefit from the enactment last year of significant reforms in federal securities litigation laws.  This is a "much-needed antidote to the avalanche of meritless suits filed by avaricious plaintiffs' attorneys whose extortive and parasitic actions debase our capital markets," he said.
<P>
<dd>Defeat of a California ballot initiative (Proposition 211) earlier in the week, he said, prevents trial lawyers from undoing the progress made through the federal reforms.  If the measure passes, the number of frivolous class action lawsuits filed in California state courts would have skyrocketed, and affected companies nationwide.
<P>
<dd>Other accomplishments in 1996, Krongard said, were: the securities regulatory reforms contained in the National Securities Markets Improvement Act; stopping New York City's practice to calculate the Alternative Minimum Tax based on officers' compensation; and formation of a board committee on technology.
<P>
<dd>"We have a new Congress and, perhaps, a different political environment," Krongard said.  "We have to sort through a variety of significant changes in the dealer marketplace and learn to operate under changed procedures.  We have the Year 2000 and its accompanying technology issues.  We shall have moved closer to the prophesied Social Security meltdown and have still to provide a suitable solution or alternative.
<P>
<dd>"Permeating all these new challenges are the same ones we have faced since 1792 when our ancestors gathered around the buttonwood tree.  How do we prosper in an industry fraught with risk, subject to frequent and violent change and utterly demanding of one's physical, mental and emotional commitment?  I don't quite know the answer but I do know that in this room is the intelligence, integrity, energy, and drive to meet these challenges," Krongard said.
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
