<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Thursday, November 7, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+3><B>SIA Publishes Innovative Guide to Help Investors<BR>Learn about Stocks, Bonds, Retirement Planning</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2><STRONG>Latest in Securities Industry's Investor Education Initiatives</STRONG></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Boca Raton, FL</STRONG> -- At its annual meeting here, the Securities Industry Association  today introduced its <I><A HREF="sia06d.htm#guide">Guide To Understanding Investing</A></I>, the latest in a series of industry initiatives to help investors learn about financial markets and investing basics.
<P>
<dd>"Americans are investing in stocks, bonds, and mutual funds in record numbers, many for the first time," said Marc E. Lackritz, SIA's President.  "The securities industry is committed to educating this new generation of investors.  The guide, SIA's other initiatives, and the educational efforts of our member firms are all designed to help investors learn what they need to make the financial decisions that are right for them, their families, businesses, and communities."
<P>
<dd>SIA worked with Lightbulb Press -- pioneers in such financial publications as the best-selling <I>Wall Street Journal</I> guides -- to develop a comprehensive book for new and more experienced investors.  SIA's guide provides a clear and concise survey of the information investors need, including detailed chapters on stocks, bonds, mutual funds, and futures and options.  Readers will also learn how to spot trends, evaluate companies, and prepare for 
retirement.
<P>
<dd>Colorful graphics and easy-to-read examples are used to explain simple and complex investing strategies, retirement plans and federal tax laws.
<P>
<dd>"Our guide takes readers behind the scenes to see how stocks and bonds raise money for companies to finance growth," said Lackritz.  "Readers will learn how securities are priced and traded and how to monitor the performance of their investments.  Throughout the book are many examples to show the risks and rewards of investing." 
<P>
<dd>The guide is available for $12, payable by check or money order to:  Securities Industry Association; 120 Broadway, 35th Floor; New York, NY  10271-0080;  Attn.:  Guide.    For bulk prices, contact SIA's Publications Office at (212) 608-1500.
<P>
<dd>The guide's announcement was made during the association's annual meeting here, which runs until Saturday, November 9.  SIA initiatives to educate investors will be highlighted during the meeting, which focuses on "New Investors, New Markets, New Ideas."
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
