<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Wednesday, November 6, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+3><B>Securities Industry's 25th Annual Meeting,<BR>Opening Today, to Focus on 'New Investors,<BR>New Markets, New Ideas'</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2><B>Program Includes:  SEC Chairman, Market Analysts,<BR>Political Pundits, Stock Market Heads,<BR>Chairmen of Intuit and Lucent Technologies</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Boca Raton, FL </STRONG> -- More than 700 executives begin gathering here today for the Securities Industry Association's 25th annual meeting, which will focus on "New Investors, New Markets, and New Ideas."
<P>
<dd>"We will look at the economic and political outlook following the Presidential election, at significant changes in investor attitudes and behavior, and at extraordinary developments in technology and their impact on our business," said A. B. Krongard, SIA's 1996 Chairman.
<P>
<dd>Krongard will open the meeting's general session at 9:15 a.m. on Thursday, November 7, outline SIA's key accomplishments during the past year and provide his insights on new challenges.  He will also release the results of a Yankelovich Partners survey of investor attitudes towards the securities industry.
<P>
<dd>A panel discussion on the 1996 election results will follow Krongard's speech, with Eleanor Clift, a contributing editor at <I>Newsweek</I>, and Robert Novak, a political columnist.  Marc E. Lackritz, SIA's President, will moderate.
<P>
<dd>Abby Joseph Cohen, Vice President and Co-Chair, Investment Policy Committee, Goldman, Sachs & Co.; Gail M. Dudack, Managing Director and Chief Investment Strategist, UBS Securities Inc.; and Byron Wien, Managing Director, Morgan Stanley & Co. Incorporated, will discuss the outlook for financial markets and the economy during a panel session led by Karen P. Gibbs, a CNBC anchor and specialist.
<P>
<dd>The opening of the Stock Market Game to more participants through the Internet will be discussed by Richard F. Brueckner, Chairman of the Board and Chief Executive Officer, Securities Industry Foundation for Economic Education, and Managing Director, Pershing Division of Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette, Inc. 
<P>
<dd>Arthur Levitt, Jr., Chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, will explore issues confronting the SEC and the securities industry.
<P>
<dd>From 12:40 until 1:40 p.m., Thursday, there will be three "mini-conferences."  Stuart J. Kaswell, SIA Senior Vice President and General Counsel, will chair a panel discussion on securities legislation and regulation.  Steve Judge, SIA Senior Vice President for Government Affairs, will lead a discussion on Federal fiscal policy and tax reform.  Hal Quinley of Yankelovich Partners will lead a discussion on the Investor Survey.
<P>
<dd>Friday's session will begin with a discussion at 7:45 a.m. on the coming Social Security "crunch" and its meaning to financial markets.  Robert C. Pozen, Managing Director and General Counsel, Fidelity Investments, will describe the coming "crunch," the reform options that will be publicly debated next year, and the implications for financial markets and the national economy.
<P>
<dd>SIA President Marc E. Lackritz will open Friday's general session at 9:15 a.m. by outlining the industry's major issues and SIA's role.
<P>
<dd>Scott Cook, Chairman of Intuit, will follow.  He will share his unique perspective on the ways in which technology is changing the way we live and work while spurring economic growth, globalization, and the restructuring of many industries.
<P>
<dd>The annual meeting's focus on technology and the securities industry will continue with a panel led by Daniel H. Case, III, President and Chief Executive Officer, Hambrecht & Quist LLC.  The panel's participants will be:  Christos M. Cotsakos, President and Chief Executive Officer, E*TRADE Group, Inc.; Beth Sawi, Executive Vice President, The Charles Schwab Corporation; Kenneth S. Spirer, First Vice President -- Assistant General Counsel, Merrill Lynch, Pierce, Fenner & Smith Incorporated; and, Bert Winemiller, President and Chief Executive Officer,  Research Ltd.  The panel will focus on alternative distribution channels for electronic brokerage, research and primary distribution.
<P>
<dd>The reorganization of the National Association of Securities Dealers and what it means  to the securities industry will be focus of a panel discussion moderated by Joseph R. Hardiman, President and CEO, NASD.  Al Berkeley, President, The Nasdaq Stock Market, Inc., and Mary L. Schapiro, President, NASD Regulation, Inc. will be the panelists.
<P>
<dd>A look at the future of the mutual funds business will be moderated by John L. Steffens, Executive Vice President, Private Client, Merrill Lynch & Co., Inc.  Jon S. Fossell, Chairman, Investment Company Institute and Chairman, Oppenheimer Funds Inc.; Edward C. Johnson, III, Chairman and Chief Executive Officer, Fidelity Investments; and A. Michael Lipper, President, Lipper Analytical Securities Corp., will offer their views on what we can expect over the short- and long-term.
<P>
<dd>"A Brave New World or Jurassic Park?"  That's the question that Donald B. Marron, Chairman and Chief Executive Officer, PaineWebber Group, Inc., will answer in his speech, which closes out Friday's general session.
<P>
<dd>On Saturday, November 9, the general session opens at 8:00 a.m. with a look at the year ahead in the securities industry and the challenges SIA faces by James F. Higgins, SIA's 1997 Chairman.
<P>
<dd>Richard A. Grasso, Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of the New York Stock Exchange, will also focus on the major challenges facing the securities industry and the NYSE.
<P>
<dd>Irving Weiser, Chairman, President and Chief Executive Officer, Inter-Regional Financial Group, will discuss the industry's progress in dealing with clients, professionalism, and the highest standards of integrity.  Weiser chairs SIA's Public Trust and Confidence Committee.
<P>
<dd>Henry P. Schacht, Chairman, Lucent Technologies, Inc., will close the meeting by providing his views on the opportunities arising from advances in communications and technology.
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
