<HTML>
<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Tuesday, November 5, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT  SIZE=+3>SIA: Investors, Issuers Won Victory<BR>in Defeat of Proposition 211</FONT>
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=+2>Averted 'Gold Rush' of Frivolous Lawsuits in California Courts<BR>That Would Have Killed Jobs, Raised Costs to Expand Business</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, D.C.</STRONG> -- The Securities Industry Association released the following statement today following the defeat of a California ballot initiative (Proposition 211) that would have made it easier for trial lawyers to file frivolous class-action lawsuits.
<P>
<dd>"Investors and issuers scored a tremendous victory today with the defeat of Proposition 211.  Had this initiative been passed, companies and their shareholders throughout the country would have soon been attacked with frivolous class-action lawsuits designed solely to enrich lawyers.  The initiative would have allowed trial lawyers to use California courts to bypass important reforms in federal securities litigation laws that have reduced frivolous lawsuits since December last year.  Defeat of 211 results from a broad coalition of seniors, small businesses, high-technology companies, taxpayers, financial services firms, and others.  For California and the country to prosper, it is important that the costs of capital are kept low and competitive worldwide.  Frivolous lawsuits raise the costs of capital, making it more expensive and, hence more difficult, for businesses to grow and create more jobs.
<P>
<dd>"211's defeat resulted from the hard work of a broad coalition of federal and state officials, seniors groups, high-tech companies, accounting firms, shareholders, and securities firms.  The opposition voiced by Presidential candidates Bill Clinton and Bob Dole, SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt, all six living former SEC chairmen, and  U.S. Senator Dianne Feinstein was equally important in defeating 211."
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia04.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Press Releases"></A>
</BODY>
