<HTML>
<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Tuesday, November 5, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>Records in Underwriting, Stock Trading Volume<BR>
<FONT  SIZE=4>Return on Equity Promises Another Career Year For Securities Industry</FONT></B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Boca Raton, FL </STRONG> -- 1996 promises to be another "career year" for the securities industry as underwriting in stocks sets a new record pace, dollar and share volume climb to levels above last year's all-time highs, and return on equity surpass 1993's record.
<P>
<dd>"Many people thought 1993 was a unique year, and one that the industry would have difficulty matching," said Jeffrey Schaefer, SIA's Senior Vice President for Economic Research.  "All the indicators point to a year when the industry has focused on its traditional lines of business -- underwriting, commissions, and trading -- and thrived.  And firms have been especially successful in exploring new areas, including those outside the United States, for sources of revenue." 
<P>
<B><CENTER>Productive Year For Underwriting Activities</CENTER></B>
<P>
<dd>The year has been marked by vibrant merger and acquisition activity, and an explosive nine months for initial public offerings.  While the 603 initial public offerings through September have already exceeded 1995's figure by 5%, the industry's annualized rate for 1996 of $46.9 billion is already 56% more than 1995's total and is 13% higher than the full year 1993 record amount.  Merger and acquisition activity is expected to bring in $496 billion in 1996, nearly three times 1993's figure.
<P>
<dd>"This year's strong equity market has made it more conducive for firms to raise equity capital rather than debt to finance expansion," Schaefer said.  "These deals are easier for the firms to bring to market in 1996, and more profitable for the industry."
<P>
<dd>International IPO's livened up an already brisk market, with 63 deals raising $6.1 billion on an annualized basis based on the first nine months; this included an $870 million offering by Gucci and a $339 million offering by Korea Mobile Telecommunications Corp.  This year's pace is 22 percent ahead of last year's, when 45 deals raised $5.0 billion, but 12 percent behind the record set in 1994, when 41 deals raised $7.0 billion.   
<P>
<dd>"The Deutsche Telekom privatization should ensure that this is near 1994's record year for underwriting of non-U.S. initial public offerings," Schaefer said.  "Top non-U.S. companies are selecting the U.S. for their offerings, either in conjunction with a domestic listing or, sometimes, singly.  
<P>
<CENTER><B>Stock Mutual Funds Continue To Boost Market</B></CENTER>
<P>
<dd>Investors' attraction to stock mutual funds increased, as they poured $228.7 billion into them through September 1996 on an annualized basis.  This inflow, added to appreciation, raised the total amount held in stock mutual funds to $1.6 billion, 48% of all mutual fund assets.
<P>
"Investors -- who a few years ago would have squirreled their money away in CDs at their banks, or in money market funds -- are plunging into equity mutual funds," said Schaefer.  "The industry is educating people to the benefits of stock ownership as part of an overall savings plan." 
<P>
<dd>Foreign investors found U.S. equities attractive, as they acquired $6.9 billion in the second quarter of 1996 alone.  And securities firms continue to make it easy for Americans to diversify their portfolios globally,  especially through depositary receipt programs, which raised nearly $6.6 billion in equity capital in the first half of 1996 alone.  U.S. holdings of foreign equities now stand at a record $488 billion.
<P>
<CENTER><B>Regionals Post Strong Return on Equity</B></CENTER>
<P>
<dd>Regional firms posted an especially strong gain in return-on-equity for 1996's first half,  rising from 34% in 1995 to 49% in the first half of 1996.  "These firms were especially well-positioned to take advantage of the strong inflow of money into equities, and the rise in the market," said Schaefer.  "Their income comes primarily from commissions and retail business."    
<P>
<dd>The industry overall posted a record 1990s pre-tax return on equity of 34.8% for the first half of 1996.  "The securities industry has outperformed other areas of business in a year of truly impressive gains in this area," stated Schaefer.  The previous record in the 1990s was 1993's 27.1%.  Pre-tax profits for the first half of the year were $6.7 billion, almost 80% of full year 1993's record $8.6 billion.
<P>
<CENTER><B>Trading Volume Continues Record Pace</B></CENTER>
<P>
<dd>Through September, average daily volume on the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq Stock Market, and American Stock Exchange all outpaced 1995's record levels.  The NYSE now handles 405-million shares a day, 17% more than in 1995; Nasdaq handles 541-million 
shares daily, 35% more than the 1995 figure; Amex's average daily volume is now 22.6-million shares, 13% more than 1995's average of 20 million.
<P>
<dd>Market capitalization on the NYSE grew 13%, from $6 trillion to $6.8 trillion, in the first nine months of 1996; in the same time period, Nasdaq's market capitalization grew 22% from $1.2 trillion to $1.4 trillion.  The American Stock Exchange's market cap grew 1.5%, from $137.3 billion to 139 billion.
<P>
<dd>The DJIA increased 15%, from 5117 to 5882, from January to September 30, 1996.
<P>
<B><CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+1>SELECTED INDUSTRY STATISTICS</FONT></CENTER></B>
<P>
<B><CENTER>U.S. UNDERWRITING ACTIVITY ($ Bils.)</CENTER></B>
<TABLE WIDTH=100%>
