<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Monday, November 4, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>SIA to Hold Conference on<BR>New Securities Regulation Reform Law <BR>
<FONT  SIZE=5>Thursday, January 9, New York Sheraton Hotel</FONT></B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, D.C. </STRONG> -- The Securities Industry Association will hold a <A HREF="nsmiapro.htm">one-day conference</A> at the Sheraton Hotel in New York City on Thursday, January 9, 1997, to discuss provisions of securities regulation reforms enacted recently by Congress.
<P>
<dd>The National Securities Markets Improvement Act of 1996 that President Clinton signed into law on October 11 eliminates unnecessary regulation and reduces the cost of raising capital without compromising important investor protections. 
<P>
<dd>The new law includes provisions that: remove restrictions on the sources of broker-dealer funding; broaden the exemptive authority of the Securities and Exchange Commission; promote better coordination among examination authorities; provide for qualified purchaser investment pools; establish federal pre-exemption for mutual funds and many other issuers; reduce regulatory burdens on many brokers and investment advisers; and reduce fees paid by market participants.
<P>
<dd>SIA's conference will include senior regulatory officials from the S.E.C., National 
Association of Securities Dealers, New York Stock Exchange, American Stock Exchange and several key states, as well as leaders from the securities industry and the securities bar.  The conference will explore the impact of the new law on state regulation;  federal preemption of issuer registration; venture capital; broker-dealers;  investment advisers; the Securities and Exchange Commission; and, self-regulatory  organizations.  A concluding panel will examine the prospects for additional securities regulatory reforms.
<P>
<dd>The cost to registrants from SIA member-firms is $270; $390 for employees of non-member firms.
<P>
<dd>For registration, hotel and other information, contact <A HREF="mailto:mbattista@sia.com">Mary Ann Battista</A> at (212) 618-0577.
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia04.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Press Releases"></A>
</BODY>
