<HTML>
<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Wednesday, October 30, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6><B>SIA Calls for Overhaul of Section 20 <BR>Firewalls rather than Piecemeal Approach</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, D.C.</STRONG> -- Steve Judge, Senior Vice President for Government Affairs for the Securities Industry Association, today issued the following statement in response to the decision today by the Federal Reserve:
<P>
<dd>"SIA believes that comprehensive modernization of the laws governing the financial services industry by Congress is the only means by which banks and securities firms (as well as insurance companies and other financial services providers) will be able to compete and affiliate on a fair and rational basis.  Today's action by the FRB on changes that will eliminate the crossmarketing and financial assets restrictions are not long-term solutions to the complicated competitive issues caused by the now-antiquated statutes regulating the financial services industry.  There is no compelling need for the FRB at this time to take piecemeal action such as eliminating firewalls that could jeopardize prospects for enacting comprehensive financial services modernization legislation in the next congress.
<P>
<dd>SIA strongly supports comprehensive financial modernization legislation that will promote competition among all financial services providers by enabling banks to own full-service securities firms and securities firms to own or affiliate with banks -- a "two-way street" -- as well as by ensuring that all financial providers be governed by consistent rules -- a policy of functional regulations."
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia04.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Press Releases"></A>
</BODY>
</HTML>
