<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Wednesday, October 23, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6><B>Strong U.S. Markets And Dollar Attract
<BR>Foreign Investment at Record Pace</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=5><B>Treasuries Remain Popular With Non-U.S. Investors</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>New York, NY</STRONG> -- Foreign investors found the U.S. securities markets extremely attractive in the first half of 1996, purchasing $143.2 billion worth of securities, according to the Securities Industry Association's Foreign Activity Report released today.  The first-half pace, if annualized, would exceed last year's record of $231.8 billion by 24%.
<P>
<dd>Purchases by foreign investors of U.S. equities during 1H96 accounted for more than $10.5 billion of the total, on track to match 1993's record $21.6 billion.  The second quarter accounted for nearly $6.9 billion of the total. 
<P>
<dd>"The almost steady climb of U.S. equity prices, combined with the recent strength of the U.S. dollar, has produced an inviting environment for foreign investors, who were missing for much of the late 1980s and 1990s," stated David Strongin, SIA's vice president and director, international finance.
<P>
<dd>As U.S. life insurance companies and pension funds divested their portfolios of U.S. Treasury securities, foreigners' affinity for Treasuries continued.  $75.3 billion of foreign capital was invested in Treasuries in the first half of 1996, easily exceeding acquisitions by U.S. investors.  Half of the amount came from central banks.
<P>
<dd>Americans took advantage of some impressive returns in foreign markets, investing almost $40 billion in foreign equities during the first half of 1996.  Japan continues to be the largest recipient of U.S. capital, receiving about $10.6 billion, or 27% of all foreign stock acquisitions, in the first half of 1996.  Total U.S. holdings of foreign equities rose to a record $488 billion as institutional investors aggressively diversified their holdings abroad.
<P>
<dd>Brazil, Mexico and Spain posted returns of 30.3%, 19.9% and 19.3% respectively, attracting the interest of U.S. investors.  Americans acquired $1.4 billion of Brazilian equities alone in the first half of the year; $817 million was acquired in the second quarter alone.
<P>
<dd>American depositary receipt programs continued to be well-received by investors, raising nearly $6.6 billion in equity capital.  This included an $870 million offering by Gucci and a $339 million offering by Korea Mobile.
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
