<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Tuesday, October 1, 1996</STRONG>
<P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6><B>SIA Lauds House, Senate Passage of <BR>Securities Law Reforms Overhaul to <BR>Benefit Investors, Lower Costs of Capital</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, D.C.</STRONG> -- Following the Senate's passage today of legislation (H.R. 3005, the "National Securities Markets Improvement Act of 1996") to reform state and federal securities regulations, Marc E. Lackritz, president of the Securities Industry Association, released the following statement:
<P>
<dd>"This effort -- the first major success in nearly 60 years to overhaul and modernize securities laws -- could not have been achieved without the leadership in the House and Senate of both parties and the particular support and dedication of Senators Alfonse D'Amato (R-NY), Chris Dodd (D-CT), Phil Gramm (R-TX), and Paul S. Sarbanes (D-MD), and Representatives Thomas J. Bliley, Jr. (R-VA), John Dingell (D-IL), Jack Fields (R-TX), and Edward J. Markey (D-MA).  This is an important bipartisan achievement for the 104th Congress."
<P>
<dd>"Needless, redundant and antiquated state and federal regulations add to the cost of capital, making it more expensive for companies to raise money to expand and create jobs, while reducing returns for investors.  The reforms approved by Congress -- which we urge, hope and expect the President to sign into law -- will clear away some of the regulatory underbrush that adds to the cost of capital without compromising investor protections."
<P>
<dd>"The bill's important accomplishments include:  allowing broker-dealers greater flexibility to borrow funds; establishing uniform standards for broker-dealer books and records requirements; improving the efficiency of regulation governing investment advisers; broadening the Securities and Exchange Commission's exemptive authority to address outdated or inconsistent statutes; enabling securities firms' mutual funds to produce readable prospectuses by eliminating redundant, inconsistent state regulations; and promoting meaningful coordination among examination authorities in conducting routine examinations."
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 760 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S., SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
For your information, an <A HREF="sia09p.htm">overview</A> of the National Securities Markets Improvement Act of 1996 is available.
