<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Wednesday, September 25, 1996</STRONG><P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6><B>SIA Lauds Financial Modernization Bill <BR>Introduced by Representative Roukema</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=5><CENTER>Bill Embraces SIA Principles:<BR>Open Competition, Functional Regulation, Taxpayer Protections</CENTER></FONT><P>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, D.C.</STRONG> -- Steve Judge, Senior Vice President and Director of Government Relations of the Securities Industry Association, released the following statement after Rep. Marge Roukema (R-N.J.) and eight other members of Congress today introduced the Depository Institution Affiliation and Thrift Charter Conversion Act.
<P>
<dd>"SIA supports comprehensive restructuring of the financial services industry in a manner that promotes fair competition among all financial services providers, protects U.S. taxpayers, and keeps the U.S. capital markets open, competitive and free. Today's introduction of a comprehensive bill to modernize the Depression-era laws governing the financial services industry is an important step forward in accomplishing the three goals SIA supports -- open competition, functional regulation and taxpayer protections.  The securities industry applauds the efforts by Representative Roukema and the bipartisan group of Members of Congress to develop this legislation and set out the framework for work to begin early next year .
<P>
<dd>"To be competitive in an increasingly global marketplace, the U.S. laws governing the financial services industry must be modernized in response to the major changes in the services that banks, securities firms and insurance companies provide to their clients worldwide.  The failure of Congress to enact comprehensive reform of Glass-Steagall, the main laws governing financial services regulation, has resulted in federal bank regulators and the courts haphazardly undertaking financial deregulation by administration fiat.      
<P>
<dd>"SIA believes that three principles must be embodied in any financial services reform legislation:  a two-way street, in which bank holding companies should be allowed to own full-service securities firms and securities firms should be able to own or affiliate with banks; that taxpayers must be protected by shrinking the scope of the activities which the federal deposit insurance safety net covers inside federally insured banks, particularly those engaged in securities and securities-related activities; and functional regulation, meaning that one federal agency applies the same set of rules to the same activity engaged in by any financial institution, no matter what the charter."
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 760 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S., SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
