<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Thursday, September 19, 1996</STRONG><P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret G. Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>New York City Mayor Giuliani and Donald Marron to Receive Travers J. Bell Memorial Award from SIA New York District Foundation</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>New York</STRONG> -- New York City Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani and Donald B. Marron, chairman and chief executive officer, PaineWebber Group Inc., will receive the Travers J. Bell Memorial Award of Distinction from the Securities Industry Association's New York District Economic Education Foundation at its annual awards dinner, October 29, 1996.
<P>
<dd>Mayor Giuliani and Mr. Marron are being honored for their continued efforts to support programs in economic education.
<P>
<dd>The Travers J. Bell Memorial Award of Distinction is named after the founder of the brokerage firm Daniels & Bell, Inc.  Mr. Bell became the first minority member of the New York Stock Exchange in 1971, and an associate member of the American Stock Exchange in 1975.  Mr. Bell was noted for his expertise in the securities industry, particularly in the area of public finance, and for his active interest in youth and economic education.  He served as chairman of the SIA New York District from 1987 until his death in January 1988.
<P>
<dd>The Annual Awards dinner will be held at the Waldorf Astoria in New York.  For more information, contact <A HREF="mailto:twolf@sia.com">Toby S. Wolf</A>, SIA New York District executive director, at (212) 618-0594.
<P>
<dd>Proceeds from the dinner help fund the foundation, which provides support for economic education, the SIA's Stock Market Game<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>TM</SUP></B></FONT> and other programs among students throughout the district.  
<P>
<dd>Developed in 1977, The Stock Market Game<FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>TM</SUP></B></FONT> was originally a classroom teaching tool for educating students in grades 4 through 12 about the financial markets.  Beginning September 30, both students and adults will be able to "click on to investing" through <A HREF=http://www.smg2000.org>SMG2000</A><FONT  SIZE=-1><B><SUP>TM</SUP></B></FONT>, the Game's new Internet-based version, enabling them to learn about investing and trading stocks, gain insights into events that shape the economy, and experience the stock market by managing their own portfolios.
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of 760 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<P>
<dd>SIA's New York District carries forward in New York and New Jersey the work of SIA in such areas as government relations and economic education.
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
