<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Thursday, September 12, 1996</STRONG><P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James Spellman</A>, SIA
<dd>(202) 296-9775								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:info@fiafii.org">Peter Burton</A>, FII
<dd>(202) 223-1528
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret G. Draper</A>, SIA
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>Treasury's Anderson to Join Gephardt, Stieglitz in Addressing <BR>Financial Derivatives Forum</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, DC</STRONG>  -- Roger Anderson, Deputy Assistant Secretary of the Treasury, will address the <I>Financial Derivatives: Risk, Return and Regulation</I> conference to be held in Washington, D.C. on Friday, September 20, 1996.  He joins the key Washington policy makers already set to address the conference:  House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt and Joseph Stieglitz, chairman of the President's Council of Economic Advisers.  David S. Broder, political analyst of <I>The Washington Post</I>, will provide luncheon remarks.
<P>
<dd>Among his responsibilities, Anderson oversees the Office of Federal Financial Policy Analysis, which is responsible for regulatory issues involving futures and related markets, government securities, alternative financing techniques, and clearing and settlement issues.  He will address issues pertaining to the Treasury Amendment of the Commodity Exchange Act.
<P>	
<dd>The Financial Derivatives conference will bring together industry participants, policy makers and the media to discuss developments and trends in the global marketplace and its regulation.  It is the third biannual meeting co-sponsored by the Futures Industry Institute and the Securities Industry Association.
<P>
<dd>In addition to key policy makers, this year's conference focuses on the end users of derivative instruments.  Participants include General Motors, The World Bank and Cargill Inc.  A panel discussion by derivatives industry officials titled "The Derivatives Revolution: Views from Wall Street" will also be featured in the <A HREF="fiiprog.htm"> conference program</A>.
<P>	
<dd>The conference will be held at the Willard Inter-Continental Hotel.  For more information, please contact Bridget Miller, FII, at (202) 223-1528 or return the conference <A HREF="fiireg.htm">registration form</A> by fax to (202) 296-3184.
<P>
<dd>The conference will be held at the Willard Inter-Continental Hotel.  The registration fee is $350 per person.  Membership in either organization is not required to attend.  For more information, contact:  Julie Greenway, FII, at (202) 223-1528 (fax: 202-296-3184, e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:info@fiafii.org">info@fiafii.org</A>) or Mary Kappa, SIA, at (202) 296-9410 (fax: 202-326-5349, e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:mkappa@sia.com">mkappa@sia.com</A>).
<P>
<dd>The Futures Industry Institute is a non-profit educational and training foundation whose purpose is to increase the understanding of the futures, options and other derivative markets.  The Securities Industries Association's membership comprises about 750 securities firms that collectively account for approximately 90 percent of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.
<P>
