<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Tuesday, September 3, 1996 1996</STRONG><P>				
Contact:								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret G. Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P><P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>SIA Urges Key Legislators to Run Homestretch Lap and Enact Securities Regulatory Reforms Bill</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=4><CENTER><B>Legislation Would Clear Away Regulatory Underbrush, Modernize Laws to Lower Cost of Capital, Promote Growth</B></CENTER></FONT>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, DC</STRONG>  -- The Securities Industry Association today urged key leaders in Congress -- Senator Alfonse M. D'Amato (R-NY), Rep. Thomas J. Bliley, Jr. (R-VA), Sen. Paul S. Sarbanes (D- MD) and Rep. John D. Dingell (D-MI) -- to enact significant securities regulatory reforms before Congress adjourns this year.<P>
<dd>"It would be very regrettable if, after months of hard work by many in Congress,  this major legislation were to die in the homestretch because of unnecessary delays," said the <A HREF="sia09k.htm">letter</A> signed jointly by SIA's President Marc Lackritz and a number of its member firms.<P>
<dd>"It would be particularly unfortunate if Congress missed the opportunity to eliminate antiquated restrictions on broker-dealers by repealing Section 8(a) of the Exchange Act and amending Section 7 to permit extensions of credit to market makers, underwriters and broker-dealers engaged in a securities business with customers," the letter said.  "It would help U.S. securities firms compete with other financial institutions and foreign competitors on a more even footing."<P>
<dd>The House and Senate both passed their versions of securities regulatory reform legislation before the August recess.  A conference committee was then formed to resolve differences between versions of the legislation that each house passed.  That committee resumes negotiations this week.<P>
<dd>SIA also urged the House and Senate conferees to include provisions in the legislation that would provide uniform federal standards in areas such as books and records requirements and uniform exemptions for secondary market trading.  Allowing states to have additional requirements that are inconsistent with each other and with federal requirements "simply adds unnecessary regulatory costs," the SIA said.<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S., SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
