<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Thursday, August 28, 1996</STRONG><P>				
Contact:								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret G. Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P><P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>SIA Comments SEC For Order Execution Rules</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=4><CENTER><B>SEC Accepts Modifications to Proposal That SIA Urged</B></CENTER></FONT>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, DC</STRONG>  --"SIA commends the Securities and Exchange Commission for its action on the order execution rules," said Stuart J. Kaswell, Senior Vice President and General Counsel.  "Although we have not seen the full text of the SEC's rules, we believe that the Commission is trying to steer a prudent course and are pleased they accepted a number of our recommendations.<P> 
<dd>Kaswell continued that "SIA is cautiously optimistic that the limit order display rule will improve price competition and market transparency.  We will need to examine closely the specifics of the rule, but we generally support improving display of customer limit orders under appropriate circumstances.  The SIA opposed requiring that size be mandated in limit order quotations and will be monitoring closely the impact that display of the full size of limit orders will have on the market."<P>
<dd>"SIA also supported the quote rule proposal and is pleased that the Commission adopted it," Kaswell noted.  He explained that "SIA will need to evaluate the new aspect of the rule that facilitates the use of electronic communications networks, a departure from the original proposal." <P>
<dd>Kaswell noted that "SIA strongly supports the ability of individual investors to participate in the marketplace on a fair basis; at the same time SIA notes that investors cannot get good execution of their orders if markets lack depth and liquidity.  Market makers have provided that crucial liquidity and must remain a vibrant part of the marketplace to ensure that investors orders are filled promptly and at fair prices.  SIA will be studying these proposals and monitoring their effects over the coming year."<P>
<dd>SIA had urged the Commission not to adopt the price improvement requirement as originally proposed because SIA believed that the proposal would be costly to the industry without any corresponding benefit to investors.  SIA is pleased that the Commission deferred action on that proposal and will evaluate how other portions of the rules operate," Kaswell said. <P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association ("SIA") is the trade association representing the business interests of about 750 securities firms in North America.  Its members include securities organizations of virtually all types--investment banks, brokers, dealers, and mutual fund companies, as well as other firms functioning on the floors of the exchange.  SIA members are active in all exchange markets, in the over-the-counter markets, and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  Collectively, they provide investors with a full spectrum of securities and investment services and account for 90% of securities firm revenue in the United States.<P> 
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
