<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Thursday, August 28, 1996</STRONG><P>				
Contact:								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret G. Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<P><P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>Stock Market Game Debuts This Fall on Internet</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT  SIZE=4><CENTER><B>Adults Will Join Students and "Click On To Investing"</B></CENTER></FONT>
<P>
<dd><STRONG>New York, NY</STRONG>  -- This fall, learning the fundamentals of financial markets will soon be as easy as clicking on your home computer's mouse.
<P>
<dd>Starting on Monday, September 30, adults in about 40 states can participate in The Stock Market Game<FONT  SIZE=-1><SUP> TM</SUP></FONT> to learn about investing and trading stocks, gain insights into events that shape the economy, and experience the stock market by managing their own portfolios.
<P>
<dd>"Bringing the Stock Market Program into the digital age will not only allow individuals and teams of students to participate, but give them access to newspaper articles, corporate web sites, and other information they need to make their investment decisions," said Richard Brueckner, a managing director at Donaldson, Lufkin and Jenrette.  Brueckner is also chairman and chief executive officer of The Securities Industry Foundation for Economic Education (SIFEE), the organization affiliated with the Securities Industry Association that administers the game.
<P>
<dd>Using a computer linked to the Internet, adults and student teams will manage hypothetical $100,000 portfolios.  They'll be able to conduct hypothetical stock purchases and sales and access research reports on companies and other information to help guide them in their investment decisions.
<P>
<dd>Each portfolio's value will be calculated automatically each business day.  Participants will also be kept informed of their current holdings, brokerage commissions, returns on their investments, and team ranking. 
<P>
<dd>During the ten-week period each spring and fall, the student teams and adults will vie to increase the value of their portfolios in comparison with other participants. 
<P>
<dd>Developed in 1977,  The Stock Market Game was originally a classroom teaching tool for educating students in grades 4 through 12 about the financial markets.  Since then, more than 5.5-million students have participated in the game, learning how to research companies' finances, track a stock's performance, and build and manage a portfolio of investments.  
<P>
<dd>To emphasize the new capabilities that the Internet link will provide, the program was renamed SMG2000.  The game will be rolled out on a state-by-state basis in the remaining areas of the country.
<P>
<dd>Registration information can be obtained by e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:sifee@sia.com">sifee@sia.com</A>, or by accessing the program's home page at <A HREF=http://www.smg2000.org>http://www.smg2000.org</A>.  The public can also write in for a free brochure by including a self-addressed stamped (32 cents) envelope:  SMG2000; Securities Industry Foundation For Economic Education; 120 Broadway, 35th Floor; New York, NY 10271-0800.
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S., SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.  
<P>  
