<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG> Tuesday, August 6, 1996</STRONG><P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=5><B>Record Share Volume, Sharp Rise in Stock Prices<BR>
Lead to 11.5 Percent Gain in Median RR Production, <BR>
8.6 Percent Gain in Median Earnings</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><B>New York, NY</B>  Record share volume on the nation's stock markets and the third largest price increase in stocks enjoyed by investors since World WarII combined to increase the retail production of registered representatives by 11.5 percent, leading to a 8.6-percent gain in their earnings, according to a survey by the Securities Industry Association. 
<P>
<dd>"The median retail production in 1995 totaled $203,034, an 11.5 percent gain from the previous year of $182,031," said  Jeffrey Schaefer, Senior Vice President and Director of Research for the SIA.  "This gain was attributed largely to an increase in the assets that registered representatives accrued under their management and the volume of transactions that they did.  Another factor was the increase in the value of stock outstanding last year  up $2.1 trillion to $8.3 trillion, a one-third increase from the total value of stocks in 1994."
<P>
<dd>"Earnings of most registered representatives are based primarily on commissions," Schaefer said.  "However, a growing number of firms are changing compensation practices, paying brokers based on  portfolio performance, assets managed, and other alternatives."
<P>
<dd>The median retail ticket for agency transactions in 1995 was $156, virtually unchanged from 1994, Schaefer noted.
<P>
<dd>The median retail payout  the percentage of commissions and other fees paid to registered representatives  stood at 43 percent, up slightly (.5 percentage points) from 1994.  
<P>
<dd>For retail registered representatives, median W-2 earnings grew 8.6 percent last year, from  $72,636 in 1994 to $78,856 in 1995.  The median branch manager W-2 earnings among the 33 firms providing responses was $196,000, 1.4 percent over the 1994 level of $193,368.  The median reflects the mid-point of earnings reported by the participating firms.
<P>
<dd>"Management at securities firms continues to show a deep commitment to controlling costs," said Schaefer.  He noted that in 1995, net revenues were up 13 percent for the industry, while net costs (total costs less interest expense) were up 9 percent.  While commission revenues increased 18.5percent and underwriting revenues 33percent (both figure in the compensation of RRs), the median percentage increase in RR earnings was 8.6percent.
<P>
<dd>The 1995 survey covered 53 SIA member firms, employing a combined 43,000 registered representatives.
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members  including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies  are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans. 
<P>
