<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG> Thursday, August 1, 1996</STRONG><P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=5><B>SIA Urges Democratic, Republican Platform Committees to Include Savings and Investment Incentives, International Tax Competitiveness Planks</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><B>Washington, D.C.</B> -- The Securities Industry Association today urged the Democratic and Republican Parties to include in their platforms several proposals to increase personal savings, reduce the cost of capital, encourage investment, and enhance the international competitiveness of the U.S. securities industry.
<P>
<dd>"For the United States economy to grow and prosper, our country needs to increase savings incentives to increase the capital available to established companies and entrepreneurs," said Marc E. Lackritz, SIA's president.  "The more capital that is made available, the lower its cost, which, in turn, increases the opportunities the securities industry creates for investors and companies."  
<P>
<dd>The proposals the SIA sent to both parties today, in short, call for: a broad-based capital gains tax cut; a better tax deal for savings held in Individual Retirement Accounts (IRAs); and, comprehensive reform of the U.S. tax laws affecting the international operations of U.S.-based securities firms. 
<P>
<B>Capital Gains Tax Cut Would Fuel Growth, Create Jobs</B>
<P>
<dd>SIA called on the platform committees to endorse a significant capital gains tax reduction (a top marginal rate of 15 to 20 percent, which is down from the current 28 percent) to stimulate economic growth, create new and better jobs, and promote savings. 
<P>
<dd>This initiative would reduce capital costs, benefit the middle class, encourage entrepreneurs, raise tax receipts, promote U.S. savings, and dampen the impact of inflation, according to the SIA.
<P>
<dd>In advocating this proposal, the SIA cited a study showing that a capital gains tax rate of 15 to 20 percent would reduce the cost of capital by 4 to 8 percent.  Another study, the SIA said, concluded that the costs of capital would fall by almost 12 percent if Congress adopted a 50-percent cut in the current capital gains tax rate (bringing the maximum rate to 19.8 percent), inflation indexing of capital gains for individuals, and a  reduction in the corporate capital gains tax rate (from 35 to 25 percent). 
<P>
<dd>Cuts in the capital gains tax would particularly benefit middle-class taxpayers, the SIA said, noting that 30 percent of the value of all capital assets in 1989 (excluding housing) were owned by families with incomes of $50,000 or less.
<P>
<dd>"Savings are unfairly taxed more than once, first, when income is earned and again when interest and dividends on the investment financed by saving are received, or when capital gains from the investment are realized," the SIA said. "The playing field is tilted [against savings] because the individual or company that saves and invests pays more taxes over time than if all income is consumed and no saving takes place.  Taxes on income that is saved raise the capital cost of new productive investment for both individuals and corporations, thus dampening such investment.  As a result, future growth in productivity and living standards is impaired."
<P>
<B>Better Tax Deal For IRAs for All Americans</B>
<P>
<dd>SIA asked both political parties to seek a full deduction from individuals' tax bills of contributions to Individual Retirement Accounts.  IRAs allow individuals to accumulate savings with no taxation of capital gains, dividends and interest payments until the funds are withdrawn upon retirement.  Contributions can only be deducted from income before taxes are calculated for families with annual incomes under $40,000, and individuals with annual income under $25,000.   
<P>
<dd>SIA also called for a better IRA deal for single-income couples.  Under current law, a couple with two wage-earners can contribute $4,000 to an IRA, but a single-income couple can only contribute $2,250.  SIA advocates the cap being raised to $4,000 for  single-income couples.
<P>
<dd>The savings accumulated by Americans, the SIA said, have fallen sharply during the last decade, with Americans now saving only 4.6 percent of their disposable income.  
Aging Baby Boomers have saved on average only one-third of the money they will need to retire comfortably.   
<P>
<dd>If IRAs could be fully deducted from the income used to compute federal taxes, one study the SIA noted estimates that 64 percent of Americans would increase their savings.  When IRAs were fully tax deductible, more than $38 billion was deposited in IRA accounts between 1985 and 1986.   In 1987, the year that federal tax breaks were cut, IRA contributions fell to $15 billion and have further decreased since then, hovering at about $10.5 billion yearly.
<P>
<dd>Research, the SIA said, shows that IRA contributions generate new savings.  One study estimates that 45 to 66 percent of increased IRA contributions come at the expense of current consumption. If the incentives to IRAs were improved, the SIA said the U.S. would see a real improvement in the ability of Americans to finance their future."
<P>
<B>International Tax Reforms Essential to Industry Competitiveness</B>
<P>
<dd>The SIA called on the Platform Committees to advocate comprehensive reform of the provisions of U.S. tax laws affecting the international operations of U.S.-based  securities firms. 
<P>
<dd> "The federal income tax system poses a significant barrier to the ability of U.S. companies to compete globally with foreign-owned financial institutions," the SIA said.  "Foreign securities firms operate under simpler, fairer and more logical tax regimes.  As a result, foreign securities firms have a lower cost of doing business than do U.S. firms."
<P>
<dd>Two particular areas, the SIA said, are:  1) provisions requiring the current inclusion of certain business income earned by foreign subsidiaries of U.S.-domiciled securities firms;  and 2) double taxation resulting from interest expense allocation rules under the federal tax code that impair the ability of U.S.-domiciled financial institutions to use credits for taxes paid in other capital market centers that are high tax jurisdictions.  
<P>
The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
For a complete copy of the SIA proposal, please contact <A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">Jim Spellman</A> or <A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>.
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia04.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Press Releases"></A>
</BODY>
</HTML>
