<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG> Wednesday, July 31, 1996</STRONG><P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=5><B>SIA to Hold First Annual Conference on Retirement Issues in D.C. September 26-27</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>Strategic Planning, Product Development, Legislative and Regulatory Outlook on Taxes, Social Security To Be Discussed</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><B>Washington, D.C.</B> -- The Securities Industry Association's first annual  Conference on Retirement Issues will be held Thursday, September 26 - Friday, September 27 at the Mayflower Hotel, Washington, D.C.  General sessions and workshops will focus on the challenges and opportunities the industry faces in helping investors plan for retirement.<P>
<dd>Dallas Salisbury, President and CEO of the Employee Benefits Research Institute, Joseph J. Grano, Jr., President, PaineWebber Inc., and David D. Hale, Chief Economist, Zurich Kemper Investments, will deliver keynote addresses.  Secretary of Labor Robert Reich and Sen. Barbara Mikulski (D-MD) have been invited to speak as well.<P> 
<dd>Panels will focus on "Will Tax Reform Flatten Retirement Programs?," "The Outlook For Retirement Legislation and Regulation," and "Social Security Privatization."  There also will be workshops on investment education, estate planning, and the technological implications for developing and marketing retirement products.<P>
<dd>Kellyanne Fitzpatrick, President of Leading Authorities Inc. and political analyst for CNN, and Mark Mellman, CEO of Mellman-Lazarus-Lake Inc. and political commentator for Fox Television News, will discuss the election outlook on Friday, September 27.<P>
<dd>Among those scheduled to participate in panels during the two-day session are:  Leo J. Corbett, Director of Planning & Administration, Lehman Bros.; Edward T. Fergus, Senior Vice President and Associate General Counsel, Prudential Securities; Randy Hardock, Partner, Davis & Harmon; Thomas J. Schendt, Office of the Chief Counsel with the U.S. Treasury Department; and Ivan Strasfeld, Director of the Pension and Welfare Benefits Administration, U. S. Department of Labor.<P>
<dd>Registration information is available for your <A HREF="sia02b.htm#ira">review</A> or you can contact SIA's Conference Services Department, (212) 608-1500, or by fax at (212) 608-1604.  The fee is $350 for members ($450 for non-members), with a $50 reduction for multiple registrations from the same firm.
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S., SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans. 
<P>
