<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG> Wednesday, July 31, 1996</STRONG><P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=5><B>Fed Board's Move to Lift Cap on Underwriting of Section 20 Bank-Affiliates Moves Efforts a Step Backward in Modernizing Financial Services Laws to Promote Competition</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><B>Washington, D.C.</B> -- Steve Judge, Senior Vice President for Government Affairs for the Securities Industry Association, today issued the following statement in response to the decision today by the Federal Reserve to propose lifting the cap on the underwriting activities of Section 20 bank-affiliates to 25 percent from the current 10-percent limit of their revenues:
<P>
<dd>"Piecemeal decisions by the Federal Reserve and other Federal agencies to set the rules for the level and type of services that different financial institutions can provide have unfortunately created a Rube Goldberg-like structure of  'quick fixes.'   What the U.S. needs, though, is a coherent, thoughtful and comprehensive modernization of the federal laws and regulations governing financial institutions.
<P>
<dd>"Today's action is unfortunately the latest quick fix.  While clearly there is a need for a temporary solution for those Section 20 bank-affiliates that have bumped up against the current 10-percent limit based on their revenues, for the Fed to propose allowing a generous and long-term solution, as they did today, just puts us back one step in our efforts to hammer out an approach to modernize existing federal laws and regulations covering the financial services industry.  What we need now is to have all parties come to the negotiating table; today's decision by the Fed, though, promises to reduce the incentive of section 20 bank-affiliates to do so.
<P>
<dd>"Given the few legislative days remaining before the November elections, what we believe needs to be done is for Congress to start anew in January to build on the legislative efforts over the last few years to develop financial services modernization legislation.  In the meantime, we believe it is fair for the Fed to grant temporary relief to those Section 20 bank-affiliates that are bumping up against the 10-percent cap.  By having that relief granted on a temporary basis, an incentive would have been created to bring all parties together to work on a comprehensive solution. 
<P>
<dd>"The SIA is committed to legislation that will promote competition among all financial services providers by enabling banks to own full-service securities firms and securities firms to own or affiliate with banks -- a 'two-way street' -- as well as by ensuring that all financial providers be governed by consistent rules -- a policy of functional regulation.  These central tenets must be part of any legislation to modernize the nation's laws to reflect dramatic changes in the financial services industry that were created through technology and increased global competition."
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 750 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans. 
<P> 
