<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG> Thursday, July 25, 1996</STRONG><P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P><P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>New Investors, New Markets, New Idea<BR>
Focus of SIA's Annual Meeting, November 6-9, 1996
<P>Meeting to Draw More Than 700 Securities Executives<P></B></FONT></CENTER>
<dd><STRONG>New York, NY</STRONG>,  --  "New Investors, New Markets, New Ideas" is the theme of the Securities Industry Association's 1996 <A HREF="Sia02b.htm#annual">Annual Meeting</A> in Boca Raton, Florida, November 6 - 9 (Wednesday - Saturday).  The 25th annual conference, which attracts top management from the association's member firms, will focus on ways to increase the public's trust and confidence in the industry, technology's impact on the way securities are traded, and the effect the dramatic influx of new investors is having on the markets.<P>
<B> Second Annual Investor Survey Slated</B><P>
<dd>At the meeting, SIA will release its second annual investor survey, a benchmark study of investor perceptions of the securities industry, conducted by Yankelovich Partners Inc., a public opinion research firm.<P>
<dd>The survey findings will reveal investors' attitudes toward their brokers and the industry, as well as what they perceive to be the major issues facing the industry; the qualities they seek in brokerage services; their use of investing technology; and their views regarding major policy issues, such as tax and retirement legislation, which affect investing. <P>
<B>Public Trust and Confidence Initiatives Update</B><P>
<dd>Irving Weiser, President and CEO of the Inter-Regional Financial Group and Chairman of the SIA's Public Trust and Confidence Committee, will report on the progress of the Association's efforts to educate the public about the financial markets and investing.<P>
<B>Regulatory Outlook</B><P>
<dd>The annual meeting will also highlight the regulatory initiatives undertaken and proposed by federal agencies and self-regulatory organizations.  Featured regulatory speakers will include:  Arthur J. Levitt, Jr., Chairman, Securities and Exchange Commission; Richard A. Grasso, Chairman and Chief Executive Officer, New York Stock Exchange; and Joseph R. Hardiman, President and Chief Executive Officer, National Association of Securities Dealers and The Nasdaq Stock Market.<P>
<B>Technology's Increasing Role In Today's Business</B><P>
<dd>Part of the program will be devoted to discussions of the increasing impact of technology on the securities industry and how to adapt to the rapidly changing environment.  Participants will include:  Scott Cook, Chairman of Intuit Inc., Daniel H.  Case III,  President and CEO of Hambrecht & Quist, and Christos M. Cotsakos, President and CEO of E*TRADE Group, Inc.<P>
<B>Views From The Top</B><P>
<dd>In addition to briefings by Levitt, Grasso and Hardiman, PaineWebber Chairman and CEO Donald Marron and Lucent Technologies Chairman Henry P. Schacht will address the conference.  Alex. Brown chairman and CEO, A. B. Krongard, who is SIA's 1996 chairman; Dean Witter Financial, Dean Witter Discover & Co. President and Chief Operating Officer James F. Higgins, who is SIA's chairman-elect; and  SIA President Marc Lackritz will update the attendees on the association's activities.<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 75 0 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.<P>
