<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>SIA Statement on Justice Department Settlement with NASDAQ Market Makers<P></B></FONT></CENTER>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, D.C.</STRONG>
 -- The Securities Industry Association released the statement below following the announcement today by the U.S. Justice Department officials of their settlement with securities firms that make markets in securities listed on the Nasdaq Stock Market:<P>
<dd>"We believe that the settlement executed between the U.S. Justice Department and 24 major Nasdaq market-making firms is an equitable resolution of the issues that have been deliberated upon for the past two years.  The changes spelled out in the settlement will ensure that the public's trust and confidence in the financial markets and the securities industry remains high.  Our industry continues to be committed to ensuring that our markets are competitive, effective and efficient in raising capital, well-run, and well-regulated.<P>
<dd>"Nasdaq and the other U.S. financial markets have accomplished a great deal for issuers and investors.  Our markets are the world's envy; no foreign markets can match their quality and sophistication as well as our tough, effective regulation.  The competition within and between our financial markets provides investors and issuers with unrivaled services to meet investing and capital needs.  More than $1 trillion is raised yearly in new capital that finances business expansion and creates ten of thousands of new jobs.  The three stock markets trade more than one-billion shares daily.  That's nearly three times the pace of only five years ago.  A record number of U.S. and non-U.S. based companies trade on the three markets.  And, ongoing technology investments made by the financial markets ensure that their customers -- issuers and investors -- are getting cutting-edge services."<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 730 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.<P>  
