<dd>(212) 618-0531
<P>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=5><B>Gephardt, Stieglitz to Address Washington Forum<BR> on Derivatives Use and Regulations</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<dd><B>Washington, DC</B> -- Congressman Richard A. Gephardt, the Democratic leader, and Joseph Stieglitz, chairman of the Council Of Economic Advisors, will address the Financial Derivatives: Risk, Return and Regulation conference to be held here on Friday, September 20, 1996.  Washington Post political analyst David S. Broder will provide commentary on the upcoming Presidential and Congressional elections.
<P>
<dd>The conference will bring together industry participants, policy makers and the media to discuss developments and trends in the global marketplace and its regulation.  It is the third biannual meeting cosponsored by the Futures Industry Institute and the Securities Industry Association.
<P>
<dd>In addition to top-level policy makers, this year's conference focuses on the end users of derivative instruments.  Participants include Margaret Eisen, managing director, General Motors Investment Management Group; Gary Perlin, treasurer, The World Bank; and Todd Petzel, chief investment officer, The Common Fund, as well as representatives from state/local authorities and companies that use derivatives.
<P>
<dd>The conference will be held at the Willard Inter-Continental Hotel.  The registration fee through August 16 is $295 per person.  Registration after August 16 is $350.  Membership in either organization is not required to attend.  For more information, contact:  Julie Greenway, FII, at (202) 223-1528 (fax: 202-296-3184, e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:info@faifii.org">info@fiafii.org</A>) or Mary Kappa, SIA, at (202) 296-9410 (fax: 202-326-5349, e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:mkappa@sia.com">mkappa@sia.com</A>).
<P>
<dd>The Futures Industry Institute is a non-profit educational and training foundation whose purpose is to increase the understanding of the futures, options and other derivative markets.  The Securities Industries Association's membership comprises about 700 securities firms that collectively account for approximately 90 percent of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.
<P>
