<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>SIA Applauds Senate Passage of Gramm-D'Amato-Dodd Bill<P>
Regulatory Reforms Would Benefit Investors, Issuers<BR> by Lowering Costs of Capital<BR></B></FONT></CENTER><P>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, D.C.</STRONG> -- The Securities Industry Association released the following statement from its president, Marc E. Lackritz, following the Senate's approval late last night under unanimous consent of <A HREF="http://Thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c104:s.1815:">S.1815</A>.  The legislation -- introduced by Senators Phil Gramm (R-TX), Alfonse M. D'Amato (R-NY), Christopher J. Dodd (D-CT), and others -- would streamline state and federal regulation of the securities industry and provide the Securities and Exchange Commission with greater flexibility to modernize securities regulations.<P>  
<dd>"With the Senate's passage today, investors and issuers move a major step forward towards obtaining much-needed regulatory reforms that will directly benefit them by lowering the costs of capital.  SIA commends the Senate Banking Committee and Senate leaders for their stewardship of this important legislation," <BR>said Marc E. Lackritz.<P>
<dd>"Strong, effective regulation has been a hallmark of our nation's markets.  Unfortunately, there is much overlap among state and federal regulators, for example, in the registration of securities and mutual funds, as well as brokers.  This regulatory excess only adds to the costs of raising capital.  These costs lower investors' returns and make it more expensive for new and established companies to raise funds to expand and improve both their services and products and create new jobs.  The Senate and House bills carefully prune the regulatory overgrowth while ensuring that investor protections remain strong.<P> 
<dd>"We encourage the House and Senate conferees to resolve their differences and enact this important bill this year." <P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 730 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies - are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S., SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.
