<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>Securities Industry Offers Investor Topics to Help Public Learn More About Savings, Investment<P> </B></FONT></CENTER>
<dd><STRONG>New York, NY</STRONG> -- The Securities Industry Association today introduced a brochure, Investor Topics, that it is offering free to the public as its latest initiative in helping to teach investors about savings and investing.<P>
<dd>"The securities industry has an enormous responsibility to educate a generation of new investors, who are putting their savings for the first time into stocks, bonds, mutual funds, and other types of investments," said Marc E. Lackritz, SIA's president.  "We are meeting this challenge in a variety of ways, which include Investor Topics."<P>
<dd>The public can obtain a copy from SIA by sending a #10 self-addressed, stamped envelope (78 cents postage) to: <EM> Investor Topics</EM>; Securities Industry Association; 120 Broadway; 35th Floor; New York, NY 10271-0080.  For multiple copies, the charge is $2 per copy; a check or money order made payable to SIA must be included. <P>
<dd>The eight chapters of Investor Topics are:  Investing Basics; Choosing an Investment Professional; Teaming Up; Solving Problems; Understanding Stocks, Bonds and Mutual Funds; Safety Nets; Understanding Account Statements; and, Holding 
Securities in "Street Name."  Throughout the 44-page brochure are a series of charts that help an investor calculate assets and liabilities as well as the savings needed to meet retirement and college costs.<P>
<dd>Last November, SIA released its first annual survey of investor perceptions of the securities industry to help guide the association's initiatives to enhance the public's trust and confidence in the financial markets.  Investor Topics responds to the educational needs investors cited in their responses to the survey's questions.<P> 
<dd>SIA, Lackritz said, is also working on a book about investing with Lightbulb Press, which publishes best-selling guides to personal finance.  SIA's book will be offered to the public in mid-November.<P>
<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 700 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S., SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans. 
