<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG> Wednesday, June 19, 1996</STRONG><P>				
Contact:								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret G. Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<P><P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>SIA Lauds House Passage of Bill Eliminating 
Redundant State, Federal Securities Regulations<P>Lower Costs of Capital to Benefit Investor, Issuers<P>Association Urges Senate to Act Swiftly on Much-Needed Revisions<P> </B></FONT></CENTER>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, D.C.</STRONG>  -- In response to the House's passage (407-8 and 1 voting present) today of legislation (H.R. 3005) to eliminate redundant state and federal regulations, revise margin requirements to expand broker-dealer access to financing, and reduce securities registration fees, Marc E. Lackritz, president of the Securities Industry Association, released the following statement:<P>
<dd>"The legislation the House approved today is an important step for investors and issuers.  By eliminating unnecessary, redundant state and federal regulations, the bill would help lower the costs of capital.  The lower costs benefit investors and issuers.  For investors, the returns on their savings are increased by reducing the regulatory burdens that add to the costs of capital.  For issuers, lower capital costs make it easier for the start-ups and new ventures to raise the funds they need to develop new products and services.  Their expansion generates new jobs, which, in turn, strengthens the nation's economy.<P> 
<dd>"The improvements that the bill makes would in no way undermine the strong, effective framework of regulations that contribute to the overall strength of U.S. capital markets.  Our markets are the envy of the world.  Tough, effective policing by federal and state agencies, coupled with the securities industry's self-regulation, ensure that investors are well protected against fraud.  The record participation of individual investors underscores the tremendous opportunities our financial markets offer. <P> 
<dd>"Capital costs for issuers and investors are also cut by the bill's provisions to reduce securities registration fees.  Doing so makes sense, and SIA joins with the Securities and Exchange Commission in supporting the House-passed measure to start the process of lowering fees to match the SEC's funding needs.<P>  
<dd>"We encourage the Senate, which has slated committee mark-up on similar legislation today, to complete their work soon so that the much-needed securities regulatory reforms can be enacted by Congress this year."<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than 730 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.<P>
