<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG> Thursday, June 13, 1996</STRONG><P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P><P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>Rapid Growth in Financial Services Demands Modernization of Glass-Steagall to Promote Industry Expansion,<BR> Flexibility in Serving Consumers<P></B></FONT></CENTER>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, DC</STRONG>,  --  In response to the House Banking Committee's action Tuesday on legislation to rewrite the Glass-Steagall Act, Steve Judge, Senior Vice President, Government Affairs, released the following statement: <P> 
<dd>"SIA is disappointed that an agreement has not been reached so far among financial service providers to enact comprehensive legislation to modernize Glass-Steagall.   We applaud Chairman Jim Leach's efforts to try to do so and will work hard with him, the House Banking Committee, and the House leadership through the next Congress on passing comprehensive legislation. <P>
<dd>"SIA continues to believe that enactment of comprehensive legislation to restructure the nation's financial regulatory framework is necessary and critical now to promote growth and innovation among U.S. financial service providers and enhance their international competitiveness.  In the 1930s when Congress enacted banking laws, U.S. financial markets were less complex, had few ties with foreign markets, and served far fewer individual investors than those participating today.  The financial services industry now offers a complex, diverse series of financial products to help customers raise new capital and manage investment needs at home and abroad.  Our industry -- driven by immense business and technological advantages and the record participation of individual investors -- is changing rapidly.  Unfortunately, the nation's regulatory structure is antiquated, a 1930's relic.<P>  
<dd>"We are reviewing now the approach that Chairman Leach proposed on Tuesday, but at first sight, we are concerned that the bill may not accord similar benefits to all providers of financial services.  Any measure the House approves must fairly treat all financial service providers and their customers. <P>  
<dd>"We think that the House's legislative efforts should continue foremost to focus on developing a comprehensive modernization of Glass Steagall.  American consumers and the industry have suffered from the piecemeal, ad hoc rewrite of financial services regulations through court decisions and regulatory fiats.  Comprehensive financial restructuring legislation will best serve American consumers and make it possible for all financial services intermediaries to operate more flexibly and competitively -- domestically and internationally. <P> 
<dd>"Essential to a comprehensive rewrite of Glass Steagall are three principles: a level- playing field so that no financial services entity would have regulatory advantages over another; a two-way street so that bank-holding companies, for example, would be allowed to own full service securities firms and securities firms would be able to own or affiliate with banks; and, functional regulation to ensure that one agency applies the same set of rules to the same activity engaged in by any financial institution.  We will continue to work with our member firms, Chairman Leach and House leaders to modernize Glass Steagall. "<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of more than  730 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans. 
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
