<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG> Wednesday, May 22, 1996</STRONG><P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P><P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>SIA Board Backs Sales Practice Recommendations <P>Hiring Procedures, Supervisory Practices, Cold-Calling Training Among Initiatives Backed To Build On Firms' Compliance Procedures<P></B></FONT></CENTER>
<dd><STRONG>New York, NY</STRONG>,  -- The Board of the Securities Industry Association today unanimously endorsed sales practice recommendations to augment current regulations and securities firm procedures governing the hiring and supervision of registered representatives. <P>
<dd>"The SIA is committed to enhancing the public's trust and confidence in the securities industry," stated SIA Chairman A. B. Krongard.  "While a very, very small percentage -- only one hundredth of one percent -- of the 100-million-plus transactions yearly result in customer complaints, we must work diligently to eliminate any sales practices abuses."<P>
<dd>The recommendations endorsed by the SIA board today resulted from a review of regulatory records of selected registered representatives at primarily small and mid-size firms.  The review was a combined effort of the National 
Association of Securities Dealers, the New York Stock Exchange, the North American Securities Administrators Association, Inc., and the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission.<P>
<dd>Under the goals and recommendations endorsed by the board, firms should: <P>
<UL>
<LH></LH>
<LI>engage in stringent hiring requirements for registered representatives;<P> 
<LI>have special supervision for registered representatives with a disciplinary history involving sales practice abuse or other customer harm; <P>
<LI>consider adopting a policy of tying a component of branch managers' compensation to their effective supervision of registered representatives; <P>
<LI>ensure that they are fulfilling their supervisory obligations; <P>
<LI>have cold calling procedures;<P>
<LI>have effective, sound supervisory procedures are the first line of defense in guarding against sales practice abuses, for detecting those problems that do rise, and for taking prompt corrective action; and, <P>
<LI>do follow-up review for firms that have been the subject of disciplinary action. 
</UL>
<P>
<dd>"We believe that the vast majority of broker-dealers are strongly committed to good supervisory practices and have appropriate procedures in place to deter and detect wrongdoing," Krongard said.  "We will continue our dialogue with the securities regulators about ways to improve compliance regulation and procedures." <P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of about 700 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.
