<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG> Wednesday, May 15, 1996</STRONG><P>				
Contact:
<dd><A HREF="mailto:skaswell@sia.com">Stuart Kaswell</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:ssingleton@sia.com">Sheila Singleton</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0539
<P><P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>SIA Applauds House Committee Approval of Legislation to Streamline Securities Industry Regulators <P>Reforms to Benefit Investors, Issuers in Lowering Costs of Capital<P></B></FONT></CENTER>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, DC</STRONG>,  -- The Securities Industry Association released the following statement from its president, Marc E. Lackritz, in response to the House Commerce Committee's approval today of the "Securities Amendments Act of 1996" (H.R. 3005).<P>
<dd>"Today's Committee approval marks a solid step forward towards enactment by Congress of much-needed reforms in securities regulations.  Federal regulation of our securities markets has long played a constructive role.  However, changing times and circumstances have made some legal requirements obsolete.  The legislation's changes in existing laws will promote efficiency, competition and capital formation.<P>
<dd>"The bill adopts a fair approach in eliminating the duplication of some state and federal registration requirements for certain securities and industry professionals.  The current regulatory duplication is bad for investors and taxpayers.<P>
<dd>"By encouraging coordination among self-regulatory organizations (SROs), the bill thoughtfully addresses an important problem for many securities firms.  Firms have asked for better coordination to minimize the occasions when different SROs visit firms, sometimes virtually on the heels of each other, to review the same documentation on the same issue.  Greater coordination will reduce the costs and time spent with routine, on-site inspections, allowing firms and regulatory organizations to use their resources more effectively in safeguarding the investors' interests.<P>
<dd>"While recent regulatory proposals by the Federal Reserve Board are responsive to many of the industry's concerns in overhauling outdated margin rules, we still believe there are areas -- for example, restrictions on broker-dealer sources of funds -- that need to be addressed through legislation.  The bill cleared today by the House Committee includes those areas.<P>
<dd>"The House Commerce Committee Chairman, Rep. Thomas J. Bliley, and ranking minority member, Rep. John D. Dingell, deserve special praise -- as well as the bill's sponsor, Rep. Jack Fields, and ranking House Telecommunications and Finance Committee member, Rep. Edward J. Markey -- for their leadership in passing this legislation.  We encourage the House leadership to bring the bill for a floor vote soon for passage."<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of about 700 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.<P> 
