<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>SIA Endorses Initiatives to Open Global Markets<BR>ICSA Addresses Accounting Standards, Sales Exam Accords, WTO Talks<P></B></FONT></CENTER>
<dd><STRONG>New York, NY</STRONG>  --  The Securities Industry Association joined with other members of the International Councils of Securities Associations (ICSA) in committing to initiatives proposed at the ICSA meeting in Vancouver, Canada from May 6-7. <P>
<dd>The initiatives, designed to promote the sound growth of the international securities markets, included actions to coordinate accounting standards and simplify registration requirements of sales professionals in foreign countries.<P>
<dd>"These initiatives will result in more efficient global markets, " said SIA President Marc E. Lackritz.  "Issuers will have easier access to capital, and   American investors will benefit from the lower costs.  We will work closely with our member firms and government agencies to achieve these goals." <P>
<dd>The initiatives included:<P>
<UL>
<LH></LH>
<LI>Recognition of the critical importance of coordinated accounting standards, and a commitment by ICSA members to work with their appropriate authorities to enhance the disclosure of material information, reduce risk and decrease costs to investors and other participants in global capital markets.<P>
<LI>Approval of recent agreements between Canada, Japan and the U.S. that recognize each other's examination for sales personnel when the individual registers to do business in the three countries.<P>
<LI>Renewed support of open and fair markets, advocating the successful conclusion of the World Trade Organization's financial services negotiations, which represent a step forward in achieving global liberalization of financial markets.
</UL>
<P>
<dd>ICSA aids and encourages the sound growth of international securities markets by promoting and encouraging harmonization in the procedures and regulation of those markets to facilitate international securities transactions. ICSA promotes the sharing and exchange of information among its members.<P>
<dd>SIA brings together the shared interests of about 700 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.
