<TITLE>Press Release </TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><P>
For Release: <STRONG>Thursday, May 9, 1996</STRONG><P>				
Contact:								
<dd><A HREF="mailto:jspellman@sia.com">James D. Spellman</A>
<dd>(202) 296-9410
<dd><A HREF="mailto:mdraper@sia.com">Margaret G. Draper</A>
<dd>(212) 618-0531
<P><P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>PSA, SIA, NYSE Urge Key House Members to Clear Margin Reforms to Expand Borrowing by Broker-Dealers<P></B></FONT></CENTER>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, DC</STRONG>,  --   The Public Securities Association, the Securities Industry Association and the New York Stock Exchange, Inc. today urged four key Congressmen to adopt legislation that would eliminate current restrictions on broker-dealer borrowing.<P>
<dd>In the joint letter, the two trade associations and NYSE stressed the ways in which current limitations on broker-dealer borrowing "significantly impair the ability of broker-dealers to obtain capital on the most favorable terms available in the market."  Such limitations ultimately penalize issuers and investors through the higher costs they impose on capital, the letter said. <P>
<dd>The letter was sent to Rep. Thomas J. Bliley (R-Va.), chairman of the House Committee on Commerce; Rep. John D. Dingell (D-Mich.), ranking minority member of that committee; Rep Jack Fields (R-Tex.), chairman of the House Commerce Subcommittee on Telecommunications and Finance, and Rep. Markey (D-Mass.), ranking minority member of that subcommittee.<P>
<dd>Federal securities regulations prohibit broker-dealers from borrowing from lenders other than broker-dealers and banks regulated by the Federal Reserve Board when using collateral consisting of equity securities listed on a national securities exchange.  Such loans to broker-dealers are subject to lending limits imposed under the Board's margin rules.<P>
<dd>"No similar restrictions affect other market participants," the letter said.  "This imposes unnecessary costs on broker-dealers and adversely affects them from a competitive standpoint.  Moreover, the percentage limits on borrowing prescribed by the margin 
rules impose a particularly great burden on broker-dealers in light of the nature of their assets and inventory."<P>
<dd>PSA, SIA and NYSE urged the Congressmen to adopt legislation that would, first, permit extensions of credit by any lender and, second, lift the Board's current lending limits for market makers, underwriters and broker-dealers engaged in a securities business with public customers. <P>
<dd>Such reforms, the letter said, "would provide broker-dealers with substantially greater ability to obtain finance for their activities at the lowest available cost."  Further, the letter said, such reforms "would enhance the competitiveness of U.S. broker-dealers and reduce costs to their customers." <P>
<dd>PSA is the bond market trade association, representing securities firms and banks that underwrite bonds and sell debt securities, both domestically and internationally.  <A HREF="http://www.psa.com">PSA's home page:  http://www.psa.com.</A> <P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association brings together the shared interests of about 700 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  SIA's home page:  http://www.sia.com. <P>
<dd>The New York Stock Exchange is the world's largest equities market, with more than $6.3-trillion worth of stock listed.  <A HREF="http://www.nyse.com">NYSE's home page:  http://www.nyse.com.</A>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia04.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Press Releases"></A>
