<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>SIPC Reduces 1996 Assessments on Securities Firms<BR>SIA Applauds SIPC Board's Action<P></B></FONT></CENTER>
<dd><STRONG>New York, NY</STRONG>,  -- The Securities Investor Protection Corporation will assess its members a flat fee of $150 for 1996, reducing the total industry charge to approximately $1.5 million, down from 1995's $57 million.  The Securities Industry Association endorsed the SIPC board's decision, and called upon the firms to continue pursuing those initiatives that strengthen the industry and benefit the individual investor.<P>
<dd>"The SIA has actively supported SIPC's setting $1 billion as the target level for its fund," stated SIA president Marc Lackritz.  "We applaud the board's reevaluation of their assessment policy now that the fund is at that level."<P>
<dd>The SIA Financial Management Division's Regulatory Committee was an integral participant in SIPC's 1991 Task Force, which recommended the $1 billion level, and has since maintained an ongoing dialogue and working relationship with SIPC staff. <P>
<dd>Prior SIPC assessments were calculated based on a percentage of each firm's net operating revenues.  The fund recently reached $1 billion.<P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association is the leading proponent of capital markets, bringing together the shared interest of about 700 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public 
finance.  In the U.S., SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50 million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans.
