<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>SIA Statement on Fed Adoption of Regulation "T" Amendments<P></B></FONT></CENTER>
<dd><STRONG>Washington, DC</STRONG>,  --  The Securities Industry Association released the following statement in response to the adoption today of the Federal Reserve of a series of amendments to Regulation "T," which sets restrictions on credit and usages of margin.  The Fed also proposed additional amendments to Regulation "T." <P>
<dd>"We welcome the Federal Reserve's action today in making progress to meet the securities industry's needs for more flexibility in complying with margin requirements.  The Fed is taking a fresh look at the way in which margin rules affect dealer-investor relationships in capital markets.<P>
<dd>"But clearly more margin reform is needed.  The Fed is limited by law in what it can do so a legislative solution is still required for those issues the Fed could not address.  We will continue to work with the leadership and relevant committees in Congress to enact comprehensive reform of margin regulations.  An important part of this reform must be to provide broker-dealers with additional flexibility in financing their securities portfolios." <P>
<dd>The Securities Industry Association is the leading proponent of capital markets, bringing together the shared interests of about 700 securities firms throughout North America to accomplish common goals.  SIA members -- including investment banks, broker-dealers, specialists, and mutual fund companies -- are active in all markets and in all phases of corporate and public finance.  In the U.S. SIA members collectively account for approximately 90 percent, or $100 billion, of securities firms' revenues and employ about 350,000 individuals.  They manage the accounts of more than 50-million investors directly and tens of millions of investors indirectly through corporate, thrift and pension plans. <BR>
