<HEAD>
<TITLE>Annex to 11/13/96 Comment Letter</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body background="sia3abac.gif">
<IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=+2><STRONG>ANNEX</STRONG></FONT></CENTER><BR>
<B>Re:</B>  <EM>Securities Act Concepts and Their Effects on Capital Formation -- File No. S7-19-96</EM>
<P>
<B>Rule 177:</B>  Reasonable Investigation, Reasonable Grounds for Belief and Reasonable Care<dd>under Sections 11 and 12(a)(2) of the Securities Act  -- Forms S-3, F-3, F-7 and F-9.
<P>
<dd>In connection with a registration statement on Form S-3, Form F-3, Form F-7 or Form F-9 and related prospectus and prospectus supplement (if any), an underwriter has conducted a reasonable investigation and has reasonable ground for belief for purposes of Section 11, and has exercised reasonable care for purposes of Section 12(a)(2), of the Securities Act of 1933 if:
<P>
(a) at or prior to the initial delivery of the securities being sold, the underwriter:
<OL>
<LI>has reviewed the registration statement (including all amendments thereto and documents incorporated therein by reference) and prospectus and prospectus supplement (if any) insofar as they relate to the securities being sold;
<LI>has discussed information contained therein with the registrant's chief executive officer, chief financial officer, chief accounting officer or a person designated for such purpose by any such officer; and
<LI>has made inquiry into any circumstance which caused such underwriter to believe that the registration statement, as amended, or prospectus, as supplemented, contained an untrue statement of a material fact or omitted to state a material fact required to be stated therein or necessary to make the statements therein not misleading;
</OL>
(b) at or prior to the initial delivery of the securities being sold, the underwriter has received:
<OL>
<LI>a certificate of an executive officer of the registrant to the effect that, to the best of his or her knowledge after reasonable investigation, (x) the registration statement, as amended, and prospectus, as supplemented, do not contain any untrue statement of a material fact or omit to state a material fact required to be stated therein or necessary to make the statements therein not misleading and (y) since the dates of the information contained in such registration statement and prospectus, there have been no material adverse changes in the registrant's affairs that are not reflected therein;
<LI>a letter of the registrant's independent accountants with respect to the audited financial statements and any unaudited financial statements of the registrant included or incorporated by reference in the registration statement, as amended, or prospectus, as supplemented, of the kind contemplated by Statement on Auditing Standards No. 72 (February 1993) of the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants, as amended from time to time; and
<LI>letters of the registrant's and the underwriter's legal counsel substantially to the effect that nothing that has come to the attention of such counsel has caused such counsel to believe that the registration statement, as amended, or prospectus, as supplemented, contains an untrue statement of material fact or omits to state a material fact necessary in order to make the statements therein, in the light of the circumstances under which they were made, not misleading (which letters need not cover any financial statements or expertized portions of the registration statement);
</OL>
which, in each case, may be subject to such exceptions as do not relate to the material misstatement or omission; and
<P>
(c) at the time of the initial delivery of the securities being sold and at the time of any subsequent sale thereof by the underwriter as part of the distribution, the underwriter does not know of any untrue statement of a material fact in such registration statement, as amended, or such prospectus, as supplemented, or of any omission to state a material fact required to be stated therein or necessary to make the statements therein not misleading.
<P>
<dd>In the case of securities that are offered and sold on a continuous or delayed basis, (i) the requirements of paragraphs (a) and (c) shall be deemed to be satisfied with respect to any sale of the securities made as part of the distribution if such requirements have been satisfied at the time of such sale and (ii) the requirements of paragraph (b) shall be deemed to be satisfied with respect to such sale if such requirements are satisfied as of a date not more than 12 months preceding the time of such sale and the documents explicitly covered by the required certificate and letters include the most recent post-effective amendment (if any) to the registration statement (other than any such amendment that includes or changes information with respect to the plan of distribution and does not effect a material change to other information in the registration statement) and the most recent annual report that is deemed to be incorporated by reference into the registration statement at the time of such sale.
<P>
<dd>An underwriter shall also be entitled to the benefits of this Rule if (i)at the time of sale of any of the securities by it as part of the distribution, it does not know of any untrue statement of a material fact in the registration statement, as amended, or the prospectus, as supplemented, or of any omission to state a material fact required to be stated therein or necessary to make the statements therein not misleading and (ii)another underwriter participating in the same distribution has satisfied the requirements of paragraphs (a), (b) and (c) required to be satisfied at or prior to the initial delivery of the securities being sold in the distribution.
<P>
<dd>This Rule does not provide an exclusive means whereby an underwriter may conduct a reasonable investigation and have reasonable grounds for belief for purposes of Section 11, and exercise reasonable care for purposes of Section 12(a)(2), of the Securities Act of 1933 in connection with registration statements on Form S-3, Form F-3, Form F-7 or Form F-9.  Failure to satisfy all the terms and conditions of this Rule shall not raise any presumption that an underwriter has not satisfied such statutory standards.
