<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Internet Newsletter Sept 96</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#0A5183" TEXT="#FFFFB8" LINK="#00EE00" VLINK="#FFCC66"><P><P>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B>Notable Events</B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B><I>New Stock Exchange, Inc. Proposed Rule Filing: Use of  Electronic Media</I></B></FONT>
<P>
On September 12, 1996 the New York Stock Exchange, Inc. filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission a proposed rule change that consists of amendments to NYSE Rules 342, 440 and 472.  The purpose, as stated in the NYSE filing, is: <P>
"New technology and new means of communication (e.g. E-mail, the Internet) have and will continue to impact and change the way member organizations and their associated persons conduct business and communicate with customers and other members of the public.<P>
The Exchange has been working with a committee, composed of member organization representatives, to study questions that have arisen as a result of those new communications means with emphasis on supervision and review.  As a result, the Exchange has developed and is proposing amendments to Rules 342  ("Offices-Approval, Supervision and Control"), 440 ("Books and Records") and 472 ("Communications with the Public"). <P>
Amended Rule 342.16 will provide that procedures for review of communications with the public relating to a member or member organization's business be designed to provide reasonable supervision of each registered representative, that these procedures be  written and that implementation and execution of these  procedures be clearly evidenced.<P>
New Rule 342.17 will require each member and member organization to develop written policies and procedures for review of incoming and outgoing communications with the public relating to its business, tailored to its structure and the nature and size of its business and customer base.<P>
Prior review of outgoing correspondence and review of all incoming correspondence will no longer be required.  However, any organization that does not conduct pre-use review (whether electronic or manual) will be required to:<P>
<UL>
<LI>regularly educate and train employees as to the organization's current policies and procedures governing review of communications,<P>
<LI>document how and when employees are educated and trained, and<P>
<LI>monitor and test to ensure implementation and compliance with such policies and procedures.
</UL>
<P>
Rule 472(a) will be amended to clarify the types of communications that continue to require pre-use approval (e.g., advertisements, market letters and sales literature), and paragraph (b) will be amended to clarify that research reports continue to be (prepared or) approved in advance by a supervisory analyst.  Pre-approval of "any" communication which is distributed or made available to customers or the public will no longer be required (see Rule 342.17 requirements for organizations not conducting pre-use reviews).  The retention requirements for communications will be amended to state that the names of persons who prepared and reviewed and approved such communications must be readily ascertainable from the retained records.
<P>
The standards for communications set forth in Rule 472 continue to apply to all communications regardless of the transmission medium used or the policies and procedures for review and supervision adopted by members and member organizations pursuant to Rule 342.
<P>
Rule 440 will be amended to recognize that retention must be in a format or medium that complies with Rule 17a-4 under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 ("the Act")."
<P>
Contact <A HREF="mailto:megert@sia.com">Mark Egert</A> at SIA for more information.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B><EM>Promotion of Commerce Online in the Digital Era Act of 1996</EM></B></FONT>
<P>
The House Judiciary Committee held a hearing on September 25 to discuss the impact of legislation designed to encourage the widespread availability of strong, easy to use privacy and security technologies for the Internet by relaxing Cold War-era restrictions on the export of strong encryption technology (H.R. 3011, S. 1726).  Patricia Ripley, Director of Security at Bear Stearns Co., Inc. <A HREF="ripley.doc">testified</A> in support of the legislation.
<P>
Both bills: 1) allow for the unrestricted export of "mass market" or "public domain" encryption programs; 2) require the Secretary of Commerce to allow the unrestricted export of other encryption technologies if products of similar strength are generally available outside the United States; and 3) prohibit the federal government from imposing mandatory key-escrow policies on the domestic market and limit the authority of the Secretary of Commerce to set standards for encryption products.
<P>
Contact <A HREF="mailto:khofeditz@sia.com">Kristen Hofeditz </A>at SIA for more information.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B><EM>SIA Meets With Industry Utilities, Associations and SROs</EM></B></FONT>
<P>
In August 1996, SIA met with representatives from various industry utilities, associations and SROs to discuss how Internet technology can be utilized to communicate more effectively with members.  A number of representatives volunteered to work with SIA to draft a proposal for the group to review and consider.  <A HREF="mailto:pgoodbody@sia.com">H. Pim Goodbody, Jr.,</A> Vice President, Management Services at SIA, is spearheading the effort to develop this proposal.  In conjunction with drafting this proposal,  various SIA Divisions have agreed to prepare a list of useful materials and information they would like to see made available on the Internet (e.g., important notices, rules, etc.).  For more information, contact <A HREF="mailto:pcassar@sia.com">Phyllis A. Cassar</A>.   
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B><EM>SIA to Hold Internet Update Conference</EM></B></FONT>
<P>
SIA has decided to hold an Internet Update Conference in New York sometime in February 1997.   The focus of the Conference will be to update the industry on the regulatory changes facing the financial community as they pursue the opportunities afforded by Internet technology as well as showcasing how securities firms are using the Internet.  The Conference will provide a forum for firms to discuss how they are coping or planning to cope with the new regulations and capitalize on the new opportunities provided by the Internet.  Representatives from the SRO's, brokerage community and other industry groups will be present.   Details on the Conference will be available on SIA's home page when finalized.  
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B><EM>Webmaster Roundtable</EM></B></FONT>
<P>
SIA is holding its first Webmaster Roundtable on October 22-23, 1996.  More than 15 firms nationwide are being represented at this meeting.  Issues to be discussed center on security, design, marketing and legal.  Firms wishing to participate in the 1997 Roundtable should contact <A HREF="mailto:pcassar@sia.com">Phyllis A. Cassar,</A> Director,  Internet Services at SIA.
<P>
<A NAME="profile"><HR SIZE=4></A>
<FONT SIZE=+3><B>Profile On: <A HREF="http://www.ernst-co.com">Ernst & Company</A></B></FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B><EM>Vital Statistics --</EM></B></FONT><P>
<DD><STRONG>Mitchell Meisler, Director of Marketing<BR>
<DD>Ernst & Company<BR>
<DD>One Battery Park Plaza<BR>
<DD>New York, NY 10004-1478<BR>
<DD>(402) 597-7702<BR>
<DD><A HREF="mailto:meisler@ernst-co.com">meisler@ernst-co.com</A><BR>
<DD><A HREF=http://www.ernst-co.com>http://www.ernst-co.com</A></STRONG>
<P>
<B>The Internet: A Clearing Firms Perspective</B>
<P>
Ernst & Company is a 71 year old broker-dealer.  We provide fully disclosed clearing for 85 correspondent broker-dealers, located throughout the world.  Last year, we cleared about 7.2 billion shares of equity transactions for our firm and correspondents.  Ernst is a NYSE specialist in 48 issues, and NASDAQ market maker in about 600 issues.
<P>
<B>Why Ernst is on The World-Wide Web</B>
<P>
Much of the financial press and securities industry seem to be looking at the Internet as a means of connecting the broker-dealer with the client; at Ernst & Company, we see equal, if not greater, productivity and economic benefit from using the Net to deliver information to our correspondent broker-dealers, as well as to their customers.   Our goal is to deliver confirms, statements, historical reports, online trading, account retrieval, portfolio accounting, and documents such as account applications and prospectuses online to our correspondent broker-dealers, and if desired, to their customers.  While our most active correspondents will still want the integrity and speed of a dedicated line, smaller and less active broker-dealers could have very low-cost access to information that will be available to meet their record retention requirements and to manage their businesses.  We also benefit from being able to eliminate overnight deliveries to correspondents.  We free up our traders and margin professionals to take fewer calls from correspondents, as orders and routine inquiries can take place online rather than on the telephone.  Once again, we see the opportunity to multiply our business while increasing our service quality and keeping our growth in headcount under control. 
<P>
<B>Our Timetable: Crawling, Rather Than Running</B>
<P>
We didnt want to rush headlong into all of the above on the Internet, however.  Our management  had reservations about security issues, and about integrity of the technology that we needed to satisfy for ourselves before plunging headlong into Internet trading.  As a result, if you look at the ernst-co.com Web site today, you see a Web "advertisement" tailored to financial professionals.  You can see a demonstration of The Ernst Paperless Solution, an optical storage system we use for record retention.  You can review sample confirms and statements.  You can read about The Ernst World Funds, our mutual fund family, as well as about our other services and product offerings.  You can fill out an online clearing proposal, answering the questions we need to send a custom clearing proposal to a correspondent.  What you cant do is trade, or look at client accounts, or access The Ernst Paperless Solution.  You cant pull down a new account application.  You cant open an account online.  
<P>
We intentionally crawled, rather than ran, onto the Internet.  The pioneers of online trading on the Net spent millions designing their systems.  Today, were hoping to develop those same capabilities, with faster access and greater integrity, at a fraction of that price.  We spent about $60,000 (not including manpower) for the Sun Sparc stations, software licenses, and hardware to establish our Web site.  The human factor, such as programming time, accounts for many hundreds of hours of unbilled time.  Were looking to further reduce our development costs and time by establishing joint ventures with vendors that could benefit from having their products and services highlighted on the Web sites of our correspondents, and have been working with one to build much of the functionality (e.g., forms retrieval and account opening) not yet delivered on our site.
<P>
<B>Turning to The Outside</B>
<P>
While we first developed our Web capabilities in-house, we are now turning outside for vendors that have developed leading edge products for online trading, account retrieval, portfolio accounting, online checking and other brokerage products and services we can deliver to our correspondents.  The reason is that these vendors have worked out the bugs of online trading, account retrieval and the other services we mention above.  One pioneer of online trading reportedly had to rebate its clients almost $2 million in one month alone due to downtime on its Web trading system.  There are chat rooms, where investors pan or praise the online trading and system capabilities of broker-dealers on the Net.  There have been security concerns relating to popular Web software packages that needed to be solved.  In short, we wanted to see how other Internet pioneers fared with their clients, the press and their online system before we were first to boldly go where no securities firm had gone before.  
<P>
<B>The Email Issue</B>
<P>
Email is an important new tool that the Web can offer to us and our correspondents.  We use the Net for email between department managers and correspondents.  We do not have email addresses for all Ernst personnel, however.  Those personnel that have email addresses received strict instructions about using email for professional uses only, and we further advised our correspondents to be sensitive about using account numbers and other client-specific data in email communications with our firm.  The reason for restricting access is that we wanted to monitor the traffic going in and out of Ernst.  We also do not allow email with individual clients of our correspondents, thereby eliminating the compliance headaches that could result from these communications.  
<P>
<B>Whats Next for Ernst</B>
<P>
Ernst & Company intends to disappear from the Net.  We want to be transparent to our correspondents and their customers.  Instead, were planning a Web site that is easily customized to become the Web site (or linked to become a part of the Web site) of each correspondent.  In turn, each broker-dealer would choose which of  their registered reps, back office personnel and clients would have access to various products and services offered on the site.  As part of our clearing partnership with correspondents, we can design and maintain their Web sites, and in the future provide the trading, account retrieval, optical storage and other tools they could access and offer.
<P>
The Internet may not be an overnight miracle for the securities industry.  It will, however, dramatically increase our productivity and profitability.  The fears that online trading and account retrieval could put the retail or institutional registered rep out of business are not part of our thinking.  Instead, we think that the Internet and other online tools will allow correspondents to will call us when they really need us, much as we still go to see a bank teller or lending professional rather than go to an ATM when we have a need to do important and substantial business with a bank.  In the clearing business, the Internet can help reduce the broker dealers paper chase.  It will increase efficiency, reduce errors and otherwise help us leverage our communications with correspondents and their customers at ever-lower cost to all.  While we did not rush to be first on the Internet, Ernst & Company now hopes to create a creative, profitable and long-lasting presence on the Web for ourselves and our clients.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3><STRONG>The "Ernst & Company" profile was submitted by Mitchell Meisler, Director of Marketing, Ernst & Company</STRONG></FONT>
<A NAME="legal"><HR SIZE=4></A>
<FONT  SIZE=+3><B>Legal & Compliance Corner</B></FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B><EM>Intellectual Property and the World Wide Web:<BR> Domain Names, Trademarks and Copyrights</EM></B></FONT><P>
<STRONG>Question:</STRONG><BR>
 We are ready to set up a site on the World Wide Web and we would like to use our firm's name as part of the address of our site.  We know that some firms have already done this but keep hearing stories about how some other firms can't use their name that way.  What do we have to do to get our name as part of our address?
<P>
<STRONG>Answer: </STRONG><BR> 
The part of a web site's address which contains a firm's name or other identifying information (in the form "someone.com") is known as a "Domain Name" and is assigned in the United States by the organization known as <A HREF=http://rs.internic.net/internic/index.html>InterNIC</A>.  InterNIC has contracted with Network Solutions, Inc. ("NSI") to administer the name registration process. NSI assigns Domain Names on a first come, first served basis.  For example, deltaComm Development, Inc. registered delta.com as its Domain Name in 1993.  Therefore, delta.com was no longer available to Delta Airlines when it sought its Domain Name in 1994 and it registered delta-air.com instead.  You can use the <A HREF=http://rs.internic.net/cgi-bin/whois>search tool</A> provided by InterNIC to determine whether the Domain Name you wish to use has already been assigned.
<P>
<STRONG>Question:</STRONG><BR>
Do the laws relating to trademarks affect Domain Name?
<P>
<STRONG>Answer: </STRONG><BR> 
While there is no requirement that any name you submit for registration as a Domain Name be registered as a trademark, you should be aware that any dispute over your right to use a Domain Name will revolve around the existence or absence of a registered trademark.
<P>
The Domain Name <A HREF=http://rs.internic.net/domain-info/internic-domain-6.html>Dispute Policy</A> established by NSI (the "Dispute Policy") places much weight on the presence or absence of a registered trademark on the disputed name.  The resolution of any dispute which may occur as a result of another's claim to a trademark in a Domain Name revolves around whether your firm and the other party have a valid federally registered (federally registered trademarks are noted by the use of the symbol "&reg;") or foreign trademark, when the trademark was registered, when the Domain Name was first activated and whether your use of the Domain Name infringes the other party's trademark.  It is important to note that the Dispute Policy will not recognize either common law trademarks or state registered trademarks (which are noted by the symbols "tm" or "sm").
<P>
The Dispute Policy is controversial because it ignores several important tenents of trademark law; that is, a trademark is limited to a particular product and to a geographic area.  That is why Cadillac could be used as a trademark for cars and dog food at the same time.  Further, it is not unusual for the same trademark to be owned by Company A in the United States while an unrelated Company B owns the trademark in Germany.  The Dispute Policy, in ignoring these rules, has the potential for creating some real problems.
<P>
<STRONG> Question: </STRONG><BR>
Then how should I handle the problem of determining what to use as a Domain Name?
<P>
<STRONG>Answer: </STRONG><BR>
For the foreseeable future, it is probably safest to treat the selection of a Domain Name like the selection of any trademark.  You may want to contact a trademark search firm for a trademark and Domain Name search to make sure the name you wish to use is not already being used, and to discuss the matter with an attorney who handles trademark matters.
<P>
<STRONG>Question:</STRONG><BR>
I saw a few graphics on another Web site that would be perfect with the Web site we are building.  I checked and found no copyright notices on that Web site.  Can I use those graphics?
<P>
<STRONG>Answer:</STRONG><BR>  
The absence of a copyright notice does not mean that material is in the public domain (not protected by copyright).  Since the penalty for use of any work protected by a U.S. copyright (which can include text, graphics or music) can be as much as $100,000 for each unauthorized use, you should not use any material you find on any Web site without first obtaining permission from the owner of the copyright to do so.  You should also get that permission in writing.
<P>
<STRONG>Question:</STRONG><BR>
How do I protect my firm's Web site or parts of it from being copied?
<P>
<STRONG>Answer:</STRONG><BR>
 It makes sense to place a copyright notice on your Web site, and to actually make a deposit of the material on your Web site with the <A HREF=http://lcweb.loc.gov/copyright/copy1.html>U.S. Copyright Office </A>(generally you need to fill out a short form, send two copies of the material you wish to copyright and pay a $20 fee) which will protect your rights should you need to go to court.  However, you may wish to use a few of the various World Wide Web <A HREF=http://home.netscape.com/home/internet-search.html>search engines</A> to check the Web from time to time to make sure copyrighted material from your Web site has not been reused without your permission.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3><B>The Legal and Compliance Corner was prepared by <A HREF="mailto:eliot_wagner@ccmail.prusec.com">Eliot Wagner</A>, First Vice President & Associate General Counsel, Prudential Securities Incorporated, a founding member of the SIA Computer Law and Intellectual Property Roundtable</B>
<HR SIZE=4>
If you have any coments or questions regarding this newsletter, please contact <A HREF="mailto:pcassar@sia.com"><STRONG>Phyllis Cassar</STRONG></A>, Director of SIA Internet Services.
<HR>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
