<HEAD><TITLE>1995 annual report</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<!-- This HTML document was generated by PageMaker -->
<!-- On Wed Aug 07 10:04:19 1996 from "H:\INT1\annual.pm6" -->
<BODY BGCOLOR="#75B77D"><FONT SIZE=+4><B><EM>To Our Members</EM></B></FONT>
<HR><P>
<P>What determines the securities industry's future success?  Quality 
products and services, imaginative marketing, technological innovation and capital all 
will be important, while a favorable economic, legislative and regulatory 
environment will also be critical.  But most significant we believe is commitment  
commitment to our clients' interests, to the highest possible ethical standards, and to 
our industry's professionalism.
<P>At last November's annual meeting, SIA member firms voted unanimously to incorporate this 
commitment into SIA's bylaws and this 1995 Annual Report highlights these values. What are we doing to ensure 
that this commitment translates into value for our clients?
<P>This past summer, SIA undertook its first annual Investor Survey to learn more about investors' 
attitudes toward the industry, our firms and investing in general.  The majority (71%) of investors surveyed said 
they were &quot;very satisfied&quot; with the service they receive from their firms; fewer investors (55%) have a 
favorable opinion of our industry as a whole; some expressed specific concerns about greed, conflicts of interest 
and deception.  Significantly, we learned that only 7 percent of investors said firms do an excellent job of 
teaching their clients how to make better investment decisions  a task that nearly half said is essential.
<P>The survey results confirm our view that, in order to ensure that the industry's commitment to our 
clients is real, we must address ethical standards, the potential for conflicts of interest, compliance, the education 
of our professionals and, equally important, the education of investors.
<P>SIA is addressing each of these points with aggressive, industrywide programs.  In 1995 we 
endorsed the findings of the Committee on Compensation Practices (The Tully Report).  We also endorsed the 
findings of SIA's special Compliance and Legal Committee's &quot;Best Compliance Practices&quot; Report.  These and 
SIA's programs for industry education and investor education are described later in this Annual Report.
<P>SIA member firms also are proceeding with innovative programs in their own organizations to 
address these same issues.  SIA has been serving as a clearinghouse to distribute information about these programs 
to all SIA members.
<P>The past year was especially active in Washington, where SIA focused on the extraordinary 
legislative agenda advanced by the 104th Congress.  Every one of SIA's major advocacy issues was in play  fiscal 
and tax policy, financial restructuring, securities litigation reform and industry regulatory reforms.  
<P>SIA played a significant role in the enactment, over a presidential veto, of securities litigation reform. 
 This legislation directly addresses one of the foremost concerns of the securities industry.  Although 
the federal budget impasse has not been resolved as of this writing, SIA played an important role in 
supporting deficit reduction and in seeing that savings and investment incentives  IRA enhancements and a reduction 
in capital gains taxes  were included in the budget proposals.
<P>In 1996, tax reform, regulatory reform and financial restructuring will be at the top of SIA's 
advocacy priorities.
<P>The securities industry can be proud of its accomplishment in converting from a five-day to a 
three-day settlement (T+3) in June.  The successful conversion was the culmination of a five-year effort to reduce 
risk in the settlement system, and it resulted in many improvements to the network of systems among the 
Depository Trust Company,  National Securities Clearing Corporation, other clearing and depository entities 
and individual firms.  SIA's Clearance and Settlement Committee played a key role in managing this 
extremely complex conversion.  We congratulate the industry for a job well done.
<P>SIA's services to our members were enhanced during 1995 with the introduction of our Internet 
Access program, offered through UUNET Technologies, and the creation of a new local communications 
access program, offered through Teleport Communications Group.  These programs, together with existing 
offerings through Sprint, NYNEX and other vendors, create savings for the securities industry of more than $40 
million annually. 
<P>The securities industry enjoyed a remarkable year in 1995.  Industry profitability was sharply higher 
from 1994  and was second only to the record level of 1993.  The opportunities ahead are also positive: 
demographic trends, signaling the entry of more investors into the marketplace; increasing demands for capital by both 
U.S. and international issuers; and the rapid deployment of new communications technologies.
<P>We would like to express deep appreciation for the support of our members, with special thanks 
to Gordon R. Watson for his invaluable contribution as chairman of the Public Trust and Confidence 
Committee and to other board members, industry volunteers and staff, all of whom give SIA its vitality in helping 
the securities industry meet the challenges of the future.
<P>
John L. Steffens<BR>      
Chairman<P>
Marc E. Lackritz<BR>
President 
