<HEAD>
<TITLE>1995 annual report</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#75B77D">
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><EM>Industry Year in Review</EM></B></FONT><P><TABLE COLSPEC="L20" BORDER=2 WIDTH=50%>
<TR><TD> <IMG SRC="an9.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>The securities industry was buoyed by record volume and sharply increased stock prices in 1995 that 
carried market indexes to all-time highs.  Long-term interest rates closed the year down 200 basis points from 
their highs in 1994.  Retail-oriented firms, notably discounters and regional brokerage firms, particularly 
benefited from the upsurge in activity and prices.  Underwriting of corporate equity and debt securities strengthened as the year wore on, but was only slightly above 1994's levels, reflecting the Federal Reserve's 
restrictive monetary policy through the first half of 1995.  Initial public offerings were off earlier in the year, but 
recovered sufficiently to edge past 1994.  This trend eased pressures on investment banks and national 
full-line firms, which also benefited from revenue generated in the secondary market. 
<P>A major success in 1995 was the strong growth in mutual fund assets, which was most pronounced 
in equity funds; bond funds recovered somewhat from a brutal 1994.  Retail firms benefited from 
increased revenues both from selling mutual funds and from associated management fees, and mutual funds became 
the largest institutional customers for some firms.
<P>Municipal bond activity, on the other hand, declined from the year before  indeed, some firms 
continued to cut back on capital and personnel dedicated to this business.
<P>Overall, the profitability of SIA member firms is expected to show significant improvement over 
1994's $1.1 billion, attaining a total of as much as $7 billion, second only to the record $8.6 billion reached in 1993.  
<HR>
