<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>1995 annual report</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<!-- This HTML document was generated by PageMaker -->
<!-- On Wed Aug 07 10:04:19 1996 from "H:\INT1\annual.pm6" -->
<BODY BGCOLOR="#75B77D">
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><EM>Focus On Education</EM></B></FONT>
<P><STRONG>I.  Investor Education:  <BR>
Responding to Investor Needs</STRONG>
<P>Investors questioned in SIA's first annual Investor Survey said that they expect security firms to teach 
clients how to make better investment decisions.  They stated, however, that relatively few firms do an 
&quot;excellent&quot; job in this respect.  
<P>In response to the survey, SIA began developing a comprehensive investor education program to 
help investors obtain the knowledge needed to make decisions that are right for them through an enhanced 
understanding of economics, investment alternatives, and the costs, risks and rewards of investing.
<P>SIA's goal is to ensure that investor education is an ongoing priority throughout the securities industry. 
 SIA's Investor Education Committee is at work defining educational curricula to be made available to 
investors and prospective investors, and how best to distribute the information, whether directly from SIA or 
from member firms, consumer organizations, regulators or other groups.
<P>Among the specific initiatives under consideration are the creation of an investor education site on 
the Internet in conjunction with the Wharton School of Business of the University of Pennsylvania; a library 
of investor-oriented information; production of a public television series on the role of the securities industry; 
and a handbook of practical guidelines for use by member firms in communicating educational messages to 
the public.  SIA's successful Briefing Book will also be updated in 1996.
<P>Member firms are encouraged to foster greater involvement by their registered representatives 
and executives before groups of current and potential investors in their communities.  SIA is developing a 
package of lecture materials under its GLOBE (Guest Lecturers on Business and Economics) program.
<P>A long-established mainstay of SIA's investor education activities is the Stock Market Game, a 
teaching tool provided schools to introduce students to the basic principles of economics, finance and capital formation. 
 Since the game's inception in 1977, more than four million students, from the fourth grade through high 
school, have participated in the program in 50 states.  Last year, more than 600,000 students took part, an 
increase from 550,000 the year before.  Plans to automate the game and to offer it on the Internet are well under way. 
<P>The Stock Market Game program is sponsored by the Securities Industry Foundation for 
Economic Education (SIFEE), with the generous support of contributors and the valued assistance in the states 
of members or affiliates of the National Council on Economic Education, colleges and universities, SMG 
coordinators and member firms.
<P><STRONG>II.  Professional Education: <BR>
Commitment to a Higher Standard</STRONG><P>
The securities industry is committed to raising the level of professionalism of its executives through industry education programs that will improve customer service.SIA introduced in 1995 its Executive Ethics Roundtable series in conjunction with leading 
business schools across the country.  Two roundtables were held with the Stern School of New York University 
during 1995, and a spring roundtable has been announced with the University of Chicago Graduate School of 
Business.
<P>The industry's Council on Continuing Education, made up of industry volunteers and representatives of 
self-regulatory organizations, has developed a continuing education program for securities professionals 
consisting of two principal components:<P>
First, the regulatory requirement, effective last July 1, that securities professionals registered for 10 years or less take training courses on regulatory, ethical, compliance and sales-practice standards on the second, fifth and tenth anniversaries of their registration dates; they have 120 days from those anniversary dates to report to centers operated by the National Association of Securities Dealers in strategic locations nationwide.
<P>Second, the firm requirement, effective January 1, 1996, that all registered representatives and their 
immediate supervisors, regardless of seniority, take special training at their respective firms to be fully informed 
on specific products and services.  To help firms prepare for this requirement, SIA's Special Committee 
on Continuing Education developed extensive support materials, including a periodic newsletter, a Training 
Needs Analysis, a vendor resource guide and a series of &quot;how to&quot; outlines on developing and monitoring 
training plans.  To further emphasize the importance of ethics in the training of securities professionals, SIA is 
developing a separate course on ethics to be offered in 1996.
<P>An important component of the industry's professional education activities over the years has been the 
Securities Industry Institute, SIA's development program for industry professionals, held in cooperation with 
the Wharton School.  The Institute offers separate courses in general management and sales and 
marketing management in three annual weeklong segments.  The courses were attended in 1995 by a record 600 
securities firm executives and managers being groomed for leadership positions in their firms.  Since its founding 
43 years ago, the Institute has graduated an estimated 13,000 persons, many of whom have become 
industry leaders.
<P>SIA also offers Branch Manager Development programs.  Each program examines the knowledge, 
skills and attitudes relating to goal setting, staffing, coaching and marketing in a branch office.  An advanced 
session has been developed with Wharton for 1996 to enable experienced managers to continue their growth 
and development.
