<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>1995 annual report</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<!-- This HTML document was generated by PageMaker -->
<!-- On Wed Aug 07 10:04:19 1996 from "H:\INT1\annual.pm6" -->
<BODY BGCOLOR="#75B77D">
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><EM>Advocacy: Promoting Sound Public Policy for Investors, 
Member Firms and the Securities Industry</EM></B></FONT>
<P>
<STRONG>I. Federal Legislation</STRONG>
<P>As a leading advocate of the securities industry and the capital markets, SIA marshals the support and 
expertise of its members through testimony, issue-briefing papers, comment letters, amicus curiae briefs, 
and meetings with members of Congress, administration officials and regulators to advance policies that 
contribute to the financial well-being of investors, and the economic strength of the nation and its capital markets.
<P>A prominent feature of SIA's advocacy program is its Grassroots Network of thousands of 
securities industry executives, branch managers and registered representatives who have good working 
relationships with government officials.  During 1995, SIA called on the Grassroots Network to address tax and 
fiscal policy, securities litigation reform, comprehensive financial restructuring, securities regulation reform and 
other issues. 
<P><STRONG>Making a Difference on Capitol Hill</STRONG>
<P>The savings rate of Americans has fallen sharply from 8 percent in 1970 to 4 percent today  the 
lowest among industrialized countries.  If this trend continues, Americans of all ages will not be financially 
prepared for retirement.  In addition, the decline in the nation's savings pool has weakened the U.S. securities 
industry's competitiveness in the global markets.
<P>SIA made great strides on legislation to increase personal savings and fuel capital formation in 
1995, spearheaded by SIA Chairman John L. (Launny) Steffens.  Mr. Steffens testified before Congress that restoration of the 
full deductibility of the Individual Retirement Account and lower capital gains tax rates would bolster savings 
and generate capital.  
<P>SIA's drive to attain this priority legislation included a comprehensive study that confirmed the value 
of savings incentives for IRAs and 401(k) plans, a cooperative effort with a broad coalition of business 
organizations similarly concerned about the nation's inadequate savings rate, and the generation of 
substantial grassroots communications from member firms and their employees to key policymakers.  SIA's efforts 
were rewarded when Congress passed legislation to balance the budget in seven years, reduce capital gains 
taxes and promote IRAs.   
<P>In the intense political battle that ensued between Congress and the Clinton administration over 
revisions in Medicare and other issues, the administration countered with a package that penalized the issuance 
of certain forms of corporate equity and debt.  SIA launched an intensive campaign to defeat the 
administration proposals, arguing that these changes would increase the capital costs of U.S. firms and stifle 
economic growth.
<P>SIA continues to participate in the budget negotiations and will join the debate on tax reform in 1996 
to enact a tax policy that promotes savings, investment and capital formation.
<P><STRONG>Securities Litigation Reform Breakthrough </STRONG><TABLE COLSPEC="L20" BORDER=2 WIDTH=50%>
<TR><TD> <IMG SRC="an13.gif"></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>The major legislative achievement in 1995 was the enactment of the Private Securities Litigation Reform 
Act, first by passing it  by overwhelming bipartisan margins and then by overriding a presidential veto.  
Over several years, SIA's coordinated industry efforts to convince Congress to pass legislation that would strike 
the appropriate balance between discouraging the filing of non-meritorious claims and giving those who 
actually had been harmed access to speedy restitution.  SIA testified that providing plaintiffs and their lawyers 
with incentives to concentrate on cases that had true merit would significantly reduce the costs of capital 
formation while preserving the rights of investors to be compensated for fraud.
<P>Grassroots efforts helped defeat repeated attempts to extend the statute of limitations for private 
actions established in the Lampf v. Gilbertson U.S. Supreme Court decision.  Currently, private actions must 
be commenced within one year after discovery of the alleged violation and not more than three years after 
the violation occurred.  This allows aggrieved investors ample time to seek relief while also providing finality 
to business transactions and deterring false claims.  SIA also defeated bids to overturn the Supreme 
Court's Central Bank decision, which denied a private right of action for &quot;aiding and abetting liability&quot; under 
Section 10(b) of the federal securities laws.
<P><STRONG>Progress on Financial Services Modernization Bill</STRONG>
<P>In early 1995, SIA hoped that Congress would modernize the nation's laws governing the financial 
services industry to reflect advances in technology and increased global competition.  The House began work 
to provide significant new benefits to consumers through increased competition and improved efficiencies, but 
the effort steadily lost momentum as traditional turf battles erupted between the banks and the insurance industry.
<P>In congressional testimony, SIA President Marc E. Lackritz said that SIA was committed to legislation 
to promote competition among all financial services providers by enabling banks to own full-service 
securities firms and securities firms to own or affiliate with banks  a &quot;two-way street&quot;  as well as by ensuring 
that all financial providers be governed by consistent rules  a policy of functional regulation.  The central 
tenets of SIA's plan for financial restructuring  providing for holding company structure; a non-federally 
insured wholesale financial institution; functional regulation; and a &quot;two-way street&quot;  were included in the 
House bill.  The Senate, which had been awaiting final House action, indicated its desire to craft a bolder approach 
to federal regulations governing financial services.  SIA will continue to argue its position as this 
legislation evolves in 1996. 
<P><STRONG>Federal Securities Regulation Reform</STRONG><TABLE COLSPEC="L20" BORDER=2 WIDTH=50%>
<TR><TD> <IMG SRC="an15.gif"></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>Recognizing the need to streamline the federal securities regulatory system and reduce the cost of 
capital-raising in the U.S., House Telecommunications and Finance Subcommittee Chairman Jack Fields 
(R-TX) solicited the industry's input in drafting the Capital Markets Deregulation Act of 1995 (H.R. 2131).  
SIA's Board of Directors unanimously voted to support the overall bill, and SIA's 1996 chairman, A. B. Krongard 
of Alex. Brown &amp; Sons Inc., strongly endorsed the key elements of the legislation in testimony before the 
House panel in early December.  One of the strongest reasons to support the bill, Krongard said, is its 
proposed rationalization of the confusing patchwork of 50 separate state regulatory requirements that add to the 
complexity of America's capital market structure, raise the cost of capital and impair investors' opportunities.  
The bill, on the other hand, would still allow states to require securities professionals to register with them, 
and preserve each state's ability to police against fraud and to collect fees from market participants.  
Krongard also praised the bill's effort to clarify the differing suitability obligations for retail and institutional clients.
<P>Although the House did not have time to act before the 1995 congressional session ended, 
Chairman Fields indicated that he plans to move the bill forward quickly in 1996.  
<P><STRONG>SEC Self-Funding Proposal</STRONG>
<P>SIA strongly supported legislation providing the SEC with adequate financial resources to effectively carry 
out its investor protection mandate, but opposed the imposition of new fees to pay down the federal deficit.  
SIA argued that current SEC fees raise hundreds of millions of dollars more annually for the federal 
government than are spent by the SEC, thereby creating a capital tax that is unfair to investors and harmful to the 
nation's capital formation process.  
<P>President Clinton subsequently proposed a budget that would increase SEC fees, with the surplus to 
be turned over to the Treasury.  SIA will work with Congress and the administration in 1996 to develop 
appropriate SEC funding legislation.
<P><STRONG>Derivatives Markets Subjected to Congressional Scrutiny</STRONG>
<P>High-profile losses by Orange County, California, and the former Barings investment firm initially 
prompted serious congressional concern with derivatives markets.   Through the efforts of SIA and others, however, 
the industry educated policymakers about the value of derivatives and the regulations that govern them.  As 
a result, Congress has retreated from proposals to regulate the derivatives market unnecessarily.
<P>In a hearing last January before the Senate Banking Committee, Mr. Lackritz emphasized that the 
losses by Orange County were caused by an aggressive investment strategy regarding interest rates, and not by 
the derivatives used to implement the strategy.  He asserted further that restricting access by certain 
institutions, such as municipalities, to derivatives would deprive investors of tools to manage their portfolio better.  
The House Banking Committee also held hearings on the Orange County bankruptcy, after which several 
key policymakers stated they did not see an immediate need for legislative action.
<P>
<P><STRONG><FONT SIZE=+1>II.  State Regulation and Legislation</FONT></STRONG>
<P>SIA represented the interests of investors, securities firms and the industry generally in the states on a 
wide variety of issues in 1995. 
<P>No fewer than 10 states sought to increase broker-dealer liability severely when dealing with 
municipalities and to limit municipal and pension fund investment authority.  By showing how modern portfolio theory 
and management can reduce risk while increasing returns, SIA succeeded in gaining approval of amendments 
in California, Florida, Ohio, Illinois and Maryland to reduce or eliminate the threat that poorly drafted 
legislation presented to the capital markets.  SIA worked successfully to stop several similar bills in New York 
and Wisconsin.  California, in a special yearlong legislative session concerning Orange County and aimed 
at increasing broker-dealer liability in municipal markets, adopted a municipal finance officer training and 
accountability package developed by an SIA-led consortium.
<P>SIA gained a securities industry exemption from Texas's Deceptive Trade Practices Act, which 
trial lawyers fought hard to retain; SIA was able to win the exemption by showing how stringently the 
securities industry is regulated  at the state as well as the federal level.  Oregon enacted SIA-supported legislation 
to increase plaintiffs' burden of proof in punitive damage causes of action and to grant broad power to trial 
court  judges to reduce excessive jury awards.  In Washington, SIA worked successfully to defeat a broad bill 
that would have created new regulatory and private rights of action against broker-dealers.
<P>New Jersey, South Dakota, Tennessee and Utah adopted the Uniform Transfer on Death 
Securities Registration Act in 1995.  This brings to 25 the number of states enabling investors to share an account with 
a beneficiary who would receive the securities immediately upon the transferor's death.  
<P>SIA was pivotal as New York became the first state legislature to approve the new Uniform 
Combined State Law Exam, which permits an applicant to qualify as both a securities agent and as a 
NASAA-recognized investment advisor.  More than 30 states have adopted the new exam.
<P>SIA contributed to legislation in Arkansas, Illinois and Missouri to assure interstate uniformity and 
reduce regulatory multiplicity with regard to securities registration exemptions, record-keeping requirements, 
statutes of limitation, and assuring due process in administrative actions.
<P>SIA stopped intangibles taxes in Florida, Georgia, South Dakota and Massachusetts, and in 
California, SIA helped gain enactment of legislation prohibiting localities from imposing taxes on non-residents.
<P>Enactment of the Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995 at the federal level has shifted 
the battle to the states.  The California plaintiffs' bar has already circulated for qualification as a referendum 
on the November ballot the Retirement Savings and Consumer Protection Act, which would make California 
state courts the courts of choice for plaintiffs' attorneys; hold firms liable for acts taken even without 
culpable intent; revive &quot;fraud on the market,&quot; &quot;aiding and abetting,&quot; and &quot;reliance&quot; presumptions long eliminated 
in securities law; remove the statute of limitation for derivative actions; and create new causes of action 
by joining statutory presumptions to common-law actions.  SIA will vigorously oppose this and similar 
legislation arising in other states.
<P>In 1996, SIA is committed to reducing broker-dealers' registration and reporting burdens; to 
reducing broker-dealer vulnerability to meritless lawsuits and arbitrary regulation; and to increasing the number 
of broker-dealers who may maintain custody of securities for insurance companies and municipalities.
<P>
<P><FONT SIZE=+1><B>III. Securities Regulation</B></FONT>
<P><STRONG>Improving Regulation of the Securities Markets</STRONG>
<P>SIA works extensively with the SEC, the CFTC, SROs and other regulators both in the U.S. and abroad 
to represent the industry's views on a host of regulatory issues.  Some recent examples include convincing 
the SEC not to alter Regulation S so as to diminish its utility for offshore transactions; urging the SEC to 
revise trading practice rules; minimizing the regulatory burden on payment-for-order-flow disclosures; 
supporting proposals to reduce holding periods for restricted securities and to eliminate restrictions on general 
solicitation under the main private placement exemption; and commenting on a company registration proposal.  
We assisted our members' efforts to work with the New York Federal Reserve Bank to develop a set of 
&quot;Principles and Practices&quot; for parties trading in the wholesale over-the-counter markets.  SIA committees 
also commented on the NASD's proposed institutional suitability rules.  Internationally, SIA filed a comment 
letter with the Australian Securities and Exchange Commission addressing regulatory proposals affecting the 
OTC derivatives market in that country.  
<P>SIA also sought solutions to the prospectus delivery problems arising in the new T+3 environment.  
SIA's committees worked together to develop two alternatives that better allow firms to deliver information 
to investors in accordance with the Securities Act of 1933.  The SEC adopted both proposals, giving firms 
the flexibility to choose the methodologies best suited to their transactions.
<P>In connection with the advent of T+3, the SEC urged the securities industry to work with transfer 
agents to develop an electronic system for executing trades for securities that are held via direct registration on 
the books of an issuer.  The system would involve an electronic linkage between the books of an issuer or 
its transfer agent and the books of broker-dealers who would execute trades in such securities.  
<P>SIA persuaded the SEC not to link development of such a system to the advent of T+3.  SIA 
also requested that the system include the participation of securities depositories, that street-name 
shareholders have access to all dividend reinvestment plans, and that investor protection be consistent between direct 
and street-name owners.
<P><STRONG>Providing the Courts with Expert Opinions <BR>
On Securities Law</STRONG>
<P>Courts pay careful attention to SIA's views as an expert on securities law and the operations of 
securities markets.  SIA filed amicus curiae briefs in 1995 in the areas of limiting liability, upholding the 
arbitration process and validating fees.
<P>In Gustafson v. Alloyd, SIA successfully argued that the U.S. Supreme Court should reject an 
interpretation of the term &quot;prospectus&quot; that would have discouraged corporations from disclosing information 
and imposed an inappropriate liability on market professionals.
<P>Arbitration is a fair, inexpensive and quick method for resolving disputes between firms and their 
customers or their employees.  In First Options v. 
Kaplan, the U.S. Supreme Court accepted SIA's views on 
the interpretation and procedural issues of arbitration agreements.
<P>In St. Jude Medical v. Medtronic, SIA successfully argued to the Minnesota Court of Appeals 
that investment banks' termination fees are valid under state law.  The decision ensures that tender offers 
can proceed in an orderly manner with all parties being able to obtain expert advice.
<P>
<P><FONT SIZE=+1><B>IV.  International</B></FONT>
<P><STRONG>Expanding U.S. Access to Markets Overseas</STRONG>
<P>Foreign markets continue to grow in importance to the U.S. securities industry and its clients.  SIA's work 
to reduce barriers to  these markets was highlighted in 1995 by the signing of <BR>
the U.S.-Japanese Framework Agreement on financial services.  U.S.-based firms thereby gained access 
to the $400-billion Japanese public pension market, and improved their access to Japan's corporate bond 
underwriting market and capital account transactions.<P>SIA also helped U.S. negotiators seek a most-favored-nation exemption in the World Trade 
Organization financial services negotiations.  This exemption allows the U.S. to deny access to firms based in countries 
that do not provide access and preserves the U.S. ability to negotiate on a bilateral basis.  
<P>South Korea has become one of Asia's wealthiest emerging markets with an economic growth 
rate among the fastest in the world.  Yet it remains one of the more restrictive markets.  Steven Judge, SIA 
senior vice president, testified before a House panel that liberalizing the South Korean market should be a key 
U.S. objective.
<P>SIA also submitted papers to the Summit of the Americas and the Asia-Pacific Economic 
Community Forum (APEC).  The 34 Western Hemisphere nations that make up the Summit aspire to create a free 
trade area of the Americas.  APEC is an 18-member-nation forum whose objective is to create the world's 
largest free-trade zone.
<HR>
