<HEAD>
<TITLE>1995 annual report</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#75B77D">
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><EM>Financial Summary</EM></B></FONT>
<P>
<P><STRONG>Fiscal Years Ended October 31, 1995 and 1994</STRONG>
<P>SIAis a not-for-profit corporation under the Internal Revenue Code.  The Association is funded by annual 
dues from its members, which make up 68% of its revenues, and by proceeds from conferences, 
publications, member services and other activities, which make up 32%. 
<P>SIA increased its financial reserves by $1,127,782 or 20.1% in fiscal 1995 to $6,727,273.  The 
increase was attributable to an appreciation on long term investment of $1,368,642 and a surplus from operations 
of $108,448, partially offset by an adjustment to recognize liability under the supplemental retirement plan 
of $349,308.
<P>Revenues from operations totaled $19.2 million and were 3.9% higher than in fiscal 1994, 
reflecting active participation by member firms in all of SIA's programs.
<P>Expenses for 1995 operations totaled $18.3 million and were 2.6% higher than in 1994.  Special 
closing adjustments and charges related to prior years brought total expenses to $19.1 million, or 7.0% higher than 
in fiscal 1994.
<P>SIA's long-term investment account totaled $9.4 million at fiscal year end and reflected an 
appreciation of $1,368,642 or 17.1% for the year.  The account is maintained to fund SIA's long term liabilities for 
employee benefits and retirement as well as for general reserves, and is managed by outside investment managers 
with oversight by the Audit and Financial Committee.
<P>The association is audited by Coopers &amp; Lybrand.
<P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Income Statement</B></FONT>
