Meeting highlights include: 
<P>
<UL>
<LI>'STREET SURVEY' - To date, there have been 32 responses.  There is still time to respond and complete the <A HREF="sia09zc.htm">survey</A>.  Survey results will be a topic of discussion at the October 24 Year 2000 Committee meeting.  A consolidated spreadsheet of Survey responses will be distributed.
<LI>Year 2000 Conversion Vendors will also be a topic of discussion at the next meeting.
<LI>The concern was raised once again that Street executives should be advised to avoid introducing new products, major system changes, etc. that would interfere with the Year 2000 effort.
<LI>Year 2000 Status reports were presented by the following agencies:
</UL>
<P>
<dd><B>NASD</B> - (Jack Samarias)
<P>
1. Year 2000 Planning to be completed by the end of 1996<BR>
2. Website for Year 2000 information will be available by end 1996<BR>
3. Modifications for Year 2000 completed by end 1998<BR>
4. Has met with a number of firms and NSCC, NYSE, DTC, AMEX, etc. to develop common standards<BR>
5. A copy of Jack's presentation will be mailed to meeting attendees and to those whose name appear on the revised list of committee members.
<P>
<dd><B>OCC</B> - (Len Neuzil)
<P>
1. OCC has contracted with COMDISCO to use the Millennium Testing Services and use COMDISCO hardware located in New Jersey for their Year 2000 testing.<BR>
2. Len suggested a comprehensive group test by firms and agencies on 'Off Site' equipment.<BR>
3. OCC's INTRACS (Intermarket Trade Clearing System) was converted to 8 character date formats between 1985 and 1994.<BR>
4. 70% of OCC's internal Year 2000 development and testing has been completed.<BR>
5. OCC's Year 2000 Strategy:<BR>
a. Completed their inventory March 31, 1996 <BR>
b. Define 1997 Test Plan - completed September, 1996 Plan will test core systems excluding outside vendors.  Will be a 3 phase plan using COMDISCO Millennium Testing Services.<BR>
<P>
<dd><B>Legal Implications of the Year 2000</B> - (William Bierce, Attorney at Law, Bierce & Kenerson, P.C.)
<P>
1. Discussed topics of Common Law, Government Regulation, Financial and Accounting Rules, and Fiduciary Obligations to shareholders and others.<BR>
2. Presented a preliminary list of Cause of Action against Directors and Officers for Year 2000 Non-Compliance.<BR>
3. Discussed limitations of liability:  incorporation, insurance, indemnification, etc.<BR>
4. Discussed legal implications of outsourcing contracts.
<P>
<dd><B>Committee to Coordinate Interfacing Agencies</B><BR>
<dd>(Exchange and Utility Industry Group) - (Stephen Romano, SIAC)
<P>
1. This currently independent committee will report to Mike Tiernan.<BR>
2. The following agencies have agreed to participate:  AMEX / NYSE / NSCC / SIAC / OCC / PHLX / DTC / MBSCC/GSCC / PTC / CHICAGO STOCK EXCHANGE / IDC / PSE / (CBOE to be contacted)<BR>
3. Will consolidate testing in 1999.<BR>
4. Will attempt to standardize date/year format.  'It is their intention...to set a direction of an eight digit contiguous date.'<BR>
5. '...plan to support both eight and six digit formats for implementation purposes.  This approach allows the flexibility of products to be implemented independent of the readiness of each of the member firms.  Our next step is to investigate a joint integrated industry test plan that we can share street wide.'<BR>
6. Steve also plans to seek bank involvement.<BR>
7. Steve requests early involvement by affected agencies.
<P>
<dd><B>Sub-Committee of Data and Service Providers</B> - (William Quinn, Lewco Securities Corp.)
<P>
1. Year 2000 Sub-Committee reporting to Mike Tiernan.<BR>
2. Currently preparing survey to be sent to Data and Service Providers.  Will request information indicating their Year 2000 efforts, how the efforts will affect member firms, and when they will be prepared to test with member firms.
<P>
<dd><B>Sub-Committee for Street-wide Testing</B><P>
Mike Tiernan is seeking a chairperson and volunteers for this sub-committee.
<P>
<IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <STRONG><A NAME="oct24">October 24, 1996</A></STRONG>
<P>
Handouts include: 
<P>
<UL>
<LI>AGENDA for the October 24, 1996 Meeting
<LI>Revised  (as of October 24, 1996) List of Year 2000 Committee Members/Attendees and Year 2000 Firm Coordinators
<LI>A  'YEAR 2000 TOOL LIST'.  This document lists Year 2000 software vendors by the following:
<dd>(1)  Company Name
<dd>(2)  Tool / Methodology
<dd>(3)  Applicable Programming Language(s)
<dd>(4)  Applicable Platform(s)
<dd>(5)  Comments regarding the product
<LI>Draft of the  'SIA/DMD Year 2000 Sub-Committee Data and Services Providers Survey'  provided by William Quinn (LEWCO Securities Corp.), chairman of the Data and Service Providers sub-committee.  See below.
<LI>List of  Year 2000 Streetwide Testing  Sub-Committee members and a draft indicating areas of testing to be defined.  See below.
<LI>Results of surveys prepared and distributed by the SIA, and the DMD Year 2000 Committee.  See below.
</UL>
<P>
Meeting highlights include: 
<P>
<OL>
<LI>Due to increased attendance and topics to be discussed, Mike Tiernan is investigating the following:<BR>
A.  Permanently changing meeting start from  3:30PM  to  2:00PM<BR>
B.  Relocating meeting site to a larger location<BR>
While the meetings are held at the SIA (120 Bdwy), those wishing to telephone conference may call 1-800- 860-2442 .  Committee members will be advised of changes involving site and/or time.
<P>
<LI>Year 2000 Status reports were presented by the following Sub-committees:<BR>
A.  Interfacing Agencies   (George Catalanotto for Steve Romano)
<dd>1.  Have met with NASD and SIAC to discuss data formats and integrated testing
<dd>2.  Sub-committee meetings will begin in mid-November
<dd>3.  There is a recognized need to involve foreign agencies<BR>
B.  Data and Service Providers  (William Quinn)
<dd>1.  Will distribute a Year 2000 Survey to Data and Service Providers by mid-November  
<dd>2.  Intends to distribute results of survey by end of  January 1997<BR>
C.  Street-wide Testing
<dd>1.  Dawn Lowell  (Lehman Brothers, Inc.) will chair this Sub-committee
<dd>2.  Volunteers are still required for this Sub-committee / Contact Dawn if interested
<dd>3.  Dawn is also seeking high level participation by large firms
<dd>4.  A draft of 'Areas to Define for Street-Wide Testing' was distributed  
<P>
<LI>Attendees discussed the status of their firms Year 2000 effort, especially their experiences with Year 2000 Software Vendors and products.
<P>
<LI>If your Year 2000 Inventory phase reveals missing program source code, there is a vendor that provides recovery capability:
<dd>The Source Recovery Co.                
<dd>992 East Freeway Dr.  Suite A
<dd>Conyers, Georgia  30207
<dd>770-785-9801
<P>
<LI>Mike Tiernan is investigating an end to end solution for a firm's Year 2000 effort.  Year 2000 Software vendors have or will be contacted regarding the partnering of their products to provide a comprehensive solution for the Year 2000 effort from  Inventory and Assessment thru the Testing and Implementation phases.
<P>
<LI>Art Thomas (Merrill Lynch)  is forming an executive steering committee to define street-wide testing at the business level
<P>
<LI>During the vendor discussion, it was revealed that in cases where conversion to  8  character date formats is impractical, firms are opting to use 'windowing'  (a.k.a. displacement or procedural methods of  representing dates).  E.G. 'Windowing using 80'  -  where only a  2  digit year is possible.  A date prior to  80  is considered  21st Century, a date after  80  is considered  20th Century. 
<P>
<LI>Following is a consolidation of comments pertaining to Year 2000 Software vendor product compliance.<BR>
A.  Two firms were noted for validating vendor compliance.
<dd>1.  Datapro
<dd>- charges $100  for each vendor contact
<dd>- will test and validate vendors
<dd>2.  ITAA
<dd>- Information Technology Association of  America
<dd>- certifies vendor capabilities but not individual vendor products<BR>
B.  A suggestion to investigate a 'street group rate' for vendor and product assurance was made.<BR>
C.  There was concern that third party vendor/product validation would be questioned by auditors.<BR>
D.  Mike Tiernan will investigate the establishment of a sub-committee whose concern would be Software vendor Year 2000 compliance.  Elizabeth McInerney (Fidelity Investments) may have someone from Fidelity to chair this sub-committee.<BR>
E.  A suggestion was made that the SIA / DMD undertake the certification of Year 2000 vendors.<BR>
F.  In conjunction with this discussion the question was presented:  If your firm has placed its software at your client(s), or allows your client(s) access to your systems, what is your liability with respect to Y2k vendor compliance?
<P>
<LI>Tom Duffy (C.S. First Boston, Inc.) presented the results of  surveys distributed by the SIA, and the DMD Year 2000 Committee.  Tom prepared a consolidated spreadsheet for the responses received in each survey.  Identity of responding firms was not revealed.<BR>
A.  There were  35  responses from the  180  mailings of the DMD survey.<BR>
B.  There were  63  responses from the mailing of the SIA survey.<BR>
C.  For each survey Tom prepared a Survey Recap sheet.
</OL>
<P>
<IMG SRC="goldball.gif"> <STRONG><A NAME="nov26">November 26, 1996</A></STRONG>
<P>
Handouts include: 
<P>
<UL>
<LI>AGENDA for the November 26, 1996 Meeting
<LI>Year 2000 Meeting Schedule inclusive of January 1997
<LI>Revised (as of November 6, 1996) List of Year 2000 Committee Members
<LI>'YEAR 2000 STATUS BY PLATFORM' Spreadsheet  (See below.)
<LI>Year 2000 BUDGET QUESTIONNAIRE (See below.)
<LI>Information pertaining to the '2ND INTERNATIONAL CONFERENCE ON YEAR 2000 COMPUTING', sponsored by DPMA Year 2000 Committee / SIG-Mainframe  (December 6 & 7, 1996)
<LI>Brochure and diskette describing DATAPRO products and services (See below.)
<LI>'SIA YEAR 2000 PROPOSAL' by CITYMAX (See below.)
</UL>
<P>
Meeting highlights include: 
<P>
<OL>
<LI>As stated in last month's minutes, Art Thomas (Merrill Lynch) is forming a 'Business Operations' Steering Committee for the Year 2000 effort.  Mike Tiernan has been requested to be a member of this Committee and will serve as a liaison between the Steering Committee and the Year 2000 DMD Committee.  The Steering Committee will begin meeting in January or February 1997.
<P>
<LI>Year 2000 Status reports were presented by the following Sub-Committees:<BR>
A.  Exchange and Utilities Sub-Committee (Steve Romano)  (Note:  This Sub-Committee was formerly known as Interfacing Agencies)
<OL>
<LI>To date, there are 8 Exchanges and 9 Utilities represented on this Sub-Committee.  Their next meeting will be December 16, 1996. 
<LI>They are standardizing on  8  character representation of dates.  For a period of time (No dates specified as yet), they will operate in both  8  and  6  character date modes.  This will allow firms to convert  to  8  character format at their convenience.
<LI>Target for industrywide testing is still early 1999
<LI>Testing Approach:<BR>
a.  Define a 'Production-like' test environment<BR>
b.  Define an Industrywide test plan across Exchanges and Utilities<BR>
c.  Schedule potential testing dates (e.g. 3 day weekends) for industrywide testing
<LI>'Street Readiness'  -  develop a method of assessing participant readiness for Year 2000 compliance
</OL>
B.  Data and Service Providers (Mike Tiernan for Bill Quinn)
<OL>
<LI>Survey for completion by Data and Service Providers has been prepared but not yet distributed.
</OL>
C.  Street-wide Testing  Sub-Committee (Dawn Lowell)
<OL>
<LI>To date,  there are  13  representatives on this Sub-Committee (a partial list: Bear Sterns, ADP, SIAC, NSCC, Fidelity, Morgan, CS First Boston, Lehman, Paine Webber).  A list of participants will be published.
<LI>Representation is still being solicited from large firms and especially Regional Firms.
<LI>First meeting will be  December 10, 1996.  Contact Dawn for membership or meeting time specifics.  This meeting may be held in coordination with the first Third Party Software Sub-Committee meeting.    
<LI>A major purpose of this Sub-Committee will be to define firm requirements as opposed to Exchange and Utility requirements in the street-wide testing scenario.  This includes planning for the reception of data from the Data and Service Providers.
</OL>
D.  Third Party Software Sub-Committee  (Elizabeth McInerney for Kathleen Ulich)
<OL>
<LI>First meeting of this Sub-Committee will be  December 10, 1996.  The meeting maybe coordinated with that of the Street-wide Testing Sub-Committee 
<LI>This Sub-Committee is soliciting members.  Contact Kathleen for membership or meeting specifics.
<LI>Meeting topics will be:  Sub-Committee objectives, Preparation of survey pertaining to Third Party Software Vendors, identification of  vendors whose software may affect the Year 2000 conversion effort.
</OL>  
<P>
<LI>A 'YEAR 2000 STATUS BY PLATFORM' spreadsheet was prepared and distributed by Mike Tiernan.  The spreadsheet consists of  3  columns.  They are:  (1)  Platform Description  -  hardware and software components, (2)  Year 2000 Compliancy information,  and (3)  Comments.  Mike is asking Committee members to provide information for platforms/software/compliancy not listed.  He will update the spreadsheet and distribute it periodically.
<P>
<LI>Attendees of this meeting were given a 'Year 2000 BUDGET QUESTIONNAIRE' prepared by Mike Baxter (Morgan Stanley).  The questionnaire contained  3  areas for completion:  (1)  Company Size (# of employees), (2)  Budget Forecast, (3)  a question - 'Have the CEO and Board of Directors been informed of the project and its projections?'.  The results of the questionnaire, completed anonymously, will be consolidated and presented at the next meeting.
<P>
<LI>There is a need for information regarding the status of Foreign Agencies and their Year 2000 activities.  Please contact Mike Tiernan if you can contribute information in this area.
<P>
<LI>The Committee may solicit presentation(s) by third party testing facility vendors (e.g. COMDISCO).
<P>
<LI>Michael Mathern and Dale Kredatus from Datapro Information Services Group (McGraw-Hill), a provider of  Third Party Software Services, presented the following:<BR>
A.  Datapro provides a service to contact software vendors (Product Managers) by questionnaire and to analyze responses for Year 2000 compliancy.<BR>
B.  The cost is  $100 per application per product.  There will be a Year 2000 Committee discount (not specified).<BR>
C.  They allow a  60  day response time to questionnaires and within that time will conduct as many as 5 follow-up requests for a response.  As of this date, they have not attempted to test third party software for Year 2000 compliancy.  They have not been able to develop a legal form that will universally be acceptable as specifying Year 2000 compliancy for a product(s).<BR>
D.  In providing their Year 2000 service, they have discovered:
<OL>
<LI>Older versions of a product are most difficult for a vendor to modify for compliancy because the human expertise may no longer be available.
<LI>THIRD PARTY SOFTWARE VENDORS HAVE NOT GRASPED THE IMPORTANCE OF THE Year 2000 EFFORT NOR VIEW IT AS A SERIOUS PROBLEM. 
</OL>
<P>
<LI>Lewis Ross of  CITYMAX presented a proposal to the DMD Year 2000 Committee.  He expressed the need to develop a common understanding of Year 2000 compliance and to 'DEFINE A STREET STANDARD FOR YEAR 2000 COMPLIANCE'.   CITYMAX proposed to do the following:<BR>
A.  Prepare and distribute a questionnaire for SIA member interviews<BR>       
B.  Interview each SIA member firm using the questionnaire our guideline<BR>
C.  Compile, organize, and present results in checklist format<BR>
D.  Publish approved checklist for use in evaluating vendor software.  A final approved checklist would be available in March 1997.  The cost of this proposal would be  $500.00  per DMD member firm plus expenses.
<P>
<LI>Mike Tiernan will solicit response from the Committee to the proposal from CITYMAX and ascertain member interest in the proposal.
</OL>
<P>
