<HTML>
<TITLE>Highlights of Investor Survey</TITLE>
<body background="sia3abac.gif"><IMG SRC="siaband.gif" ALT="Securities Industry Association"><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+4><B><EM>1995 Investor Survey --<BR> Highlights of Key Findings</EM></B></FONT><P><P>
<HR NOSHADE=4>
<EM><STRONG>Views Toward Brokers</STRONG></EM><BR>
The majority of investors -- 71 percent of investors with a full-service broker, and 67 percent of investors with a discount broker -- are "very satisfied" with the service they receive.<P>
Investors give their brokers high marks for good, prompt service (34 percent for both those with full-service and discount brokers), providing information to make them more knowledgeable about their investments (30 percent for those with full-service brokers and 13 percent for those with discount brokers), and convenience (26 percent and 25 percent).<P>
Nearly half (47 percent) of investors say it is "absolutely essential" or "extremely desirable" for brokerage firms to teach them how to make better investment decisions.  However, brokerage firms receive the lowest marks for their performance in this area, with only 7 percent of investors saying that firms do an "excellent" job of teaching them how to make better investment decisions.<P>
<EM><STRONG>Views Toward Securities Industry</STRONG></EM><BR>
More than half of investors surveyed (55 percent) say they have a "very" or "somewhat" favorable opinion of the securities industry.<P>
Investors with a brokerage account are nearly twice as likely (21 percent) to hold a very favorable opinion of the industry than those without a broker (11 percent).<P>
Women and young investors are the least likely to have a "very favorable" opinion of the securities industry, with only 12 percent of women and 13 percent of investors under 40 expressing a "very favorable" opinion.<P>
Nearly half of investors (46 percent) are unable to pinpoint the main issues facing the industry when responding on an unaided basis.  However, when provided with a range of issues that may be considered problems for the industry, investors most frequently cite greed, putting broker interests ahead of the investors', and industry reluctance to punish wrongdoers as "big problems." <P>
About 1 in 4 investors hold a "very" or "somewhat" unfavorable opinion of the industry.  When asked what issues shape this opinion, they most frequently cite "fraud/dishonesty," "greed/high compensation" and "high commissions/fees."<P>
While industry issues concern investors of all ages, investors over the age of 65 consistently indicated fewer problems with specific securities industries issues than their younger counterparts.  Only 36 percent of investors over the age of 65 feel there is a problem with brokers or firms putting their own interests ahead of investors' interests, while 52 percent of investors under 65 feel there is a problem.<P>
Investors without a brokerage account show greater concern about greed (60 percent), punishment of wrongdoers (53 percent), and the stability of brokerage firms (42 percent) than those currently working with a broker. <P>
<EM><STRONG>Investor Confidence</STRONG></EM><BR>
More than 7 in 10 investors say they feel "very" or "fairly" confident in their own ability to make sound investment decisions, with older investors reporting greater confidence than younger investors.<P>
Few investors (5 percent) say they know "everything they need to know" to make good investment decisions, whereas 57 percent feel they know "just some" or "very few" things necessary to make good decisions.<P>
Three-quarters of investors with a brokerage account (74 percent) say their brokers help them make smarter investment decisions.<P>
Men are only slightly more confident in their investing abilities than women, with 74 percent of men and 67 percent of women saying they are "very" or "fairly" confident.<P>
<EM><STRONG>Investor Protection</STRONG></EM><BR>
The majority of investors (51 percent) feel that there should be more investor protections in place.  Two-thirds (65 percent) of those who want more protections say they should be implemented by the brokerage/securities industry, rather than by the government (25 percent). <P>
<EM><STRONG>Investment Goals</STRONG></EM><BR>
Three-quarters of investors say they are investing mainly for long-term growth, and only 1 in 10 are looking for a quick return on their investments. <P>
Saving for retirement is the prime motivator for the majority of investors (53 percent), but one fourth of investors under age 40 say the cost of children's college education is their foremost goal.  Nineteen percent of women say their primary investment goal is saving for college, compared to 13 percent of men.<P>
Gaining a better return on savings is far more important for seniors than for younger investors -- 24 percent say this is their most important investment goal (compared to 10 - 14 percent of investors in other age groups).<P>
<EM><STRONG>Sources of Investment Advice</STRONG></EM><BR>
Investors use a variety of sources for information, with 53 percent relying on advice from colleagues, friends, or relatives, and 42 percent consulting personal finance magazines.<P>
Eight in 10 investors having an account with a full service broker compared with 45 percent of investors with discount brokers say they consult their broker for investment decisions "very often" or "sometimes." <P>
<EM><STRONG>Broker Fees</STRONG></EM><BR>
While more than half of investors feel they understand brokerages' pricing structures "very" or "fairly" well, a significant number -- 45 percent -- say they have difficulty understanding brokerage pricing.<P>
Investors are split on whether brokers offer enough fee choices, with close to half of all investors surveyed (47 percent) saying they feel there are a sufficient amount of fee structures and 36 percent saying there are not.<P>
There is no definitive preference for commissions or flat fees.  Forty-two percent prefer commission pricing, while 48 percent want a flat fee structure.<P>
<EM><STRONG>Outlook for 1996</STRONG></EM><BR>
Investors have an optimistic outlook for 1996.  Close to half (47 percent) of the investors surveyed believe 1996 will be a "very good" or "good" year for investments.  Forty percent predict at least an "average year," while only 8 percent say it will be a bad year.<P>
The health of the economy plays a leading role in investors' positive or negative outlook for the investing climate.  Forty-seven percent of optimistic investors cite a strong economy as the leading reason for a positive investment climate, while 38 percent of pessimistic investors feel a poor economy will negatively affect investors.<P>
<EM><STRONG>Policy Issues</STRONG></EM><BR>
When asked to choose between a capital gains tax cut and a balanced budget, 60 percent of investors favor balancing the budget, compared to 37 percent who favor a tax cut.<P>
More than 7 in 10 investors say tax-deductible IRAs (72 percent) and a balanced budget (71 percent) are "extremely" or "very" important in encouraging investments. <P>
More than half (52 percent) of investors favor the institution of a flat tax system.<P>
<EM><STRONG>Use of On-line Investing Services</STRONG></EM><BR>
Two-thirds of investors who do not currently use on-line services to invest (65 percent) say they either have no interest in making their own on-line investments or would prefer dealing with a "real person."  Half of those investors who use on-line services (54 percent) describe them as "very" or "fairly" useful in their investing; however, 44 percent find these services to be only "somewhat" useful or "not really" useful.<P>
<EM><STRONG>Investor Profile</STRONG></EM><BR>
Most investors say they fall into the middle of the investing style spectrum -- 42 percent say they are moderately conservative, while 35 percent call themselves moderately aggressive investors.<P>
Forty-nine percent of men and half of investors under 40 describe themselves as aggressive or moderately aggressive, while two-thirds of investors who are women (65 percent) and who are seniors (67 percent) call themselves "moderately conservative" or "conservative." <P>
Investors who use a broker are more likely to describe themselves as aggressive or moderately aggressive, with 58 percent of investors using a discount broker describing themselves as such, compared to 49 percent of those with a full-service broker and 35 percent of those without any broker.<P>
Compared to investors without a broker, those with a broker are older, more likely to be male, better-educated, have a higher household income and greater assets, and are more experienced investors. <P>
Women and investors younger than 40 have the greatest proportion of assets invested in CDs, savings accounts, and money market funds.  Men are more likely than women to hold individual stocks.<P>
A free copy of the survey may be obtained by contacting <A HREF="mailto:rthornblad@sia.com">Dick Thornblad</A>.
<BR><BR><HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
&copy; 1996 Securities Industry Association
<A HREF="sia00.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="siahome.gif" ALT="Homepage"></A>
<A HREF="sia06a.htm"><IMG Border=0 ALIGN=right SRC="ballleft.gif" ALT="Previous"></A></body></HTML>
