<head>
<title>Michael Itamura</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff"">
<center><h1>Michael Itamura, PhD</h1><p>
<img src="../../../BERC/Gallery/Michael.jpg" border = "2"></center>
<hr>
I am a post-Doc in the Department of Mechanical Engineering
at the University of California, Berkeley.   If you want to know what
sort of work that the students in my lab are working on, you can read the
<a href="../../../BERC/Documents/LabAbstract.html">Lab Abstracts</a>.
I have also had numerous <a href="../../../BERC/Personnel/Itamura/pub.html">
publications and presentations</a>.
<hr>
I was born
and raised in the southern California suburb of Montebello.  I have received
a BS, an MS, and a PhD degree in Mechanical Engineering from the University of
California.  
<hr>
Earlier in life, I was the Associate Editor of the "California Engineer"
magazine.  I have worked for three summers at Rockwell International (now owned by Boeing) in 
Downey, California in a computer programming group that supported the 
thermal insulation tile engineering group for the space shuttle program.
I also worked two summers at Douglas Aircraft (soon to be owned by Boeing) in Long Beach, California.
I worked in the advanced military projects group of the propulsion and
environmental control group during both of the summers.   More information about 
me can be found in my
<a href="../../../BERC/Personnel/Itamura/resume.html">resume</a>.
<hr>
Here are some photos of me at work and at play.  A few years ago, I visited the
<a href="../../../BERC/Gallery/Mike.jpg">Nixon Library</a>  
in beautiful Yorba Linda, California.
It was a somewhat interesting place to visit -- although at the time, they
didn't have the "so-called smoking gun" tape on display. 
<hr>
One of the big projects for the lab in the summer of 1994 was the clean-up
of a JP-5 fuel spill at the Naval Air Station in Lemoore, California.  I
was involved in the University portion of the project.  Students from the
Berkeley Environmental Restoration Center were involved in the collection
and analysis of temperature, pressure, and flow measurements that were used
to monitor the progress of the clean-up.  
Having taken one of the lead roles in the coordination of the Center's
activities at the site, I co-authored the 
<a href="../../../BERC/Projects/Lemoore/index.html">Final Lemoore Report</a>.  
<hr>
The current large project for the BERC lab is at the Naval Air Station in
Alameda, California.  My responsibilities have included the initial drafting
of a Health and Safety Plan as well as the characterization of the subsurface
for the proposed site for one of the clean-up efforts.  Since I don't have
any photos of that site, I thought that you might want to see a neat looking
<a href="../../../BERC/Gallery/Alameda2.jpg">pelican</a>  that
I photographed near the wetlands area.   The pelican was getting some sun on
the riprap at the edge of the wetlands area of the Naval Air Station.   You can see an
aircraft carrier in the background.
<hr>
One of the perks of studying the clean-up of hazardous waste spills is the
exciting training sessions that we get to attend.  In the HAZWOPER training,
we were instructed on the dangers of many of the chemicals that we might be
exposed to and what sort of safety precautions we should take to safely deal
with them.  Of course, when it was my turn to wear the proper PPE, I was the
only one who looked like a large
<a href="../../../BERC/Gallery/Mike&Bobby.jpg">banana with two legs</a>.  
That's Bobby in white scooping up the mock hazardous waste.
As you might guess, it is rather uncomfortable trying to work in such
clothes.
<hr>
Of course, all work and no play makes will turn even the most humble
graduate student into a bitter, anti-social recluse.  So, to keep myself
from getting more bitter, more anti-social than I normally was, I entertained
myself by taking photographs and following Cal basketball.  Here is a
<a href="../../../BERC/Gallery/Mike1.jpg">self portrait</a> taken last fall for a 
assignment for a lighting class.
You can also see some of my photographic work if you look in the
<a href="../../../BERC/Gallery/index.html">BERC photo gallery</a>.
Most of the photos that are black and white in the gallery were taken by me. 
I shoot mostly 35mm black and white but I have dabbled in 3-D photographs
and in the large format view cameras.
<hr>
Here is a photograph of comet
<a href="../../../BERC/Gallery/Comet.jpg">Hyakutake</a>
that I took in March 1996.  I used my Nikon 8008 with a 50mm lens at f1.8
for a 1.5 minute exposure using Kodak T-Max 400 Black and White film. 
I was up near Lake Tahoe at the time.  The sky was quite dark and the comet was near the
pole star when this photograph was taken.  
<hr>
230 Hesse Hall<br>
Department of Mechanical Engineering<br>
University of California<br>
Berkeley, CA 94720<br>
<a href=mailto:mike@clubmezz.me.berkeley.edu>mike@clubmezz.me.berkeley.edu</a>
