<html>
<head>
<title>NAS Lemoore</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><h1>NAS Lemoore JP-5 Cleanup Demonstration</h1>
<center><img src="../../../BERC/Gallery/Lemoore2.jpg" border=2><br></center>
By<br>
Professor Kent Udell<br>
Michael Itamura<br>
Professor Lisa Alvarez-Cohen<br>
Mark Hernandez<br>
Berkeley Environmental Restoration Center<br>
University of California, Berkeley<br></center>
<hr>
<h2>The Site</h2><p>
Naval Air Station Lemoore (NASL) is approximately seven miles west 
of the city of Lemoore, California.  Lemoore is located midway between Los 
Angeles and San Francisco, in the central portion of the San Joaquin 
Valley.  During routine maintenance in December 1987, workers discovered a 
leak in a 0.41 meter (16-inch) diameter aluminum pipe carrying JP-5 jet 
fuel.  The leak was repaired and the excavation was refilled.  Initial 
removal of fuel saturated soil adjacent to the leak site resulted in an 
excavation approximately 4.3 meters (14 feet) deep.  JP-5 fuel which 
accumulated in this pit was pumped into a storage tank on the surface for 
disposal.  The excavation depth was subsequently increased to 5.2 meters 
(17 feet) and later to 6.4 meters (21 feet).  The total quantity of fuel 
recovered from the pit was approximately 492,000 liters (130,000 gallons).  
The extent of the spill is shown in 
<a href="Figure1.gif">Figure 1</a>.
<hr>  
<h2>The Process</h2><p>
Application of the steam injection to a spill consists of placing 
steam injection wells within and around the contaminated soil, and 
extraction wells within the contaminated region.  Steam is injected both 
above and below the water table, if necessary.  Groundwater, condensate, 
NAPLs and air are pumped from the extraction wells.  The soil is heated as 
the steam condenses until it reaches steam temperature.  The steam 
thereafter displaces the water from the pore space, creating a steam zone.  
This steam zone grows toward the extraction wells and pushes contaminants 
ahead of it.  In the steam zone, the residual contaminants are volatilized 
by evaporation and are swept toward the extraction wells due to imposed 
pressure gradients.  After steam breaks through at the extraction wells 
and the target soil is sufficiently heated to the steam temperature, 
injection continues cyclically to enhance evaporation rates and recover 
residual NAPL compounds.  Since depressurization of a steam zone leads to 
the vaporization of liquids in all pore spaces containing a gas-phase 
conduit, the cessation of high-pressure steam injection results in 
dramatic increases in the contaminant vaporization rates.  The extracted 
vapors are condensed and cooled to ambient conditions.  Standard 
technologies are used to separate the product from water and to treat 
contaminated air and water.  The surprisingly broad effectiveness of the 
process for <i>in situ</i> remediation is due to several mechanisms: steam 
displacement of mobile fluids from the pore space, boiling of volatile 
non-aqueous phase liquids, temperature enhanced evaporation rates of semi-
volatile and low volatility non-aqueous phase liquids in direct contact 
with the flowing steam, desorption of contaminants from solid surfaces, 
and vapor venting from otherwise inaccessible soils due to the 
depressurization of a steam zone.<p>
The SEE process is a thermal enhancement to pump-and-treat and soil 
vapor extraction, which occur simultaneously with the injection of steam.  
The major benefits of this enhancement are the drastically reduced volumes 
of contaminated fluid to be handled on the surface, order-of-magnitude 
decreases in the time for remediation, applicability to source 
contamination both above and below the water table, and potential for 
recycling recovered product.  Additional steam generation and cooling 
equipment beyond that required for isothermal pump-and-treat techniques 
are required however.  The disruption of the ongoing surface operational 
activities can often be limited to system installation.  System operation 
requires space for equipment, but might not interfere with other 
activities if piping is located in covered trenches.  The process is 
feasible to depths of hundreds of meters and may be applied underneath 
structures in some cases.
<hr>
<h2>System Design Considerations</h2><p>
Proper design of SEE requires the appropriate coupling of the above 
ground process plant and the subsurface hydrocarbon recovery processes.  
The basic functions of the plant are to provide the steam required by SEE 
and process the liquid and vapor phase effluent trains  from the 
extraction wells.  Integral to the plant is a data acquisition system 
sufficient to monitor the performance of SEE, measure the subsurface 
temperatures, and document adherence to contaminant concentration limits 
for the proper disposal of the waste water and extracted air.<p>
The sizing of the steam generation equipment is determined by 
estimates of the amount of steam that can be injected into the system 
given the permeability of the soil strata and the design injection 
pressure.  The injection pressure should be as high as possible, limited 
by the soil fracture pressure which is estimated to be 11.3 kPa/meter (0.5 
psi/foot) multiplied by the distance from the ground surface to the top of 
the steam injection interval.  Factors that determine the sizing of the 
effluent treatment facility are the rates of liquid and vapor effluent 
that can be extracted based on the prescribed extraction vacuum pressure, 
water table draw-down, and soil permeability.  To maintain good vertical 
sweep of the soils, the distance between the injection wells and the 
extraction wells should be about the same as the depth to the top of the 
steam injection interval.  The treatment facility must meet the criteria 
that are set by the permit conditions imposed by the local air pollution 
control district on the gas effluent discharge from the system and the 
conditions imposed on the liquid effluent discharge to the on-site waste 
water treatment facility.
<hr>
<h2>System Design</h2><p>
The SEE process flow diagram can be divided into three parts.  The 
first part is the steam generator unit that converts water to steam at the 
desired pressure and rate.  The second part is a vapor extraction and 
processing system in which the steam and jet fuel vapor are extracted, 
cooled, measured, and treated.  This system includes the treatment of the 
hydrocarbon-laden air removed from the subsurface.  The third part is the 
process liquid treatment system.  This system separates, measures, and 
provides for convenient site disposal of the water and liquid JP-5 pumped 
from the extraction wells or condensed during vapor cooling.<p>
The steam generator unit is comprised of a water treatment system, a 
water pump, and a boiler.  Since dry steam is required, a water treatment 
device is included to soften the supplied water to prevent the boiler from 
being fouled.  A water meter was installed in this line to provide a 
measure of the cumulative steam produced and injected.  Occasional blow-
down of the boiler and disposal of the boiler waste water was necessary.  
A water pump upstream of the boiler was used to provide sufficient steam 
pressure.  After the water pump, the pressurized water would either 
directly enter the boiler or run through a heat exchanger first where the 
water is pre-heated prior to entering the boiler.  The dry steam from the 
boiler flowed to the two injection wells.<p>
The vapor processing line included an air-cooled exchanger, a 
separator/pump unit, a separation/metering unit, and an activated carbon 
filter.  Once the hot vapor mixture is brought to the surface and enters 
the vapor line, it is cooled in heat exchanger, where the steam and much 
of the jet fuel vapor condense to form two separate liquid phases.  When 
the vapor stream leaves the heat exchanger, the temperature of the stream 
is near ambient temperature.  Typically, since liquid phase water and fuel 
appear in the fluid stream and mix with the remaining gas phase 
(essentially air), the concentrations of water and fuel vapors would be 
near saturation values.  The stream then flowed to a steel separator/pump 
unit where the vapor phase was separated from the liquid phases.  The 
vapor phase was extracted from the top of the separator to a vacuum pump.  
The liquid phases of water and jet-fuel flowed from the bottom of the 
vessel into a sump from which they are pumped.  To avoid the complete 
emptying of the sump, level switches were installed to control the liquid 
levels. <p>
The vapors expelled from the vacuum pump entered a set of carbon 
canisters where the concentration of jet fuel in the vapor was reduced to 
an allowable level before discharge to the atmosphere. <p>
The liquid water and JP-5 condensate from the heat exchanger is 
pumped into the a separation/metering unit, which operated at atmospheric 
pressure.  In this unit, the free product of jet fuel was separated from 
the water phase.  After separation, both phases were metered and pumped to 
two separate buffer tanks.  The separate phase jet fuel was pumped from 
the fuel buffer tank to a trailer mounted tank and trucked from the site 
by a fuel recycler.  The water phase was likewise pumped to a buffer tank 
upstream of the water treatment unit.<p>
The liquid treatment system received water and free product jet fuel 
delivered by submersible pumps from the eight extraction wells.  The 
water/fuel stream passed through the air-cooled heat exchanger where its 
temperature was lowered to ambient temperature.  The stream then entered 
the separation/metering unit.<p>
Both separation/metering units are operated at atmospheric pressure.  
Vented vapors from the two liquid separators flowed at atmospheric 
pressure through a set of carbon canisters before being released to the 
environment.<p>
The water treatment system consisted of a carbon filter to reduce 
the amount of the fuel in the water before disposal to the pipeline 
leading to the evaporation ponds of the site waste water treatment system.  
There were two units connected in series and water samples from the inlet 
of the first carbon unit, the outlet of the first carbon unit, and the 
outlet of the second carbon unit were tested periodically to determine the 
amount of JP-5 entering the filters as well as determine if the carbon 
units were spent.
<hr>
<h2>SEE Demonstration</h2><p>
<img src="../../../BERC/Gallery/Lemoore1.jpg" align=left>Three extraction wells to be used in the SEE demonstration were 
installed and tested in February, 1993 by Udell Technologies.  Ten 
centimeters (4 inches) of free product JP-5 was observed in EW-2 and 1 cm 
(3/8 inch) of JP-5 was measured in EW-4.  While no free product was 
observed in EW-7, high soil concentrations just above the water table 
indicated past presence of mobile JP-5.  The permeabilities of the shallow 
sandy silt and deeper silty sand were estimated to be 4 Darcy and 14 
Darcy, respectively.  Soil samples were analyzed for TPH and 
concentrations of JP-5 greater than 10,000 ppm were observed both on the 
water table and a location about 1.2 meters (4 feet) below the water table 
at the North-East corner in well EW-2.<p>
Six additional extraction wells, two steam injection wells, and 16 
temperature observation wells were installed in 1994.  Additional site 
definition was obtained from geologist logs and free-product depth 
measurements in the extraction wells.  After installation, seven out of 
the eight extraction wells contained over 0.3 meters (1 foot) of free-
product JP-5 at that time.<p>
<img src="Figure2.gif" align=right border=2>
The location of the two injection wells (IW-1 and IW-2), the eight 
extraction wells (EW-1 to EW-8), the fourteen temperature monitoring wells 
(Temp-A to Temp-N), and the four post-steaming soil borings (SB-2 to SB-5) 
are shown in 
<a href="Figure2.gif">Figure 2</a>.
The details of the well construction and a 
simplified picture of the subsurface geology at the demonstration location 
are presented in
<a href=Figure3.gif>Figure 3</a>
.  As inferred from this figure, the hydrology of 
the site is dominated by the presence of the deep clay aquitard along the 
southern boundary of the demonstration location.  Since the liquid pumping 
rates are determined by the extent of the water table draw-down, those 
southern wells will be limited in pumping capacity.  The geology of the 
vadose zone is relatively consistent at the demonstration location, 
however, a clay layer overlies the site, with a variable thickness sandy 
silt layer beneath.  Near the location of the water-table, the soil turns 
to a silty sand.  The presence of the clay cap and the trend towards 
increasing permeability with depth makes this site particularly attractive 
for the demonstration of SEE.
<hr>
<h2>SEE System performance</h2><p>
The steam injection system was run intermittently from 5 July 1994 
to 23 September 1994.  Steam was injected continuously for the first 35 
days.  From 9 August until 23 September, the steam boiler was run for 12 
hours a day; usually between 7:00 AM to 7:00 PM.  The injection pressure 
was originally at 163 kPa (9 psig) but was throttled down to 146 kPa (6.5 
psig) on day 13 (18 July 1994) because steam started to break through to 
the ground surface near IW-2.<p>
The total quantity of water injected as steam during the project was 
482,000 kg or 482,000 liters (1,060,000 pounds or 128,000 gallons).  A 
total of 200,000 kg or 200,000 liters (439,000 pounds or 52,900 gallons of 
water) of steam were injected in to IW-1 and 282,000 kg or 282,000 liters 
(624,000 pounds or 75,100 gallons of water) of steam were injected into 
IW-2.  Initially, more steam flowed into well IW-1.  But after week 2, 
when 58% of the steam flowed into IW-2, more steam entered IW-2 than IW-1.  
During the last three weeks of steam injection, IW-2 was taking 77% of the 
steam from the boiler.  The amount of steam injected per week from week-6 
(35 days) onward was approximately 50% lower than the first five weeks due 
to steam cycling.
<hr>
<h2>Steam Zone Growth</h2><p>
The subsurface growth of the steam zone in response to the injection 
of steam was tracked from subsurface temperature measurements.
<a href="Figure4a.gif">Figure 4a</a>,
<a href="Figure4b.gif">Figure 4b</a>,
<a href="Figure4c.gif">Figure 4c</a>,
<a href="Figure4d.gif">Figure 4d</a>, and
<a href="Figure4e.gif">Figure 4e</a>
shows the temperature profile for the subsurface 7, 14, 35, 56, and 79 days
from the start of steam injection. 
The temperature isotherms were drawn based on the values 
and the time history of the temperature at the temperature observation and 
extraction wells.  There were no thermocouples located in EW-2, EW-4 or 
EW-7 but insight into the temperatures could be inferred from the liquid 
and vapor effluent temperatures. <p>
The temperature readings for the five extraction wells were measured 
with fixed thermocouples.  The liquid temperature out of well EW-1 
remained between 45
<img src="degreeC.gif">
and 55
<img src="degreeC.gif">
(113
<img src="degreeF.gif">
and 131
<img src="degreeF.gif">
) during most of the 
project.  The liquid flow from this well was the highest of any of the 
southern four extraction wells at 280,000 liters (75,000 gallons) total 
but this was still much less than any of the flow rates of the northern 
wells.<p>
The temperature of the liquid effluent from EW-2 was between 40
<img src="degreeC.gif">
and 45
<img src="degreeC.gif">
(104
<img src="degreeF.gif">
and 113
<img src="degreeF.gif">
) for most of the project.  The flow rate from 
this well was the second highest at 2,770,000 liters (733,000 gallons).<p>
Extraction well EW-3 effluent temperature of the liquid started to 
rise on day 5 (10 July 1994) and was between 50
<img src="degreeC.gif">
and 65
<img src="degreeC.gif">
(122
<img src="degreeF.gif">
and 140
<img src="degreeF.gif">
) during most of the project indicating that most if not all of the 
fluid that was being produced came from the top of the water table near 
6.1 meters (20 feet) bgs.<p>
There were no fixed thermocouples in well EW-4.  The liquid effluent 
temperatures from EW-4 started to rise on day 5 and were between 50
<img src="degreeC.gif">
and 60 
<img src="degreeC.gif">
(122
<img src="degreeF.gif">
and 140
<img src="degreeF.gif">
) during most of the project.  The total liquid flow 
from well EW-4 was the third highest at 2,180,000 liters (577,000 
gallons). <p>
The temperature of the liquid effluent from EW-5 started to rise on 
day 13 and steadily rose to nearly 55
<img src="degreeC.gif">
(131
<img src="degreeF.gif">
) on day 80 (24 September 
1994).  The 9.1 meter (30 foot) fixed thermocouple did not see any change 
in temperature but the 7.6 meters (25 foot) bgs increased to 40
<img src="degreeC.gif">
(104 
<img src="degreeF.gif">
) after a month of steam injection and then to nearly 60
<img src="degreeC.gif">
(140
<img src="degreeF.gif">
) on 
day 80.  The total effluent was only 235,000 liters (62,000 gallons), the 
third lowest total. <p>
The liquid effluent temperature out of EW-6 did not show any 
increase in temperature during the project.  The fixed thermocouples did 
show elevated temperatures at 3.0 and 4.6 meters (10 and 15 feet) below 
ground surface but there was no change from the original temperature at 
1.5, 6.1, and 7.6 meters (5, 20, and 25 feet) bgs.<p>
The temperature of the liquid effluent from EW-7 did not change from 
ambient temperature during the entire project.<p>
The liquid effluent temperature from EW-8 was increased from 22
<img src="degreeC.gif">
(72
<img src="degreeF.gif">
) at the start of steam injection until it reached 36
<img src="degreeC.gif">
(97
<img src="degreeF.gif">
) at 
the end of the project.  The temperature of the 9.1 meter (30 foot) fixed 
thermocouple never changed but the thermocouples at 6.1 and 7.6 meters (20 
and 25 feet) bgs began to rise on day 23 (28 July 1994) to 60
<img src="degreeC.gif">
and 30 
<img src="degreeC.gif">
(140
<img src="degreeF.gif">
and 86
<img src="degreeF.gif">
) respectively.  The liquid recovery was 870,000 liters 
(229,000 gallons), the fourth lowest of the eight extraction wells.
<hr>
<h2>Vapor Train Flowrates</h2><p>
The distribution of vapor flow rates is different from that observed 
for the liquid recovery  rates.  The best two producers were well EW-6 at 
277 million liters (9.8 million scf) and EW-1 at 178 million liters (6.3 
million scf).  The two worst producers were well EW-3 at 50.4 million 
liters (1.78 million scf) and EW-8 at 53 million liters (1.88 million 
scf).  Ignoring the value of EW-6 due to the suspicion of a vapor by-pass 
conduit, the vapor recovery rates varied by less than a factor of 4 among 
wells, significantly less than the variation in the liquid rates.<p>
The volume fraction of fuel in the condensed phase stayed lower than 
20% except for a few isolated spikes.  There seems to be some correlation 
of higher fractions of JP-5 upon system restart after the boiler was off 
for a day or more.  Due to the lack of data other than the daily logs, the 
degree of enhancement of mass transfer during cyclic injection cannot be 
ascertained.<p>
The hydrocarbons that were not condensed and removed from the vapor 
train were removed in the carbon filters.  The quantity of contaminant 
that went into the carbon canisters was estimated to be 300 kg (663 
pounds) over the entire project.  Two carbon filters, each containing 900 
kg (2000 pounds) of activated carbon, were connected in series to filter 
out almost all of the remaining vapor phase hydrocarbons.  Assuming a 
vapor inlet to outlet hydrocarbon removal efficiency of 95% for each 
filter, less than 1 kg (2 pounds) of vapor phase hydrocarbon was vented to 
the atmosphere over the entire project.  A total quantity of 22,400 kg 
(49,400 pounds) of activated carbon was used during the project.  The 
carbon canisters were recharged or the order of the carbon canisters were 
switched a total of 14 times during the project.  The hydrocarbon 
concentrations of the air going into the first carbon canister, the air 
going out of the first carbon canister/going in to the second carbon 
canister, and the air coming out of the second carbon canister were 
monitored using a portable PID meter.
<hr>
<h2>Total Fuel Recovered</h2><p>
The total quantities of fuel removed from the ground during the 89 
days of steam extraction were as follows: 285,000 liters (75,300 gallons) 
from the liquid train, 11,500 liters (3029 gallons) condensed from the 
vapor train, 300 kg (663 pounds) from the vapor phase canisters (380 
liters or 100 gallons assuming a specific gravity of 0.81 for JP-5), and 
160 kg (350 pounds) from the liquid phase canisters (190 liters or 50 
gallons assuming an average concentration of 350 ppm).  The total volume 
of JP-5 removed was just over 297,000 liters (78,479 gallons) of which all 
but 570 liters (150) gallons was recovered as liquid.  The cumulative fuel 
recovered and the total fuel recovery rate are plotted versus time in 
<a href="Figure5.gif">Figure 5</a> and 
<a href="Figure6.gif">Figure 6</a>.<p>
The horizontal line at 57,000 liters (15,000 gallons) in 
<a href="Figure5.gif">Figure 5</a> is 
an approximation of the quantity of JP-5 originally boounded by the eight 
extraction wells.  Since more than five times this amount was recovered 
during the SEE project, much of the JP-5 recovery was due to fuel being 
pulled in from the outside of the pattern.
<hr>
<h2>Soil Analysis</h2><p>
Nine soil borings were taken and analyzed by BSK & Associates 
(Fresno, CA) personnel.  The location of the soil borings with respect to 
all of the wells is shown in 
<a href="Figure2.gif">Figure 2</a>.  On 15 August 1994 a boring was 
taken at the location marked SB-2.  A second round of soil borings were 
taken on 30-31 August 1994 with borings taken at SB-2 and SB-3 on the 
first day and at SB-4 and SB-5 on the second day.  Second and subsequent 
borings taken at the same location involved borings close enough to 
previous sampled locations to expect similar subsurface thermal conditions 
and soil concentration distributions as adjacent boring; in this project, 
boring were made within a meter of each other.  The final round of soil 
samples were taken on 26-27 September 1994 with borings taken at SB-2 and 
SB-3 on the first day and at SB-4 and SB-5 on the second day.  Samples 
were taken using a 20.3 cm (8-inch) diameter hollow stem auger with 0.15 
meter (six inch) samples taken continuously.  Half of the samples were 
analyzed at the BSK analytical labs for total petroleum hydrocarbons (TPH) 
remaining and the other half were taken by U.C. Berkeley personnel to 
investigate the level of biological activity present in the heated soil.<p>
The TPH concentrations in the soil samples from SB-2 are presented 
in 
<a href="Figure7.gif">Figure 7</a>. 
Soil TPH concentration data from samples taken in February 
1993 during the installation of nearby EW-2 are also shown in the figure 
to compare with the progress of the clean-up.  The original data revealed 
high levels of contamination at 4.0 to 4.3 meter (13 to 14 feet) and 
another highly contaminated zone at 5.2 meters (17 feet).  The soil was 
found to be clean above seven feet and below 6.1 meter (20 feet) bgs.  The 
first set of soil borings was taken on day 41 (15 August 1994) of the SEE 
demonstration.  At that time, the JP-5 concentrations had increased to 
10,000 ppm levels near the clay-sandy silt interface at 1.5 meters (5 
feet) bgs.  This initial increase in concentration was probably due to JP-
5 being evaporated into the steam vapor as it flowed through highly 
contaminated zones and then condensing with the steam as it contacts the 
cooler upper regions of the site. It is also possible that initial JP-5 
concentrations in the upper regions at the location of SB-2 were higher 
than at EW-2.  The contamination levels at the 4.0 to 4.3 meter (13 to 14 
foot) bgs level dropped from the original 100,000 ppm levels to around 100 
ppm by the first round of soil samples, however.  The high level of 
contamination at the 6.1 meter (20 foot) bgs location was still present.  
Fifteen days later when the second round of samples were taken, the 
contamination levels dropped significantly in the upper five feet from 
10,000 ppm to 1000 ppm.  The concentration levels from 1.5 to 4.9 meter (5 
to 16 feet) bgs were mostly in the 15 to 100 ppm range.  The high 
concentration levels near 100,000 ppm were still present at 6.1 meter (20 
feet) bgs.  When the last round of soil borings were taken on 26 September 
1994, the concentration of TPH had dropped to between 20 and 50 ppm 
throughout the entire 7.6 meters (25 feet) tested except for the 20,000 
ppm readings at 6.1 meter (20 feet) bgs.<p>
The location of well SB-2 was in between wells EW-2 and IW-1 just a 
few feet from well EW-2.  While there were no fixed thermocouples placed 
in well EW-2, the thermal conditions at SB-2 can be inferred from the 
effluent liquid and vapor temperatures from EW-2  The liquid effluent 
temperature remained within a few degrees of 40
<img src="degreeC.gif">
(104
<img src="degreeF.gif">
) for most of 
the project.  The total liquid recovery rate as determined by the well 
pump controllers was the second highest of all of the wells and the total 
vapor recovery was the fourth highest of the eight extraction wells.  The 
relatively low temperature of the liquids pumped from EW-2 implies that 
over 75% of the liquid originated from outside of the pattern.  However, 
due to the high pumping rate, EW-2 produced a large fraction of the hot 
water flowing from the pattern, indicating good hydraulic communication 
between EW-2 and the steamed pattern.  The temperature of vapors extracted 
from EW-2 was 80
<img src="degreeC.gif">
(176
<img src="degreeF.gif">
) during the first month of steam injection.  
Being in line from the injection well and the extraction well, the region 
above the water table and below the sandy silt layer near SB-2 was 
probably subjected to an almost continuous supply of steam from the 
injection well during the first half of the demonstration.  During the 
second half, the vapors cooled to 50
<img src="degreeC.gif">
(122
<img src="degreeF.gif">
), suggesting that ambient 
air was flowing from the surface through the soil to the extraction well. 
This airflow would increase vaporization and biodegradation rates, and 
thus serve to reduce the hydrocarbon concentrations in the upper zones as 
observed.<p>
The high concentrations of JP-5 located at 6.1 meter (20 feet) at 
all sampling times  indicates that this depth was at or below the level of 
the water table, and thus was not contacted by flowing steam.  No data are 
available on the depth to water in the extraction wells during the 
demonstration.  It is possible that pump adjustments, both depth in the 
well-bore and rates, may have increased the pumping rate to design 
specifications, thus providing the dewatering needed to bring the steam 
zone down to this lower zone of contamination.
<hr>
<h2>Biological Activity</h2><p>
Soil samples taken during the 26-27 September 1994 were analyzed by 
UC Berkeley personnel to determine what level of biological activity was 
present in the soils after being subjected to the high temperatures 
associated with the steam as well as the elevated levels of hydrocarbons.  
The soil samples were aseptically transferred to sterilized Erlenmeyer 
flasks within 48 hours of acquisition.  The sample temperature was kept at 
35
<img src="degreeC.gif">
.  Soils were transferred from the brass casings and diluted with a 
sterilized phosphate buffer and aliquots of approximately 350 mL were 
divided among sterile flasks.  The samples were then subjected to (i) 
direct total and active bacterial counts, (ii) oxygen uptake and carbon 
dioxide evolution microcosm measurements, and (iii) solids analysis.  With 
the exception to total solids determinations, all analysis were done in 
triplicate.<p>
<center><table>
<tr><td><img src="Figure8.gif"><td><img src="Figure9.gif"></tr>
<tr align=center><td>Figure 8<td>Figure 9</tr>
</table></center>
Total and active bacteria were counted and using a combined membrane 
filtration - epiflourescent technique.  This analysis found that the total 
number of bacteria was 2.3x
<img src="ten9.gif" align=bottom>
/gm for the 2 foot sample with the active 
bacteria for that sample at 0.5x
<img src="ten9.gif" align=bottom>
/gm.  Total bacteria was greater than 
0.5x
<img src="ten9.gif">
/gm for soil samples taken at 2, 4, 6, 16, and 18 feet.  Active 
bacteria were only seen in samples taken at 2, 4, 6, 10 and 18 feet.  
<a href="Figure8.gif">Figure 8</a> and 
<a href="Figure9.gif">Figure 9</a>
show a microscopic image of a bacteria found in a 
soil sample at NAS Lemoore.  
<a href="Figure8.gif">Figure 8</a> shows a field of FITC stained 
bacteria viewed under UV illumination and 
<a href="Figure9.gif">Figure 9</a> shows the same 
microscopic field exposed to transmitted visible light.<p>
Microbial respiration was confirmed by measuring 
<img src="o2.gif" align=top> and <img src="co2.gif" align=top> 
composition in the headspace of sealed microcosms.  Approximately 30 mL of 
soil diluted 10:1 in sterile phosphate buffered saline was added to 
sterilized bottles.  The bottles were sealed with a teflon cap containing 
a repeating pierce valve.  The headspace gas was analyzed weekly for a 
month to determine the mass fractions of 
<img src="o2.gif" align=top> and 
<img src="co2.gif" align=top>.  The greatest increase 
in the <img src="co2.gif" align=top>
percentage occurred in soil samples from 2, 4, and 18 feet.  
Small changes on 
<img src="co2.gif" align=top> 
were seen in soil samples taken at all of the other 
depths.
<hr>
<h2>Energy Balance</h2><p>
The enthalpy flux as measured daily of the liquid phase removed from 
each of the eight extraction wells was calsulated using temperature and 
flow measurements of all modes of energy transport.  The only wells that 
ever had liquid phase enthalpy extraction rates higher than 8 kW for an 
extended period of time were wells EW-2, EW-3, EW-7, and EW-8.  These four 
wells correspond to the four northern wells in the SEE system -- 
indicating that, as expected, the heated water was flowing faster from the 
northern wells than from the southern wells.  Well EW-7, which produced 
the largest volume of fluids, produced only about half as much energy in 
the liquid phase than did wells EW-2 or EW-3.  Well EW-2 liquid phase 
enthalpy extraction rate was between 8 and 25 kW over most of the project.  
The liquid phase enthalpy extraction rate for EW-3 was less than 7 kW 
during the first 46 days of the project and then the liquid phase enthalpy 
extraction rate increased to almost 40 kW for a period of three weeks 
before dropping to around 15 kW for the final three weeks of the project.  
The liquid phase enthalpy extraction rate for the southern four wells (EW-
1, EW-4, EW-5, and EW-6) were almost always less than 5 kW during the 
duration of the SEE project.  The total enthalpy recovered from the four 
southern wells was actually smaller than that recovered from well EW-7, 
the second worst producer of the northern four extraction wells. <p>
Wells EW-2 and EW-3 produced the most energy with EW-2 producing 
between 30 and 40 kW during the first half of the project and between 10 
and 20 kW during the second half of the project.  Well EW-3 produced 
between 10 and 20 kW during the first 45 days of the project before 
increasing to ~40 kW for three weeks and then dropping to around 20 kW for 
the remaining time of the project.  The two worst total enthalpy produces 
were wells EW-6 and EW-8. <p>
The steam flow provided around 300 kW of thermal energy into the 
system during the five weeks of constant steam injection.  The energy flow 
rate dropped off to between 100 and 200 kW during the latter stages of the 
SEE project when steam was only injected for 12 hours a day.  The enthalpy 
flux from the vapor and liquid effluent trains varied from 0 kW at the 
start of steam injection to around 50 kW after the first week from the 
start of steam injection.<p>
The injected enthalpy from the steam train was 179 MW-hrs for the 
first 35 days of steam injection and 94 MW-hrs over the duration of the 
project.  The vapor stream effluent contained 26 MW-hrs of enthalpy during 
the first 35 days of the project and another 49 MW-hrs over the final 54 
days of the project.  The liquid stream effluent contained 20 MW-hrs of 
enthalpy during the first 35 days of the project and another 44 MW-hrs 
over the final 54 days of the project.  The net enthalpy flux for all 
three flow streams was 134 MW-hrs over the first 35 days of the project 
and only 1 more MW-hrs over the remaining 54 days of the project.  Since 
most of the energy was injected over the first 35 days of the project, it 
is not surprising that the temperature profiles did not change 
significantly after the steam cycling began.
<hr>
<h2>Discussion</h2><p>
The implementation of SEE at Lemoore at the pilot scale demonstrated 
the applicability of the process to relatively low volatility hydrocarbon 
fuels such as JP-5.  Regions containing high initial JP-5 soil 
concentrations and sustaining steam flow were found to be effectively 
cleaned by the process over time.  However, substantial upward spreading 
of the JP-5 into previously clean soils was also observed as the steam 
invaded those regions.  This spreading was presumed to be due to free-
product buildup above the water mound produced by initial steam 
displacement and the upward flow of condensing vapors into the cool 
permeable zones above.  Thus, the upward spreading would have been 
partially avoided if the vapor extraction system had met design 
specifications, particularly where the geology constrained fluid 
extraction flow rates.  There was evidence showing that the soils that 
were contaminated by condensing vapor upward flow were also remediated by 
downward air flow from the surface during the depressurization mode of 
cyclic injection.  The removal of those hydrocarbons by air flow would be 
due to increased vaporization rates in the high temperature, moist soils, 
and enhanced biodegradation in heated soils under oxygen-rich conditions.<p>
Reductions in JP-5 concentrations in regions below the initial water 
table were not achieved during this demonstration.  While the detailed 
interactions between the liquid JP-5 flowing into the test pattern from 
outside, the depth and liquid extraction rates of the extraction well 
pumps, the applied vacuum, and the steam injection rate are not clear, one 
may expect that there would be significant infiltration of the test site 
by liquid JP-5 during periods when there was no steam injection.  Thus, 
the effectiveness of the process for soils at the groundwater-steam zone 
interface would be inherently limited under the condition of a pilot scale 
demonstration within a larger, highly contaminated site.  However, greater 
attention to groundwater elevations in the extraction wells and the 
flexibility to raise and lower the extraction well pumps during operation 
would have allowed better control of the hydrodynamics specific to that 
location.  The large decreases in JP-5 concentrations in regions 
sustaining substantial steam flow imply that the process would have 
removed the JP-5 below the initial water table if the site were 
sufficiently dewatered and if no flow of JP-5 occurred from regions 
outside of the pattern, as would be the case for full-scale cleanup.  The 
evidence of thermally enhanced biological activity in the JP-5 
contaminated soil at the water table - steam zone interface suggests that 
the use of the injection and selected extraction wells for air injection 
would be an obvious bio-stimulation polishing step.<p>
The limitation of steam injection into only two wells was also 
substantial in terms of system operational flexibility and effectiveness.  
If steam could have been injected into the extraction wells at various 
times during the project, better isolation of the pilot pattern from the 
exterior field would have occurred, better coverage of the contaminated 
zones by flowing steam would have resulted, and higher rates of energy 
input to the site would have been achieved.  In addition, the ability to 
extract liquid and vapor from the two injection wells when the boiler was 
down could have caused greater pressure swings in the reservoir leading to 
a larger quantity of immobile JP-5 being vaporized in the subsurface and 
its subsequent extraction.  The ability to turn any of the 
extraction/injection wells in to an injection or an extraction well could 
also have opened up the possibility of alternating the steam injection 
direction.  Steam injection into the extraction wells could have been 
easily implemented by placing a tee on the well head vapor extraction line 
with valves to either the steam injection line or the vapor extraction 
line as was done on the steam injection wells.  Maximum total steam 
injection rates, pressurization and depressurization magnitudes, and 
overall system dynamic range could have been increased, producing greater 
process effectiveness, particularly if the well vacuums were greater.<p>
Smaller well spacing on the east side of the site appeared to be 
superior to the longer distances between the wells on the west side of the 
site.  This might be partially attributable to the smaller vacuum 
pressures than were expected.  The smaller pressure difference between the 
injection wells and the extraction wells negatively affected the control 
of the direction of steam zone expansion.  Additional fuel may have also 
have been removed if the steam cycle time were longer.  The east side of 
the site cooled off substantially during the steam cycling meaning that 
the amount of contaminant removed from that side of the site was not as 
high as it could have been.  Steam on for a day and a half with a 12 hour 
period down time or a three day steam on and a day of steam off might have 
allowed more steam to be injected into the ground between times of vacuum 
extraction.<p>
Overall, this demonstration clearly showed that SEE is applicable to 
the full scale clean-up of the Lemoore site.  Two primary modifications of 
the design would be beneficial however.  First, the wells should be re-
designed to allow either steam injection or fluid extraction.  An 
appropriate design would be a high pressure steam injection section at 
depth (below the water table), and an upper completed interval that allows 
liquid extraction and vapor extraction, or steam injection.  The upper 
well bore should be equipped with a liquid pump that could be raised or 
lowered, and a groundwater elevation monitoring device.  Such a design 
would have allowed optimization of free product JP-5 pumping, greater 
energy input rates, and higher JP-5 extraction rates.  Second, either a 
heat exchanger should be placed after the vacuum pump to decrease carbon 
canister inlet temperatures, or the vacuum pump should have been installed 
upstream of the vapor line heat exchanger, in order to operate at the 
design well head vacuum.  The installation of the vacuum pump upstream of 
the vapor condenser would have resulted in greater liquid JP-5 removal 
from the condenser since it would have operated at a higher pressure.  
(For a fixed exit temperature from the condenser, the equilibrium vapor 
pressure of the JP-5 would be nearly constant.  For a higher exiting total 
gas phase pressure, the JP-5 equilibrium concentration in the gas would 
thus be lower.)  The disadvantage of the vacuum pump upstream of the vapor 
condenser would be greater pump power usage since the vapor mass flow rate 
is substantially greater upstream of the condenser.  If non-condensable 
gas mass fractions are small in the vapors extracted from the wells, then 
it may be much better to place the vacuum pump downstream of the condenser 
for optimal energy efficiency.  Another satisfactory design would be the 
use of thermal oxidation to destroy the hydrocarbon vapors in the air 
leaving the vacuum pump if placed downstream of the condenser.
<hr>
<h2>Conclusions</h2><p>
The pilot-scale demonstration of SEE at NAS Lemoore clearly showed 
the applicability of the process to full scale clean-up of the site. 
<ul>
<li>Over 297,000 liters (78,300 gallons) of liquid JP-5 was removed from 
the site and sold to a recycler.  An additional 570 liters (150 
gallons) of JP-5 equivalent mass was removed in the waste water and air 
carbon treatment canisters.
<li> A relatively high degree of control of the subsurface thermal field was 
maintained given the variations in hydro-geology and the relatively low 
steam injection rates.
<li> Hydrocarbon concentrations remained unchanged beneath the steam zone in 
saturated soils.  Concentrations increased in soils above the steam 
zone, but readily decreased with time, presumably due to vaporization 
and biodegradation.  In regions near the initial water table, soil 
concentrations dropped from initial values of over 20,000 ppm to values 
typically lower than 100 ppm.
<li> Overall effectiveness of the process would have been improved if the 
vapor extraction system had operated at design specifications.  
Approximately 11,800 liters (3130 gallons) of JP-5 was removed in the 
vapor phase during the 90 days of steam operation.  Operation at design 
specifications may have resulted in an increase in vapor mass removal 
by a factor of over 3.
</ul>
Based on these conclusions, full-scale clean-up of this site using 
SEE is recommended.  The data obtained from the pilot demonstration show 
that the technology can meet any reasonable clean-up standards.  
Modifications in well bore design, well spacing, and the vapor extraction 
system should be made as detailed in the discussion section.  It is also 
recommended that additional biological evaluations be conducted at this 
site.  Preliminary studies show that thermally enhanced biodegradation 
processes were occurring at the end of the demonstration and the progress 
of those processes is of great long-term interest.
<hr>
