<head>
<title>Numerical Simulation</title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#FF0000" vlink="#0000FF" alink="#00FF00">

<h1 align=center>Numerical Simulation for Steam Enhanced Extraction 
<hr size=3 width="100%" ></h1>

<p>Numerical Simulations were performed to predict the propagation of the
steam zone during the implementation of SEE at <a href="../../../BERC/Projects/Alameda/site13.html">Site
13, NAS Alameda</a>. Dewatering of the aquifer and removal of hydrocarbons
from the waste bearing zone were also predicted with the model.</p>

<p>For this purpose, the numerical simulator Multiphase Multicomponent
Non Isothermal Organics Transport Simulator (M<sup>2</sup>NOTS), developed
at the <a href="http://www.berkeley.edu/">University of California at Berkeley</a>
by Adenakan and Patzek was employed. This is a fully implicit, non-linear,
three-phase, multi-dimensional simulator which is capable of handling any
number of hydrocarbon components which are fully-partitioned into all the
phases present. It is primarily used to model the multiphase transport
of multicomponent organic contaminants in the subsurface.</p>

<center><p><img src="figure1.gif" border=0 height=399 width=407 align=bottom></p></center>

<p>The discretization of the domain of interest is shown in Figure 1. The
grid shows 15 elements in the vertical direction over a distance of 25
ft and 12 elements in the radial direction over a distance of 35 ft. The
permeability in the horizontal direction is 2 Darcy and in the vertical
direction is 0.2 Darcy. The solution is only carried out for one sixth
of the cylinder extending from the location of the injection well as the
subsurface around it is assumed to be radially symmetric. Hence, only one
sixth of the total design flow rate is entering this sector. In Figure
1, the injection well is shown on the left side of the grid and extraction
well on the right. </p>

<p>The injection well interval is 3 ft located at 19.5 ft below the gound
surface. Production takes place over the extent of 17 ft located at 8 ft
below the gound surface. The steam injection rate is 240 lb/hr (only 1/6
of this, i.e., 40 lb/hr, is injected into the simulation domain) over the
period of the simulation which is 80 days. At the extraction end, the vacuum
pressure of -7.8 psig is applied. The injected steam is kept at 100&deg;C
and the initial soil temperature is assumed 20&deg;C. The water table is
assumed at 0 ft (the top of the grid). The oil saturation composed of equal
amount of n-Decane, Dodecane, Tetradecane and Hexadecane is modeled roughly
as a 5 ft strip of 25 % at 10 ft below the surface. </p>

<p>Representative samples of the results are displayed in figures 2 to
5. <a href="figure2.gif">Figures 2</a> shows the development of the temperature
profiles over the course of the simulation, specifically after intervals
of 1 day, 5 days, 10 days, 22 days, 34 days and 50 days. It can be seen
how the advent of steam proceeds to heat up the entire domain in that much
time. (The steam zone is defined as the region where the local temperature
is above tor equal to the saturated temperature corresponding to the local
pressure and saturations.) At day one steam injection has warmed the soil
to a 10 ft radius from the injection well. By day 10, 25 ft from the injection
well. Steam breakthrough happens approximately around day 20. The results
after 50 days to the end of the simulation run remain relatively unchanged
and are not reported here. </p>

<p><a href="figure3.gif">Figure 3</a> and <a href="figure4.gif">Figure
4 </a>show the profiles for the water and oil saturations at the same time
intervals. As the subsurface heats up due to the invasion of steam, it
can be seen that the water and oil are being driven towards the production
well by liquid phase mobility at levels where the amount exceeds residual
saturation levels as well as by volatilization and subsequent transport.
The drop in water saturation can be observed with the progression of the
figures and can be seen to be consistent with the movement of the steam
front as inferred from the temperature profiles. By 50 days, almost all
the water has been removed and the entire domain has achieved steam temperature
levels. A total of 6 feet of dewatering is achieved over a period of 5
days. After 10 days have elapsed, oil saturation levels everywhere are
seen to be down around 10%. </p>

<center><p><img src="figure5.gif" border=0 height=286 width=274 align=bottom></p></center>

<p>Figure 5 shows the trace of the rate of extraction of the liquid water
from the system. As can be seen, dropping rapidly from 1,500 lb/hr in the
first 5 days, the rate levels off around 500 lb/hr and from day 25 decreases
towards the steady-state value. </p>

</body>
