<html>
<head><title>Subsurface Integrated Well Bore Logger </title></head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><h1>Subsurface Integrated Well Bore Logger</h1><br>
By Cliff Yuan<br>
Berkeley Environmental Restoration Center<br>
University of California at Berkeley</center>
<hr>
<h2>Abstract</h2><p>
The development of data acquisition tools to quantify subsurface conditions 
are necessary for the proper implementation of thermally enhanced remediation 
processes.  One must characterize the thermal state and contaminant 
concentrations on a real time basis in order to properly assess the 
progress of these techniques and decide what proceeding actions to take. 
Thus the objective was to design and construct a real time data logging 
system to evaluate vertical gas flow rate, soil temperature, and hydrocarbon 
concentrations which can be utilized in both monitoring and extraction 
wells in the vadose zone.  By measuring the flow rate within an 
extraction well, one can numerically determine the permeability of the 
soil via Darcy's Law.  It is also important to obtain temperature profiles 
which allow one to observe the advancement of the steam front through 
the ground during processes such as cyclic steam injection and 
vacuum extraction.  In addition, one can determine the location and track 
the movement of hydrocarbons by measuring local concentrations.<hr>
<h2>1.0  Introduction</h2><p>
<h3>1.1  Background and Project Description</h3><p>
In thermally-enhanced remediation projects, steam is injected at various 
locations and allowed to pass through the subsurface to extraction 
wells by way of pressure gradients.  A typical subsurface consists of 
many layers of sand, gravel, and soil of varying thicknesses, 
permeabilities, and contaminant concentrations as shown in Figure 1. <p>
<center><img src="Figure1.gif"><br>
Figure 1:  Subsurface with Injection and Extraction Wells</center><p>
Not only does the steam front push contaminants out of the high 
permeable zones as in conventional "pump and treat" techniques, but 
the high heat content of steam has the ability to volatilize the 
contaminant.  The procedure allows access to contamination residing 
in low permeable regions which are evaporated by conduction.  This 
reduces the required clean up time by orders of magnitude as compared 
to more conventional methods.<p>
However, it is very difficult to determine the location of pollutants 
and the geophysical characteristics of the subsurface without extensive 
and costly core sampling.  The development of a tool which could 
quickly monitor the progress of the steam front, movement of soil vapors, 
effluent contaminant concentrations, and production rates would be 
very useful in the placement of extraction and injection wells.  Instead 
of drilling all the extraction and injection wells at once, several 
initial extraction well could be installed with soil vapor extraction 
and ground water pumping implemented.  The data acquisition system can 
then identify where the contaminants are coming from thus aiding in 
the placement of additional injection and extraction wells.  Once the 
installation of all wells are complete, the logging tool can track the 
steam front in order to determine proper injection rates.  Also, the 
aquisition system facilitates in the modification of existing wells to 
increase efficiency.  Concentration and flow rate profiles allows one 
to determine where production occurs.  Consequently, modifications can 
be made to extraction wells to reduce the amount of waste vapor and 
water produced.<p>
<h3>1.2  Development of Previous Data Acquisition Tools</h3><p>
Chung (1992) first designed and developed a temperature acquisition tool 
which recorded the movement of the steam front.  The temperature probe 
consisted of a 10 feet long rod assembly with conventional thermocouples 
place at 1 foot intervals.  A rubber bladder was attached along side the 
probe and inflated to ensure proper contact between the thermocouples 
and well wall.  The bladder would then deflate and the probe lowered an 
additional 10 feet.  However, this initial system had several major 
problems associated with it. The system often required thermocouple to 
be replaced or patching leaks on the bladder.  Secondly, a significant 
amount of time was required for the thermocouple to reach thermal 
equilibrium.  Therefore, at a site such as the subsurface gasoline spill 
at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, where the wells were 
approximately 45 to 50 meters deep, a single well would easily 
take 20-30 minutes to log the heated zone of the well.<p>
Goldman (1992) completely redesign the temperature measurement system 
making significant improvements.  The most important modification 
incorporated an infrared (IR) thermocouple which did not require 
contact with the well surface.  This eliminate the maintenance 
problems associated with thermocouples and air bladder.  Also, 
the data logging system was automated and allowed for the probe 
to be continuous lowered down the well.  Consequently the time 
required to log an entire well was reduced to less than 10 minutes.  
The only critical problem associated with the IR thermocouple was 
its tendency to heat up as the probe was lower through the steam zone.  
The output would then read high since the thermocouple picked up the 
radiation emitted by the thermocouple itself.  This problem would become 
very significant especially if the probe was used to log multiple wells.<p>
<h2>2.0  Temperature Measurement</h2><p>
<img src="../../../BERC/Gallery/Lemoore1.jpg" align=left>
The measurement of the temperature of the inside surface of the well poses 
several problems.  The use of conventional thermocouples presents several 
problems.  As experienced by Chung, thermocouples tended to wear out 
and break after repeatedly being in contact with the well surface.  
However, simply placing a thermocouple in the middle of the well will 
not give an accurate measurement of the subsurface temperature.  
A typical temperature profile is shown in Figure 2. <p>
<center><img src="Figure2.gif"><br>
Figure 2.  Sample Temperature Profile Using IR Thermocouple<br>
(Source:  Laboratory Data,  Berkeley Environmental Restoration Center in 
conjunction with<br> the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, March 
15,1993.)</center><p>
One can clearly see that steep temperature gradients exist throughout 
the subsurface.  If one simply used a conventional thermocouple placed 
in the middle of the well and not in contact with the well walls, the 
temperature drop at 35 meters would not have been detected due to 
natural convection. <p> 
Sammel (1968) conducted a study of convective effects on temperature 
logging in small diameter wells of infinite length.  Eq (1) predicts 
the onset of natural convection<br>
<table width=100%>
<tr Align="center" valign="center"><td><img 
src="Eq1.gif"><td align=right>(1)</tr>
</table><br>
where <img src="theta.gif" align=absmiddle> 
is the critical temperature gradient.  C is a dimensionless constant based 
on the limiting case of infinite conductivity in the surrounding medium 
and is equal to 216, an acceptable approximation for most rocks.  For a 
4 inch (10.16 cm) diameter extraction well, temperature gradients over 
10 K/m will induce significant natural convective flows.  From Figure 2, 
temperature gradients of 15 to 17 K/m existed at depths of approximately 
17 and 35 meters.  Hence if conventional thermocouples were used to 
measure the temperature at these depths, the recorded temperature would 
not be of the well surface but that of the gas stream which is much 
higher.  Also, data acquisition system will be used in extraction wells 
and condensation of steam on the thermocouple will give false readings.<p> 
Therefore, an IR thermocouple must be utilized to assure accurate 
measurements.  Two problems must first be overcome in order to properly 
utilize an IR thermocouple. The IR thermocouple tends to heat up while 
in an extraction or monitoring well causing the output to be higher than 
expected.  Also, the steam present in extraction wells interferes with 
the measurement of well wall temperature. Water vapor behaves as an 
absorbing and emitting medium. The vapor reduces the radiosity from the 
well surface as well as attenuating the measured intensity due to the 
radiosity emitted from the water vapor itself.  Assuming the soil vapor 
and steam behaves as a gas with uniform temperature and composition, 
the intensity measured by the IR thermocouple is defined as<br> 
<table width=100%>
<tr Align="center" valign="center"><td><img 
src="Eq2.gif"><td align=right>(2)</tr>
</table><p>
<center><img src="Figure3.gif"><br>
Figure 3:  IR Thermocouple Measuring Well Wall Radiosity</center><p>
Thus the measured intensity depends on the composition of the gas.  Table 
1 shows the difference in measured intensity depending on the percentage of 
water vapor present.  The calculations were based on Figure 3 with S = 5 cm 
and assuming the soil vapor behaves as a nonparticipating gas and water 
vapor as a participating gas.  Other assumptions include neglecting water 
droplets that cause scattering and that the mean beam length equals S. 
As shown in Table 1, the presence of of steam significantly alters the 
measured intensity up to 24%.<p>
<center><table border>
<caption align=bottom>Table 1:  Effect of Water Vapor on Measured 
Intensity</caption>
<tr><th>Percentage Water Vapor<th>i'(S)/i'(0)</tr>
<tr align=center><td>0<td>1.00</tr>
<tr align=center><td>25<td>1.11</tr>
<tr align=center><td>50<td>1.17</tr>
<tr align=center><td>75<td>1.21</tr>
<tr align=center><td>100<td>1.24</tr>
</table></center><p>
In order to ensure precise and accurate readings of well wall temperatures, 
two things must be done: prevent steam from coming into the line of sight 
of the IR and maintain the internal temperature of the IR relatively 
constant.  Both goals can be accomplished by attaching an air hose to a 
sleeve that sheaths the IR thermocouple.  A compressor pumps air from 
the surface down the well and flows over the IR thermocouple as shown in 
Figure 4.<p>
<center><img src="Figure4.gif"><br>
Figure 4:  Air Purging Passages For IR Thermocouple</center><p>
However, there is a concern that the air purge may have an impingement 
cooling effect on the well surface.  The flow rate must be set sufficiently 
high that steam is purged from the IR's line of sight but low enough 
that cooling of the well does not take place.<p>
Due to monetary and time constraints, the first prototype will use 
just a conventional thermocouple placed in the middle of the well bore.  
The temperature of the gas stream can then be used to approximate the well 
wall temperature via an energy balance.<p>
<h2>3.0  Gas Sampling</h2><p>
The current technologies available for sampling soil gases include gas 
chromatography/mass spectrography, electrochemical cells, and infrared 
analyzers.  Although gas chromatography and mass spectrography offer the 
most accurate and reliable means of measuring hydrocarbon, oxygen, and 
carbon dioxide concentrations, they are very time consuming and costly.  A 
typical specimen requires approximately 20 minutes to analyze and does 
not satisfy the objective of obtaining real-time gas concentration profiles.  
On the other hand, electrochemical sensors offer many attractive features.  
Electrochemical sensors are solid state and require very little maintenance.  
Many of the solid state probes can be lowered directly down monitoring 
and extraction wells giving instantaneous response time.  However, no such 
electrochemical devices exist for carbon dioxide.  The soil gas must be 
pumped to the surface and evaluated using infrared techniques for carbon 
dioxide and electrochemical cells for the hydrocarbon and oxygen 
concentrations.<p>
There are two important aspects which are of concern: dispersion/diffusion 
and the sampling time required to pump the gas from the inlet of the tubing 
to the analyzer.  The governing mass transfer equation for unsteady 
diffusion, dispersion, and advection is<br>
<table width=100%>
<tr align="center" valign="center"><td><img src="Eq3.gif"><td align=right>(3)</tr>
</table><br>
where D<sub>eff</sub>  accounts for both diffusion and dispersion.<br>
<table width=100%>
<tr align="center" valign="center"><td><img src="Eq4.gif"><td align=right>(4)</tr>
</table><br>
Assuming the sampling tube behaves as a semi-infinite region with zero 
initial concentration, the initial and boundary conditions are<br>
<table width=100%>
<tr align="center" valign="center"><td><img 
src="Eq5a.gif"><td align=right>(5a)</tr>
<tr align="center" valign="center"><td><img 
src="Eq5b.gif"><td align=right>(5b)</tr>
<tr align="center" valign="center"><td><img 
src="Eq5c.gif"><td align=right>(5c)</tr>
</table><br>
for a step change in the concentration at the inlet.  The solution is obtained 
by taking the LaPlace transform with respect to time and solving for x.  
The concentration of the soil gas in the tubing is given as<br>
<table width=100%>
<tr align="center" valign="center"><td><img src="Eq6.gif"><td align=right>(6)</tr>
</table><br>
Solving for the time needed for 99% of C<sub>0</sub> to reach the 
analyzer, the sampling time can be determined.<p>
However, the effective difusivity is very small, on the order of 10<sup>-
5</sup> m<sup>2</sup>/s. Since sampling rates range from 0.15 to 
0.5 liters/minute (depending on the gas examined), the Peclet number is 
10<sup>3</sup> or greater.  Hence, axial diffusive effects are 
negligible compared to the advective term.  The soil gas travels as "shock" 
front with dispersion and diffusion smearing the front slightly.  At a depth 
of 30 meters, the lag time is approximately 1.8 to 5.9 minutes for a 1/4" 
inner diameter tube with a sampling rate of 0.15 and 0.5 liters/minute, 
respectively.<p>
Due to monetary and time constraints, the first prototype data logger will 
only have a gas sampling tube with no on board gas analyzers.  This gives 
the option of either connecting the sampling tube to a gas chromatography, 
electrochemical, and/or infra-red device.

