<h3>
<hr size=3 width="100%" >Executive Summary<a name="Executive Summary"></a>
</h3>

<p>This report describes one-and two-dimensional treatability experiments
to determine the applicability of Steam Enhanced Extraction to remediate
the Visalia Pole Yard site. The soil sample preparation procedures, experimental
procedures, experimental results, and the conclusions drawn from the work
are presented. </p>

<p>The experimental studies included three one-dimensional column experiments,
and two two-dimensional vertical cross-section experiments. The one-dimensional
experiments were conducted to obtain the rates and endpoints of soil cleanup
using steam, and the two-dimensional experiments were aimed at identifying
mechanisms that may lead to potential problems in field implementation
of the process. </p>

<p>The first two one-dimensional experiments demonstrated over 99% of the
hydrocarbon mass being removed by steam enhanced extraction after subjecting
the soil to a throughput of about 180,000 pore volumes of steam. The third
one-dimensional experiment was conducted with additional Pentachlorophenol
(PCP) added to the hydrocarbon mixture obtained from the Visalia Pole Yard
site subsurface. A significantly shorter steam injection period (9000 pore
volumes of steam) was selected for this third run to more appropriately
scale the steam use to field conditions. In addition, pre-steaming and
post-steaming leachability tests were run to determine the effect of steam
injection on the concentration of PCP in the aqueous phase before and after
the steaming operation. While the percentage of total hydrocarbon mass
removed is unknown for the third experiment, over 80% (probably 99%) of
the initial PCP was removed. Based on the single post-steaming leachate
analysis, reduction in PCP concentrations in the aqueous phase in equilibrium
with the residual hydrocarbon mixture in the steamed soil was less than
50% of the pre-steamed soil leachate PCP detection limit. </p>

<p>Two-dimensional experiments were conducted to assess the potential for
downward movement of the wood preservative chemicals. It was found that
the pole treating chemicals did not move downward if the water table was
not lowered. However, contaminant removal rates were correspondingly low
since little steam-hydrocarbon contact existed. It was found that deep
aquifer steam injection will provide upward hydraulic pressure gradients,
inhibiting downward NAPL movement, while producing steam flow through the
contaminated low permeability zone, thus increasing recovery rates. 
<hr size=3 width="100%" ></p>

<h3>Introduction <a name="Introduction"></a></h3>

<p>Steam flooding has been used for decades to enhance petroleum recovery
(Mandel and Volek, 1969, Volek and Pryor, 1972, Blevins et al. 1984). A
number of steam flood sites have demonstrated that steam injection can
increase oil production rates at sites with high permeability, moderate
viscosity (180 - 4000 cp), and high oil content (Boberg 1988). The use
of steam injection in the environmental restoration field is relatively
new, however. </p>

<p>The effectiveness of steam enhanced remediation of soils and groundwater
containing volatile compounds such as gasoline and chlorinated solvents
has been demonstrated in numerous laboratory studies (Hunt et al, 1988b,
Udell and Stewart, 1992). Well-documented field demonstrations have been
conducted to remediate soils and groundwater containing chemical mixtures
(Udell and Stewart, 1989), gasoline (Newmark, et. al, 1995), and jet fuel
(Udell and Itamura, 1995). The operation of steam injection in a cyclic
manner after the soils reach steam temperatures has been shown to enhance
mass transfer rates and accelerate clean-up (Itamura and Udell, 1995).
Such a process is termed Steam Enhanced Extraction and is protected by
U. S. Patent # 5,018,576 (Udell, et al, 1991). </p>

<p>The applicability of steam enhanced extraction to soils containing low-volatility
priority chemicals such as those found in the subsurface of the Visalia
Pole Yard has not been previously reported. Thus, Southern California Edison
contracted the University of California at Berkeley, through Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory, to perform two one-dimensional experiments to determine
the applicability of Steam Enhanced Extraction to the soils and chemical
mixture of the site. Given the positive results of the first two one-dimensional
experiments, Southern California Edison contracted the University of California
at Berkeley to perform a series of two-dimensional experiments to identify
and mechanisms that might lead to downward migration of the chemical mixture
during field application of Steam Enhanced Extraction at the Visalia site.
This report documents the findings of these studies. </p>

<h4>Objectives <a name="Objectives"></a></h4>

<p>The objectives of this study are: </p>

<ul>
<p>To determine the extent of applicability of Steam Enhanced Extraction
to remove the semi-volatile and low volatility components of the liquid
pole treatment chemical mixture from Visalia soils. </p>

<p>To identify any gravitational mechanisms which may lead to irreversible
downward migration of the liquid pole treatment chemicals into uncontaminated
regions. </p>
</ul>

<h3>
<hr size=3 width="100%" >NAPL Description and Physical Characterization<a name="NAPL Description and Physical Characterization"></a>
</h3>

<p>Before beginning the one-dimensional experiment, a few properties of
the contaminant were measured to better predict its behavior in an environment
subjected to steam injection. Non-Aqueous-Phase-Liquid (NAPL) samples were
obtained from the Visalia site subsurface as free product. All free product
was recovered by pumping from a single recovery well in a region of high
contaminant concentration. Some sample jars received at Berkeley contained
a relatively viscous liquid (about sixty-percent by volume) beneath a layer
of cloudy water. Others were emulsions of water and small droplets of dense
non-aqueous phase liquid (DNAPL) at the jar bottoms. Tar droplets were
dense enough to begin settling immediately after agitation. All samples
had a strong odor of naphthalene. </p>

<p>To prepare a sample of NAPL relatively free of water and silt, four
containers with the largest amount of tar free product were selected. One
container was set aside under refrigeration to serve as a control sample
throughout the experiments. The other three were used to make a blend that
would give average properties across the samples. These three samples were
chilled to increase the viscosity of the tar so it remained in the bottom
of the jar while the overlying water was poured from the containers. The
NAPL was then strained through a four-hundred mesh stainless steel filter.
This filtered and mixed NAPL formed the base stock for all experiments.
The NAPL was then characterized by centrifuging, measuring viscosity, and
measuring density. Chemical characterization of the compounds in the NAPL
is presented in the experiment results section. </p>

<p>The first step in characterizing the NAPL was to centrifuge the samples.
Centrifuging separated the tar into its lighter and heavier compounds giving
some sense of the density variation. Samples were centrifuged in test tubes
for twenty, sixty, and eighty minutes. All samples separated into essentially
the same parts. Each had a light brown/tan color in the top one-sixth of
sample with a black liquid in the rest. The brownish substance was waxy
and viscous, while the underlying black liquid flowed freely and exhibited
a viscosity similar to light oil. These results suggest the tar contains
a number of compounds of varying density which might be removed in stages
during steam injection. </p>

<h4>Viscosity<a name="Viscosity"></a> </h4>

<p>The second step in characterizing the tar was to measure the viscosity
of the sample. Viscometer readings were made using a Fann V-G Model 35
rotational viscometer. This viscometer subjected the NAPL to a rotating
cylinder and measured the force transmitted by shear across a small gap
between the rotating cylinder and an outer housing. Since steam injection
raises subsurface temperatures, the viscosity variation with temperature
was of interest. To test over a range of temperatures typical of steam
injection, the contaminant was placed in a beaker wrapped with heater tape
and insulation. Viscometer readings were taken at temperatures of 20 &deg;C,
40 &deg;C, 60 &deg;C, 80 &deg;C, 100 &deg;C, and 110 &deg;C. The resulting
data indicated the tar behaved as a Newtonian fluid. It also had a large
decrease in viscosity with increasing temperature as shown below. </p>

<center><p><img src="Image1.gif" border=0></p></center>

<p>This figure shows nearly a six-fold decrease in viscosity from 20 &deg;C
to 100 &deg;C. The decrease in viscosity is most important when the steam
front initially mobilizes the contaminant as a separate phase liquid. This
decrease in viscosity with increasing temperature may allow significant
displacement of contaminant as the steam heats the NAPL-laden soils, but
inhibits its movement into cold zones. </p>

<h4>Density<a name="Density"></a> </h4>

<p>The third step in characterizing the tar was to measure the change in
density with temperature. Density was measured by placing 46.4 grams of
tar into a graduated cylinder. The cylinder was wrapped with a heater tape
to control temperature. This temperature was measured with a thermocouple
suspended in the tar within the graduated cylinder. As temperature increased,
the volume of the tar increased, and density was determined by dividing
the tar mass by its volume. The NAPL density decreased with increasing
temperature as shown below in Figure 2. For comparison, the variation in
water density with temperature it is also plotted. </p>

<center><p><img src="Image2.gif" border=0>
<br></p></center>

<p>Vapor bubbles began to evolve from the NAPL at 110 &deg;C. The mixture
was weighed after cooling, and no mass change was found. Thus the volatilization
did not reduce the mass more than 0.1 g (0.2 percent of the original 46.4
g mass) over the procedure. An uncertainty analysis of these measurements,
taking into account the difficulty of clearly determining the volume of
the mixture as it began to froth near 110 C, indicates the values of NAPL
density could vary by plus or minus 10 kg/m<sup>3</sup>. Considering this
uncertainty, it is impossible to determine the relative density of the
tar compared to water. This is of interest because if the tar remains more
dense than water while its viscosity is reduced by steam injection, there
is a potential for downward migration of tar during steaming. The two-dimensional
experiments described later in this report address this question more fully.
</p>

<h3>
<hr size=3 width="100%" >One-Dimensional Treatability Experiments<a name="One-Dimensional Treatability Experiments"></a>
</h3>

<h4>Experimental Apparatus<a name="Experimental Apparatus"></a> </h4>

<p>As shown in Figure 3, the apparatus for the one-dimensional experiment
consists of a pair of metering pumps to deliver a constant flow rate of
distilled water, a steam generator to boil the water into steam, a stainless
steel pipe to hold the contaminated soil sample, and an effluent collection
jar maintained in an ice bath to minimize loss of components in the effluent
through partitioning with the atmosphere. The inlet and outlet of the sample
holder have end caps which can be unbolted and removed to pack the tube
with a soil sample. These caps have channels cut on their inner surface
in contact with the soil to help spread the injected steam across the entire
cross section of the sample holder and reduce the end effects of the one-dimensional
experiment. In addition to these channels, four-hundred mesh stainless
steel screens are attached to the inner surfaces of the end caps to encourage
uniformity of the steam over the sample holder cross section and to prevent
the grains of soil in the sample from escaping the sample holder. The stainless
steel sample holder is wrapped with heater tape and insulated. During injection,
this heater tape is set to a constant supply power to offset the heat loss
through the insulation, maintaining a constant temperature down the length
of the tube and providing an adiabatic environment. Thermocouples are mounted
at the steam inlet tubing, the upstream end of the soil sample, the downstream
end of the soil sample, and the outlet tubing. Teflon tubing is used to
carry all fluids in the system to insure no degradation of the tubing leading
to contamination of the effluent samples. The outlet tubing was made long
enough to allow the effluent to cool to near room temperature before it
enters the effluent collection bottle. Because flow rates are low, usually
one meter of tubing is of sufficient length. Not shown in the diagram is
a condenser stage which can be added to the outlet tubing between the outlet
of the stainless steel piping and the effluent collection jar when the
effluent flow rate is too high to condense all of the steam in the effluent
tube. </p>

<center><p><img src="Image3.gif" border=0></p></center>

<center><p>Figure 3 
<br>Experimental Apparatus </p></center>

<h3>
<hr size=3 width="100%" >Experimental Procedures<a name="Experimental Procedures"></a>
</h3>

<p>Each of the three experiments was conducted with different procedures
and goals. The first experiment consisted of steady steam injection over
a long duration (with several short periods of pressure cycling) as a preliminary
investigation of steam&iacute;s ability to reduce NAPL concentration. This
experiment used a fairly coarse clean sand approximating the most porous
soils expected in field operations at the site of interest. The second
experiment was filled with finer sands taken from the field site. It also
was conducted using cyclical pressurization of the test cell since this
had been found to effectively increase removal rates during the first experiment.
The third experiment, conducted with site soils and pressure cycling, was
designed to investigate the effectiveness of steam injection over a much
shorter time. The sample preparations and experimental procedures for each
of these experiments are detailed below. </p>

<h4>Trial Injection <a name="Trial Injection "></a></h4>

<p>Before performing the actual experiment, various steam flow rates were
injected through the sand to gain insights into any problems that might
arise during the actual injection. To investigate the possibility of tar
free product occluding the effluent tubing as it exited the sample holder
and cooled on its way to the effluent container, the sand was mixed with
a 20,000 ppm sample of tar. Since the planned experiments were to use soils
with a NAPL concentration of 10,000 ppm, any tendency to occlude would
be evident at these larger concentrations in the trial injection. In addition,
the effluent was cooled in an ice bath to increase the viscosity of the
exiting contaminant and create the worst case scenario for blockage. The
trial injection also afforded an opportunity to observe the rate of contaminant
removal with time to develop an effluent sampling procedure that would
capture the details of the cleaning process. </p>

<p>The results of the trial injection showed that the effluent did have
a tendency to build-up on the walls of the effluent tube. This build-up
occurred whether or not the effluent was cooled in a condenser, though
cooling exacerbated the problem. Using an effluent tube with a 1.5 mm inside
diameter, the buildup was severe enough to completely plug the effluent
tube and prevent flow from the sample holder. To prevent this buildup in
the planned experiments, the tube inner diameter was increased to 4.0 mm
and the ice bath was removed from the effluent line to reduce the cooling
rate of the effluent. </p>

<p>The trial injection also indicated that a free product bank of NAPL
was displaced ahead of the steam front and the following several hours
of steam flow carried large masses of contaminant out of the column. To
obtain detailed results of this early stage, a sampling schedule with more
frequent samples in the early part of the injection was prepared. The nature
of the effluent was also observed to change with time. The first few hours
of operation produced an effluent that contained a light brown NAPL that
flowed smoothly through the lines. The next few hours of operation produced
an effluent that contained a tan-colored waxy material that tended to build-up
on the walls of the effluent tube as it cooled on its way to the collection
jar. 
<br></p>

<h4>Experiment 1 Preparation <a name="Experiment 1 Preparation "></a></h4>

<p>For the steady steam injection, the one dimensional sample holder was
filled with site soil and the NAPL mixture. To reduce variation in the
sand properties and simplify interpretation of the injection results, a
fairly narrow range of soil grain size was used. To determine a grain size
range best approximating the soil from the site, sand and silt samples
from the site of interest were sifted through fourteen, twenty, forty,
sixty-five, eighty, and one-hundred mesh sieves. The volumes retained by
each sieve were as follows: </p>

<table border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 >
<tr>
<td align=baseline width="100" >
<center><p>Mesh Size, d</p></center>
</td>

<td>
<center><p>Volume Percentage</p></center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
<center><p>d &gt; 14</p></center>
</td>

<td>
<center><p>20.0 % </p></center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
<center><p>14 &gt; d &gt; 20</p></center>
</td>

<td>
<center><p>10.8 % </p></center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
<center><p>20 &gt; d &gt; 40</p></center>
</td>

<td>
<center><p>40.0 %</p></center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
<center><p>40 &gt; d &gt; 65</p></center>
</td>

<td>
<center><p>21.6 % </p></center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
<center><p>65 &gt; d &gt; 80</p></center>
</td>

<td>
<center><p>6.0 % </p></center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
<center><p>80 &gt; d &gt; 100</p></center>
</td>

<td>
<center><p>0.2 % </p></center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr align=baseline >
<td>
<center><p>d &lt; 100</p></center>
</td>

<td>
<center><p>1.4 % </p></center>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p>Most of the soil passed through a twenty mesh screen, but not sixty-five
mesh. Since finer sands within this range provide a larger soil specific
surface area, thus increasing the difficulty of contaminant removal, Experiment
1 was run with sand passing a 40 mesh screen, but not a 50 mesh screen.
The soil sample was prepared from clean, washed sand as opposed to sand
from the site to insure that no contamination existed in the sand before
mixing with pole tar. </p>

<p>The refrigerated, separated, and filtered NAPL prepared earlier was
mixed with the sand at a NAPL concentration of one percent by mass (ten-thousand
parts per million). This soil-hydrocarbon mixture was placed into the stainless
steel sample holder by alternately adding a few centimeters of mixture
and compacting with a large wooden dowel to eliminate any large void spaces
in the sand pack. Thermocouples were placed within the soil during this
packing. To minimize voids created during settling of the sand pack, enough
sand was added to require slight compression of the end caps. Such voids
are undesirable since they can provide high-permeability channels through
which the steam could finger and compromise the homogeneity of the one-dimensional
sand pack. </p>

<h4>Experiment 1 Procedure<a name="Experiment 1 Procedure"></a> </h4>

<p>For the first experiment the sample holder was packed with a mixture
of sand and one percent tar by mass as described in the sample preparation
section. Throughout the injection the metering pumps delivered a constant
water flow rate of 38 ml. All of the effluent coming from the sample holder
was collected into sample bottles according to the sampling schedule detailed
in Figure 4. </p>

<center><p><img src="Image4.gif" border=0></p></center>

<center><p>Figure 4 
<br>Experiment 1 Sampling Procedure 
<br></p></center>

<p>This regime provided small samples of effluent during the first few
hours of injection allowing detailed analysis of effluent concentrations
during times of rapid change. And it gave large samples of effluent later
in the experiment when concentrations were low and changing slowly. To
minimize sample degradation, an ice bath surrounded each bottle while collecting
the effluent. As each bottle filled, it was sealed with a Teflon cap and
placed it in a refrigerator at 4 &deg;C ( &plusmn;2 &deg;C) or an ice bath.
</p>

<p>Pressure in the sample holder was cycled while collecting samples eleven,
sixteen, twenty-five, and thirty-one. The maximum desirable pressure was
determined from field constraints. Field surveys indicated contaminant
at and below 60 feet. Since the earth overburden can contain injection
pressures of about one-half psi per vertical foot before fracturing begins,
a 30 psig injection pressure is possible. Pressure was cycled by closing
the valve at the outlet end of the sample holder while maintaining steam
flow into the inlet. The valve was closed until steam pressures rose to
about 207 kPa gage (30 psig). The valve was then opened to depressurize
the system over about two minutes. Since saturated temperatures were maintained
through the pressure increase, cycling in this way first increased the
pressure and temperature of NAPL. Since vapor pressures increase with temperature,
components from this hotter NAPL could partition more readily into the
vapor phase. Then as the system depressurized, gasses generated within
the soils in the test cell carried hydrocarbon vapors from the cell at
an increased rate. This cyclical process increased component concentrations
in the effluent by mobilizing compounds trapped in less accessible regions
such as crevices between sand grains. During steam cycling the effluent
tube was placed in an ice bath to condense the effluent before it reached
the sample bottle. This was necessary because the fairly rapid depressurization
of the test section produced enough steam to heat the effluent tube and
send vapors to the collection bottle where they could have been lost to
the atmosphere from around the tube&iacute;s entrance through the bottle
cap. There was no occlusion of the effluent tube with the addition of this
condenser because steam cycling was not begun until the concentrations
of contaminant in the effluent had dropped to a level at which no free
product was visible in the effluent. </p>

<h4>Experiment 2 Preparation<a name="Experiment 2 Preparation"></a> </h4>

<p>For the second experiment the sample holder was packed with a sand and
silt soil from the Visalia site, sieved with a two-hundred mesh screen
to eliminate the finer grains that would pass through the screens at the
ends of the test section. The resulting permeability when packed was about
three darcy. This sand pack was finer than that used for Experiment 1,
having a higher soil specific surface area, and making the contaminant
more difficult to remove. </p>

<h4>Experiment 2 Procedure<a name="Experiment 2 Procedure"></a> </h4>

<p>As described for steady injection, the sample holder was filled with
a mixture of sand and one percent NAPL by mass. The metering pumps delivered
a constant water flow rate of 38 ml/hr. All of the effluent coming from
the sample holder was collected into sample bottles according to the sampling
schedule detailed in Figure 5. 
<br></p>

<center><p><img src="Image5.gif" border=0></p></center>

<center><p>Figure 5 
<br>Experiment 2 Sampling Procedure 
<br></p></center>

<p>Pressure was cycled in the sample holder throughout the injection using
a timer on a solenoid valve at the outlet end of the sample holder. The
valve was closed for periods of one hour and opened for periods of thirty
minutes while maintaining steady steam flow into the inlet. With the valve
closed steam pressures rose to about 207 kPa gage (30 psig). During this
cycling the effluent tube was placed in an ice bath to condense the effluent
before it reached the sample bottle. Because contaminant tended to build
on the cool tube walls during the first few hours of injection, the effluent
tube was periodically removed from the ice bath to allow warm effluent
to flow through the tube and clear the accumulated waxes from the sides
of the effluent tube. </p>

<h4>Experiment 3 Preparation <a name="Experiment 3 Preparation "></a></h4>

<p>For the third experiment the sample holder was packed with a sand and
silt mixture from the Visalia site. This mixture was sieved with a 325
mesh screen to eliminate the finer grains that would pass through the screens
at the ends of the test section. The resulting permeability of this sand
when packed into the test section was about 2.5 darcy. </p>

<p>This third experiment was designed to investigate the removal rate of
pentachlorophenol (PCP, formula C<sub>6</sub>HCl<sub>5</sub>O) from the
NAPL during a relatively short injection period. One percent by mass of
PCP was added to the NAPL. This was then added at one percent by mass to
washed and sieved sand to give a 100 ppm PCP concentration in the soil.
A similar sample holder as used in experiments 1 and 2 was filled with
this mixture. This sample holder had a length of 13 inches (0.33 m), compared
to 9 inches (0.23 m) in experiments 1 and 2, giving a larger volume for
study. One inch of clean sand was placed at each end of the sample holder
to minimize end effects such as condensation near the end caps. </p>

<h4>Experiment 3 Procedure <a name="Experiment 3 Procedure "></a></h4>

<p>The sample was subjected to steam injection with cyclical pressure variation
as in experiment 2. The metering pumps delivered a constant water flow
rate of 38 ml/hr. </p>

<p>The duration of injection for the third experiment was based on the
number of pore volumes of water that could be economically injected as
steam in a field operation. The effectiveness of these steam injection
in remediating NAPL in these experiments can be compared to the effectiveness
of steam injection in a field operation by equating pore volumes of steam
condensate. The energy cost per unit volume of soil for the steaming process
is proportional to the pore volumes of steam injected which is linearly
related to the pore volumes of steam condensate. The costs can thus be
calculated from the following equation which was derived from energy and
mass balances. </p>

<p><img src="Image6.gif" border=0></p>

<p>The factor 0.661 is the porosity (0.35) multiplied by the water density
(62.3 lbm/ft<sub>3</sub>) multiplied by the difference between the steam
enthalpy and the inlet water enthalpy (1.1228 x 10<sup>-3</sup> MBtu/lbm),
and the conversion factor between cubic feet and cubic yards (27 ft<sup>3</sup>/yd<sup>3</sup>).
</p>

<p>Using the above equation and a maximum energy cost per cubic yard of
$20, the number of pore volumes of steam condensate to be injected as steam
is obtained. Using energy costs of field steam enhanced extraction at Lawrence
Livermore National Laboratory during the summer of 1993 ($3.8/Mbtu), the
resulting amount of condensate is 8 pore volumes. The third experiment
was conducted with about 9 pore volumes which would result in an energy
cost of about $23 per cubic yard. </p>

<p>All of the effluent coming from the sample holder was collected into
sample bottles according to the sampling schedule detailed in Figure 6.

<br></p>

<center><p><img src="Image7.gif" border=0></p></center>

<center><p>Figure 6 
<br>Experiment 3 Sampling Procedure 
<br></p></center>

<p>Pressure was cycled in the sample holder throughout the injection as
in experiment 2. The valve was closed for periods of thirty minutes and
opened for periods of 2.5 hours while maintaining steady steam flow into
the inlet. With the valve closed steam pressures rose to about 207 kPa
gage (30 psig). During this cycling the effluent tube was placed in an
ice bath to condense the effluent before it reached the sample bottle.
The longer cycle times for this experiment were due to changes in the steam
generator. This experiment used a larger steam generator that operated
with longer cycle times. Since the average injection rate remained the
same in all experiments, results should be comparable. </p>

<h3>One-Dimensional Treatability Experiment Results<a name="One-Dimensional Treatability Experiment Results"></a>
</h3>

<p>The results of the experiments fall into two categories, general observations
and results from the analysis. The general observations, seen in each of
the three experiments, are presented below. The data from the chemical
analysis of the soils and effluent samples are more detailed. The data
for Experiments 1 and 2 are presented together because those experiments
were similar in purpose, execution and results. Since experiment 3 was
designed to examine the effectiveness of relatively short-duration steam
injection, its results are presented separately. All results are scaled
by pore volumes of steam condensed to facilitate comparison among the experiments
and with field-scale operation. </p>

<h4>General Observations <a name="General Observations "></a></h4>

<p>General observations during operation of the experiments confirmed the
tendency of the waxes to build on the effluent tube walls when present
in high concentrations during the first few hours after steam break through.
During the first ten hours after steam break through tar partially occluded
the tube walls and had to be cleaned to prevent total occlusion. Cleaning
was accomplished by closing the outlet valve on the sample holder and allowing
pressure to build inside the pipe to about 35 kPa gage (5 psig) before
opening the valve. This flooded the tube with warm effluent and liquefied
the tar deposits on the tube walls. In addition the increased the flow
rate of liquid through the tube flushed the deposits into the sample bottle.
With this procedure the tube could be cleaned without introducing any foreign
substance or opening the tube. </p>

<p>The nature of the effluent changed visibly with time. Samples collected
prior to steam break through contained water tinted light brown with no
visible free product. Samples collected during the first fifteen hours
of injection contained free product in the form of light brown DNAPL, with
the relative volume of DNAPL to water decreasing with successive samples.
Later samples contained waxy solids that floated on the water in the effluent
sample bottles. All samples collected while cycling pressure contained
noticeably increased levels of contaminant compared to samples collected
during steady injection. </p>

<h4>Experiments 1 and 2 Analytic Results <a name="Experiments 1 and 2 Analytic Results "></a></h4>

<p>The analytical reports from Experiment 1 (see Appendix A for analytical
data and B for gas chromatograms) indicates the total hydrocarbon concentration
in the soil was reduced from 6620 mg/kg to 39 mg/kg at the outlet end of
the sample holder as determined from EPA Method 8015M. This represents
a reduction of hydrocarbon mass of 99.4%. The analytical report from Experiment
2 (see Appendix C) indicates the total hydrocarbon concentration in the
soil was reduced from 6870 mg/kg to 19 mg/kg at the outlet end of the sample
holder. This represents a reduction of 99.7%. </p>

<p>Soil and effluent samples were also analyzed for poly-nuclear aromatics
by EPA Method 8270. From these analyses, the following chemicals of interest
were detected in the soil and effluent samples. </p>

<center><p><img src="Image8.gif" border=0></p></center>

<center><p>Figure 4 
<br>Compounds of Interest In Pole Tar 
<br></p></center>

<p>These compounds are listed in order of decreasing vapor pressure. At
100 &deg;C, their vapor pressures range from about 2.5 kPa for Naphthalene
to 0.035 kPa for Phenanthrene to still lower values (Reid 1987). </p>

<p>The effectiveness of steam in removing these compounds from the soil
matrix can be examined by analyzing the chemical composition of the soil
before and after steam injection, and by analyzing the effluent stream
during injection. Figure 5 shows the concentrations of contaminant in soil
samples before and after steam injection for Experiment 1. Figure 6 shows
similar data for Experiment 2. 
<br></p>

<p><img src="Image9.gif" border=0></p>

<p><img src="Image10.gif" border=0></p>

<p>Sample S0 is untreated soil and serves as a baseline for comparing removal
effectiveness of the different compounds. The other soil samples were collected
from the treated soil in the test cell at one inch from the inlet (sample
S1), half-way between inlet and outlet (sample S5), and at the outlet (sample
S9). The soil should be progressively cleaner moving from the inlet to
the outlet. Figures 5 and 6 indicates that this is generally the case.
</p>

<p>Comparison of Figures 5 and 6 indicates that compounds were more completely
removed in Experiment 2, likely because of the cyclic pressurization employed
throughout that experiment. For both experiments, the data indicate that
the more volatile compounds were removed and concentrations of the less
volatile compounds were also reduced by at least an order of magnitude.
</p>

<p>Figure 6 does indicate that some compounds were present at higher concentrations
in the soils closer to the inlet than in soils farther downstream. This
could imply that the sand and pole tar were not mixed with complete uniformity
and that the mixture at the inlet started with a higher concentration of
tar than that at the outlet. It could also imply that steam entering the
sample holder did not immediately spread over the cross section of the
pipe and flow downward with a uniform velocity over the cross section but
instead formed a cone of steam spreading into the sample holder. This would
create regions near the pipe wall at the injection end with lower steam
flow rates and correspondingly lower contaminant removal rates. A third
possibility could be that there is an error in the analysis of compound
concentrations at these locations arising from their fairly low concentrations.
Despite this irregularity, the general trends of contaminant concentrations
in soil clearly indicate that steam significantly reduced the concentrations
of the compounds measured. </p>

<p>The rate of NAPL compound removal with time can be inferred from the
concentrations of the compounds of interest in the effluent versus time
as shown in Figures 7 through 16. To simplify the presentation, the fourteen
identified compounds are plotted on five graphs for each experiment. And
for comparison, the Experiment 1 and 2 graphs are paired for the same compounds.
</p>

<center><p><img src="Image11.gif" border=0></p></center>

<center><p>Figure 7 
<br>Effluent Concentrations Versus Pore Volumes Effluent Condensed 
<br></p></center>

<center><p><img src="Image12.gif" border=0></p></center>

<center><p>Figure 8 
<br>Effluent Concentrations Versus Pore Volumes Effluent Condensed 
<br>
<br></p></center>

<center><p><img src="Image13.gif" border=0></p></center>

<center><p>Figure 9 
<br>Effluent Concentrations Versus Pore Volumes Effluent Condensed 
<br></p></center>

<center><p><img src="Image14.gif" border=0></p></center>

<center><p>Figure 10 
<br>Effluent Concentrations Versus Pore Volumes Effluent Condensed 
<br>
<br></p></center>

<center><p><img src="Image15.gif" border=0></p></center>

<center><p>Figure 11 
<br>Effluent Concentrations Versus Pore Volumes Effluent Condensed 
<br></p></center>

<center><p><img src="Image16.gif" border=0></p></center>

<center><p>Figure 12 
<br>Effluent Concentrations Versus Pore Volumes Effluent Condensed 
<br>
<br></p></center>

<center><p><img src="Image17.gif" border=0></p></center>

<center><p>Figure 13 </p></center>

<center><p>Effluent Concentrations Versus Pore Volumes Effluent Condensed

<br></p></center>

<center><p><img src="Image18.gif" border=0></p></center>

<center><p>Figure 14 
<br>Effluent Concentrations Versus Pore Volumes Effluent Condensed 
<br></p></center>

<center><p><img src="Image19.gif" border=0></p></center>

<center><p>Figure 15 
<br>Effluent Concentrations Versus Pore Volumes Effluent Condensed 
<br></p></center>

<center><p><img src="Image20.gif" border=0></p></center>

<center><p>Figure 16 
<br>Effluent Concentrations Versus Pore Volumes Effluent Condensed 
<br></p></center>

<p>Because each effluent sample was not analyzed separately, the data shown
in these graphs represent average concentrations in sample groups. For
Experiment 1, samples were grouped for analysis as: samples three through
seven, samples eight through ten and twelve, samples thirteen through fifteen,
samples seventeen through nineteen, and samples twenty through thirty-three.
For Experiment 2, samples were grouped for analysis as: samples one through
two, samples four through six, samples seven through ten, samples thirteen
through fourteen, samples fifteen through nineteen, samples twenty through
twenty-four, and samples twenty-five through twenty-nine. The concentrations
are reported for these sample groups at the average time for the group.
For Experiment 1, the concentrations are initially low and rise steeply
because the first effluent sample was collected before steam break-through,
and the second sample was effluent from the first hour after break-through.
This shows the large increase in effluent concentrations as the steam front
passes through the sand pack and mobilizes NAPL. </p>

<p>These graphs illustrate several points. First, the concentrations in
the effluent are initially large and drop by at least one order of magnitude
in the first twenty pore volumes. Most of the contaminant is removed in
this time. Second, the data clearly show the increases in concentration
associated with pressure cycling. The labeled peaks in Experiment 1 effluent
data represent effluent samples which were taken during pressure cycling.
Finally, it is clear that the concentrations of more volatile compounds
such as naphthalene are more reduced faster than those of less volatile
compounds. This is consistent with the preferential distillation of compounds
with higher vapor pressures. </p>

<p>As previously noted, the nature of the effluent changed with time appearing
first as a light brown liquid heavier than the surrounding aqueous phase
(DNAPL) and later as a waxy solid. To better understand the nature of these
physically different mixtures emerging from the test cell, separate analyses
on the liquids, waxy solids, and the aqueous phase surrounding them were
performed. The comparison between the NAPL and the aqueous phase at various
stages in the injection is presented for Experiments 1 and 2 in Figures
17 through 20. 
<br></p>

<p><img src="Image21.gif" border=0>
<br></p>

<p><img src="Image22.gif" border=0></p>

<center><p><img src="Image23.gif" border=0><img src="Image24.gif" border=0></p></center>

<p>Concentrations in the aqueous phase are shown as the leftmost bars while
concentrations in the DNAPL are shown as the rightmost bars. In these plots
the contaminant concentrations in the water decreases with time as one
might expect, but the concentrations in the DNAPL remain relatively high.
This implies that the thermodynamic behavior of these components is similar
to that of the bulk hydrocarbon mixture. All figures indicate the concentrations
in the free product are several orders of magnitude higher than those in
the aqueous phase. Furthermore, these plots suggest the DNAPL emerging
from the test section early in the injection has relatively high concentrations
of more volatile compounds as one would expect. </p>

<p>The waxy solid phase appeared later in the injection. Concentrations
in the solid are shown on Figures 21 through 25 along with concentrations
in the aqueous phase. </p>

<p><img src="Image25.gif" border=0></p>

<p><img src="Image26.gif" border=0></p>

<center><p><img src="Image27.gif" border=0></p></center>

<center><p><img src="Image28.gif" border=0>
<br></p></center>

<p><img src="Image29.gif" border=0></p>

<p>Concentrations in the aqueous phase are shown as the leftmost bars while
concentrations in the waxy solid are shown as the rightmost bars. These
plots suggest the waxy material has relatively high concentrations of less
volatile compounds. </p>

<p>These graphs suggest the DNAPL contains higher percentages of more volatile
compounds than does the waxy material. To further clarify the differences
in the liquid and the waxy solid the concentrations in each phase can be
normalized by reporting the concentration of each compound as a fraction
of the total concentrations of all components listed. This is presented
in Figure 26 for the liquid free and waxy free product in Experiment 2.

<br></p>

<p><img src="Image30.gif" border=0>
<br></p>

<p>In Figure 26, the two leftmost columns in each grouping are concentration
fractions for each compound in the NAPL free product separated from the
effluent water, while the three rightmost columns are concentration fractions
for each compound in the waxy free product. This data supports the previous
observation that the liquid free product contains a larger fraction of
more volatile compounds such as naphthalene while the waxy material contains
a larger fraction of less volatile compounds. This can also be interpreted
as the more volatile compounds being removed first followed by less volatile
compounds. Note that these graphs only account for a small percentage of
the total mass of the NAPL samples so this analysis does not account for
most of the constituents of these phases. Although data shown in Figure
26 indicate that the waxy solids have higher concentrations of less volatile
compounds than the liquids, the total levels of these concentrations are
on the order of one-hundred parts per million. Therefore the difference
in physical characteristics between the waxy solid and the liquid may not
be due to the different concentrations of the compounds measured but instead
may arise from the presence of compounds not analyzed. The waxy material
may be just a wax base that happens to have high concentrations of anthracene,
fluoranthene, and pyrene. It is also of note that if such hydrocarbons
remained in the Visalia soils after field application of Steam Enhanced
Extraction, they would be in a solid phase once the subsurface temperatures
decreased to ambient. </p>

