<title>Lab Abstract of Graduate Student Researcher at BERC</title>
</head>
<body>
<h2>Lab Abstract of Graduate Student Researcher at BERC<br>
</h2>
<hr>
<h3>
Moving Finite Element Front Tracking in Soil Remediation Processes<br>
</h3>
Student: <a href="../../BERC/Personnel/Liu/index.html">Ssy-Wen Liu</a><p>

A C++ program is to be developed to solve two-dimensional Front Tracking
problems for the cleanup of subsurface DNAPL spills.  The program will be able
to handle both steam injection and vacuum extraction situations with any
number of DNAPL components without any modification to the source code.
It will be able to track the evaporation fronts of all DNAPL components,
and the steam front if there is one.  These fronts can vanish or be created
if necessary.  The variables to be solved will be minimized and the governing
equations the least complicated.<p>

The user can input all the required data in the format of input files
containing material properties and initial and boundary conditions, or
through a Graphic User Interface (GUI), probably developed in the next
phase of the project.  The output will be presented on the screen in real time
and also be stored in a file that can be played back.  The platform will be
a Macintosh computer (PowerMac or higher) and can be ported to
UNIX workstations, except for the real time presentation and GUI.
<hr>

<h3>
An Analysis of Optimal Cycle Time and Ultimate
Chlorinated Hydrocarbon Removal from Heterogeneous 
Media Using Cyclic Steam Injection<br>
</h3>
Student: <a href="../../BERC/Personnel/Itamura/index.html">Michael T. Itamura</a><p>

A numerical and theoretical study of chlorinated hydrocarbon removal
from porous media using cyclic steam injection is presented. The porous
medium modeled is a high permeability fracture, adjacent to a thick,
contaminated low permeability zone. Two-dimensional computer simulations
were run for different initial saturations of trichloroethene (TCE) and
perchloroehtene (PCE) until aqueous phase concentration levels were below
1 ppb (mg/kg). The simulations provided details of the steam-water contaminant
redistribution and volatilization rates during various steam cycling modes.
It was found that cyclic steam injection increased removal rates, and
decreased the steam requirements to meet clean-up goals. The mechanism
responsible for the accelerated removal rates was internal steam generation
within the porous structure due to depressurization when steam injection
ceased. To generalize the results of numerical simulations, theory is
developed to estimate optimal cycle times and the effectiveness of cyclic
steam injection in reducing aqueous concentrations to drinking water
standards. The analytic predictions of optimal cycle times and ultimate
rates of contaminant concentration reduction compared well with those of
the numerical simulations.
<hr>

<h3>
Isothermal Evaporation of Multicomponent Hydrocarbon Liquids in Porous Media
with Residual Water<br>
</h3>
Student: <a href="../../BERC/Personnel/Liang/index.html">Angela Liang</a><p>

Drying of porous media containing multicomponent hydrocarbon liquids and
residual water has been experimentally and theoretically studied. The first
limiting condition, through-flow drying, occurs when air flows through the
porous region containing liquid hydrocarbons. A one-dimensional,
multicomponent liquid evaporation model was developed to predict removal
rates of the hydrocarbons in a porous media saturated by three fluid
phases and experiments were performed to optain the evaporation front
velocities and hydrocarbon concentraion distributions. Results from the model
are compared to the results of one-dimensional through-flow venting
experiments. Findings indicate that residual water presence does not
significantly affect the evaporation rates of hydrocarbons.<p>

The second limiting condition, mass transfer limited drying, occurs when the
air flow bypasses regions containing liquid hydrocarbons. One-dimensional,
mass-transfer-limited drying experiments were conducted in which air
flowed over the top of a sand-filled tube containing mixtures of hydrocarbons
and residual water. The data are compared to theoretical predictions from a
second one-dimensional model developed to describe the mass-transfer-limited
case. Theoretical and experimental results show that the velocity of
the hydrocarbon evaporation front increased compared to that in
the experiments where there was no water present in the sand column. The
effluent concentration of the more volatile compound also increased
slightly due to the presence of water.
<hr>

<h3>
Numerical Study of Vacuum Extraction of Volatile Organic Contaminants From
Heterogeneous Steam Saturated Porous Media<br>
</h3>
Student: <a href="../../BERC/Personnel/Ranganathan/index.html">Satyajit Ranganathan</a><p>

A numerical investigation was conducted on the effects of vacuum extraction
on a heterogeneous porous medium initially containing steam, water, and a
volatile organic contaminant. Of interest is the additional removal of Dense
Non-Aqueous Phase Liquids (DNAPL's) by pulling a vacuum on an initially
heated medium as would be the case after a steam injection phase. The
elevated temperatures give enhanced heat and mass transfer thus yielding
greater mass extraction rates and reduced process times.<p>

A fully implicit non-linear finite difference numerical method was developed
to model these scenarios. The simulator is a multi-phase multi-component
three-dimensional code with a built-in capability to allow mass transfer
limited or simulations based on an assumption of local chemical equilibrium.<p>

The behavior of a clean, homogeneous, steam-saturated sandpack was modeled
and the results compared to available experimental data. Heat transfer occurs
by multiphase convection, conduction and water evaporation. From this study,
it was concluded that in some cases the drying front could propagate from
the air inlet end as well as from the extraction end. The conditions
necessary for the condensation of the vapor at dryout locations were examined.
It was established that the initial water saturation profile should be known
in order to accurately model dryout scenarios. The results show that high
water extraction rates and slow medium cooling rates can be expected for
significant times beyond the end of the steam injection phase which points to
the effectiveness of vacuum extraction as a remediation mechanism.<p>

The removal of DNAPL's from a heterogeneous steam saturated sandpack by
pulling a vacuum was modeled numerically. Similar enhanced effluent
extraction rates were obtained with the removal of contaminants from the
high permeability zones occuring initially followed by those in the lower
permeability zones in longer time. An evaporation front is observed from the
air inlet end for the water as well as the organic contaminants which proceeds
in the direction of flow. However, because of recondensation of vapor phase
contaminants into the liquid phase near the extraction end, no evaporation
front propagates into the pack against the direction of flow.
<hr>

<h3>
An Analysis of Vaporization of Volatile Organic Liquids from
Porous Media by Conductive Heating<br>
</h3>
Student: <a href="../../BERC/Personnel/Fan/index.html">Yong-Hu Fan</a><p>

In subsurface cleanup using steam injection, different processes are involved
in the zones of different permeabilities. The high permeability zones can be
cleaned up readily through a combination of several mechanisms as steam flows
through, while in the low permeability zones, conduction is the dominating
heat transfer mechanism. The ultimate time scale associated with the cleanup
of the whole contaminated subsurface is thus that associated with the zones of
low permeabilities.<p>

In this paper, an one-dimensional analytical model is developed for the
vaporization of a single hydrocarbon liquid in low permeability zones in
the presence of a liquid water phase. Energy equations are solved to give
temperature distributions in the two regions separated by the propagating
non-aqueous-phase liquid evaporation front in terms of a defined similarity
variable. Darcy's law is then applied to predict the pressure distribution
in the region between the evaporation front and the top surface in contact
with the steam flowing above. <p>

It is found that the length scale associated with the medium cleanup is
proportional to the square root of the time scale and that the temperature at
the evaporation front has a significant effect on the front propagation
behavior. For relatively high permeability media, the evaporation front
temperature is significantly lower than the boiling point of the hydrocarbon
phase. This phenomenon is due to a convective flux of hydrocarbon and water
vapor from the evaporation front caused by local total gas phase pressures
exceeding the free stream steam pressure. The evaporation front temperature
increases with decreasing medium permeability, and increasing liquid
hydrocarbon saturations. Interative proceedures are outlined to obtain the
temperature and pressure distributions, evaporation front propagation
behavior, and the mass removal rates. The analytical solution is shown to be
in good agreement with numerical simulation conducted using a validated
simulator.
<hr>

<h3>
Dynamic Characterization for Enhanced Bioremediation Processes<br>
</h3>
Student: <a href="../../BERC/Personnel/Alcantar/index.html">Celia Maria Alcantar</a><p>

The use of microorganisms to degrade or detoxify contaminants in the subsurface has been recognized as a developing technology for the last 20 years.  Enhanced bioremediation processes use dynamic flow control of either subsurface water or gas in order to develop a subsurface environment in which indigenous microbial populations can be stimulated to grow and degrade dissolved contaminants.  Through the low velocity extraction of subsurface gases, air is induced through the unsaturated zone, thus augmenting the supply of oxygen to indigenous soil microbes and enhancing aerobic biodegradation.  However, a typical subsurface consists of many layers of varying compositions, permeabilities and contaminant concentrations.  Effective remediation strategy design is therefore hindered by the lack of knowledge of the subsurface flow and transport pathways. As such, the use of data acquisition tools to quantify subsurface conditions is of great value in the effective implementation of an enhanced bioremediation process.<p>

Through the evaluation of soil vapor concentrations as well as wellbore gas flow rates and temperatures, the wellbore prototype developed at the University of California at Berkeley will be used to characterize both the chemical and physical subsurface.  By analyzing samples of soil vapor taken by the prototype, hydrocarbon, oxygen and carbon dioxide concentrations may be measured in order to monitor the occurrence of in situ  biodegradation.  From the measured gas velocity profiles, subsurface permeability regions and preferential gas flow paths can be identified.  Finally, wellbore gas temperature measurements may be used to monitor possible thermal effects on the presence and activity of the microbial population.
<hr>

<h3>
One-Dimensional vacuum extraction of a heterogeneous, partially saturated and heated porous media containing a single volatile organic compound at solubility<br>
</h3>
Student: <a href="../../BERC/Personnel/Stacey/index.html">Devin Stacey</a><p>

The removal of a single component hydrocarbon contaminent from a heterogeneous, partially saturated and heated porous media is being studied.  During the steam injection process, separate phase liquids are normally removed by the propagation of a condensation front through the porous material.  However, water can be left behind at irreducible saturation levels which contain the contaminent at or near solubility limits.  This concentration can be many orders of magnitude higher than the maximum concentration level for drinking water.  For many volatile compounds, vacuum extraction is a viable alternative for removing these compounds becuase they preferentially partition to the vapor phase.<p>

A one dimensional experiment has been set up to study this removal process.  Preliminary results from the Experiment and Numerical Simulations indicate that removal occurs quickly in the higher permeability regions.  Removal from the low permeability regions is governed by how quickly the low pressure wave can propagate into the low permeability region from the interface with the high permeability region.  Transport through the lowest permeability region limits the ultimate cleanup.  At interest is quantifying results which show that this vacuum extraction process can bring concentrations to below drinking water standards even in these low permeability regions in a reasonable time scale.
<hr>
<h3>
Thermodynamics of Removal of Residual TCE from Porous
Media by High Temperature Depressurization 
<br>
</h3>
Student: <a href="../../BERC/Personnel/Stevens/index.html">Peter Stevens</a><p>

A numerical and theoretical study of chlorinated hydrocarbon
removal from porous media using cyclic steam injection is presented.
 Numerical simulations indicate the reduction of aqueous phase
contaminants to below 1 ppb through the removal of a small fraction
of the water present.  An equilibrium model of the contaminant
removal rate during system depressurization is developed.  For
contaminants such as trichloroethene (TCE) and tetrachloroethene
(PCE) the model predicts a reduction of the aqueous phase concentration
of seven orders of magnitude by removal of less than ten percent
of the water mass.<p>

 An experimental investigation of the removal of TCE from a partially
saturated sand pack by steam pressure cycling is also presented.
 The experiment is an equilibrium or zero dimensional approach
and consists of emplacing TCE to near solubility in a body of
sand partially saturated with water.  The mixture is brought to
an elevated temperature (70C) to simulate the conditions found
after steam injection.  The pressure of the sand pack is reduced
by means of a vacuum pump, while the effluent is trapped and sampled
periodically to obtain the TCE and water removal profiles.  The
remaining water is then analyzed to determine the level of residual
TCE contamination.
<hr>

