<html>
<head>
<title>New UC Method from San Francisco Chronicle, Sep 6, 1991</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><h2>
New UC Method to Clean Deep Toxic Spills <br>
</h2></center>
<h4>
Steam injections reportedly remove nearly 100 percent of the chemicals from soil<br>
</h4>
<hr>
<br>University of California engineers showed off in Berkeley yesterday a newly patented way to clean underground chemical spills that they said is nearly 100 percent effective and features injection of high-pressure steam.</b><p>
The inventors said their method occurs many of the most common contaminants from soils even if the chemical "plume" has soaked thousands of feet down.<p>
"We are trying to solve what some people said was impossible problem," said
UC Berkeley mechanical engineer <a href="../../BERC/Personnel/Udell/index.html">Kent
S. Udell,</a> who invented the process with two other professors,
civil engineers <a href="http://www.ce.berkeley.edu/Programs/Geotech/Faculty/Sitar/sitar.html">Nicholas Sitar</a> and
<a href="http://www.ce.berkeley.edu/Programs/Environment/ljrhint.html">James R. Hunt</a>,
and graduate student Lloyd D. Stewart Jr....<p>
<h3><u>A Big Moneymaker</u><br></h3>
<p>The University made $22.2 million last year in royalties and patent license fees. This is double the amount that it made the year before, "and we expect it to keep growing very fast," said Candace Voelker, licensing manager for the UC Office of Technology Transfer. She said the soil cleaner may be one of UC's biggest moneymakers yet, with money to be spilt with inventors.<p>
Local, state and federal regulations are forcing a national cleanup of contaminated soil whose costs could reach hundreds of billions of dollars in coming years. Udell cited studies that suggest the nation's groundwater and subsoil are threatened by 2 million underground storage tanks, of which between one-third and two-thirds leaks, and by thousands of miles of underground pipelines.<p>
Five years ago, Udell said, he and Sitar began wondering how to clean up a small paint thinner spill. "We knew there was no easy way," he said.<p>
The pair, joined by the other two inventors, modified a steam injection method that oil companies sometimes use to extract heavy crude oil. The difference is that an oil company may be happy to get half the oil from the ground, "while we have to get everything out."<p>
<h3><u>5 Years of Tests</u><br></h3>
<p>After five years of tests, many with scale models at the Berkeley campus and large scale tests at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, they say they have found reliable ways to inject high pressure steam, at about 250 degrees Fahrenheit, into perforated steel pipe sunk around the region of heaviest contamination.<p>
Workers turn on vacuum pumps that suck the steam from the outer ring to a central well. The steam scours out many of the most common liquid contaminants, including gasoline, diesel fuel and industrial solvents. Condensers at the surface should capture all the fluids and vapors for recycling, Udell said.<p>
<hr>
From San Francisco Chronicle, September 6, 1991<br>
<address>By Charles Petit<br>
Chronicle Science Writer</address>
<hr>
