<HEAD><TITLE><H2><B>LISA ALVAREZ-COHEN, Assistant Professor

</B></H2></TITLE></HEAD><HR><H2><B>LISA ALVAREZ-COHEN, Assistant Professor

</B></H2>

<HR><BODY>

<A NAME="top"></A>
<img src=LAC.jpg align=right height=200>
Civil and Environmental Engineering<BR>

726 Davis Hall<BR>

(510) 643-5969<BR>

<A href="mailto:alvarez@ce.berkeley.edu"> e-mail: alvarez@ce.berkeley.edu</A><BR>

<BR>

<A name="alvarez" 
HREF="http://www.ce.berkeley.edu/Programs/Environment/alvarez.html">Prof. Alvarez Cohen's CV</A>

<br clear=right>

<HR>

<H3><I><B>Education</B></I></H3>

<P>

B.A.    Engineering and Applied Science, Harvard University, 1984.<BR>

M.S.    Environmental Engineering and Science, Stanford University, 1985.<BR>

Ph.D. Environmental Engineering and Science, Stanford University, 1991.

<P>

<H3><I><B>Teaching and Research</B></I><BR></H3>

<P>

Professor Alvarez-Cohen teaches undergraduate courses in environmental engineering

and environmental

microbiology and a graduate course in hazardous and industrial waste management.  Her

research interests are

the microbial degradation of environmental contaminants in natural and engineered

systems with application

to innovative hazardous waste treatment technologies and groundwater remediation. 

<P>

Ongoing research projects include studies on the microbial degradation of chlorinated

solvents and petroleum

hydrocarbons for <I>in situ</I> bioremediation of contaminated aquifers,

biodegradation kinetics of complex

mixtures including cometabolism and toxicity, and remediation of microbially-induced

acid mine drainage. 

<P>

<I><B>Evaluating the progress of in situ bioremediation</B></I> (with J. Hunt; P.

Daley and P. Krauter at

Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory; and M. Conrad and H-Y. Holman, Lawrence

Berkeley National

Laboratory)

<I>In situ</I> bioremediation is a popular alternative for treatment of subsurface

contamination.  However,

due to the inaccessible nature of subsurface processes and the variability of microbial

activities, there are major

difficulties in evaluating its progress.  The approach of this research is to develop rapid

and quantitative

microbiological, physical and chemical analyses to assess the distribution, activity and

characteristics of microbial

populations within subsurface environments. These techniques will be used to evaluate

the subsurface microbial

activity at two experimental field test plots with appropriate geologic characteristics,

contaminant profiles, and

physical locales to promote bioremediation.  A time-series application of these

techniques will be made to

evaluate the efficacy of thermal and physical subsurface manipulations for enhancing

<I>in situ</I>

bioremediation rates in the test plots and to assess the response of the subsurface

microbial population to

applied enhancements.

<P>

<I><B>Thermally enhanced aquifer bioremediation </B></I>(with K. Udell,

Mechanical Engineering)

Since there is little chance that any one aquifer remediation technique will provide

complete and rapid removal

of contaminants, the application of complementary processes capable of diverse means of

contaminant removal

or destruction is desirable. A study is underway to explore the potential for promoting

thermally-enhanced

bioremediation in a gasoline contaminated aquifer which has undergone partial

remediation by steam treatment. 

The growth and biodegradation potential of microbial populations in the contaminated

aquifer sites will be

evaluated.  Laboratory studies will be conducted with aquifer columns and a

two-dimensional aquifer simulator

to evaluate the microbial recovery following steam treatment and to assess overall

potential for achieving

ultimate aquifer cleanup goals.

<P>

<I><B>A comparison of product toxicity from cometabolic transformations of

halogenated organics for four

microbial enzyme systems.</B></I>

Methane, propane, toluene and phenol oxidizing bacteria each produce a non-specific

enzyme capable of

oxidizing a range of halogenated organics.  Recent studies have shown that the

cometabolic transformation of

some halogenated organics results in significant product toxicity to microbial cells. Only a

limited amount of

work has been done to quantify the toxic effect or compare it across enzyme systems. 

This project involves the

experimental measurement of product toxicity caused by several halogenated organics to

populations of

methanotrophs, propane oxidizers, and toluene degraders grown under similar conditions

in continuously fed

bioreactors. Results will be used to develop models that predict degradation kinetics for

each enzyme system

and to develop bioreactors for the treatment of contaminated waste streams.

<P>

<I><B>Biological transformation of polynuclear aromatic hydrocarbons

(PAHs)</B></I><BR>

Petroleum wastewaters contain mixtures of PAHs, monoaromatics, and other organics.

Few studies have been

conducted to evaluate the biodegradation of PAHs in mixtures, especially the effect of

one wastewater

component on the biodegradability of another.  In this research project, aspects of PAH

degradation will be

investigated that are of importance to the development of improved systems for the

treatment of PAH laden

wastewaters. These include the kinetics of PAH degradation by activated sludge cultures,

the impact of co-

occurring monoaromatics on PAH degradation, and the utilization of PAH degradation

intermediates to select

for PAH degrading characteristics within mixed cultures.

<P>

<I><B>Remediation of acid mine drainage</B></I> (with J. Hunt; and F. M. Doyle,

Mineral Engineering) 

Acid mine drainage (AMD), occurs when pyrite, a mineral containing reduced iron and

sulfur, is exposed to

air and water.  AMD is typically characterized by water with an extremely low pH (1-3)

and high concentrations

of dissolved metals.  AMD can be highly toxic to downstream ecology and may be

produced indefinitely from

exposed mine wastes.  The oxidation of pyrite to ferrous iron and sulfate occurs by a

chemical reaction that is

slow and acid producing at neutral pH and by a microbially mediated reaction that is

rapid at pH less than 4.

The major goals of the biological segment of this project are to evaluate the mechanisms

of microbially

enhanced solubilization of pyrite ores, to quantify and model the kinetics of pyrite

oxidation under controlled

and environmentally realistic conditions, and in conjunction with the physical/chemical

research segment of this

project to develop methods for elimination or reduction of acid mine drainage.

<P>

<H3><I><B>Recent Publications</B></I></H3><BR>

Chang, H-L., and Alvarez-Cohen, L. (1995) A model for the cometabolic
degradation of
chlorinated organics.
<I>Env. Sci. Technol.</I> in press.<BR>
Chu, K. H., and Alvarez-Cohen, L. (1995) TCE degradation by methane
oxidizing
cultures grown with various
nitrogen sources. <I>Water Env. Res.</I> in press.<BR>
Chang, H-L., and Alvarez-Cohen, L. (1995) Transformation capacities of
chlorinated
organics by mixed
cultures enriched on methane, propane, toluene or phenol, <I>Biotechnol.
Bioeng.</I>
45, 440.<BR>
Alvarez-Cohen, L. (1993) Engineering challenges associated with the
application of in
situ bioremediation in
<I>In Situ Bioremediation: When Does it Work?</I>, National Academy Press,
Washington DC.<BR> 
Alvarez-Cohen, L., McCarty P.L., and Roberts, P.V. (1993) Sorption of
trichloroethylene
onto a zeolite
accompanied by methanotrophic biotransformation, <I>Environ. Sci.
Technol.</I>,27,
2141.

</BODY>
