<head><title>Site 5</title></head>
<body background=../../../../BERC/UCSeal.gif>
<center><h1>Site 5</h1></center><hr>
<h2>Site History</h2><p>
Site 5 consists of Building 5 and has been in operation since 1942.
Operations conducted at this site include cleaning, reworking, and
manufacturing of metal parts, tool maintenance, plating, and painting
operations. The plating shop was used to plate aircraft parts using both
cyanide and chromium processes. The processes include degreasing; caustic
and acid etching; metal stripping and cleaning; and chrome, nickel, silver,
cadmium, and copper plating. The plating shop was closed in 1990. The former
hazardous waste storage area was closed in 1988. Drummed wastes formerly
stored in this area included spent solvents, waste paint, and waste oil. 
It is currently used to store drummed hydraulic fluid and lubricating oils.
<hr>
<h2>Chemicals of Concern</h2><p>
<dl>
<dt><b>Soil</b>
<dd>1,1,1-trichloroethane, 1,1-dichloroethane, trichloroethene, ethylbenzene,
toluene, xylenes, semi-volatile organic compounds, cyanide, cadmium,
chromium, and lead.
<dt><b>GroundWater</b>
<dd>1,1-dichloroethene, 1,1-dichloroethane, 1,1,1-trichloroethane,
trichloroethene, tetrachloroethene, vinyl chloride, chloroethane,
chlorobenzene, benzene, ethylbenzene, xylenes, semi-volatile organic
compounds, and cyanide.
<dt><b>Sediments from Storm Sewer Drain</b>
<dd>1,1,1-trichloroethane, 1,1-dichloroethane, trichloroethene,
terachloroethene, vinyl chloride, toluene, xylene, motor oil, other total
petroleum hydrocarbons, semi-volatile organic compounds, lead, and chromium.
</dl>
<hr>
</body>
</html>
