2713 Haste<br>
Berkeley, CA 94704<br>
Phone:510-704-9349 <br>
<hr>
<dl><dt><b>Job Objective:</b>
<dd>To become an engineer, focusing in the area of heat and mass transfer phenomenon.</dl>
<dl><dt><b>Education:</b><br>
<dd><a href="http://www.berkeley.edu/"><b>University of California, Berkeley</b></a>, 1995 - Present<br><br>
<dd>Expected Master of Science degree, <a href="http://me.berkeley.edu/">Mechanical Engineering</a>, May, 1997.  Focus of coursework is on heat transfer
and transport in porous media.<br>
<br>
<a href="http://www.tamu.edu/"><b>Texas A&M University</b></a>, 1990 - 1995<br>
<br>
Bachelor of Science degree, <a
href="http://trinity.tamu.edu/">Nuclear Engineering</a>,
May, 1995.  
</dl>
<dl><dt><b>Practical Experience:</b><br>
<dd><a href="http://abacus.me.berkeley.edu/"><b>Berkeley Environmental Restoration Center</b></a>, Fall, 1995 - Present<br>
<br>
Graduate Student Researcher at U.C. Berkeley under the supervision of <a
href="http://abacus.me.berkeley.edu/BERC/Personnel/Udell/index.html">Dr. Kent Udell
</a>.  Currently working on experimental and numerical studies associated with thermally enhanced extraction of contaminants from porous media.  Master's report titles (two parts); One-Dimensional vacuum extraction of a heterogeneous, partially saturated and heated porous media containing a single volatile chlorinated solvent at solubility; Propagation of thermal and evaporation waves through a capillary porous body during through flow air drying. This research is funded by   <a
href="http://www.niehs.nih.gov/">The National Institute of Environmental Health Sciences
</a>.  Also have worked on
various projects associated with an environmental cleanup
field demonstration project, which utilizes <a href="http://abacus.me.berkeley.edu/BERC/Projects/
Alameda/see.html">steam enhanced extraction</a>. 
Accomplishments include:
<ul>
<li> design of a data acquisition system
<li> laboratory treatability study of steam enhanced extraction
<li> design of a water treatment system
<li> Completion of 40 hour HAZWOPER training
</ul><br>
<b>South Texas Project Electric Generating Station</b>, Spring, 1993; Fall, 1993; Summer, 1994<br>
<br>
Worked as a Co-op in the Reactor Engineering section of the Nuclear
Fuels and Analysis Division.  Major responsibilities and accomplishments
included:
<ul>
<li>fuel performance tracking
<li> plant procedure writing and revising.
<li> code development: real time tracking of reactor fission product
reactivity worths and reactor power history.
<li> incore detector system operation and data analysis.
</ul></dl>
<dl><dt><b>Honors and Awards:</b><br>
