<DT>
<UL>
<LI> Master of Science, Mechanical Engineering, University of California, Berkeley,
1993
</UL>
<DD> PROJECT:"Numerical Modeling of Vacuum Drying in Steam Saturated Porous Media"
<DD> Advisor: Professor Kent S. Udell
<DT>
<UL>
<LI> Bachelor of Technology, Mechanical Engineering, <a href="http://www.cs.wisc.edu/~shubu/iitk/iitk.html"> Indian Institute of Technology, Kanpur </a>, India, 1986-1990
</UL>
<P>
<DT> WORK EXPERIENCE
<P>
<UL>
<LI> 07/94 -  Naval Air Station, Alameda, California <br>
BERC contracted by the Navy for a $25 million project for implementation of innovative technologies for sub-surface remediation involving thermally enhanced remediation of contaminated naval base <P>
<LI> 01/95 - 05/95 Graduate Student Instuctor (Laboratory), Department of Mechanical
Engineering, University of California at Berkeley <br>
Introduction to Experimental Methods and Instrumentation. Experiments on Acoustics, Vibrations, Heat Transfer and Fluid Mechanics. Use of Laser Doppler Velocimetry for flow measurements, use of HP-VEE Data Acquisition Software. <P>
<LI> 08/90 - 12/94 Graduate Student Researcher, <a href="/index.html"> Berkeley Environmental Restoration Center (BERC) </a>, University of California at Berkeley <br>
Heat Transfer in Porous Media Laboratory: Numerical Simulations and Modeling, Experiments on Mass Transfer Limitations. Steam Injection and Vacuum extraction Remediation of Steam Saturated Heterogeneous Porous Media contaminated with Multi-phase, Multi-component Hydrocarbons <P>
<LI> 5/93 - 08/93 Naval Air Station, Lemoore, California <br>
Logging of Thermocouple Data and Flow-rate and Monitoring Field Equipment. Used Infra-Red Sensor Data-logger and data-acquisition software developed at BERC for Logging Continuous Temperature Profiles from Temperature Monitoring Wells at Naval Base Remediation Project.<P>
<LI> 05/91 - 08/91 Sandia National Laboratories, Livermore, California <br>
Logging Temperature at Monitoring Wells and Collecting Flow-rate Data at a Clean Site Pilot Remediation Project.
</UL>
<P>
