<HTML>

<HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff"">
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0 beta 1">
<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<CENTER><h3>Thermodynamics of Removal of Residual TCE from Porous
Media by High Temperature Depressurization <BR></h3>
<BR>
</center>

<P>
 A numerical and theoretical study of chlorinated hydrocarbon
removal from porous media using cyclic steam injection is presented.
 Numerical simulations indicate the reduction of aqueous phase
contaminants to below 1 ppb through the removal of a small fraction
of the water present.  An equilibrium model of the contaminant
removal rate during system depressurization is developed.  For
contaminants such as trichloroethene (TCE) and tetrachloroethene
(PCE) the model predicts a reduction of the aqueous phase concentration
of seven orders of magnitude by removal of less than ten percent
of the water mass.<BR>

<P>
 An experimental investigation of the removal of TCE from a partially
saturated sand pack by steam pressure cycling is also presented.
 The experiment is an equilibrium or zero dimensional approach
and consists of emplacing TCE to near solubility in a body of
sand partially saturated with water.  The mixture is brought to
an elevated temperature (70_C) to simulate the conditions found
after steam injection.  The pressure of the sand pack is reduced
by means of a vacuum pump, while the effluent is trapped and sampled
periodically to obtain the TCE and water removal profiles.  The
remaining water is then analyzed to determine the level of residual
TCE contamination.<BR>

</BODY>

</HTML>
