<!-- Page Title: MATECH: Biosensors -->
<!-- HTML Author: Ahmed A. Enany              -->
<!-- Graphics: Ahmed A. Enany                 -->
<!-- Copyright owner: MATECH                        -->
<!-- E-Mail: matech@sure.net                                 -->
<!-- **************************************** -->
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>MATECH: Biosensors</TITLE></HEAD><Meta name="description" content="MATECH is developing biosensors for biomedical and environmental applications using porous ceramic microspheres."></HEAD>
<Body background="bacteria.gif">
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=483 Align=right>
<TD WIDTH=483>
<CENTER><img src="logo2.jpg" Width=400 Height=78 Alt="Logo"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><img src="bar5.gif" Width=483 Height=27 Alt="Bar"></CENTER>
<P>

<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Arial" FONTCOLOR="#C00000">BIOSENSORS</FONT></B></CENTER><BR>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=4 Face=arial>In a new sensor designed for biomedical and environmental applications, a porous ceramic microsphere is attached by an adhesive to the distal end of an optical fiber. The head is doped with either an organic dye or an inorganic ion, selected on the basis of its specific biological or chemical reactivity. These optically active molecules can be embedded in the heads at near-room temperatures. The rest of the components are a spectrophotometer coupled to the proximal end of the fiber and a light source that causes either the dye or ion to fluoresce.<BR>
<P></P>
<CENTER><img src="sense.gif" Width=265 Height=292 Alt="Picture of sensors"></CENTER>
<P></P>
The sensor has been demonstrated on solution pH and alcohol content, temperature measurement, and detection of heavy metals and adenosine triphospate. Other applications under study include sensing of antibodies and viruses. For example, R-phycoerythrin, a phycobiliprotein known to readily conjugate with a wide range of antibodies, has already been successfully doped into silica gel microspheres.<BR>
<P></P>
Patents have been issued for the doping process (No. 5,480,582) and the sensor itself (No. 5,496,997)<BR></FONT>
<HR>
<B><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>[<a href="http://www.socalbio.org/matech/index.htm">Home Page</a>][<a href="http://www.socalbio.org/matech/wellplat.htm">Fluorescent Reference Products</a>][<a href="http://www.socalbio.org/matech/diabetes.htm">Transplantation Therapy</a>]<BR>
[<a href="http://www.socalbio.org/matech/press.htm">Press Releases</a>]
[<a href="http://www.socalbio.org/matech/biolink.htm">Favorite Links</a>][<a href="http://www.socalbio.org/matech/pope.htm">About Founder</a>]<BR>
[<a href="mailto:matech@sure.net">Contact Matech</a>][<a href="http://www.socalbio.org">Go to SCBC's Web Site</a>]<BR></CENTER></FONT></B>
<HR>
Copyright &#169 MATECH 1996 
<CENTER>Your are visitor # <IMG SRC="http://www.socalbio.org/CGI-BIN/Counter.exe?link=socalbio.org/matech/_sensors&style=cntdnwn"> to this page!</CENTER>
