<!-- Page Title: MATECH: Transplantation Therapy -->
<!-- HTML Author: Ahmed A. Enany              -->
<!-- Graphics: Ahmed A. Enany                 -->
<!-- Copyright owner: MATECH                        -->
<!-- E-Mail: matech@sure.net                                 -->
<!-- **************************************** -->
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>MATECH: Transplantation Therapy</TITLE></HEAD><Meta name="description" content="MATECH is developing living ceramics for treating diabetes."></HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="islet1.gif">
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=483 Align=right>
<TD WIDTH=483>
<CENTER><img src="logo5.jpg" Width=400 Height=78 Alt="Logo"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="LIGHTL~1.GIF" Width=483 Height=50 Alt="Bar"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><H1><FONT SIZE=5><B>TRANSPLANTATION THERAPY</B></FONT></H1></CENTER><BR>

<FONT SIZE=4><B>* DIABETES:</B><BR></FONT>
<FONT SIZE=4 face="arial">MATECH Biomedical Technologies (Westlake Village, CA) has been awarded a grant by the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases (NIDDK) of the National Institutes of Health (NIH) to further develop its new diabetes treatment. The grant is titled "Ceramic gel Encapsulation of Islets for Treating Diabetes." Working in collaboration with the Sansum Medical Research Foundation (Santa Barbara, CA), diabetic lab mice have been successfully treated for up to 3 months, showing no sign of diabetes. Further research is aimed at extending the treatment to one year.<BR>
<P>
The new technology, invented at MATECH, involves the formation of a porous ceramic gel network around living tissue cells. Dubbed "Living Ceramics"  by its inventor Dr. Edward J. A. Pope, the ceramic gel provides protection to the cells from antibodies, bacteria and viruses. This immunoisolation is what permits foreign tissue to be transplanted without the need for immunosuppressive drugs. In treating diabetes in humans, it is envisioned that pancreatic tissue will be harvested from pigs. The insulin produced by pigs is virtually identical to human insulin. Diabetes affects over 15 million people in the United States (Over 5% of the total population).<BR>
<P>

<CENTER><img src="islets.gif" Width=380 Height=232 Alt="Immunoisolation"></CENTER>
<P>
Fetal mouse islets encapsulated in silica gels produced insulin in response to glucose challenge. Secretory capacity of the encapsulated fetal islets performed  as well as the unencapsulated control cells. Life span<I> in vivo</I> and host/implanted tissue immunologic and/or fibrotic responses are currently under investigation. Elimination of symptoms of diabetes for up to 3 months has thus far been achieved in preliminary animal models.<BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>* OTHER APPLICATIONS OF SOL GEL</FONT></B><BR>
The formation of bioengineered materials incorporating living cells as an integral component of the material's design and function hold a great promise for cell transplantation, bioremediation and pharmaceutical manufacturing. In our earliest work, the single cell ascomycete fungus, <I>Saccharomyces cerevisiae</I>, has been encapsulated in a transparent matrix of silica gel. After gelation, aging, and prolonged storage, bioactivity of the microorganism could be triggered. Bioactivity was followed by the evolution of alcohol within the microorganism as a function of time during incubation by the molecular probe molecule pyranine. Yeast cells could be stored in silica gel for over one year while preserving their bioactivity.<BR>
<P>
In addition to pancreatic islets, the encapsulation of other mammalian tissue cells, such as rat PC-12 cells, hepatocytes, and osteoblasts are the subject of on going collaborations. PC-12 cells have been recently demonstrated as biosensors for chemical separations. These cells also have potential for neurological and adrenal secretory applications. Encapsulated hepatocytes offer promise in the management and treatment of short term liver failure and/or impairment. Osteoblasts and stem cells have potential in bone regeneration.<BR></FONT>

<HR>
<B><FONT SIZE=3><CENTER>[<a href="http://www.socalbio.org/matech/index.htm">Home Page</a>][<a href="http://www.socalbio.org/matech/sensors.htm">Biosensors</a>][<a href="http://www.socalbio.org/matech/wellplat.htm">Fluorescent Reference Products</a>]<BR>
[<a href="http://www.socalbio.org/matech/press.htm">Press Releases</a>]
[<a href="http://www.socalbio.org/matech/biolink.htm">Favorite Links</a>][<a href="http://www.socalbio.org/matech/pope.htm">About Founder</a>]<BR>
[<a href="mailto:matech@sure.net">Contact Matech</a>][<a href="http://www.socalbio.org">Go to SCBC's Web Site</a>]<BR></CENTER></FONT></B>
<HR>
Copyright &#169 MATECH 1996 
