<!-- **************************************** -->
<!-- Page Title: MATECH: Favorite Links       -->
<!-- HTML Author: Ahmed A. Enany              -->
<!-- Graphics: Ahmed A. Enany                 -->
<!-- Copyright owner: MATECH                  -->
<!-- E-Mail:                                  -->
<!-- **************************************** -->
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>MATECH: Biomaterials Related Sites</TITLE></HEAD><Meta name="description" content="Annotated links to biomaterials research sites.">
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FF80" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000C0" ALINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF00FF">

<BODY>
<CENTER><img src="http://www.socalbio.org/matech/logo4.jpg"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>Favorite Biomaterials Sites</B></FONT></CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=4>(Arranged Alphabetically)</FONT></CENTER>
<CENTER><img src="molecule.gif"></CENTER>
<HR>

<UL>
<IMG SRC="new.gif" ALT="new" align=middle><a href="http://www.13ecb.gu.se/13ECB/13ECB.Welcome"><B>The 13th European Conference on Biomaterials</B></a>. This conference will be held 4-7 Sept 1997 in Gteborg, Sweden . This is the organizers' statement of purpose: "Biomaterials research is an essential part of the scientific efforts needed to improve the quality of life of a large number of patients. The solution related to medical devices require a joint effort of scientists working in a wide range of clinical, biomedical and technical disciplines. Furthermore the introduction and use of safe and optimally functioning devices requires the expertise of a large number of professionals. Sweden has long tradition of research and development in the biomaterial research area. As local organisers it is our intention that the 13th European Conference on Biomaterials in Gteborg will be a meeting place for communication of results, exchange of ideas and increased activities across the borders. The creativity of today is needed to provide the concepts of the next generation of medical devices to be used beyond the year 2000."<BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF= "http://chemx2.chem.rochester.edu:2024/gcb/gcb_home.html"><B>Bazan Group, University of Rochester.</B></A>  Professor Bazan's group is interested in the development of methods for the preparation of macromolecules. The use and development of properly characterized transition metal reagents are central to this investigation since the activity of these reagents can be tuned, via ligand manipulation, to achieve maximum control of the polymerization process.<BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.qmw.ac.uk/~ugez027/"><B>Biomedical Materials: Queen Mary and Westfield College, University of London.</B></A> The objectives of this program are: (a) to establish a second generation of implant materials and prostheses with enhanced lifetimes in orthopaedic, ophthalmic, cardiovascular and dental applications, (b) to progress innovative Biomedical Materials from concept to patient, and (c) to facilitate technology transfer through an IRC Industrial Affiliates Club. <BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.lib.umich.edu/libhome/Dentistry.lib/Dental_tables/intro.html"><B>The University of Michigan School of Dentistry.</B></A>  A database of biomaterials properties provided as a service by the University of Michigan-NIDR Materials Science Research Center at the University of Michigan School of Dentistry.<BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="http://mems6.cwru.edu/WWW/sensors.html"><B>Case Western Reserve University CWRU.</B></A> CWRU has been a leader in microsensor technology since the 1960s. Physical, chemical and biological sensors have been and are under study currently at CWRU. Some of the types of physical sensors under study are surface and bulk
micromachined pressure sensors, accelerometers, shear stress sensors and temperature sensors.
<P>
<LI><A HREF= "http://www.ch.cam.ac.uk/CUCL/Intro.html"><B>Cambridge University Chemical Laboratory</B></A> The work of the Cambridge Materials Chemistry Group involves the synthesis and analysis of new materials with specifically designed physical and chemical properties which have applications in new areas of chemistry, physics, materials science and engineering. Chemists from all four branches of the subject work together in this important area of modern chemistry.<BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF= "http://cps-www.bu.edu/cps-home.html"><B>Center For Polymer Studies (CPS), Boston University.</B></A>  The center is devoted to interdisciplinary research in aspects of polymeric, random, or fractal systems. CPS utilizes expertise in interdisciplinary physics research to develop experimental and computational materials for K-12 and undergraduate education. 
<P>
<LI><A HREF= "http://www.cstl.nist.gov/"><B>The Chemical Science and Technology Laboratory provided by The National Institute of Standards & Technology (NIST).</B></A> As part of the <A HREF="http://www.doc.gov/">U.S. Commerce Department's</A> Technology Administration, the <A HREF="http://www.nist.gov/">National
Institute of Standards and Technology</A> works to <B><I>promote U.S. economic growth</I></B> by working with industry to <B><I>develop and apply technology, measurements, and standards.</I></B> The Chemical Science and Technology Laboratory is one of seven Laboratories at NIST.<BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF= "http://www.chem.csiro.au/chempol.htm"><B>CSIRO, Division of Chemicals and Polymers.</B></A> The CSIRO Division of Chemicals and Polymers is housed in specially designed buildings at the Ian Wark Laboratory, Bayview Avenue, Clayton in Victoria (Australia). The Division also has facilities located at Lower Plenty, also in Victoria, and at The University of New South Wales. Within the Division a work force of 170 scientists and technicians is focussing its expertise in chemical, polymer and waste water treatment areas on solutions to a range of industry and community problems. <BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF= "http://bmewww.eng.uab.edu/BME/"><B>Department of Biomedical Engineering, University of Alabama at Birmingham.</B></A> Areas of interest include dental composite wear mechanisms, silicone implant wear  characterization, influence of strain on osteogenesis, proteoglycans at the bone - implant interface, cytotoxic effects of orthopedic and dental alloys, growth factors, and bone regeneration implants.<BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="http://weber.u.washington.edu/~chemeng/"><B>Department of Chemical Engineering, University of Washington, College of Engineering.</B></A> Areas of interest include biomaterials, protein adsorption at surfaces, and  
protein technology and gene splicing. <BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF= "http://angel.chem.rug.nl/"><B>Department of Polymer Science, University of Groningen.</B></A> Focuses on synthetic and mechanistic research of hybrid organic-inorganic small molecules and block
copolymers towards materials with desired properties such as magnetic, electronic, optical and photochemical at the molecular and organized supramolecular levels. The final goal of this research effort is the design of new high-performance functional polymer materials for the present electronic and future Molecular Electronics Devices. <BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF= "http://www.umass.edu/polymer/pse.html"><B>Department of Polymer Science and Engineering, University of Massachusetts at Amherst.</B></A>  The study of polymers is carried out by researchers familiar with molecular structure, synthetic chemistry, reaction kinetics and mechanisms, and the physical properties of fluids and solids, subjects normally covered in the study of chemistry and physics. Polymer specialists may also bring to their work an understanding of continuum mechanics, reactor design, hydrodynamics, and theology, generally studied as areas of engineering. At the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, this educational breadth is assured by the interdisciplinary structure of the Polymer Science and Engineering Department.<BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF= "http://www.psrc.usm.edu/index.html"><B>Department of Polymer Science, The University of Southern Mississippi.</B></A> Areas of research include polymer engineering, polymer physical chemistry, polymer synthesis and characterization. <BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF= "http://www.esca.cheme.washington.edu/uweb/uweb.html"><B>Engineering Research Center, University of Washington</B></A> Created by a National Science Foundation Grant directed toward new generations of biomaterials for medical implants and other biological and biotechnological applications. UWEB biomaterials will be specifically recognized by biological systems and will precisely trigger desired biological responses. <BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF= "http://www.kun.nl/biomat/"><B>Laboratory for Biomaterials, University of Nijmegen, The Netherlands.</B></A> Focuses on microtextured surfaces and corresponding cellular behavior, RF magnetron sputtering of calcium/phosphate coatings and the sputtering process,  effect of hydroxyapatite coated implants on bone behavior,    milled adhesive porcelain inlays, and development of a new percutaneous implant. <BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="http://alicudi.usc.edu:80/~lmr/"><B>Laboratory for Molecular Robotics, University of Southern California.</B></A>Seeks to develop nanorobots programmed to recognize and repair specific kinds of cells, and to perform a large variety of other tasks that are now impossible to accomplish. The technology has the potential for major scientific and practical breakthroughs. <BR> 
<P>
<LI><A HREF="http://rustico.chem.indiana.edu/"><B>Laboratory of Spectrochemistry, Indiana University.</B></A>The Laboratory for Spectrochemistry (LFS) is run under the supervision of Gary M. Hieftje, Ph.D., who is a Distinguished Professor of Chemistry at Indiana University. Focuses on the research and development of atomic and mass spectrometry, chemical sensors, molecular fluorometry, and fundamental plasma investigation.<BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF= "http://www.nas.nasa.gov/NAS/Education/nanotech/nanotech.html"><B>Links to nanotechnology sites provided by Numerical Aerodynamic Simulation (NAS).</B></A> Provides lists of links to sites dealing with computational nanotechnolgy, molecular manufacturing and nanorobotics, nanotechnology laboratories, and nanotechnology journals. <BR>
<P>
<LI><a href="http://www.wag.caltech.edu/"><B>The Materials and Process Simulation Center, California Institute of Technology</B>.</a>The Materials and Process Simulation Center (MSC) was established in July 1990 as a part of the Beckman Institute at the California Institute of Technology. The objectives of the MSC are to: (a) develop the tools necessary for atomic level modeling and simulation of materials; (b) illustrate and validate new methods by applications to critical problems; (c) initiate the development of specific models by tackling the applied problems of importance to      industry; (d) develop solutions to critical bottlenecks for applications to advanced materials; (e) transfer this technology to industry through collaborations, publications, and workshops; and (f) assist industrial and government laboratories with support and guidance on theory, modeling, and simulation. <BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="http://ezekiel.ucsb.edu/mrl/mrl.html"><B>Materials Research Laboratory, University of California, Santa Barbara.</B></A> Established in September 1992 currently involves 35 faculty from 8 departments and 52 research students and postdocs. A new 14,000 square foot MRL building, which is planned for mid 1996, will house 
central facilities, seminar rooms, research office space and the MRL administration. The scientific activities of the
UCSB-MRL are focused around three major interdisciplinary research groups (IRGs) : solution templating, self-assembling
complex fluids and high performance electrical & optical polymers, and a non-linear phenomena in complex materials
seed project. <BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF= "http://web.dent.umn.edu/"><B>Minnesota Dental Research Center for Biomaterials and Biomechanics (MDRCBB), University of Minnesota.</B></A>  The center is a matrix of members and sponsors reflecting multi-disciplinary and multi-institutional resources. The governance and working agreements are in place. MDRCBB offers equality in governance between academia and industry. 50% of MDRCBB's effort meets the 3M Foundation mission in community affairs in public dental health, education and career development, and international and minority involvement. The remaining 50% is focused on new dental technologies realized through cooperation with 3M Dental Products Division. <BR>
<P>
<li><a href="http://www-mtl.mit.edu/MTL/NSL.html"><b>Nanostructures Laboratory (NSL), Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).</b></a> The NanoStructures Laboratory (NSL) at MIT (formerly the Submicron Structures Laboratory)
develops techniques for fabricating surface structures with feature sizes in the range from nanometers to micrometers, and uses these structures in a variety of research projects. The NSL includes facilities for lithography (photo, holographic electron beam, ion beam, and x-ray), etching (chemical, plasma and reactive-ion), lift-off, electroplating, sputter deposition and e- beam evaporation. Much of the equipment and nearly all of the methods utilized in the NSL are developed in house. Generally, commercial IC processing equipment cannot achieve the resolution needed for nanofabrication, and it lacks the required flexibility. <BR>
<P>
<LI><A HREF= "http://www.esca.cheme.washington.edu/surfchar/surfchar.html"><B>Society For Biomaterials: Surface Characterization and Modification (SIG).</B></A>  Encourages the development of surface characterization techniques
and modification methods for both basic and applied biomaterial research. Two major goals of the SIG are: (1) improve our understanding of the relationship between the surface structure of a biomaterial and its biological performance, and (2) develop surface modification strategies to enhance the biological performance of biomaterials. <BR>
<P>
<LI><a href="http://www-nanonet.stanford.edu/NanoFab/"><b>Stanford NanoFabrication Research Facility.</b></a> The Stanford NanoFabrication Research Facility is located in the Center for Integrated Systems on the west side of the campus. This state-of-the-art research laboratory consists of over $10M worth of modern processing equipment in a 10,000 sq.ft. clean room, extensive computing and networking capability, established processes for silicon, gallium arsenide and other material, a highly skilled technical staff and some of the most advanced research projects in the world. <BR>
</UL>

