<CENTER><H4>INFORMATION ABOUT THE</H4></CENTER>

<CENTER><H1>SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA </H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>BIOMEDICAL COUNCIL</H1></CENTER>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.socalbio.org/graph/LOGO.GIF"></CENTER>
<CENTER><A NAME="Jump 5"></CENTER>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#Jump 1"><B><I><FONT SIZE =5>Mission and Objectives</FONT></I></B></A>
<LI><A HREF="#Jump 2"><B><I><FONT SIZE =5>Membership and Fees</FONT></I></B></A>
<LI><A HREF="#Jump 3"><B><I><FONT SIZE =5>Officers</FONT></I></B></A>
<LI><A HREF="#Jump 4"><B><I><FONT SIZE =5>Location</FONT></I></B></A>
</UL>
<BR>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.socalbio.org/graph/BAR1.JPG"></CENTER>

<CENTER><A NAME="Jump 1"><H4><B><FONT SIZE =5>Mission and Objectives</FONT></B></H4></CENTER>
<BR>SCBC's mission, as stated in the organization's by-laws, is:
<B><BR>"to encourage networking and promote the development of 
the biomedical industry in the Greater Los Angeles area leading to the 
enhancement of the quality of medical products and services for the 
health of the general public." </B>
<BR>
<P><BR>SCBC's founders believe that, in today's challenging health 
care environment characterized by fast technological change, intensified 
competition, and complicated local and national regulations, the model of 
the isolated firm is neither efficient in enabling firms to mobilize resources, 
nor adequate in meeting the challenges of medical research and manufacturing. 
SCBC's members therefore believe that<B> an alternative model of doing 
business based on networking is key to biomedical technology development 
in the region. The council is a vehicle for initiating and facilitating such 
networking. </B></P>

The Council carries out a number of programs seeking to: 
<BR>
<BR>(a) Encourage networking among greater LA's biomedical firms, providers of allied 
<BR>products and services, and users of medical products; 

<BR>(b) Build systematic linkages with public and private sources of capital for start-ups and 
<BR>expansion;
 
<BR>(c) Foster interface with local governments and development agencies; 

<BR>(d) Promote linkages with local universities and other educational and research institutions 
<BR>for training and technology transfer purposes; 

<BR>(e) Provide the information, including a newsletter, a biomedical industry directory for the 
<BR>State of California, and technology and market research, to support the industry and 
<BR>educate the public about the benefits of biomedical technology development.
<BR>
<CENTER><A HREF="#Jump 5"><B><I>Go to Top of Page</I></B></A></CENTER>
<HR>

<CENTER><A NAME="Jump 2"><FONT SIZE =5><B>Membership and Fees</B></FONT></CENTER>
<UL>
<B><LI>Membership:</B>
<BR>
<BR>SCBC is open to all firms and organizations interested in biomedical technology 
<BR>development. The council has two categories of members:<B> core and affiliate.</B>
<BR>
<BR>(1)<B>Core members</B> are for-profit organizations having a substantial portion of 
<BR>their activities (manufacturing, research and/or investment) in biomedical technology 
<BR>development in greater LA. Firms providing pharmaceuticals and reagents, medical 
<BR>devices and surgical appliances, vision care products, equipment for the disabled, 
<BR>specialized hospital supplies, and equipment for biomedical research fall into this 
<BR>category. This category also includes for-profit providers of allied products and services.
<BR>
<BR>(2)<B>Affiliate members</B> are not-for-profit organizations having interest in biomedical 
<BR>technology development in Greater LA.
<BR>
<BR><B><LI>Annual Dues (1996): </B>
<BR>
<BR>(1) A core member pays $250 for the first employee and $10 for each additional 
<BR>full-time employee with a maximum of $3000. 
<BR>
<BR>(2) An affiliate member pays a flat fee of $500.</UL>
<BR>
