<!-- **************************************** -->
<!-- Page Title: The Los Angeles Biomedical Industry                        -->
<!-- HTML Author: Ahmed A. Enany              -->
<!-- Graphics: Ahmed A. Enany                 -->
<!-- Copyright owner: SCBC                    -->
<!-- E-Mail: scbc@socalbio.org                -->
<!-- **************************************** -->
<HTML>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" ALINK="#FF00FF" VLINK="#FFFF00">

<HEAD><TITLE>The Los Angeles Biomedical Industry </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H3>BIOMEDICAL SYNERGIES</H3></CENTER>
<CENTER><B>VOLUME I, ISSUE 1</B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B>SUMMER 1995</B></CENTER>
<HR>
<BR><B>OVERVIEW OF THE LOS ANGELES BIOMEDICAL INDUSTRY</B>
<BR>by<I> Ahmed A. Enany</I>
<P>
============<BR>
<P>
Medical manufacturing is becoming a big business in Southern California. The seven-county region contains about 
2300 biomedical firms, employing at least 80,000 people. Of these, over 800 biomedical firms employing over 
30,000 people and generating about $4 billion in revenues call LA County home. These firms develop and 
manufacture a wide variety of products -- drugs, reagents, vitamins, biologicals, surgical instruments, hospital 
supplies, vision care products, clinical research instruments, imaging and diagnostic tools, artificial limbs, implants,  
catheters, dental products, medical plastics and personal hygiene products. 
<P>
LAs biomedical industry has evolved almost unnoticed and unappreciated. Most of the regions firms are young and 
small  (75% emerged during the last 25 years, and 80% employ less than 50 employees). The industry, as a result, 
has been overshadowed by bigger, more visible, and older industries, such as aerospace and entertainment. 
Furthermore, the overwhelming majority of the regions firms are privately-owned, and do not release much 
information about their activities. This is another factor contributing to their almost stealthy existence. As a result, 
only a few people know that LA is home to a relatively vibrant and innovative biomedical industry.  
<P>
The biggest segment of this industry (see graph1) is made up of 458 medical device makers (mainly 
Standard Industrial Classification (SIC) 384) employing over 12,000 people and generating about $1.5 billion in 
revenues. Notable among these firms are Pacesetter Systems (Sylmar), the second biggest producer of pacemakers 
in the US, International Remote Imaging Systems (Chatsworth), a leader in the manufacturing of urine analysis 
workstations, Minimed Tech. (Pacoima), a producer of implantable insulin pumps for diabetics, 3M/Unitek 
(Monrovia), an innovator in orthodontics; and Ace Medical (LA), a leader in orthopedic implants. 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.socalbio.org/graph/biostat.gif></CENTER> 
<P>
The second biggest segment consists of firms manufacturing  drugs and reagents (mainly SIC 283). In LA, there are 
172 of these firms which employ over 10,000 people and generating $1.75 billion in revenues. The top employers 
include Baxter (Glendale), Alpha Therapeutic (East LA), Diagnostic Products (LA), Neutrogena (LA), Leiner Health 
Products (Carson), Miles - Biologicals Division, (Covina), International Medication Systems (South El Monte), 3M 
Pharmaceutical (Northridge), and Syncor (Chatsworth). Taken together, these 9 firms employ over 50% of LAs drug 
manufacturing work force. 
<P> 
Ophthalmics (SIC 385) is a small segment of LAs biomedical industry. About 101 firms producing different kinds 
of vision care products, and employing 3849 people, exist in the region. The county contains many innovative firms 
specialized in manufacturing of intraocular lenses, making LA the world capital of this niche industry. Kabi 
Pharmacia (Monrovia), STAAR Surgical (Monrovia), Ioptex (Irwindale), Iolab (Claremont), and Alcon Labs 
(Pomona), are among the leaders in this niche segment of the ophthalmic market.  
<P> 
LA is also home to a group of firms (about 52 employing 3000 people) whose products, although having no direct 
therapeutic or diagnostic functions, embody medically-oriented knowledge and, therefore, should be taken into 
account by industry observers. Notable among these firms are Ricon (Pacoima), a producer of wheelchair lifts, 
Devon Industries (Chatsworth), a manufacturer of medical disposable plastics, Precision Dynamics (Pacoima), a 
dominant player in the hospital identification tag market, and ADD Specialty Seating (South Central LA), a producer 
of seating devices for the disabled and elderly. These 4 firms employ a total of 1030 people. 
There are also many small firms that have no products on the market now, but experiment with new technologies, 
such as biotechnology, to generate breakthrough drugs and devices. Chantal Pharmaceuticals (West LA), Immuno-
Biogene (Canoga Park), Sanguine (Pasadena), Trigen (Santa Monica), VivoRx (Santa Monica), and  Xoma (Santa 
Monica) are examples of such development-stage firms. The continued dynamism of LAs biomedical industry rests 
on the ability of these firms to bring novel medical products to the market, and contribute to job growth. 
<P> 
The diversity of LAs biomedical technologies and products is among the factors causing the organizational 
fragmentation of the industry, and the lack of consciousness on the part of biomedical entrepreneurs that they 
belong to a community of producers who (a) provide products having life-enhancing value; (b) operate, more or 
less, under similar cost, profit and regulatory constraints; and (c) rely, for the most part, on science as a source of 
product innovation and legitimation.  
<P> 
In LA, biomedical firms are stand-alone entities. Many industry leaders indicate that, although LA is well endowed 
with capital, technology and labor, the absence of networking and coordination complicates the process of 
resource mobilization, and threatens the continued flexibility and innovativeness of existing firms. Also, the 
geographical fragmentation of the industry reduces chances of networking. Although there are detectable 
concentrations of firms, as in the Chatsworth-Canoga Park area, Torrance, or around the I-5 in the East side of the 
San Fernando Valley, LAs biomedical industry exhibits a great degree of geographical dispersal (see map). This 
frustrates attempts to place the industrys concerns on the priority lists of local policy makers, and accounts for the 
lack of attention to the growth needs of the industry. 
<P>
<BR><CENTER><B>Biomedical Firms in LA County</B></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.socalbio.org/graph/labio.gif></CENTER>
<P>
Thus, while LA still spawns many biomedical start-ups, the regions political economy does not offer the necessary 
institutional supports to nurture this industry. As a result many firms, such as MedClone, AMDL, automedix 
Sciences, CoCensys, Micro-Aire Surgical, and Vision Ten, tend to gravitate towards other regions offering programs 
that facilitate, among other things, linkages with universities, access to capital, information exchange, and collective 
action to overcome barriers to technology development. 
<P> 
Local entrepreneurs, in collaboration with venture capital, universities and research institutions, and public officials 
should work collectively and patiently on creating the required institutional supports to retain and nurture home 
grown firms. Rebuild LA, under the leadership of Linda Griego, has already made the first move in this direction. 
RLA was instrumental in the creation of the Southern California Biomedical Council as a regional industry 
association to articulate and pursue proposals for promoting biomedical business in and outside of LAs neglected 
areas. Other public policy agencies, particularly in the City of LA which has the lions share of the county's 
biomedical firms and employment (32.3% and 38% respectively) should capitalize on this development to fashion, 
in collaboration with the Councils members, a public-private initiative targeting the  biomedical industry for 
promotion.  
<P> 
There are many factors working in favor of this industry making it a suitable target for promotion. For one thing, 
the region's universities, such as UCLA, USC and Cal. Tech., research hospitals, such as Cedars-Sinai and the City of 
Hope, and entrepreneurs generate  many innovations in fields, such as biotechnology, nanotechnology, and bio-
compatible materials, which can be the foundation for new firm formation and job creation.
<P> 
In addition, local biomedical entrepreneurs expect demand for medical products to expand significantly. They 
indicate that reforming the national health care system, if resulted in the inclusion of millions of medically 
uninsured people, will contribute to stimulating such demand. Also, the increasing openness of foreign markets 
offer local producers growth opportunities through increasing exports. Right now, the region's firms export, on 
average,  between 15% and 20% of their output to Asia, Canada and Europe.  Many local firms are already 
dependent on exports for survival. The list is long, and includes: Ophthalmic Innovations (Claremont) which 
exports all of its output of intraocular lenses, Advanced Bionics (Sylmar) which earns 80% of its revenues from 
selling cochlear implants overseas, Alpha Therapeutic (East LA) which derives 55% of its income from exporting 
blood products, and 3M/Unitek (Monrovia) which, like Ormco and Kerr Corporation (Both located in Glendora), 
exports almost half of its output of orthodontic goods.  
<P> 
Furthermore, the growth of biomedical business will contribute to improving the standard of living of the average 
worker in LA. Data from the County Business Patterns show that, from 1975 to 1991, the annual average wage in 
the biomedical industry (SICs 283, 384 & 385) has been rising faster than that of other industries, including 
aerospace, entertainment and electronics (see graph 2). Also, in 1991, the average annual biomedical wage was 
about 14% higher than that of LA County. These trends will continue in the future, if local firms develop 
breakthrough products enabling them to earn above average profits  from national and international markets. 
<P> 
<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.socalbio.org/graph/wage.gif></CENTER> 
<P>
Nurturing LAs biomedical industry will also help in stimulating the growth of allied industries, i.e., suppliers of 
electrical and electronic components, software, programming services, plastics, glass, chemicals, metal parts, and 
scientific instruments. Data from SCAG show that biomedical manufacturing generates strong employment 
multiplier effects. These effects are bound to get stronger as the industry grows. For example, drug manufacturing 
has 1.87 and 3.73 of indirect and induced employment effects respectively. This means that for every job created in 
pharmaceuticals, a total of additional 5.6 jobs are generated or affected in other sectors. These effects are not as 
strong as those of aerospace or entertainment. Aircraft manufacturing, for example, has 2.04 and 4.96 of indirect 
and induced employment effects respectively. But the biomedical multiplier effects are stronger than those of other 
manufacturing and service activities, such as furniture and finance (1.5 & 2.91, and 1.43 & 2.93 respectively).  
<P> 
In short, the region's biomedical industry, if nurtured, can contribute significantly to job growth and wealth 
creation.
<P>
<HR>
