<!-- **************************************** -->
<!-- Page Title: Defense Conversion                        -->
<!-- HTML Author: Ahmed A. Enany              -->
<!-- Graphics: Ahmed A. Enany                 -->
<!-- Copyright owner: SCBC                    -->
<!-- E-Mail: scbc@socalbio.org                -->
<!-- **************************************** -->
<HTML>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" ALINK="#FF00FF" VLINK="#FFFF00">

<HEAD><TITLE> Defense Conversion</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H3>BIOMEDICAL SYNERGIES</H3></CENTER>
<CENTER><B>VOLUME I, ISSUE 1</B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B>SUMMER 1995</B></CENTER>
<HR>
<BR><B>CONVERSION TO THE MEDICAL MARKET IS A DOUBLE-EDGED SWORD FOR DEFENSE FIRMS</B>
<BR>by<I> Ahmed A. Enany</I>
<P>
============<BR>
According to the Defense Budget Project, a Washington research group, defense budgets declined by about 28%, from 
1985 to 1993, and may fall some more. Southern Californias 1990s recession resulted, more than anything, from 
these cuts which caused more than 50% of the regions job losses. 
<P> 
Adjusting to cuts in defense contracts has proven an arduous task for many of LAs defense companies. Large firms 
discovered that diversification into commercial markets was difficult. Not only were they smaller than defense 
markets, they were also highly competitive. But the brunt of cutbacks in military programs was born primarily by 
LAs small and medium-size 4000 job shops -- metalworking, mechanical engineering, electrical and electronic 
firms, many of which were located in LAs neglected areas served by RLA -- whose revenues evaporated when large 
defense contractors cut ties with them. Survivors of the plunge found out that conversion is too costly because of, 
among other things, sunk investment in defense-specific technology, production processes, and networking 
relations.  
<P> 
Some Southland firms discovered the medical market which compensated for the drying up of military business. The 
Medical market, according to the chief scientist of a defense-dependent hybrid maker  in Marina Del Rey, "tends to 
use many of the same specifications that the military or the space people use, particularly the emphasis in design on 
high-reliability, utilization of advanced materials, and miniaturization. This helped some subcontractors in 
minimizing the cost of conversion, and finding growth in niche segments of the medical device market. 
<P> 
Shogun (Compton) is one of these firms. This 35-employee firm produced customized metal parts for LA's defense 
firms. The decline of defense business prompted the firm to explore opportunities in other markets. Its technology 
for molding metal is now employed in making dental alloys. We were 95% defense-dependent during the 1980s, 
said John Guyton, Shoguns founder and President, now Shogun generates 50% of its revenues from serving 
commercial customers. The biggest chunk of the firms commercial business is done with labs that buy dental alloys 
generating about 30% of Shoguns revenues. 
<P> 
A manufacturer of electrical cables in East Los Angeles, which prefers to be unnamed,  produces customized 
wiresets for makers of medical devices. "Demand for our cables used in defense or aerospace applications is on the 
decline. By contrast, demand for our specialized cables and wiresets for medical devices, such as defibrillatros and 
cardiac monitoring devices, has increased significantly, said the firms General Manager. He revealed that the 
firms medically-related business almost doubled from 1980 to 1993. 
<P> 
A producer of electronic chips in Hawthorne has also been eyeing the medical market in its conversion efforts. The 
firm, which has 300 workers on its payroll, specializes in the design and manufacturing of customized silicone 
photodiods sold to defense and aerospace firms. Company officials mentioned that the decline of demand for 
photodiods used in defense applications has been offset by selling these chips to firms producing medical imaging 
devices. At the moment, about 30% of the firms output is sold to medical OEMs.  
<P> 
Turning plowshares into products that save lives is not without precedent in Los Angeles. Many of the regions 
medical device firms were based on defense technologies. Others were founded by engineers who employed 
technical skills developed in aerospace to service the medical market.  
<P> 
For example, Everest & Jennings was founded in LA in 1932 to produce foldable light-weight wheelchair using 
aerospace tubing and fabric. SpaceLab Medical (Chatsworth) produces patient-monitoring devices based on 
technologies used in observing the vital signs of astronauts. Aura Medical Systems (El Segundo) was founded in 
1989 to commercialize micro-surgical procedures for removing cataract based on magnetic techniques developed 
for the Strategic Defense Initiative.  
<P>
Columbia Medical Manufacturing (Venice), Damaco (formerly in Chatsworth, now located in Ventura County), 
Innovative Medical Engineering (Hawthorne), Integral Systems (Culver City), Ricon (Pacoima), and Scole 
Engineering (Culver City) are among the regions medical device, dental appliance, and rehabilitation equipment 
firms founded by former aerospace engineers. 
<P> 
However, conversion is a different endeavor in comparison to building a company from the ground up. Certainly, 
all players in the medical market feel the pinch of uncertainties about the future of the health care system.  Entrants 
also find that success depends,  not just on excellence in manufacturing, but also on constructing networking 
relations with medical device dealers. All have to carve niches in markets where a premium is placed on break-
through innovations. 
<P> 
On top of that, and contrary to the image you get from instruction manuals spewed by conversion consultants, 
Southland firms discovered that targeting the medical market for conversion required nothing short of reinventing 
the firm. Internally, production processes and work routines had to be altered to fit the Good Manufacturing 
Practices set by the FDA, new departments were set up to handle marketing, quality control and R&D tasks, and 
labor-management relations had to be changed to foster new work ethics emphasizing workers involvement. 
Externally, firms have to invest in constructing new types of ties  with suppliers and customers to insure success. 
<P> 
When we moved into the medical area, we had to transform ourselves into a manufacturing firm that pays 
meticulous attention to documenting every step in the manufacturing process, insuring product uniformity, and 
controlling quality. The process required re-educating our work force and  building a new type of firm. This was 
our main challenge, said Bob Wood, Chief Engineer at Kuster Company (Long Beach) which now produces dental 
drills and implants.  
<P> 
Other defense-dependent firms emphasized  the uncertainties surrounding the reconstructing the firms external 
relations as a factor making them shy away from conversion. According to a maker of electric transformers, the 
medical market offers numerous opportunities for growth. We make miniaturized transformers that can fit into 
pacemakers. But, it is uncertain that we will succeed on our own in building trust-based networking relations with 
new customers, most of whom are outside LA, to take advantage of these opportunities. Although risky, our strategy 
is to retrench and continue serving the defense market that we know best.
<P>
<HR>
