<!-- Page Title: USC Medical Technology Transfer                        -->
<!-- HTML Author: Ahmed A. Enany              -->
<!-- Graphics: Ahmed A. Enany                 -->
<!-- Copyright owner: SCBC                    -->
<!-- E-Mail: scbc@socalbio.org                -->
<!-- **************************************** -->
<HTML>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" ALINK="#FF00FF" VLINK="#FFFF00">

<HEAD><TITLE> USC Medical Technology Transfer</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H3>BIOMEDICAL SYNERGIES</H3></CENTER>
<CENTER><B>VOLUME I, ISSUE 1</B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B>SUMMER 1995</B></CENTER>
<HR>
<BR><B>USC SPONSORS A BIOMED FORUM</B>
<BR>by<I> Ahmed A. Enany</I>
<P>
============<BR>
The University of Southern California (USC) created a new forum, in 1994,  to ease technology transfer to, and 
network with biomedical firms. The forum is co-sponsored by the USC School of Pharmacy and a coalition of 
biomedical firms, mostly from Orange and LA Counties, including Allergan (Irvine, CA), Bergen Brunswig (Irvine, 
CA), Biocell (Rancho Dominguez, CA), Leiner Health Products (Carson, CA), Pharmative Corp. (Pacoima, CA),  and 
PreFree Technologies (Irvine, CA).  
<P> 
The forum is called the LifeScience Information Networking Council (LINC). It targets firms in the biotechnology, 
Pharmaceutical, medical device and nutrition industries. LINC - according to a promotional pamphlet - seeks to 
facilitate activities which will promote university-private sector partnerships in addition to serving the needs of 
high-technology organizations. Jennifer Watson, Executive Director of Development at the USC School of 
Pharmacy, said that LINC is perhaps the only comprehensive program initiated by a university in LA County for the 
purpose of networking with biomedical firms to offer them a window on many biomedical technologies spawned at 
USC. 
<P> 
The USC School of Pharmacy - founded in 1905 - has a number of on-going research programs with commercial 
promise. These include, among other things, work on drug targeting and  real-time monitoring of drug levels in 
patients based on spectroscopic methods, novel drugs for neurological disorders, such as Alzheimers, gene 
expression to target diseases, such as hepatitis B, and the role of oxygen free radicals in inducing mutations leading 
to diseases, such as dementia, ataxia or cardiomyopathy.  
<P> 
Through LINC, USC officials hope to boast university revenues by networking with industry and licensing 
technology to existing firms. An example of this networking is the on-going collaboration between Dr. Parkash Gill 
of USC and  NeXstar (formerly known as Vestar) of San Dimas in the development of DaunoXome, a liposomal 
formulation for treating Kaposis Sarcoma.  
<P> 
We can also turn our research into useful medical products and contribute to local economic development by 
encouraging our own researchers to start their own firms, Ms. Watson added. One of the recent USC spin-offs is 
CoCensys, a neurobiology start-up located in the Irvine Spectrum (Orange County). This 20-employee firm seeks to 
develop therapeutics for age-related disrorders. LINC encompasses organizations in banking, accounting, 
regulations and venture capital to provide support to similar spin-offs. 
 <P> 
Peter Chan, CEO of PreFree Technologies and member of LINCs Steering Committee, emphasized that LINC is also 
a medium for facilitating the synergistic interface and informational exchange necessary for new technology 
development. By interacting with other members of the biomedical community, you get solutions to product 
development problems. This is very important for small firms that do not have the necessary resources to discover 
these solutions on their own.  
<P> 
Two other university-based networking programs were initiated in Southern California, UC Irvines  ACCELERATE 
and UC San Diegos CONNECT. The latter is the oldest and most successful of these programs. It is credited for  
fueling the dynamism of San Diegos thriving biotechnology industry. 
<P>
<HR>
<A HREF="su95menu.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.socalbio.org/graph/smicon.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT=RETURN><STRONG> Go Back</strong></A>
