<!-- Page Title: THE FDA AND BIOMEDICAL ENTREPRENEURS                        -->
<!-- HTML Author: Ahmed A. Enany              -->
<!-- Graphics: Ahmed A. Enany                 -->
<!-- Copyright owner: SCBC                    -->
<!-- E-Mail: scbc@socalbio.org                -->
<!-- **************************************** -->
<HTML>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" ALINK="#FF00FF" VLINK="#FFFF00">

<HEAD><TITLE>THE FDA AND BIOMEDICAL ENTREPRENEURS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H3>BIOMEDICAL SYNERGIES</H3></CENTER>
<CENTER><B>VOLUME I, ISSUE 1</B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B>SUMMER 1995</B></CENTER>
<HR>
<BR><B>THE FDA AND BIOMEDICAL ENTREPRENEURS: THE EVOLUTION OF MUTUAL DISTRUST, AND THE LOSER IS .....</B>
<BR>by<I> Thomas Asher, Ph.D.</I>

<BR><CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.socalbio.org/graph/asher.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
============<BR>
The following is a true tale and worthy of all men and women to hear. 
<P> 
In perfect unison, a focus group of ten biomedical industry executives responded to the question, What is your 
worst business problem today? in resounding syllables, FDA. The next obvious question, Would you like to see 
the FDA abolished? was answered as quickly but in the negative. We justified this dichotomy as follows: 
<P>  
(1) Human nature dictates that even the best person is tempted to cut corners (i.e., cheat) when given sufficient 
motivation; and (2) Greed, or a desire for more, is basic to all humans. 
<P>  
Hence, we need and even desire a gatekeeper in order to : 
<P>  
(1) Keep us honest, and guard against our lesser nature, (2) Protect our business from unfair, competitive practices 
of the schlocks lurking on the edges of all activities; and (3) Protect ourselves, our families and our fellow citizens 
from potential physical harm from unsafe drugs and devices. 
<P>  
If such is the case, why did we all chorus FDA as an expletive? Simply, because they have demonstrated in our 
dealings with them one or more of the following human frailties: 
<P>  
(1) Bigotry, bias and distrust (Capitalists have always exploited the public); (2) Lack of common sense, 
judgment or sense of proportions (A drug can only be safe or lethal, nothing in between; risk vs. benefit cannot 
be allowed to influence safety decisions, when in doubt, dont, etc.); and (3) Envy (Those commercial guys swill 
up at the trough while we work our rear ends off for the public good and get paid peanuts). 
<P>  
In other words, neither industry nor the FDA trust each other, and both operate with presummed, negative 
suspicions of the other. 
<P>  
Certainly the aberrant behavior of some elements of the industry in the past continues to reinforce the FDAs bias, 
but this hardly justifies the obstructive and zealous behavior of some elements of the FDA. In short, this bias has 
produced erroneous decisions, delays and actions (or rather inactions) which have harmed both sides to say nothing 
of the public which has been denied, and continues to be denied, beneficial drugs. 
<P>  
Now for the solution(s). How about, both commerce and bureaucracy should practice the following: (1) good faith; 
(2) empathy; (3) allowance (i.e., give the other fellow the benefit of the doubt); and/or (4) open mindedness? Of 
course, this set of solutions works beautifully if all parties involved are Eagle Scouts.  
<P>  
Other, and more plausible solutions, are: (1) rewrite the Food, Drug and Cosmetic Acts (FD&C); (2) make a mass 
appeal for fairness directly to the public; and/or (3) appeal directly to the FDAs own sense of logic. However, the 
biblical parable of the camel passing through the eye of the needle might apply to these solutions. 
<P>  
I lean toward the simplistic; lets start by communication with the FDA in a common language, that of regulatory 
legislation but adding the forgotten dimension, the original legislative intent of the FD&C Acts and/or FDA 
regulations. A careful reexamination of the Federal Register for the written justifications for regulations and a 
review of the FD&C Acts will reveal that flexibility is allowable, desired or even required (as in the case of the 
AIDS Fast Track legislation).  
<P>  
Armed with such ammunition, particularly if presented with persistence (i.e., nagging) and using their own 
respected language (e.g., 21 CFR), how can justice not emerge triumphant? After all, using the system itself is like 
fighting fire with fire, and most importantly, it gets the bureaucrat off the hook. 
<P>  
As for style, why not try persistence? Persistence has won mighty battles. Ghandi freed India by practicing firmness 
in the truth (he refused to accept passive resistance, a name coined by others). He realized the British did not 
respect wimps, and he wasnt fearful of getting noses out of joint by forcing the issue. After all, he had in common 
with his oppressor, the same goal of improving society. And dont the capitalists and bureaucrats share the same 
goal? And guess who loses if we dont act together.
<P>
<BR><CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.socalbio.org/graph/bar1.jpg"></CENTER>
*Dr. Asher is the Chairman of HemaCare Corporation, Sherman Oaks, CA. He is also President of the 
Southern California Biomedical Council. Dr. Asher has spent 44 years since receiving his Ph.D., (Microbiology, 
University of London, Imperial College) as an academic researcher, PHS officer and plasma industry executive. He 
has founded two successful biological businesses, bringing both public and selling one to Johnson & Johnson. If you have comments, contact Dr. Asher at 818-986-3883, or fax him your views at 818-386-6522. 
<P>
<BR><CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.socalbio.org/graph/bar1.jpg"></CENTER>
<A HREF="su95menu.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.socalbio.org/graph/smicon.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT=RETURN><STRONG> Go Back</strong></A>
<HR>
Send comments or suggestions to: <ADDRESS><A HREF="MAILTO:scbc@socalbio.org">scbc@socalbio.org</A></address><BR>
<HR>
Copyright &#169 1996 SCBC
</BODY>
