<!-- **************************************** -->
<!-- Page Title: Ricon Corporation (Pacoima, CA)                        -->
<!-- HTML Author: Ahmed A. Enany              -->
<!-- Graphics: Ahmed A. Enany                 -->
<!-- Copyright owner: SCBC                    -->
<!-- E-Mail: scbc@socalbio.org                -->
<!-- **************************************** -->
<HTML>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" ALINK="#FF00FF" VLINK="#FFFF00">

<HEAD><TITLE>Ricon Corporation (Pacoima, CA) </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H3>BIOMEDICAL SYNERGIES</H3></CENTER>
<CENTER><B>VOLUME I, ISSUE 1</B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B>SUMMER 1995</B></CENTER>
<HR>
<BR><B>IN THE SPOTLIGHT: RICON MAKES LIFE EASIER FOR PEOPLE WITH DISABILITIES</B>
<BR>by<I> Ahmed A. Enany</I>
<P>
============<BR>
Ricon Corporation (Pacoima, CA) is one of the top manufacturers of customized wheelchair lifts in the US. These lifts 
enable wheelchair users  about one million persons in the US  to board buses, vans and trains, or climb stairs. 
Ricon is one of the world leaders in this segment of the US $2 billion durable rehabilitation equipment market which 
also includes other types of mobility and seating devices used by persons with disabilities. 
<P> 
According to Andrew Loduha, Ricons President, the firm was founded in 1969 by two laid-off aerospace engineers, 
Leonard Rice and William Deacon. After they were laid off in 1969,  they invented a wheelchair lift, and  decided 
to commercialize this product on their own. With personal savings, they founded Ricon and located it in Van Nuys, 
Mr. Loduha said. 
<P> 
When Ricon started, the manufacturing of durable rehabilitation equipments was a small industry. But, during the 
last two decades, a number of developments has stimulated this segment of the medical device market.  
<P>
One of these developments was the rise in demand for better wheelchairs and other mobility devices by the disabled. 
Medical research showed that better rehabilitation equipment translated into more psychological and physical 
benefits for the disabled, and made them contributing members of society. These people wanted better devices - 
wheelchairs, walkers, crutches and lifts - to maximize self-reliance and functionality. A large number of wheelchair 
users wanted to go to schools, have jobs, raise families, participate in sports, travel and enjoy outdoor activities ... 
Our lifts enable them to use transportation vehicles and climb stairs, Loduha stated.  
<P> 
The critical factor in stimulating demand for wheelchair lifts was the passing of local and national legislative acts in 
the 1980s mandating access by the disabled to public building and transportation systems. These developments, 
particularly the passing of the Americans With Disabilities Act in 1990, were good for us. They have led to a sharp 
increase in demand for our lifts ... and meant that buses, trains and other forms of public transit had to be equipped 
with wheelchair lifts, Loduha commented.  
<P>
Since 1980, Ricon has been growing very fast. When the company relocated to Sun Valley in 1980, it had about 20 
employees. In 1988, the number of its employees in LA County rose to 75 and, by the beginnings of 1995, it reached 
200. Demand for our lifts is still growing and we will add about 75 employees to our work force in the next two 
years, Loduha proudly added.  
<P> 
International demand for Ricons lifts is also expanding because other countries have started to pay attention to the 
needs of their disabled populations. At the moment, Ricon is exporting about 25% of its output, and it operates 
manufacturing and sales facilities in Canada, U.K. and Norway where an additional 300 people are on its payroll. 
Ricon, Loduha stated, will manufacture and sell over 18,000 lifts this year. About 15,000 of these lifts will be made 
here in Los Angeles. 
<P> 
<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.socalbio.org/graph/lifts1.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><B>ONE OF RICONS S-SERIES LIFTS </B></CENTER>
<P>
Ricons product portfolio includes (a) the S-Series automatic lifts to secure entry and exit from cars or vans; (b) the 
sturdier Mirage lifts installed on buses; (c) the compact, light weight Uni-Lite Series lift; (d) the Spirit Series designed 
to enable wheelchair users to enter or exit vehicles parked in tight spaces; and (e) the Liberty Series of residential 
lifts designed to assist the elderly and disabled in climbing straight, curved or spiral stairways. 
<P> 
One factor working in favor of Ricon has been the small number of competitors in this market segment. Although 
demand for lifts has been on the rise, there are only 48 specialized lift makers in the US employing about 1187 
people. Many of these firms are small outfits founded in the 1980s and 1990s, and do not pose a significant threat 
to the four dominant players: Ricon, Hogan Manufacturing (Escalon, CA), Access Industries (Grandview, MO), and 
Braun Corp. (Winamac, IN). These firms control over 65% of the US wheelchair lift market.  
<P>
In this market,  the learning curve is steep, the cost of liability insurance is high, and the development of a 
worldwide dealers network is a slow and expensive process. In serving disabled people, you have to learn how to 
provide high quality, customized products meeting their varying needs, without forgoing the benefits of scale 
economies. These are some of the factors working in favor of established players, such as Ricon, who, although far 
ahead on the learning curve, always innovate and never take their market position for granted, he explained. 
<P> 
Loduha credits the LA economy for helping Ricon maintain its innovative edge. LA County contains one of the 
nations densest concentrations of metalworking and electronics firms providing Ricon with access to vendors, 
subcontractors, and a large pool of talented workers. We could not have it any better. Internally, we have  the 
strongest engineering  capability in the industry due to the availability of local talent that keeps us technologically 
sharp. We run a just-in-time manufacturing operation envied by even our Japanese visitors. Although we try to 
manufacture much of what we design, sometimes we need to subcontract out certain jobs. There is nothing we need 
that we cannot obtain from subcontractors in LA. Our close relationship with them allows us to insure quality, 
provides us with innovative ideas that we often incorporate in product design, and helps us in cutting the cost of 
production.  
<P> 
He argued that medical device and rehabilitation equipment makers must always perform the delicate balancing act 
of producing high quality products while controlling cost in order to compete: we produce for the medical market 
where product specifications are as tough as those of aerospace. We have to insure quality because design safety 
can make the difference between life and death for the user. This means that Ricon has to spend a lot on R&D and 
quality control. But, we cannot set prices at excessive levels. We are bound by the cost-containment policies of 
buyers. In addition, many people who need our product cannot afford it if it is priced too high. This is the dilemma 
that medical manufacturers have to solve,  and this is why minimizing the cost of doing business in LA has always 
been one of our business challenges.	 
<P>
In its continuing efforts to control cost, Ricon moved in 1989 from Sun Valley to its current location in Pacoima to 
take advantage of the enterprise zone incentives offered by the State of California. The firm moved to one of the 
neglected areas in the Valley  composed of 4 contiguous census tracts  having a combined 1990 population of 
29,520 people, mainly Hispanics (73%) and African-Americans (16.75%).  According to the 1990 census, residents 
earn an average per capita income of about $7,878 a year. This is 54.7% lower than the average for LA County. 
<P> 
In 1987, the firm outgrew its  Sun Valley facility, and needed a bigger building to expand in. We received offers 
from other counties and states to relocate, but we chose Pacoima instead. The enterprise zones incentives were 
certainly attractive, said Loduha, but we also wanted to move to a location close to where our employees lived. 
<P> 
As for the future, Loduha is optimistic that Ricon will continue to grow. He praises the States reform of workers 
compensation as a right step in the direction of reducing the cost of doing business in California. He expects the 
increasing openness of foreign markets, the graying of the US population, and health care reforms emphasizing 
both home-care and the functionality of the disabled to contribute to expanding demand for rehabilitation products, 
including wheelchair lifts. We are committed to staying in Los Angeles because it has the technology and talent we 
need to stay ahead in this field, Loduha asserted. 

<P>
